description: The ampulla is the second portion of the uterine tube. It is an intermediate dilated portion, which curves over the ovary. It is the most common site of human fertilization. The word ampulla is from the Latin for flask.

name: lumbar artery
description: The lumbar arteries are in series with the intercostals. They are usually four in number on either side, and arise from the back of the aorta, opposite the bodies of the upper four lumbar vertebrC&. A fifth pair, small in size, is occasionally present: they arise from the middle sacral artery. They run lateralward and backward on the bodies of the lumbar vertebrC&, behind the sympathetic trunk, to the intervals between the adjacent transverse processes, and are then continued into the abdominal wall. The arteries of the right side pass behind the inferior vena cava, and the upper two on each side run behind the corresponding crus of the diaphragm. The arteries of both sides pass beneath the tendinous arches which give origin to the Psoas major, and are then continued behind this muscle and the lumbar plexus. They now cross the Quadratus lumborum, the upper three arteries running behind, the last usually in front of the muscle. At the lateral border of the Quadratus lumborum they pierce the posterior aponeurosis of the Transversus abdominis and are carried forward between this muscle and the Obliquus internus. They anastomose with the lower intercostal, the subcostal, the iliolumbar, the deep iliac circumflex, and the inferior epigastric arteries.

name: trunk maxillary-mandibularis
description: Portion of the trigeminal nerve where the maxillary and mandibular rami run together prior to bifurcating.

name: central nervous system cell part cluster
description: A multi cell part structure that is part of a central nervous system.

name: coronal organ
description: Mechanoreceptor organ found in oral siphon of botryllid ascidians, made of hair cells, similar to the vertebrate octavolateralis system. A possible candidate of the vertebrate lateral line.

name: obsolete terminally differentiated odontoblast
description: Odontoblast that is terminally differentiated and derived from an odontogenic papilla and associated with dentine.

name: proventriculus
description: The glandular or true stomach of a bird that is situated between the crop and gizzard.

name: arterial system
description: The part of the cardiovascular system consisting of all arteries.

name: uvular muscle
description: The musculus uvulae (azygos uvulae) is a muscle of the soft palate. It arises from the posterior nasal spine of the palatine bones and from the palatine aponeurosis. It descends to be inserted into the uvula and functions to move and shape it. It is innervated by the pharyngeal branch of the vagus nerve via the pharyngeal plexus[WP].

name: brainstem white matter
description: White matter that is part of a brainstem [Automatically generated definition].

name: epiphysis of second metatarsal bone
description: An epiphysis that is part of a metatarsal bone of digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: skin epithelium
description: Any region of epithelium that is part of a skin region.

name: granulosa cell layer
description: A layer of the ovarian follicle that consists of granulosa cells.

name: hypothenar muscle
description: Any of three muscles of the palm that control the motion of the little finger.

name: obsolete posterior iliac process
description: Posterior most of the two 'double heads' of the blade of the ilium in some take. Distinct and separate for the dorsal iliac process. [AD]

name: obsolete posterior iliac process
description: Distinct posterior most of the two 'double heads' of the blade of the ilium.

name: proximal epiphysis of phalanx
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a phalanx [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior auricular vein
description: The anterior auricular veins are veins which drain the anterior aspect of the external ear. [WP,unvetted].

name: right crus of diaphragm
description: A crus of diaphragm that is in_the_right_side_of a diaphragm.

name: hip joint
description: A synovial joint that connects the femur to the acetbulum of the innominate bone.

name: macula lutea
description: An oval area in the retina, usually located temporal to the posterior pole of the eye and slightly below the level of the optic disk. It is characterized by the presence of a yellow pigment diffusely permeating the inner layers, contains the fovea centralis in its center, and provides the best phototopic visual acuity. It is devoid of retinal blood vessels, except in its periphery, and receives nourishment from the choriocapillaris of the choroid. (From Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed)

name: macula
description: Thickened areas of the saccule or utricle where the termination of the vestibular nerve occurs[MESH,modified].

name: uncinate process of ethmoid
description: In the ethmoid bone, a curved lamina, the uncinate process, projects downward and backward from this part of the labyrinth; it forms a small part of the medial wall of the maxillary sinus, and articulates with the ethmoidal process of the inferior nasal concha.

name: anterior tibial artery
description: The anterior tibial artery of the lower limb carries blood to the anterior compartment of the leg and dorsal surface of the foot, from the popliteal artery. It is accompanied by a deep vein, the anterior tibial vein, along its course. It crosses the anterior aspect of the ankle joint, at which point it becomes the dorsalis pedis artery. [WP,unvetted].

name: acinus of lactiferous gland
description: An acinus that is part of a mammary gland.

name: life cycle
description: An entire span of an organism's life, commencing with the zygote stage and ending in the death of the organism.

name: Grueneberg ganglion
description: An olfactory ganglion at the entrance of the nose of mammals that is involved in the detection of alarm pheromones and cold temperatures.

name: primary lymphoid nodule of tonsil
description: A primary nodular lymphoid tissue that is part of a tonsil.

name: deep dorsal vein of clitoris
description: The deep dorsal vein of clitoris is a vein which drains to the vesical plexus.

name: sublaminar layer S4
description: A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the S3 and S5 layer and comprises 20 percent of the inner plexiform layer of retina.

name: choroidal tapetum cellulosum
description: A choroid tapetum lucidum that consists of layers of cells containing organized, highly refractive crystals. These crystals are diverse in shape and makeup

name: rib of vertebra 1
description: Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the first centrum.

name: barbel
description: Surface structure which is a tactile structure found in the branchial region. Barbels are covered with epidermis rich in taste buds, and are innervated by branches of the cranial nerves.

name: chaeta
description: A sensillum with a long, unicellular, setiform outgrowth that is strongly chitinized.

name: suborbital shelf
description: On the neurocranium, a horizontal plate arising on the ventral junction of the orbital wall and basal plate on each side which extends from the nasal capsule to the otic capsule; it forms the floor of the orbit.

name: ureter ureteric bud
description: The portion of the ureteric bud that contributes to the morphogenesis of the ureter. The ureter ureteric bud is the initial structure that forms the ureter[GO].

name: female urethral meatus
description: A urethral meatus that is part of a female urethra[Automatically generated definition].

name: shoulder joint
description: The joint that is formed by the union of the humerus, the scapula (or shoulder blade), and the clavicle (or collarbone). Commonly thought of as a single joint, the shoulder is actually made up of two separate joints - the glenohumeral and acromioclavicular joints

name: vidian nerve
description: A nerve that is formed by the junction of the great petrosal nerve and the deep petrosal nerve and continues on to innervate the palate, nose and lacrimal gland.

name: metanephric long nephron
description: Long nephrons are associated with juxtamedullary glomeruli and extend into the inner medulla in the metanephros[GO].

name: paratrigeminal nucleus
description: The term paratrigeminal nucleus refers to a group of cells located lateral to the spinal trigeminal tract of the medulla and medial to the spinocerebellar tracts at the level of the spinal trigeminal nucleus. The cells, identified by Nissl stain, are partially embedded in the adjacent tracts; their distribution varies by species. The paratrigeminal nucleus may represent an extension of the lateral cervical nucleus into the medulla ( Swanson-2004 ). It is found in the human ( Carpenter-1983 ), the macaque ( Paxinos-2009a ), the rat ( Swanson-2004 ) and the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ). In the functional model of central nervous system organization it is classified as part of the subcortical somatosensory system ( Swanson-2004 )

name: nucleus of Bischoff
description: A midline nucleus of the dorsal motor column found in animals with a prominent tail, including alligator, some birds, kangaroo, rat, shrew, great anteater.

name: lower lobe of right lung
description: The lobe of the right lung that is furtherst from the head.

name: right external ear
description: An external ear that is in the right side of a multicellular organism.

name: respiratory system muscle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: muscle layer of anal canal
description: A muscular coat that is part of a anal canal.

name: molar tooth
description: Molars are the rearmost and most complicated kind of tooth in most mammals.

name: distal tarsal endochondral element
description: A distal mesopodial endochondral element that is part of a hindlimb.

name: thoracic cavity vein
description: A vein that is part of a thoracic cavity [Automatically generated definition].

name: mucosa of major calyx
description: A mucosa that is part of a major calyx [Automatically generated definition].

name: perichondrium
description: Fibrous connective tissue that surrounds cartilage.

name: obsolete regional part of pontine tegmentum
thyroid gland
description: A two-lobed endocrine gland found in all vertebrates, located in front of and on either side of the trachea in humans, and producing various hormones, such as triiodothyronine and calcitonin[BTO].

name: renin-angiotensin system
description: A system consisting of renin, angiotensin-converting enzyme, and angiotensin II. Renin, an enzyme produced in the kidney, acts on angiotensinogen, an alpha-2 globulin produced by the liver, forming angiotensin I. The converting enzyme contained in the lung acts on angiotensin I in the plasma converting it to angiotensin II, the most powerful directly pressor substance known. It causes contraction of the arteriolar smooth muscle and has other indirect actions mediated through the adrenal cortex.

name: laryngeal vocal fold
description: Either of two pairs of folds of mucous membrane projecting into the larynx.

name: ethmoid region
description: The most anterior region of the braincase. Provides structural support for peripheral olfactory organ.

name: descending limb of loop of Henle
description: the portion of the renal tubule that constitutes the proximal part of the loop of Henle, has low permeability to ions and urea, and is highly permeable to water; it consists of an initial short thick segment lined by low simple cuboidal epithelium and a long thin segment lined by simple squamous epithelium; however, this distinction is not as important physiologically as in the ascending limb, so often the two are treated as one structure

name: forebrain neural plate
description: A neural plate that develops_from a future forebrain.

name: organism substance
description: Material anatomical entity in a gaseous, liquid, semisolid or solid state; produced by anatomical structures or derived from inhaled and ingested substances that have been modified by anatomical structures as they pass through the body.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of frontal lobe
ileocecal valve
description: The ileocecal valve is a sphincter muscle situated at the junction of the small intestine (ileum) and the large intestine. Its critical function is to limit the reflux of colonic contents into the ileum.

name: obsolete seta
description: A hair-like unicellular external process of the body wall or any derivative of the latter; a hair; a bristle.

name: laryngo-tracheal chamber
description: Muscular vestibule between the pharynx and lungs, lying between the posterior cornua of the hyoid.

name: crista supraorbitalis
description: Short and blunt process that extends posteriorly from the posteromedial margin of the postnasal wall, on the anterodorsal corner of the orbit above the medial orbitonasal foramen.

name: exorbital lacrimal gland
description: A lacrimal gland located subcutaneously at the anteroventral base of the ear adjacent to the parotid gland.

name: lingual tonsil
description: the lymph tissue on the floor of the oropharyngeal passage, near the root of the tongue

name: appendage blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a limb/fin.

name: limb blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a limb [Automatically generated definition].

name: lung primordium
description: A pair of lateral diverticula just over the liver rudiment representing the primordia of the lungs, formed by the floor of the foregut just anterior to the liver diverticulum.

name: spine appendage of head
description: A spine appendage that is part of a head.

name: pharyngeal pouch 4
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arch 4 and arch 5 or 6 (a fifth arch never establishes in amniotes).

name: allantois
description: A membranous sac that develops from the posterior part of the alimentary canal in the embryos of mammals, birds, and reptiles, and it is important in the formation of the umbilical cord and placenta in mammals[VHOG].

name: branchiomeric muscle
description: A jaw muscle that arises from cranial mesenchyme and is innervated by cranial nerves.

name: transversus menti muscle
description: The transversus menti, or transverse muscle of the chin, is a facial muscle that is often considered to be the superficial fibers of the depressor anguli oris muscle which cross to the other side of the face.

name: uroneural
description: Neural arch that extends along the dorso-lateral surface of the last preural centra and/or ural centra and the notochord (Arratia & Schultze, 1992). An uroneural develops as a modification of the neural arch of an ural centrum (Patterson, 1968). The series of uroneurals may include from 7 to 1 elements that are numbered from rostrad to caudad. An uroneural is a paired membrane bone.

name: distal phalanx of digit 1
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a digit 1 [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior commissure
description: A bundle of myelinated nerve fibers passing transversely through the lamina terminalis and connecting symmetrical parts of the two cerebral hemispheres; it consists of a smaller anterior part (pars anterior commissurae anterioris) and a larger posterior part (pars posterior commissurae anterioris).

name: manual digit 5 epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a manual digit 5.

name: primary ovarian follicle
description: An ovarian follicle that has one layer of granulosa cells.

name: gill membrane
description: Membrane organ that is usually supported by branchiostegal rays and forms the ventral and posterior wall of the gill cavity. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: area X of ventral lateral nucleus
epipubis
description: Small prepubic element formed by a plate of cartilage (which may calcify in the adult) that is synchondrotically united with the pubis.

name: carapacial ridge
description: A longitidunial ridge on the lateral aspect of the flank that appears in the late pharyngula stage of chelonians. It forms the leading edge of the laterally expanding carapacial primordium.

name: back nerve
description: A nerve that is part of a back [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of paraventricular nucleus of hypothalamus descending division
external medullary lamina of thalamus
description: A medullary lamina that separates ventral and lateral thalamus from the subthalamus and thalamic reticular nucleus.

name: obsolete retinal rod cell outer segment
description: The retinal rod cell region which contains stacks of membranous discs separate from the outer cell membrane that are rich in the visual pigment rhodopsin

name: urothelium of ureter
description: The luminal epithelium of the tube that conducts the urine from the renal pelvis to the bladder[MP]

name: pedicle of vertebra
description: the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the body to the laminae

name: subepiotic fossa
description: Fossa for epaxial musculature inserting on the braincase. Forey et al. 1996.

name: isthmus of cingulate gyrus
description: Component of the cingulate cortex. The rostral and caudal boundaries were the posterior division of the cingulate cortex and the parahippocampal gyrus respectively. The medial and lateral boundaries were the medial wall (area unknown) and the precuneus respectively (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: obsolete scapular area
description: Dorso-lateral portion of the pectoral girdle.

name: posterior dorsolateral plate
description: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms.

name: interclavicle
description: Dermal bone of pectoral girdle that is median and ventral in position.

name: prezonal element
description: All those parts of the pectoral girdle that lie anterior to the zonal area.

name: omosternum
description: Proximal portion of the prezonal element of the pectoral girdle. It may be a flat, midventral cartilaginous structure or a calcified or bony element elaborated into a stylum.

name: pole of cerebral hemisphere
description: The anterior end of the hemisphere is named the frontal pole. The posterior end is named the occipital pole. The anterior end of the temporal lobe, the temporal pole.

name: dermal pulp of feather shaft
description: A tissue that is part of a cavity of feather shaft.

name: ovarian follicle
description: A spherical aggregation of cells in the ovary that contains a single oocyte[WP,modified].

name: metacromion
description: A process projecting backward and downward from the acromion of the scapula of some mammals.

name: pectoral fin intermediate radial bone
description: Radial bone found in between the proximal and distal radial bones.

name: superior horn of thyroid cartilage
description: The superior horn of thyroid cartilage is long and narrow, directed upward, backward, and medialward, and ends in a conical extremity, which gives attachment to the lateral hyothyroid ligament.

name: subscapularis muscle
description: The subscapularis is a large triangular muscle which fills the subscapular fossa and inserts into the lesser tubercle of the humerus and the front of the capsule of the shoulder-joint. [WP,unvetted].

name: infraorbital 8
description: Infraorbital that is the eighth bone of the infraorbital series.

name: abdominal nerve plexus
description: The abdominal aortic plexus (aortic plexus) is formed by branches derived, on either side, from the celiac plexus and ganglia, and receives filaments from some of the lumbar ganglia. It is situated upon the sides and front of the aorta, between the origins of the superior and inferior mesenteric arteries. From this plexus arise part of the spermatic, the inferior mesenteric, and the hypogastric plexuses; it also distributes filaments to the inferior vena cava.

name: epibranchial 4 bone uncinate process
description: Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 4 bone.

name: profundal placode
description: An embryonic structure positioned halfway between the prospective eye and ear, adjacent to the future midbrain-hindbrain boundary. The profundal and the trigeminal ganglia are separate distally but fused at their proximal end as they condense around NF stage 24.

name: ventral patch of Leydig's organ
description: The ventralmost of the two bodies of the elasmopbranch hemopoietic organ betweean the esophageal mucosa and muscularis

name: pharyngeal tooth plate
description: Dermal bone of the pharyngeal arches usually bearing teeth.

name: nerve innervating pinna
description: Any nerve that innervates the pinna.

name: optic foramen
description: An opening in the skull through which cranial nerve II passes.[MP].

name: pectoral appendage bud ectoderm
description: An unilaminar epithelium that surrounds a pectoral appendage bud.

name: orbit of skull
description: Subdivision of skeleton that is an anterolateral part of the cranium and structurally supports the eye. Includes bones formed and located in sclerotic layer of eyeball.

name: primary incisor tooth
description: A incisor tooth that is part of a primary dentition.

name: buttock
description: A zone of soft tissue located on the posterior of the lateral side of the pelvic region corresponding to the gluteal muscles.

name: manual digit 1 metacarpus endochondral element
description: A manual digit 1 metacarpus bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: imaginal disc primordium
description: Population of contiguous, morphologically distinct cells that will form an imaginal disc.

name: metencephalon
description: Rostral segment of the hindbrain that has as its parts the pons (where present) and the cerebellum[WP,modified].

name: auditory hillocks
description: A collection of protruberances derived from pharyngeal arches 1 and 2 that develop into the folds of the pinna and gradually shift upwards and backwards to their final position on the head.

name: bronchial lumen
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a bronchus.

name: wall of crypt of Lieberkuhn of large intestine
description: A wall of crypt of Lieberkuhn that is part of a large intestine.

name: epithelium of forearm
description: An epithelium that is part of a lower arm [Automatically generated definition].

name: lower digestive tract
description: The region of the digestive tract extending from the beginning of the intestines to the anus[GO - gut definition].

name: bulbus arteriosus outer layer
description: Composed of scattered layers of interrupted elastic lamina. Hu et al. 2001.

name: inferior colliculus
description: Part of the midbrain tectum, consisting of paired predominantly gray matter elevations on the dorsal aspect of the midbrain, located caudal to the superior colliculus, dorsal to the periaqueductal gray of the cerebral aqueduct and rostral to the cerebellum. According to Neuronames, the inferior colliculus comprises the central, pericentral and external nucleus and two predominantly white matter structures, the brachium of the inferior colliculus and the commissure of the inferior colliculus (MM).

name: somite 25
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: anterior lateral line primordium
description: A migrating group of cells originating from an anterior lateral line placode. The primordium deposits neuromasts and interneuromasts between them during its migration.

name: upper primary molar tooth
description: A primary molar tooth that is part of a upper jaw region.

name: splenic flexure of colon
description: The splenic (or left colic) flexure is a sharp bend between the transverse and the descending colon in the left upper quadrant of humans. The left colic flexure is near the spleen, and hence called the splenic flexure. There are two colic flexures in the transverse colon — the other being the hepatic flexure in the right upper quadrant.

name: superior bulb of internal jugular vein
perirhinal cortex of Burwell et al 1995
description: Rostral portion of the parahippocampal cortex

name: perirhinal cortex
description: Region of cortex near to the rhinal sulcus. It is defined differently in different nomenclatures, due in part to the lack of agreement on the definition of the border of this region. In the rat, the perirhinal cortex occupies only caudal levels of the rhinal sulcus while in the monkey, it occurpies the full rostrocaudal extent of the rhinal sulcus (Burwell et al., Hippocampus, 5: 390-408, 1995).

name: iliac circumflex artery
description: One of two (deep circumflex and superficial circumflex) iliac arteries that supply the lower abdomen, inguinal lymph nodes, sartorius, and tensor fasciae latae.

name: postminimus
description: A rounded  cartilage lying in the postaxial margin of the mesopodium, adjacent to the distal end of the fibulare.

name: somite 24
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: carapace
description: Dorsal subdivision of turtle shell, consisting of the animal's ribcage combined with dermal bone[WP, modified].

name: posterior interventricular sulcus
description: The ventricles are separated by two grooves, one of which, the anterior longitudinal sulcus, is situated on the sternocostal surface of the heart, close to its left margin, the other posterior longitudinal sulcus (posterior interventricular sulcus, inferior interventricular groove), on the diaphragmatic surface near the right margin. In it run the posterior interventricular artery and middle cardiac vein.

name: entorhinal cortex layer 3
description: Layer of the entorhinal cortex lying superficial to layer 4and deep to layer 2. It is characterized by cells of various sizes and shapes with a predominance of pyramidal cells (Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 474)

name: obsolete gonochoristic organism
description: Multi-cellular organism that has male and female sexes.

name: medial motor nucleus of vagal nerve
appendage girdle complex
description: An organism subdivision that includes both an appendage and its associated girdle region. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc).

name: limb
description: A paired appendage that is evolved from a paired fin. The extent of this structure includes autopod, stylopod and zeugopod regions when present, but excludes the girdle and its parts.

name: upper lateral primary incisor tooth
description: A upper primary canine tooth that is in_the_lateral_side_of a dentition.

name: metanephridium
description: A type of excretory gland or nephridium found in many types of invertebrates such as Annelids, Arthropods and Molluscs. It typically consists of a ciliated funnel opening into the body cavity or coelom connected to a duct which may be variously glandularized, folded or expanded (vesiculate) and which typically opens to the organism's exterior. These ciliated tubules pump water carrying surplus ions, metabolic waste, toxins from food, and useless hormones out of the organism through openings known as nephrostomes. This waste is passed out of the body at the nephridiopore. The primary urine produced by filtration of blood (or a similar functioning fluid) is modified into secondary urine through selective reabsorption by the cells lining the metanephridium. In many earthworms the nephridial ducts open into the digestive tract instead, a condition known as enteronephry.

name: tuberomammillary nucleus
description: The tuberomammillary nucleus is a subnucleus of the posterior third of the hypothalamus. It consists of, largely, histaminergic and is involved with the control of arousal, sleep and circadian rhythm. Axons of the tuberomammillary nucleus project primarily to the cerebral cortex, thalamus, basal ganglia, basal forebrain, and hypothalamus. The projections to the cerebral cortex directly increase cortical activation and arousal, and projections to acetylcholinergic neurons of the basal forebrain and dorsal pons do so indirectly, by increasing the release of acetylcholine in the cerebral cortex. [WP,unvetted].

name: hemipenial mucuous gland
description: A gland within the hemipenial sheath that provides lubrication for the hemipenis.

name: efferent nerve
description: A nerve that transmits nerve impulses from the central nervous system to effectors such as muscles or glands.

name: incisor region of dentition
description: The subdivision of the dentition that consists entire of incisor teeth.

name: brachium of superior colliculus
description: Bundle of fibers that passes over the medial geniculate nucleus (in humans) to reach the superior colliculus. Contains afferents from the retina.

name: otic capsule
description: The capsule surrounding the inner ear mechanism.

name: pineal parenchyma
description: Parenchymal tissue that forms the pineal gland.

name: scapula
description: Endochondral bone that is dorsoventrally compressed and provides attachment site for muscles of the pectoral appendage.

name: primary heart field
description: A specific region of the lateral mesoderm that will form the primary beating heart tube. In mammals the primary heart field gives rise to the left ventricle.

name: cotyla
description: A cup shaped articular surface on a bone.

name: extraembryonic coelomic cavity
description: the fluid-filled spaces formed within the mass of extraembryonic mesoderm that later fuse to become a large extraembryonic cavity

name: zone of polarizing activity of pelvic appendage
description: A zone of polarizing activity that is part of a pelvic appendage bud mesenchyme.

name: cerebral crus
description: The cerebral crus is the anterior portion of the cerebral peduncle which contains the motor tracts, the plural of which is cerebral crura. In some older texts, it is used as a synonym for the entire cerebral peduncle, not just the anterior portion of it. [WP,unvetted].

name: xiphoid process
description: A cartilaginous extension to the distal part of the sternum.

name: fossa maxillaris
description: Depression lacated on the inner surface of the maxilla between the palatine process and the pars palatina.

name: obsolete regional part of Parahippocampal gyrus
vestibular aqueduct
description: At the hinder part of the medial wall of the vestibule is the orifice of the vestibular aqueduct, which extends to the posterior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone. It transmits a small vein, and contains a tubular prolongation of the membranous labyrinth, the ductus endolymphaticus, which ends in a cul-de-sac between the layers of the dura mater within the cranial cavity. [WP,unvetted].

name: lesser tubercle of humerus
description: The lesser tubercle of the humerus, although smaller, is more prominent than the greater tubercle: it is situated in front, and is directed medially and anteriorly. Above and in front it presents an impression for the insertion of the tendon of the Subscapularis.

name: m.scapulotriceps
description: Muscle that represents one branch of the larger triceps brachii, origination site near the glenoid fossa on the scapula.

name: transverse gyrus of Heschl
description: The area of the temporal lobe concerned with hearing[MP]. The transverse temporal gyri (also called Heschl's gyri or Heschl's convolutions) are found in the area of primary auditory cortex in the superior temporal gyrus of the human brain, occupying Brodmann areas 41 and 42. It is the first cortical structure to process incoming auditory information. Anatomically, the transverse temporal gyri are distinct in that they run mediolaterally (towards the center of the brain) rather than dorsiventrally (front to back) as all other temporal lobe gyri run. The Heschl's gyri are named after Richard L. Heschl.

name: midline crest
description: A ridge or peak located along the middle part of the head, located approximately equidistant from the left and the right sides of the head.

name: preopercular ramule
description: Ventral branch of the ramus mandibularis externus. This ramule have a superior and an inferior division, both innervating the preopercular line of neuromasts.

name: obsolete regional part of sacral spinal cord white matter
leg
description: The portion of the hindlimb that contains both the stylopod and zeugopod.

name: iris epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a iris [Automatically generated definition].

name: prostate epithelial cord
description: A solid cord of prostate epithelium.

name: crico-esophageal tendon
description: Longitudinal fibers of the esophagus that attaches to the posterior aspect of the cricoid cartilage of the larynx

name: pelvic radial 3 cartilage
description: Small cartilage that forms at the posterior and medial edge of the basipterygium.

name: anococcygeus muscle
description: One of a pair of thin sheets of smooth muscle inserting on the rectum, having a tendinous origin largely on sacral vertebrae.

name: hemal spine
description: Hemal spines are extensions of hemal arches in the ventral skeletogenous septum of the caudal region.

name: Weberian apparatus
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of the anteriormost vertebrae and associated structures that connect the swim bladder to the inner ear.

name: organ system subdivision
description: A subdivision of an anatomical system.

name: lower outer quadrant of breast
description: The quarter of the breast which is inferior and lateral.

name: neurohypophyseal duct
description: Embryonic duct that is the rudiment of cerebral ganglion and and neural gland of adult in the ascidians.

name: pelvic fin distal radial bone 2
description: pelvic fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: digit 3
description: A digit that is part of a digit 3 plus metapodial segment.

name: ceratobranchial 5 bone
description: Ceratobranchial bone that is the most posterior, bilaterally paired ventral pharyngeal arch bone.

name: diaphragma sellae
description: The diaphragma sellae or sellar diaphragm is the circular fold of dura mater that almost completely roofs the fossa hypophyseos in the sphenoid bone of the skull. It retains the pituitary gland in the fossa hypophyseos, with only the infundibulum of the pituitary gland passing through it.

name: orthodentine
description: Odontoid tissue that typically contains tubules and is acellular.

name: abomasum
description: The fourth stomach of ruminating animals, which is an elongated pear-shaped sac lying on the floor of the abdomen, on the right-hand side, and roughly between the seventh and twelfth ribs. It leads to the beginning of the small intestine. (Adapted From Black's Veterinary Dictionary, 17th ed)

name: systemic artery
description: An artery of the systemic circulation, which is the part of the cardiovascular system which carries oxygenated blood away from the heart, to the body, and returns deoxygenated blood back to the heart.

name: skeletal muscle organ
description: A muscle organ that consists of skeletal muscle tissue ensheathed in epimysium, that develops from myotome and that is innervated by some somatic motor neuron. Skeletal muscles are typically attached (via a tendon) to a bone but there are exceptions (e.g. intrinsic tongue muscles).

name: epiphysis of third metatarsal bone
description: An epiphysis that is part of a metatarsal bone of digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: bronchus basal lamina
description: A basal lamina that is part of a bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: posterior process of ilium
description: A posteriorly directed bony projection from the ilium that is the attachment site of the iliofibularis muscle (see Sumida, 1997). [AD]

name: distal epiphysis of phalanx
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a phalanx [Automatically generated definition].

name: cerebral vein
description: The cerebral veins are divisible into external and internal groups according to the outer surfaces or the inner parts of the hemispheres they drain into. The external veins are the superior cerebral veins, inferior cerebral veins, and middle cerebral vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: left crus of diaphragm
description: A crus of diaphragm that is in_the_left_side_of a diaphragm.

name: pes joint
description: A skeletal joint that is part of a pes [Automatically generated definition].

name: mid cerebral vein
description: The mesencephalic veins (MsV) enter the mid cerebral veins (MCeV) at the dorsal midline. THe MCeVs originate at the dorsal midline, proceede lateraly in a ventral direction to drain into the paired primordial midbrain channels (PHBC). ogai et al. 2001., Kimmel et al. 1993

name: lumbar vertebra pre-cartilage condensation
description: A lumbar vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: fibulare
description: One of two elements that constitute the basal row of tarsals. The fibulare constitutes the preaxial element[AAO].

name: cranial ganglion
description: the groups of nerve cell bodies associated with the twelve cranial nerves

name: foregut-midgut junction gland
description: A gland that is part of a foregut-midgut junction.

name: uncinate process of pancreas
description: In the head of the pancreas, the angle of junction of the lower and left lateral borders forms a prolongation, termed the uncinate process. During the embryonic development of the distal foregut, the duodenum c-shape is formed while rotating the ventral pancreatic bud into the dorsal bud. The dorsal and ventral pancreatic buds fuse. The dorsal pancreatic bud becomes the body, tail, and isthmus of the pancreas and the ventral pancreatic bud forms the pancreatic head and uncinate process[WP]

name: posterior tibial artery
description: The posterior tibial artery of the lower limb carries blood to the posterior compartment of the leg and plantar surface of the foot, from the popliteal artery. It is accompanied by a deep vein, the posterior tibial vein, along its course. [WP,unvetted].

name: trunk of common carotid artery
description: The initial part of the entire common carotid artery ending with the point where the artery bifurcates into an external carotid artery and an internal carotid artery.

name: acinus of lacrimal gland
description: An acinus that is part of a lacrimal gland.

name: life cycle stage
description: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.

name: paleocortex
description: Part of the allocortex defined on the basis of cytoarchitecture. The other two are archicortex and periallocortex. It consists of very thin, primitive cortex with few clearly defined layers. It is distinguished ontogenetically by the fact that it does not develop through a cortical plate. It includes the olfactory bulb, accessory olfactory bulb, olfactory tubercle, septum, prepyriform area and periamygdalar area ( Stephan-1975 ). (adapted from Brain Info)

name: tentorium cerebelli
description: The tentorium cerebelli or cerebellar tentorium is an extension of the dura mater that separates the cerebellum from the inferior portion of the occipital lobes.

name: sublaminar layer S5
description: A retinal neural layer that is immediately adjacent to the retinal ganglion cell layer and comprises 20 percent of the ganglion plexiform layer of retina.

name: choroidal tapetum fibrosum
description: A choroid tapetum lucidum that is an array of extracellular fibers.

name: basipterygium bone
description: basipterygium element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: supracondylar tubercle
description: Anatomical projection on the distal region of the femur or humerus and close to the condyles.

name: tube lumen
description: A hole in a tube[GO].

name: canthus
description: A canthus is a corner of the eye where the upper and lower eyelids meet. The bicanthal plane is the transversal plane linking both canthi and defines the upper boundary of the midface.

name: left ventricle myocardium
description: A myocardium that is part of a left ventricle of a heart.

name: epithelium of terminal part of digestive tract
description: Epithelium lining the distalmost portion of the digestive tract.

name: facial nerve canal
description: A Z-shaped canal running through the temporal bone from the internal acoustic meatus to the stylomastoid foramen. It is located within the middle ear region, according to its shape it is divided into three main segments: the labyrinthine, the tympanic, and the mastoidal segment .

name: metanephric glomerulus vasculature
description: The metanephric glomerulus vasculature is composed of the tubule structures that carry blood or lymph in the metanephric glomerulus[GO].

name: dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway
description: A sensory tract originating in the spinal cord responsible for transmitting fine touch, vibration and conscious proprioceptive information from the body to the cerebral cortex. The components include the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus.

name: left external ear
description: An external ear that is in the left side of a multicellular organism.

name: esophagus muscle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

name: mesopodium bone
description: A bone that is part of a mesopodial skeleton.

name: cholinergic system
description: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to acetylcholine.

name: mucosa of minor calyx
description: A mucosa that is part of a minor calyx [Automatically generated definition].

name: endolymphatic sac
description: From the posterior wall of the saccule a canal, the ductus endolymphaticus, is given off; this duct is joined by the ductus utriculosaccularis, and then passes along the aquaeductus vestibuli and ends in a blind pouch, the endolymphatic sac, on the posterior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone, where it is in contact with the dura mater. Studies suggest that the endolymphatic duct and endolymphatic sac perform both absorptive and secretory, as well as phagocytic and immunodefensive,functions . [WP,unvetted].

name: pontine raphe nucleus
description: The pontine raphe nucleus is one of the raphe nuclei. It is located in the pontine tegmentum. [WP,unvetted].

name: sinus of Valsalva
description: one of the anatomic dilations of the ascending aorta, which occurs just above the aortic valve.

name: embryo
description: Anatomical entity that comprises the organism in the early stages of growth and differentiation that are characterized by cleavage, the laying down of fundamental tissues, and the formation of primitive organs and organ systems. For example, for mammals, the process would begin with zygote formation and end with birth. For insects, the process would begin at zygote formation and end with larval hatching. For plant zygotic embryos, this would be from zygote formation to the end of seed dormancy. For plant vegetative embryos, this would be from the initial determination of the cell or group of cells to form an embryo until the point when the embryo becomes independent of the parent plant.

name: cartilago ectochoanalis
description: Lateral cartilaginous border of the fenestra endochoanalis.

name: dorsal nerve root of lumbar spinal cord
midbrain neural plate
description: A neural plate that develops_from a presumptive midbrain.

name: vermis of the flocculonodular lobe of the cerebellum
ectethmoid
description: either of two lateral parts of the ethmoid bone that form part of the anterior wall of the orbit

name: intermediate gastric gland
description: Any of the branched tubular glands in the mucosa of the fundus and body of the stomach that secrete most of the digestive substances secreted by the stomach

name: cartilago lateralis of aryngo-tracheal chamber
description: A series of semicircular cartilages on the side of the laryngo-tracheal chamber.

name: longitudinal arch of pes
description: A curved region of the skeleton of the pes (foot) formed by the tarsal and metatarsal bones.

name: preoptic nucleus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a preoptic area.

name: dermomyotome
description: The bilaminar epithelium formed from the myotome and dermatome.

name: pterygoid
description: Palatal bones of intramembranous origin that lie anterior to the otic capsules, lateral to the orbits, and medial to the maxillae.

name: obsolete preodontoblast
description: Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to form an odontoblast, deposits predentine, and arises from a neural crest cell.

name: pectoral appendage vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a pectoral appendage.

name: trunk somite
description: A somite that is part of a trunk.

name: cephalic spine
description: One of the spines, probably denticle derivatives, occurring singly or in pairs just behind the orbit on the cheek area in some fossil sharks. May have occurred only in males and may have served to hold the female during copulation, e.g. in the Jurassic genera Hybodus, Asteracanthus and Acrodus.

name: pharyngeal pouch 5
description: A pharyngeal pouch between pharyngeal arches 5 and 6.

name: primitive streak
description: The primitive streak is a structure that forms during the early stages of avian, reptilian and mammalian embryonic development[WP]. the midline ridge of the embryonic epiblast that later develops into mesoderm and endoderm[MP]

name: vastus medialis
description: The vastus medialis, often called the 'teardrop' muscle, is a medially located muscle of the quadriceps. [WP,unvetted].

name: distal phalanx of digit 2
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: pedal digit 1
description: 1st digit of the hind autopod.

name: pedal digit 1 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of pedal digit 1 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: pedal digit 2 epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a pedal digit 2.

name: accessory cuneate nucleus
description: The accessory cuneate nucleus is located lateral to the cuneate nucleus in the medulla oblongata at the level of the sensory decussation. It receives input from cervical spinal nerves and transmits that information to the cerebellum. These fibers are called cuneocerebellar fibers. In this function, the accessory cuneate nucleus is comparable to the upper extremity portion of the posterior spinocerebellar tract. [WP,unvetted].

name: pelvic intercleithral cartilage
description: Cartilage element that lies between processes of the cleithrum and pelvic girdle in gobioid fishes. Posterodorsal to the ventral end of each cleithrum is a posteriorly projecting process. The pelvic intercleithral cartilage (an unpaired, median structure) forms a bridge between the processes (From Springer, 1983).

name: corpus cavernosum clitoridis
description: The corpus cavernosum clitoridis is one of a pair of sponge-like regions of erectile tissue which contain most of the blood in the clitoris during clitoral erection. This is homologous to the corpus cavernosum penis in the male; the body of the clitoris contains erectile tissue in a pair of corpora cavernosa (literally 'cave-like bodies'), with a recognisably similar structure.

name: supramarginal gyrus
description: Component of the parietal lobe. The first coronal slice between the superior temporal gyrus and the postcentral gyrus where the supramarginal gyrus appears was the rostral boundary whereas the slice where the supramarginal gyrus becomes continuous with the superior parietal gyrus was the caudal boundary. The medial and lateral boundaries were the lateral banks of the intraparietal sulcus and the medial banks of the lateral fissure and/or the superior temporal gyrus respectively (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: obsolete Nobelian bone
description: Paired cartilaginous rods that lie within the copulatory organ (or so-called tail) and are attached to the posteroventral part of the pelvic girdle.

name: postpubis
description: The region of the pubis posterior to the acetabulum.

name: carapacial ridge mesenchyme
description: A mesenchyme that is part of a carapacial ridge.

name: lower arm nerve
description: A nerve that is part of a lower arm [Automatically generated definition].

name: future falx cerebri
description: A developing anatomical structure that has the potential to develop into a falx cerebri.

name: urinary bladder
description: distensible musculomembranous organ situated in the anterior part of the pelvic cavity in which urine collects before excretion[MP].

name: postcentral sulcus of parietal lobe
description: The postcentral sulcus of the parietal lobe lies parallel to, and behind, the central sulcus in the human brain. (A sulcus is one of the prominent grooves on the surface of the brain. ) The postcentral sulcus divides the postcentral gyrus from the remainder of the parietal lobe. [WP,unvetted].

name: mesonephric duct lumen
description: A tube lumen that is part of a mesonephric duct.

name: prezygapophysis
description: Paired processes at the cephalic end of the neural arch. The articular facets of the prezygapophyses face dorsomedially and articulate with the lateroventrally facing facets of the postzygapophyses of the preceding vertebra.

name: endoskeletal cranial joint
description: The braincase of most plesiomorphic sarcopterygians is divided by the intracranial point into ethmosphenoid and otic-occipital portions each covered by dermal bones. The function of the joint is presumably to increase the gape of the mouth rapidly during opening phases. (Forey 1997)

name: medial dorsal nucleus of thalamus
description: The medial dorsal nucleus (or dorsomedial nucleus of thalamus) is a large nucleus in the thalamus. It receives inputs from the Pre-Frontal Cortex and the Limbic System and in turn relays them to the Pre-Frontal Association Cortex. As a result, it plays a crucial role in attention, planning, organization, abstract thinking, multi-tasking and active memory. The connections of the medial dorsal nucleus have even been used to delineate the prefrontal cortex of the G√∂ttingen minipig brain. By stereology the number of brain cells in the region has been estimated to around 6.43 million neurons in the adult human brain and 36.3 million glial cells, and with the newborn having quite different numbers: around 11.2 million neurons and 10.6 million glial cells. Lesions of the medial dorsal nucleus have been associated with Wernicke's encephalopathy [WP,unvetted].

name: zonal element
description: All those parts of the pectoral girdle in the central region of the zonal area.

name: anterior ventrolateral plate
description: Dermal bone that is part of the scapular complex in placoderms.

name: primitive sex cord of indifferent gonad
description: A sex cord that is part of a indifferent gonad.

name: dermal condensation of feather follicle
description: A suprabasal cell population which together with the feather follicle placode develops into the feather follicle.

name: cumulus oophorus
description: A cluster of cells that project into the cavity of the mature ovarian follicle. It is released with the embedded oocyte during ovulation. In order for fertilization to occur this layer must be penetrated by the spermatocyte. [WP,modified].

name: anterior superior iliac spine
description: The anterior superior iliac spine (ASIS) is an important landmark of surface anatomy. It refers to the anterior extremity of the iliac crest of the pelvis, which provides attachment for the inguinal ligament, the sartorius muscle, and the tensor fasciae latae. ASIS provides a clue in identifying some other clinical landmarks, including: McBurney's point Gardner's line Roser-NC)laton line A - Anterior (front, like the face) S - Superior (towards the head, opposite to feet) I - Iliac S - Spine

name: inferior horn of thyroid cartilage
description: The inferior horn of thyroid cartilage is short and thick; it is directed downward, with a slight inclination forward and medialward, and presents, on the medial side of its tip, a small oval articular facet for articulation with the side of the cricoid cartilage.

name: postaxial process of the ulnare
description: A projection on the postaxial region of the ulnare.

name: thoracic aortic plexus
description: The thoracic aortic plexus is a sympathetic plexus in the region of the thoracic aorta.

name: lateral line scale
description: Scale that is associated with the lateral line sensory canal.

name: spiral valve of intestine
description: Coiled structure in the lumen of the small intestine that increases the length of the route through the digestive tract.[WP,cjm,Kardong]

name: basihyal tooth plate
description: Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to the basihyal cartilage or bone.

name: future cardiac ventricle
description: Multi-tissue structure that is part of the heart tube and will become the cardiac ventricle.

name: left adrenal gland cortex
description: the thick outer layer of the adrenal gland that is in the left side of the abdomen

name: nerve of penis
description: Any nerve that innervates the penis.

name: mucosa of epiglottis
description: A mucosa that is part of a epiglottis [Automatically generated definition].

name: posterior lateral line
description: One of eight distinct lateral lines in the 4-day larva. A sensory system on the surface of the fish, consisting of small sensory patches (neuromasts) distributed in discrete lines over the body surface. The lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance.

name: ectoderm of footplate
description: An ectoderm that is part of a footplate.

name: major alar cartilage
description: The greater alar cartilage (lower lateral cartilage) is a thin, flexible plate, situated immediately below the preceding, and bent upon itself in such a manner as to form the medial wall and lateral wall of the naris of its own side. The portion which forms the medial wall (crus mediale) is loosely connected with the corresponding portion of the opposite cartilage, the two forming, together with the thickened integument and subjacent tissue, the septum mobile nasi. The part which forms the lateral wall (crus laterale) is curved to correspond with the ala of the nose; it is oval and flattened, narrow behind, where it is connected with the frontal process of the maxilla by a tough fibrous membrane, in which are found three or four small cartilaginous plates, the lesser alar cartilages (cartilagines alares minores; sesamoid cartilages). Above, it is connected by fibrous tissue to the lateral cartilage and front part of the cartilage of the septum; below, it falls short of the margin of the naris, the ala being completed by fatty and fibrous tissue covered by skin. In front, the greater alar cartilages are separated by a notch which corresponds with the apex of the nose.

name: zygomatic process of maxilla
description: The zygomatic process of the maxilla (malar process) is a rough triangular eminence, situated at the angle of separation of the anterior, zygomatic, and orbital surfaces. In front it forms part of the anterior surface. Behind it is concave, and forms part of the infratemporal fossa. Above it is rough and serrated for articulation with the zygomatic bone. Below it presents the prominent arched border which marks the division between the anterior and infratemporal surfaces.

name: inframammary fold
description: Inframammary fold, inframammary crease or inframammary line is the feature of human anatomy which is a natural boundary of a breast from below, the place where the breast and the chest meet. The choice of the term depends on the prominence of the feature.

name: inferior nasal meatus
description: The inferior meatus, the largest of the three meatuses of the nose, is the space between the inferior concha and the floor of the nasal cavity. It extends almost the entire length of the lateral wall of the nose, is broader in front than behind, and presents anteriorly the lower orifice of the nasolacrimal canal.

name: skeletal muscle connective tissue
description: A connective tissue that surrounds a skeletal muscle tissue.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 45
description: Part of the cytoarchitecturally defined frontal region of cerebral cortex. In the human, it occupies the triangular part of the inferior frontal gyrus (human) and, surrounding the anterior horizontal limb of the lateral sulcus (human), a portion of the orbital part of the inferior frontal gyrus (human). Bounded caudally by the anterior ascending limb of the lateral sulcus (human), it borders on the insula in the depth of the lateral sulcus. Cytoarchitectonically it is bounded caudally by the opercular area 44, rostrodorsally by the area 46 of Brodmann (human) and ventrally by the area 47 of Brodmann (human) (Brodmann-1909) (Adapted from Brain Info)

name: manual digit 2 metacarpus endochondral element
description: A manual digit 2 metacarpus bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: medulla oblongata
description: Organ component of neuraxis that has as its parts the medullary reticular formation, inferior olivary complex and cochlear nuclear complex, among other structures[FMA]. The medulla oblongata lies directly above the spinal cord and controls vital autonomic functions such as digestion, breathing and the control of heart rate[GO].

name: basioccipital cartilage element
description: A basioccipital endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: mesenchyme of hard palate
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing hard palate [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete pelvic fin radial cartilage
description: pelvic fin radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: lumen of primary bronchus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a main bronchus.

name: white matter of frontal lobe
description: A white matter of cerebral lobe that is part of a frontal lobe.

name: base of crypt of Lieberkuhn of small intestine
description: The basal portion (further from lumen) of a intestinal crypt that is located in the small intestine.

name: epithelium of footplate
description: An epithelium that is part of a footplate.

name: upper digestive tract
description: The region of the digestive tract extending from the mouth cavity through pharynx esophagus stomach and duodenum.

name: bulbus arteriosus middle layer
description: Composed of 7-10 layers of helically arranged smooth muscle cells surrounded by a fine network of collagen, reticular, and elastic fibrils. Hu et al. 2001.

name: preopercle-opercle joint
description: Joint that articulates the preopercle and opercle. Preopercle-opercle joint is paired.

name: deep lateral cervical lymph node
description: The deep lateral cervical lymph nodes are found near the upper part of the internal jugular vein in the neck, lateral or posterior to the carotid sheath.

name: angulosplenial coronoid process
description: Point of insertion of the adductor mandibulae musculature.

name: red nucleus
description: Large round nucleus located in the midbrain tegmentum, consisting of a magnocellular and parvicellular portion in most species studied.

name: somite 29
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: olfactory entorhinal cortex
description: A part of the entorhinal area defined on the basis of connectivity. It is the rostral portion, which receives a projection from the olfactory bulb (Price-90)-Adapted from Brain Info

name: middle lateral line primordium
description: A migrating group of cells originating from the middle lateral line placode. The primordium deposits neuromasts with interneuromasts between them.

name: hepatic flexure of colon
description: Hepatic (or the right colic) flexure is the sharp bend between the ascending and the transverse colon. The right colic flexure is adjacent to the liver, and is therefore also known as the hepatic flexure. Thus, the left colic flexure is also known as the splenic flexure (as it is close to the spleen). The hepatic flexure lies in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen in humans.

name: internasal suture
description: A suture joining the nasal bones.

name: inferior bulb of internal jugular vein
vesical artery
description: An artery that supplies blood to the urinary bladder.

name: somite 28
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: plastron
description: A composite bony plate forming the floor of the shell of a turtle consisting of fused dermal elements, including contributions from the clavicles (epiplastrons) and interclavice (epiplastron).

name: glossopharyngeal neural crest
description: Cranial neural crest which gives rise to the glossopharyngeal ganglion.

name: obsolete mesonephric podocyte
description: Podocyte that is part of the kidney (mesonephros).

name: pectoral complex
description: Appendage girdle complex that when present, encompasses the pectoral appendicular skeleton and the pectoral girdle.

name: lower central primary incisor tooth
description: A lower primary incisor tooth that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition.

name: scleral ossicle
description: A bony plate around the eyes, are situated at the corneal-scleral limbus. They do not articulate with other elements of the skull. Typically, the scleral ossicles overlap the rim of a cup of scleral cartilage that supports the eyeball. Situated near the equator of the eye and may slightly overlap the rim of scleral cartilage.

name: esophagus smooth muscle circular layer
description: A circular muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a esophagus.

name: central lobule
description: The central lobule is a small square lobule, situated in the anterior cerebellar notch. It overlaps the lingula, from which it is separated by the precentral fissure; laterally, it extends along the upper and anterior part of each hemisphere, where it forms a wing-like prolongation, the ala lobuli centralis. [WP,unvetted].

name: hemipenial holocrine gland
description: A holocrine gland that is part of a hemipenis.

name: glandular epithelium
description: An epithelium that is composed primarily of secretory cells.

name: premolar tooth 5
description: The premolar tooth of the upper or lower jaw that is phylogenetically number 5

name: olfactory lobe
description: The lobe at the anterior part of each cerebral hemisphere, responsible for olfactory functions.

name: somatosensory cortex
description: Area of the parietal lobe concerned with receiving general sensations. It lies posterior to the central sulcus.

name: postcentral gyrus
description: Component of the parietal lobe. The appearance and disappearance of the central sulcus were the rostral and caudal boundaries of the postcentral gyrus respectively. The medial and lateral boundaries were the lateral bank of the precentral gyrus and the lateral fissure and/or the medial bank of the superior parietal gyrus respectively (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: scapular muscle
description: Any of the muscles that are responsible for moving the scapula. In humans these are the levator scapulae, the infraspinatus muscle, the teres major, the teres minor, and the supraspinatus muscle.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 10
description: Brodmann area 10, or BA10, is part of the frontal cortex in the human brain. BA10 encompasses the most anterior part of the frontal cortex, known as the frontopolar region. This area is believed to play a part in strategic processes involved in memory retrieval and executive function. This area is also called frontopolar area 10, and it refers to a subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined frontal region of cerebral cortex. It occupies the most rostral portions of the superior frontal gyrus and the middle frontal gyrus. In humans, on the medial aspect of the hemisphere it is bounded ventrally by the superior rostral sulcus (H). It does not extend as far as the cingulate sulcus. Cytoarchitecturally it is bounded dorsally by the granular frontal area 9, caudally by the middle frontal area 46, and ventrally by the orbital area 47 and by the rostral area 12 or, in an early version of Brodmann's cortical map (Brodmann-1909), the prefrontal Brodmann area 11-1909.

name: cotyloid notch
description: A notch or opening in the ventral part of the acetabular rim.

name: fallopian tube
description: Initial section of the oviduct through which the ova pass from the ovary to the uterus

name: forelimb bud
description: A limb bud that develops into a forelimb.

name: medial part of medial mammillary nucleus
internal thoracic artery
description: An artery that supplies the anterior chest wall and the breasts. It is a paired artery, with one running along each side of the sternum, to continue after its bifurcation as the superior epigastric and musculophrenic arteries. [WP,unvetted].

name: pars glenoidalis of quadratojugal
description: Portion of the quadratojugal that makes contact dorsally with the distal portion of the squamosal.

name: obsolete dendrite
description: The region of a neuron receiving inputs from other neurons, typically a slender neurite, often branched. In insect neurons, this is often not a clear designation and often presynaptic sites co-extend with postsynaptic ones.

name: median dorsal plate
description: Dermal armour plate that is situated behind the head and constitute the dorsal most portion of the dermal shoulder girdle. Modified from Brazeau 2009, Young 2010

name: ramus supraotic
description: Small ramus of the MLLN that innervates neuromasts located at the posterior margin of the otic capsule.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of basal nuclear complex
surface of mandible
description: A anatomical surface that is part of a mandible.

name: tibia
description: The major preaxial endochondral bone in the posterior zeugopod[Phenoscape].

name: abdominal lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of an abdomen [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior intervertebral notch
description: Indentation on the posterior margin of the pedicel. When two vertebrae articulate, the anterior notch of one vertebra and the posterior notch of the other create a bilateral intervertebral space.

name: urogenital sinus lumen
description: An anatomical space that surrounded_by a primitive urogenital sinus.

name: pelvic radial 2 cartilage
description: Small cartilage with a long posterior process and a shorter lateral one that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium, between radial cartilages 1 and 2.

name: ventral mesentery
description: Ventral mesentery is the part of the peritoneum closest to the navel.

name: mandibular lymph node
description: The mandibular lymph node is a lymph node found near the jaw.

name: obsolete superficial feature part of posterior hypothalamic region
upper inner quadrant of breast
description: The quarter of the breast which is superior and medial.

name: tunicate siphon
description: tubular appendage for drawing or ejecting fluids

name: pelvic fin distal radial bone 3
description: pelvic fin distal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: adult prothoracic segment
description: Any prothoracic segment (UBERON:6000017) that is part of some adult thorax (UBERON:6003018).

name: digit 4
description: A digit that is part of a digit 4 plus metapodial segment.

name: temporomandibular joint
description: A synovial joint of the jaw that connects the mandible to the temporal bone.

name: supraorbital lateral line
description: The lateral line that is located above the eye.

name: blastoderm
description: A layer of cells formed at one pole of macrolecithal eggs such as the yolky egg of birds. The yolk prevents the division from taking place through the egg, resulting in meroblastic cleavage during the many cleavage divisions. At the animal pole (containing less yolk than the vegetal pole), the zygote divides and subdivides, forming the blastoderm, which gradually spreads around the yolk and forms the embryo. The blastoderm is composed of two layers, the epiblast and the hypoblast, which enclose the fluid-filled blastocoel cavity.

name: ruminant forestomach
description: Any of the first three stomachs of a ruminant, i.e., the rumen, reticulum, or omasum.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 35
description: Brodmann area 35, together with Brodmann area 36, is most frequently referred to as perirhinal cortex.

name: epiphysis of fourth metatarsal bone
description: An epiphysis that is part of a metatarsal bone of digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: cervix epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a uterine cervix [Automatically generated definition].

name: suprainiac fossa
description: The suprainiac fossa is an elliptic depression on the occiput above the superior nuchal line, or inion.

name: lateral lumbar region of abdomen
description: A region of the posterior torso (lower back) beneath the ribs and above the ilium.

name: semicircular canal
description: One of three half-circular, interconnected tubes located inside each ear[WP].

name: matrix part of head of caudate nucleus
description: Matrix compartment located in the head of the caudate nucleus

name: cerebral artery
description: One of three main pairs of arteries and their branches, which irrigate the cerebrum of the brain.

name: inferior cerebral vein
description: The inferior cerebral veins, of small size, drain the under surfaces of the hemispheres. Those on the orbital surface of the frontal lobe join the superior cerebral veins, and through these open into the superior sagittal sinus. Those of the temporal lobe anastomose with the middle cerebral and basal veins, and join the cavernous, sphenoparietal, and superior petrosal sinuses. [WP,unvetted].

name: genu of facial nerve
description: The bend in the facial nerve at the lateral end of the internal acoustic meatus.

name: superior palpebral vein
description: A blood vessel that drains from from an upper eyelid.

name: ankle joint
description: A joint that connects the hindlimb autopod and zeugopod skeletons.

name: pseudobranchial artery
description: A vascular loop attached to the efferent part of the mandibular arch that forms at 3.5 dpf. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: ambiens muscle
description: A long muscle found in reptiles that originates on the ilium and crosses the acetabulum and the knee joint before being inserted on the tibia.

name: postcommissural fornix of brain
description: The posterior fibers of the fornix, which continue through the hypothalamus to the mammillary bodies; then to the anterior nuclei of thalamus, which project to the cingulate cortex.

name: obsolete Schreckstoff
description: Chemical substance that functions as an alarm signal.

name: pedal digit 4 metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pedal digit metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a pedal digit 4 mesenchyme.

name: vessel
description: A tubular structure that contains, conveys body fluid, such as blood or lymph.

name: oculomotor nuclear complex
description: Nuclear complex containing subnuclei that give rise to the axons of the occulomotor nerve, both motor and parasympathetic fibers, situated at the midline at the level of the superior colliculus in the midbrain tegmentum (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 3rd ed., 1981, pg 533-534).

name: dorsalis pedis artery
description: A blood vessel of the lower limb that carries oxygenated blood to the dorsal surface of the foot. It arises at the anterior aspect of the ankle joint and is a continuation of the anterior tibial artery. It terminates at the proximal part of the first intermetatarsal space, where it divides into two branches, the first dorsal metatarsal artery and the deep plantar artery. Along its course, it is accompanied by a deep vein, the dorsalis pedis vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: carotid duct
description: A segment of the embryonic dorsal aorta between points of juncture with the third and fourth arch arteries; it regresses early in development to allow the carotid axis to take its definitive appearance.

name: acinus of exocrine gland
description: An acinus that is part of a exocrine gland.

name: branchiostegal ray series
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of the branchiostegal rays within an individual.

name: zygote stage
description: A stage at which the organism is a single cell produced by means of sexual reproduction.

name: internal naris
description: A naris that is located inside the nasal cavity and connects to the pharynx.

name: vertebral canal
description: A conduit enclosed within the vertebral foramen of the vertebrae through which the spinal cord passes.

name: sublaminar layers S1 or S2
description: One of sublaminar layers S1 or S2.

name: posterior meningeal artery
description: The posterior meningeal artery are small vessels which are branches of the ascending pharyngeal artery which supply the dura mater. It passes through the mastoid foramen before entering the cranium via the jugular foramen.

name: obsolete supracoracoid nerve foramen
description: Opening for the supracoracoid nerve in the supracoracoid.

name: nipple sheath
description: A circular ingrowth of the epidermis around the region of the mammary sprout[GO].

name: right ventricle myocardium
description: A myocardium that is part of a right ventricle of a heart.

name: pronephric nephron tubule
description: The pronephric nephron tubule is an epithelial tube that is part of the pronephric nephron and connects the filtration unit (glomerulus or glomus) of the pronephros to the pronephric duct[GO].

name: supracleithrum
description: Dermal bone that articulates dorsally with the posttemporal and ventrally with the cleithrum. Supracleithrum is part of the secondary pectoral girdle and commonly, carries part of the lateral line canal.

name: muscle tissue of terminal part of digestive tract
description: Any muscle tissue of the distalmost portion of the digestive tract.

name: metanephric nephron epithelium
description: The metanephric nephron epithelium is a tissue that covers the surface of a nephron in the metanephros[GO].

name: dorsal column nucleus
description: A nucleus that contain secondary neurons of the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway, which carries fine touch and proprioceptive information from the body to the brain. Examples: gracile nucleus, cuneat nucleus, nucleus of Bishoff.

name: subcutaneous lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a hypodermis.

name: pulmonary alveolar duct
description: the respiratory conducting tubes distal to the respiratory bronchiole that lead to the alveolar sacs and the alveoli

name: atrium auricular region
description: A small conical pouch projections located on the upper anterior portion of each atrium of the heart.

name: abdominal segment muscle
description: A muscle organ that is part of an abdominal segment of trunk [Automatically generated definition].

name: limb joint
description: Any joint that is part of a (free) limb.

name: parietal pleura
description: The outer serous membrane of the pulmonary pleural.

name: mucosa of trigone of urinary bladder
description: A mucosa that is part of a trigone of urinary bladder [Automatically generated definition].

name: thoracic cavity
description: The part of the coelemic cavity lumen that is enclosed by the walls of the thorax.

name: epicranial aponeurosis
description: The galea aponeurotica (epicranial aponeurosis, aponeurosis epicranialis) is a tough layer of dense fibrous tissue which covers the upper part of the cranium; behind, it is attached, in the interval between its union with the Occipitales, to the external occipital protuberance and highest nuchal lines of the occipital bone; in front, it forms a short and narrow prolongation between its union with the Frontales. On either side it gives origin to the Auriculares anterior and superior; in this situation it loses its aponeurotic character, and is continued over the temporal fascia to the zygomatic arch as a layer of laminated areolar tissue. It is closely connected to the integument by the firm, dense, fibro-fatty layer which forms the superficial fascia of the scalp: it is attached to the pericranium by loose cellular tissue, which allows the aponeurosis, carrying with it the integument to move through a considerable distance.

name: lung
description: Respiration organ that develops as an oupocketing of the esophagus.

name: ramus auricularis of the vagus nerve
description: An afferent branch of the vagus nerve.

name: carotid sinus
description: A localized dilation of the internal carotid artery at its origin, the common carotid artery bifurcation.

name: germ layer
description: A layer of cells produced during the process of gastrulation during the early development of the animal embryo, which is distinct from other such layers of cells, as an early step of cell differentiation. The three types of germ layers are the endoderm, ectoderm, and mesoderm.

name: embryonic tissue
description: A portion of tissue that is part of an embryo.

name: muscle layer of intestine
description: A muscle layer that is part of an intestine.

name: humeroulnar joint
description: The humeroulnar joint, is part of the elbow-joint or the Olecron Joint, between the ulna and humerus bones is the simple hinge-joint, which allows for movements of flexion, extension and circumduction. The Humero-Ulnar Joint is the junction of trochlear notch of the ulna and the trochlea of the humerus. Owing to the obliquity of the trochlea of the humerus, this movement does not take place in the antero-posterior plane of the body of the humerus. When the forearm is extended and supinated, the axis of the arm and forearm are not in the same line; the arm forms an obtuse angle with the forearm. During flexion, however, the forearm and the hand tend to approach the middle line of the body, and thus enable the hand to be easily carried to the face. The accurate adaptation of the trochlea of the humerus, with its prominences and depressions, to the semilunar notch of the ulna, prevents any lateral movement. Flexion is produced by the action of the Biceps brachii and Brachialis, assisted by the Brachioradialis, with a tiny contribution from the muscles arising from the medial epicondyle of the humerus. Extension is produced by the Triceps brachii and AnconC&us, with a tiny contribution from the muscles arising from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus, such as the Extensor digitorum communis.

name: transverse process-bearing vertebra
description: A vertebra that has a transverse process.

name: pyloric gastric gland
