description: The spino-olivary tract is located in the ventral funiculus of the spinal cord. This tract carries proprioception information from muscles and tendons as well as cutaneous impulses to the olivary nucleus. [WP,unvetted].

name: apophysis proximalis
description: Swelling on the extensor surface of the proximal compound head of the tibiale and fibulare.

name: obsolete regional part of spinal cord gray commissure
scale row
description: A series of scales in alignment with each other along some axis of the body. [PHENOSCAPE:bf].

name: posttemporal fossa
description: Fossa where the exoccipital forms the medial portion and the epioccipital forms the lateral margin. The posttemporal fossa in most species has two openings separated by the epioccipital bridge.

name: levator anguli oris
description: The levator anguli oris (caninus) is a facial muscle of the mouth arising from the canine fossa, immediately below the infraorbital foramen. Its fibers are inserted into the angle of the mouth, intermingling with those of the Zygomaticus, Triangularis, and Orbicularis oris.

name: premaxilla ascending process
description: Process of the premaxilla that extends posteriorly and overlays the mesethmoid.

name: supracoracoideus muscle of wing
description: A muscle in the bird's thorax region that originates from carina of the sternum, furcula, and sternal ribs and inserts onto proximal dorsal surface of the humerus. It acts as a primary elevator of the wing in upstroke. [Manual of Ornithology: Avian Structure and Function, by Proctor and Lynch, 1998].

name: arcuate fasciculus
description: The arcuate fasciculus (Latin, curved bundle) is the neural pathway connecting the posterior part of the temporoparietal junction with the frontal cortex in the brain and is now considered as part of the Superior longitudinal fasciculus.

name: olfactory nerve foramen
description: Foramen for the passage of the olfactory nerve or cranial nerve 1.

name: muscle layer of sigmoid colon
description: A muscle layer that is part of the sigmoid colon

name: internal arcuate fiber bundle
description: Internal arcuate fibers are the axons of second-order neurons contained within the gracile and cuneate nuclei of the medulla oblongata. These fibers cross from one side of the medulla to the other to form the medial lemniscus. Part of the dorsal column-medial lemniscus system (second neuron), the internal arcuate fibers are important for relaying the sensation of fine touch and proprioception to the thalamus and ultimately to the cerebral cortex.

name: posterior auricular muscle
description: The posterior auricular muscle consists of two or three fleshy fasciculi, which arise from the mastoid portion of the temporal bone by short aponeurotic fibers. They are inserted into the lower part of the cranial surface of the concha.

name: metacarpophalangeal joint of manual digit 5
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 5.

name: larval abdominal segment 8
description: Any abdominal segment 8 (UBERON:6000029) that is part of some larval abdomen (UBERON:6001746).

name: gastrointestinal system mucosa
description: A mucosa that is part of a gastrointestinal system.

name: bodily fluid
description: Liquid components of living organisms. includes fluids that are excreted or secreted from the body as well as body water that normally is not.

name: parvocellular reticular nucleus
description: The parvocellular reticular nucleus is part of the brain located dorsolateral to the nucleus reticularis pontis caudalis. The dorsal portion of the reticular nucleus has been shown to innervate the mesencephalic trigeminal nucleus and its surrounding area. Also, it projects to the facial nucleus, hypoglossal nucleus and parabrachial nucleus along with parts of the caudal parvocellular reticular formation. This nucleus is also involved in expiration with a part of the gigantocellular nucleus.

name: epithelium of hindgut
description: An epithelium that is part of a hindgut [Automatically generated definition].

name: priapium
description: A complex muscular and bony clasping and copulatory organ derived mainly from the pelvic fins, found under the head of male Phallostethoidea with the anus opening on one side and the genital pore on the other. The structure varies among family members. Hook-like ctenactia articulate basally with the aproctal axial which is movably articulated with the proctal axial bone itself, suspended anteriorly by the outer (and sometimes inner) pulvinular bone from the cleithrum and perhaps the urohyal. Other elements are the priapal ribs, the anteplural cartilage (supporting elements along with the cleithrum and the pulvinar), the toxactinium, the infrasulcar and the uncus (forming the claspers along with the ctenactinium), the penial, basipenial, papillary, prepapillary and cristate bones (forming the papillary unit).

name: longissimus muscle
description: The longissimus is the muscle lateral to the semispinalis. It is the longest subdivision of the sacrospinalis that extends forward into the transverse processes of the posterior cervical vertebrae. [WP,unvetted].

name: Press, Brewer, Dougherty, Wade and Wandell (2001) visuotopic area V7
unbarbed keratin-coated spine
description: A keratin-coated spine that is lacks a barbed end.

name: manual digit phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: amygdala
description: Subcortical brain region lying anterior to the hippocampal formation in the temporal lobe and anterior to the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle in some species. It is usually subdivided into several groups. Functionally, it is not considered a unitary structure (MM).

name: lobar bronchus of right lung
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a right lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: lobar bronchus of right lung middle lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a middle lobe of right lung.

name: intromittent organ (Ascaphus type)
description: A tail like posterior extension of the cloaca supported by a pair of Nobelian rods

name: supinator muscle
description: A muscle which originates on the distal humerus, inserts on the radius and accomplishes supination (rotation of the wrist).

name: left testicular vein
description: A vein that drains the right pampiniform plexus and empties into the inferior vena cava.

name: M. tibialis posticus
description: Originates on the entire medial surface of the shaft of the tibiofibula. Inserts on the tibiale by a long tendon proximo-lateral to the insertion of the medial belly of M. tibialis anticus longus.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 16
description: Brodmann area 16 is a subdivision of the cerebral cortex of the guenon defined on the basis of cytoarchitecture. It is a relatively undifferentiated cortical area that Brodmann regarded as part of the insula because of the relation of its innermost multiform layer (VI) with the claustrum (VICl). The laminar organization of cortex is almost totally lacking. The molecular layer (I) is wide as in area 15 of Brodmann-1905. The space between layer I and layer VI is composed of a mixture of pyramidal cells and spindle cells with no significant number of granule cells. Pyramidal cells clump in the outer part to form glomeruli similar to those seen in some of the primary olfactory areas (Brodmann-1905). This term also refers to an area known as peripaleocortical claustral - a cytoarchitecturally defined (agranular) portion of the insula at its rostral extreme where it approaches most closely the claustrum and the prepyriform area (Stephan-76).

name: peroneus
description: One of a group of three muscles fibularis (peron√¶us) longus, brevis, and tertius originating on the fibula and inserting on the metatarsals

name: medial geniculate body
description: Nuclear complex of the thalamus situated on the caudal, subpial aspect of the thalamus (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 3rd ed., 1981, pg 622).

name: pelvic axillary process
description: Anatomical cluster consisting of only a bony element or a combination of a bony element and one or more scales, or only modified scales, which lies in a fin fold at the base of the uppermost ray.

name: manual digit phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit mesenchyme.

name: cud
description: A bolus of semi-degraded food regurgitated from the reticulorumen of a ruminant, produced during the physical digestive process of rumination

name: obsolete T cell
description: A type of lymphocyte whose defining characteristic is the expression of a T cell receptor complex.

name: sclerotome somite 4
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: supraglottic part of larynx
description: The upper part of the larynx, including the epiglottis; the area above the vocal cords.

name: copulatory lymph heart
description: A lymph heart that assists in the return of lymph from the penis to the venous system

name: superficial inguinal lymph node
description: A group of 12-20 lymph nodes that lie in the subcutaneous tissue below the inguinal ligament and along the terminal part of the great saphenous vein; they drain the skin and subcutaneous tissue of the lower abdominal wall, perineum, buttocks, external genitalia, and lower limbs.

name: thoracic vertebral foramen
description: A vertebral foramen that is part of a thoracic vertebra.

name: sclerotome somite 30
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: left clavicle
description: A clavicle that is in the left side of a entire appendicular skeleton.

name: right umbilical vein
description: An umbilical vein that is in the right side of a multicellular organism.

name: autopod skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a autopod region.

name: sex cord
description: Cordlike masses of epithelial tissue that invaginate from germinal epithelium of the gonad and give rise to seminiferous tubules and rete testes in the male, and primary ovarian follicles and rete ovarii in the female.

name: uterine epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a uterus.

name: superficial white layer of superior colliculus
description: superficial white matter layer of superior collilculus that consists mainly of axions from the optic nerve.

name: pelvic ligament
description: The dorsal sacroiliac, the sacrotuberal and/or the iliolumbar ligaments associated with the bony ring formed by the pair of hip bones fused at the symphysis and their firm articulation with the sacrum

name: heart endothelium
description: An endothelium that is part of a heart [Automatically generated definition].

name: lumen of central nervous system
description: The cavity that is enclosed by the central nervous system. In vertebrates this is the cavity that includes as parts ventricular cavities and the central canal of the spinal cord that develops from the lumen of the neura tube

name: muscle tissue
description: Muscle tissue is a contractile tissue made up of actin and myosin fibers[GO].

name: sulcus dentalis of premaxilla
description: Groove located between the pars dentalis and the bases of the premaxillary teeth.

name: caudalipuboischiotibialis
description: Muscle that is associated with tail flexion. Orginates on one of the first post sacral vertebrae posteriorly and inserts on the posterior edge of the m.puboischiotibialis. (modified from Duellman and Trueb 1994)

name: presumptive ganglion
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a ganglion.

name: caudal-sacral region of vertebral column
description: Subdivision of vertebral column that is posterior to the sacral region and anterior to the caudal region.

name: anal canal epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a anal canal.

name: primary visual cortex
description: A subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined occipital region of cerebral cortex in the human. Defined by the band of Gennari, which gives it the name striate (furrowed) area, it occupies the banks of the calcarine sulcus which are located in the cuneus and the lingual gyrus of the occipital lobe. Cytoarchitecturally it is bounded by the area 18 of Brodmann (human) which surrounds it ( Brodmann-1909 ). In the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ) and the rat ( Swanson-1998 ) it is located on the dorsolateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere[BrainInfo].

name: portal vein
description: A vein that conducts blood from the digestive organs, spleen, pancreas, and gallbladder to the liver[BTO].

name: vertebra pre-cartilage condensation
description: The pre-cartilaginous form of a vertebral element, a skeletal element that forms around the notochord and is part of the vertebral column.

name: anterior lateral line
description: The anterior lateral line consists of small sensory patches (neuromasts) located superficially on the skin or just under the skin in fluid-filled canals on the head of all fishes and most amphibians. The anterior lateral line develops from cranial ectodermal placodes situated between the eye and ear.

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between digits 2 and 3
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between digits 2 and 3.

name: skin epidermis
description: The outer epithelial layer of the skin that is superficial to the dermis.

name: mylohyoid nerve
description: A nerve that innervates the mylohyoid muscle and the anterior belly of the digastric muscle.

name: head segment
description: Any segment that is part of some head.

name: optic chiasma
description: A decussation of the diencephalon where the fibers of the optic nerve cross

name: silk gland
description: Any of the glands in silk-spinning insects and spiders that secrete a protein liquid that hardens into silk on exposure to air.

name: ceratobranchial 5 cartilage
description: Ceratobranchial cartilage that is the most posterior, bilaterally paired ventral pharyngeal arch cartilage.

name: left ear
description: The organ of hearing located on the left side of the head[ncit,modified].

name: eyelid subcutaneous connective tissue
description: A eyelid connective tissue that is part of a hypodermis.

name: premotor cortex
description: The premotor cortex is an area of motor cortex lying within the frontal lobe of the brain. It extends 3 mm anterior to the primary motor cortex, near the Sylvian fissure, before narrowing to approximately 1 mm near the medial longitudinal fissure, which serves as the posterior border for the prefrontal cortex. The premotor cortex is largely equivalent to Brodmann area 6. Activity within this region is critical to the sensory guidance of movement and control of proximal and trunk muscles of the body.

name: fin
description: An external projection of an aquatic animal as a fish used in propelling or guiding the body[BTO].

name: vertebral element 3
description: Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 2.

name: hippocampus stratum lacunosum moleculare
description: Layer of the hippocampus lying just superficial to the stratum radiatum and bounded by the pial surface of the hippocampus. The fibers of the perforant pathway fibers from entorhinal cortex and several other brain areas terminate in this layer. Adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 460)

name: premaxilla articular process
description: Pharyngeal arch bone immediately posterior to the ascending process, the medial surface of which articulates with the anterior end of the maxillary.

name: presumptive forebrain midbrain boundary
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a forebrain-midbrain boundary.

name: root of olfactory nerve
description: The initial segment of an olfactory nerve, leaving the central nervous system.

name: pectoral fin proximal radial cartilage
description: pectoral fin proximal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: trigeminal placode complex
description: A neurogenic placode that arises at the level of the midbrain-hindbrain boundary and develops into a trigeminal ganglion.

name: right branch of atrioventricular bundle
description: The right branch of the atrioventricular bundle that separates just below the bundle of His, descends the septal wall of the right ventricle and connects to the terminal Purkinje fibers[MP].

name: instar larval stage
description: This begins with the newly hatched first-instar larva, through its maturation to the end of the last larval stage. An example of this process is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

name: chondroid tissue
description: Skeletal tissue that is mineralized, has large chondrocyte-like cells, sparse extracellular matrix, and minimal perichondrium; develops from non-mineralized chondroid tissue.

name: hindlimb digital artery
description: A digital artery that is part of a hindlimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of pedal digit 3
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of pedal digit 3.

name: proximal metaphysis
description: A metaphysis that is in the proximal side of a diaphysis.

name: venous plexus
description: A congregation of multiple veins.

name: pharyngeal arch artery 4
description: The vessels formed within the fourth pair of branchial arches in embryogenesis

name: obsolete regional part of posterior superior frontal sulcus
intestine
description: Segment of the alimentary canal extending from the stomach to the anus and, in humans and other mammals, consists of two segments, the small intestine and the large intestine.

name: rib 5
description: The fifth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: sweat gland
description: any of the coil glands of the skin that secrete sweat

name: proximal epiphysis of third metatarsal bone
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a metatarsal bone of digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: trochlear nerve
description: A cranial nerve that runs to the eye muscles.

name: obsolete rhinencephalon
description: The olfactory region of the brain, located in the cerebrum.

name: terminal scale
description: The posteriormost scale in a scale series.[PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: talocalcaneonavicular joint
description: The talocalcaneonavicular articulation is an arthrodial joint: the rounded head of the talus being received into the concavity formed by the posterior surface of the navicular, the anterior articular surface of the calcaneus, and the upper surface of the plantar calcaneonavicular ligament. There are two ligaments in this joint: the articular capsule and the dorsal talonavicular.

name: intervertebral joint
description: The joint between adjacent vertebral bodies. May be composed of the nucleus pulposus, annular ligament, and the anterior and posterior longitudinal ligaments.

name: ligament
description: Dense regular connective tissue connecting two or more adjacent skeletal elements or supporting an organ.

name: ventral keel of coracoid
description: Process on the ventral surface of the horizontal limb of the coracoid, close to and parallel to the coracoid-cleithrum joint. Ventral keel of coracoid is paired.

name: hind flipper
description: Hindlimb that is used to propel an animal through water.

name: ligament of liver
description: A nonskeletal ligament that is part of a liver.

name: centrum 4
description: Centrum that is part of vertebra 4.

name: skin of manus
description: A zone of skin that is part of a manus [Automatically generated definition].

name: olfactory tract linking bulb to ipsilateral dorsal telencephalon
spinal cord lateral motor column
description: Column of motor neurons which innervate muscles in the limb; motor neurons in the lateral motor column are further organized into pools, each of which innervates a specific muscle in the limb

name: posthypocrista
description: A crest on the hypoconid of molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/)

name: incisive canal
description: One of several bony canals leading from the floor of the nasal cavity into the incisive fossa on the palatal surface of the maxilla; they convey the nasopalatine nerves and branches of the greater palatine arteries that anastomose with the septal branch of the sphenopalatine artery.

name: dermal bone
description: Skeletal element that forms superficially in the organism, usually in association with the ectoderm[VSAO].

name: forehead
description: The part of the face above the eyes[MESH]. In human anatomy, the forehead is the fore part of the head. It is, formally, an area of the head bounded by three features, two of the skull and one of the scalp. The top of the forehead is marked by the hairline, the edge of the area where hair on the scalp grows. The bottom of the forehead is marked by the supraorbital ridge, the bone feature of the skull above the eyes. The two sides of the forehead are marked by the temporal ridge, a bone feature that links the supraorbital ridge to the coronal suture line and beyond[WP].

name: ruminant esophageal groove
description: A muscular structure at the lower end of the esophagus that, when closed, forms a tube allowing milk to go directly into the abomasum. (This prevents milk from being fermented or soured by the ruminal microorganisms).

name: oviduct mucosal fold
description: The wall of the fallopian tube includes an elaborately folded mucosa (endosalpinx) surrounded by a muscularis (myosalpinx). The mucosa is lined by a ciliated columnar epithelium with secretory cells, and is folded out into the lumen so that an ovum in the lumen will always be close to the cilia for transport to the uterus.

name: cervical spinal cord
description: A spinal cord segment that adjacent_to a cervical region.

name: cochlear modiolus
description: the central cone shaped core of spongy bone about which turns the spiral canal

name: digit 6 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 6 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: trunk connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a trunk [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric ascending thin limb
description: The metanephric ascending thin limb is a segment of a nephron tubule in the metanephros lying in the inner medulla that is permeable to ions but not to water and has a simple epithelium; active transepithelial solute transport is absent[GO].

name: blood vessel external elastic membrane
description: A thin layer of fibrous tissue capable of stretching and contracting. It is part of the tunica media of the blood vessels.

name: fastigial nucleus
description: the most medial of the cerebellar nuclei; it receives its afferent input from Purkinje cells of the flocculonodular lobe and the vermis, and most of its efferent connections travel via the inferior cerebellar peduncle to the vestibular nuclei and to the medullary reticular formation

name: hepatoduodenal ligament
description: The hepatoduodenal ligament is the portion of the lesser omentum extending between the porta hepatis of the liver and the superior part of the duodenum.

name: manual digit 3 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a hand digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: pectoral fin ray 3
description: Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the third most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.

name: paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus magnocellular division - posterior magnocellular part lateral zone
urethral crest
description: A longitudinal mucosal fold in the dorsal wall of the urethra[MP]

name: nerve fasciculus
description: A slender neuron projection bundle[FBbt]; A bundle of anatomical fibers, as of muscle or nerve (American Heritage Dictionary 4th ed).

name: musculoskeletal system
description: Anatomical system that consists of the muscular and skeletal systems.

name: hindbrain
description: The most posterior of the three principal regions of the brain. In mammals and birds the hindbrain is divided into a rostral metencephalon and a caudal myelencephalon. In zebrafish, with the exception of the cerebellum, the ventral remainder of the metencephalon can be separated only arbitrarily from the more caudal myelencephalic portion of the medulla oblongata (From: Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain)[ZFA]. Organ component of neuraxis that has as its parts the pons, cerebellum and medulla oblongata[FMA].

name: ramus hyomandibularis
description: The posttrematic branch of the facial nerve, both motor and sensory in function.

name: rugal fold
description: A ridge or fold, such as the rugae of the stomach, which are large folds in the mucous membrane of that organ.

name: presumptive mesencephalic artery
description: precursor to mesencephalic artery

name: serosa of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A serous membrane that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.

name: suspensory ligament
description: A ligament that supports a body part, especially an organ.

name: nucleus of phrenic nerve
description: neuron cell bodies located in the more medial portions of the anterior horn at cervical levels C3-C7 that innervate the diaphragm via the phrenic nerve.

name: piriform cortex layer 1b
description: Deeper part of the plexiform (layer 1) of piriform cortex characterized by projection of association fibers from other parts of the piriform cortex and other olfactory areas

name: lateral part of mediodorsal nucleus of the thalamus
inferior pharyngeal constrictor
description: The inferior pharyngeal constrictor, the thickest of the three constrictors, arises from the sides of the cricoid and thyroid cartilage. Similarly to the superior and middle pharyngeal constrictor muscles, it is innervated by the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X), specifically, by branches from the pharyngeal plexus and by neuronal branches from the recurrent laryngeal nerve. [WP,unvetted].

name: outflow tract pericardium
description: A pericardium that is part of a outflow tract [Automatically generated definition].

name: paired fin skeleton
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in a single paired fin.

name: hilum of kidney
description: An opening on medial margin of the kidney leading into the renal sinus. he renal vessels enter/leave the kidney at the hilum; the renal pelvis leaves the kidney at the hilum.

name: primary choana
description: initial opening of the nasal pits and olfactory sac of the embryo into the rostral part of the primordial oronasal cavity, before the formation of the secondary palate.

name: anterior nucleus of hypothalamus central part
obsolete extracellular matrix
description: Combination of protein fibers, ground substance and tissue fluid; typically has embedded cells.

name: rhombomere 5 floor plate
description: A rhombomere floor plate that is part of a rhombomere 5.

name: medial longitudinal fasciculus of pons
description: A medial longitudinal fasciculus that is part of a pons [Automatically generated definition].

name: middle phalanx of manual digit 4
description: A middle phalanx that is part of a hand digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: terminal nerve root
description: A nerve root that extends_fibers_into a terminal nerve.

name: His-Purkinje system
description: The His-Purkinje system receives signals from the AV node and is composed of the fibers that regulate cardiac muscle contraction in the ventricles

name: femoral vein
description: In the human body, the femoral vein is a blood vessel that accompanies the femoral artery in the femoral sheath. It begins at the adductor canal (also known as Hunter's canal) and is a continuation of the popliteal vein. It ends at the inferior margin of the inguinal ligament, where it becomes the external iliac vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: portal system
description: In the circulatory system of animals, a portal venous system occurs when a capillary bed drains into another capillary bed through veins, without first going through the heart. Both capillary beds and the blood vessels that connect them are considered part of the portal venous system. They are relatively uncommon as the majority of capillary beds drain into veins which then drain into the heart, not into another capillary bed. Portal venous systems are considered venous because the blood vessels that join the two capillary beds are either veins or venules. Examples of such systems include the hepatic portal system and the hypophyseal portal system. Unqualified, 'portal venous system' often refers to the hepatic portal system. For this reason, 'portal vein' most commonly refers to the hepatic portal vein[WP].

name: antorbital fenestra
description: An antorbital fenestra is an opening in the skull, in front of the eye sockets. This skull formation first appeared in archosaurs during the Triassic Period. Living birds today possess antorbital fenestrae, but the feature has been lost in modern crocodilians. In some archosaur species, the opening has closed but its location is still marked by a depression, or fossa, on the surface of the skull. This is called an antorbital fossa.

name: right renal artery
description: Renal artery that supplies the right kidney

name: iliac peduncle of the pubis
description: Bony projection that is part of the dorsal surface of the pubis where it meets the ilium.

name: glossopharyngeal nerve foramen
description: Foramen for the passage of the glossopharyngeal nerve IX. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: anterior horizontal limb of lateral sulcus
agger limitans anterior of ilium
description: Shelf-like expansion of the ilial corpus that forms the anterior border of the acetabulum.

name: adrenal medulla
description: the inner portion of the adrenal gland that consists mainly of chromaffin cells which produce, store and secrete neurotransmitters such as epinephrine and norepinephrine

name: zygomaticomaxillary suture
description: A suture between the zygomatic bone and the zygomatic process of the maxilla.

name: palatoquadrate element
description: Endochondral element that is part of the suspensorium sometimes ossifying distally as the quadrate bone and linking the basal section of the braincase to the lower jaw.

name: accessory vomerine tooth plate
description: Dermal bone that is located lateral to vomer off midline of palate. Accessory vomerine tooth plate bears teeth and may be present as one or more pairs.

name: apophysis distalis of tibiale fibulare
description: Swelling on the extensor surface of the distal compound head of the tibiale and fibulare.

name: male external urethral sphincter
description: The external sphincter muscle of urethra (or sphincter urethrae membranaceae) surrounds the whole length of the membranous portion of the urethra, and is enclosed in the fasci√¶ of the urogenital diaphragm. They arch across the front of the urethra and bulbourethral glands, pass around the urethra, and behind it unite with the muscle of the opposite side, by means of a tendinous raph√©.

name: medial pelvic process
description: Process that is posteriorly oriented and medially located on the basipterygium. It is a paired projection. [PHENOSCAPE:bf]

name: anterior dorsomedial process of autopalatine
description: In cypriniforms the anterior portion of the palatine has a dorsomedial process which abuts against the mesethmoid. Such a process is not present in other ostariophysans or in other primitive teleosts.

name: bronchial lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a bronchus.

name: hyomandibular bone
description: Replacement bone that is bilaterally paired and (in teleosts) articulates with the neurocranium dorsally and the opercle posteriorly[TAO,modified].

name: articular bone
description: Endochondral bone that is located posterior to the dentary, medial to the angular and antero-dorsal to the retroarticular forming the lower jaw. The articular bears a dorso-posterior articular facet for the condyle of the quadrate. The articular is a paired bone.

name: os clitoris
description: The ossified region of endochondral and membranous bone located in the clitoris of most mammals except humans; it is homologous to the penile bone (aka as baculum, penis bone or os penis) in male mammals

name: otic sensory canal
description: Sensory canal between and in close proximity posteriorly with the post-otic and preoperculo-mandibular sensory canals, and anteriorly with the supraorbital and infraorbital sensory canals. The otic sensory canal is bilaterally paired.

name: mouth-foregut junction
description: An anatomical junctions that overlaps the mouth and foregut.

name: Hensen stripe
description: The dark, nonstriated, V-shaped band (ridge) found on the underside of the tectorial membrane in the basal region of the cochlea, from which fine gelatinous trabeculae extend to fix the TM to the border cells, i.e. cells directly adjacent to the inner phalangeal cells.

name: inferior parietal cortex
description: Component of the parietal lobe. The inferior parietal cortex label includes the inferior parietal gyrus and the angular gyrus and lies inferior to the superior parietal gyrus. The rostral and caudal boundaries were the supramarginal gyrus and the parieto-occipital incisure respectively. The medial and lateral boundaries were the superior parietal gyrus and the middle temporal gyrus respectively (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: muscle layer of rectum
description: A muscle layer that is part of the rectum

name: dorsal hair
description: A strand of hair that is part of a dorsum.

name: larval abdominal segment 9
description: Any abdominal segment 9 (UBERON:6000030) that is part of some larval abdomen (UBERON:6001746).

name: urethra urothelium
description: An urothelium that is part of a urethra [Automatically generated definition].

name: pedal digit skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a toe [Automatically generated definition].

name: plantar digital vein
description: The plantar digital veins arise from plexuses on the plantar surfaces of the digits, and, after sending intercapitular veins to join the dorsal digital veins, unite to form four metatarsal veins.

name: epithelium of rectum
description: An epithelium that is part of a rectum [Automatically generated definition].

name: tuberal supraoptic nucleus
description: Posterior division of the supraoptic nucleus, formed by the ascension of the optic tract splitting the nucleus into two regions. The tuberal SON lies along the posterior tuber cinereum of the hypothalamus. In some species, some neurons lie under the optic chiasm.

name: esophageal hiatus
description: A hole in the diaphragm through which the esophagus passes

name: os priapium
description: Bone of the priapium.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 44
description: Brodmann area 44, or BA44, is part of the frontal cortex in the human brain. Situated just anterior to premotor cortex and on the lateral surface, inferior to BA9. This area is also known as pars opercularis (of the inferior frontal gyrus), and it refers to a subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined frontal region of cerebral cortex. In the human it corresponds approximately to the opercular part of inferior frontal gyrus (H). Thus, it is bounded caudally by the inferior precentral sulcus (H) and rostrally by the anterior ascending limb of lateral sulcus (H). It surrounds the diagonal sulcus (H). In the depth of the lateral sulcus it borders on the insula. Cytoarchitectonically it is bounded caudally and dorsally by the agranular frontal area 6, dorsally by the granular frontal area 9 and rostrally by the triangular area 45 (Brodmann-1909).

name: Ongur, Price, and Ferry (2003) prefrontal cortical partition scheme region
muscularis orbicularis
description: A fringe of muscle running along the periphery of the panniculus.

name: manual digit 1 phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit 1 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: medial septal nucleus
description: Cells lying generally in front of Regional_part_of_septal_nuclei, lying ventral to and slightly medial to the lateral septal nucleus. Neurons in this nucleus give rise to the bulk of efferents from the septal nuclei. A major projection from the medial septal nucleus terminates in the hippocampal formation (Adapted from Brodal, 1981).

name: lobar bronchus of left lung
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a left lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: cavity of right ventricle
description: Luminal space of the right ventricle of the heart.

name: epithelium of elbow
description: An epithelium that is part of a elbow [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior parahippocampal gyrus
description: The part of the parahippocampal gyrus that includes the perirhinal and entorhinal cortices.

name: primitive prosencephalic artery
description: Vessel that branches from cranial division of the internal carotid artery, extending laterally around the rostral end of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: pleuroperitoneal membrane
description: A fold of tissue which extends into the peritoneal cavity of the developing embryo and participates in the separation of the pleural and peritoneal cavities.

name: preoptic area
description: Area of the forebrain between the anterior commissure and optic chiasm.

name: islands of Calleja of olfactory tubercle
description: Part of olfactory tubercle defined by dense aggregations of granule cells

name: pectoral axillary process
description: Pectoral axillary process is an elongate structure formed by one or more additional postcleithra or modified scales or a combination of both, that is firmly attached to a skin fold above the articular condyle of the uppermost pectoral fin ray or lepidotrichium 1.

name: dental comb
description: A dental structure found in some mammals, comprising a group of front teeth arranged in a manner that facilitates grooming.

name: obsolete thymocyte
description: An immature T cell located in the thymus.

name: sclerotome somite 7
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: zygomaticotemporal nerve
description: The zygomaticotemporal nerve or zygomaticotemporal branch (temporal branch) is derived from the maxillary branch of the trigeminal nerve (Cranial nerve V). It runs along the lateral wall of the orbit in a groove in the zygomatic bone, receives a branch of communication from the lacrimal, and passes through zygomaticotemporal foramen in the zygomatic bone to enter the temporal fossa. It ascends between the bone, and substance of the Temporalis muscle, pierces the temporal fascia about 2.5 cm. above the zygomatic arch, and is distributed to the skin of the side of the forehead, and communicates with the facial nerve and with the auriculotemporal branch of the mandibular nerve. As it pierces the temporal fascia, it gives off a slender twig, which runs between the two layers of the fascia to the lateral angle of the orbit.

name: primary superior olive
description: Part of the superior olivary complex of nuclei in the caudal pontine tegmentum, situated within the trapezoid body in humans. (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 3rd edition, 1981, pg 617). In many species, it comprises a medial superior olivary nucleus and a lateral superior olivary nucleus.

name: M. cruralis
description: Originates from the anterior surface of the hip joint capsule between the iliacus internus and the pectineus. Inserts by an aponeurosis attaching to the condyles of the femur and on the head of the cruris. This continues over the cruris to cover the tibialis anticus longus and peroneus to insert on the dorsal surface of those muscles.

name: cytotrophoblast
description: The inner layer of the trophoblast, interior to the syncytiotrophoblast in an embryo. It serves to anchor the embryonic chorion to the maternal endometrium. Cytotrophoblasts are stem cells in the chorionic villi. During differentiation, mononuclear cytotrophoblast fuse together into the multinucleated syncytiotrophoblasts. The primary villi has only the cytotrophoblast as an axe. [WP,unvetted].

name: lateral fornix of vagina
description: The vaginal fornix that is to the side of the cervix.

name: lateral line canal lumen
description: Anatomical space that contains a portion of the lateral line system.

name: lumbar vertebral arch
description: A neural arch that is part of a lumbar vertebra.

name: sclerotome somite 6
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: radial sesamoid
description: In the giant panda, a large digitlike preaxial element that articulates with the scapholunatum and the medial border of the first metacarpal.

name: right vitelline vein
description: A vitelline vein that is in the right side of a multicellular organism.

name: digit connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a digit.

name: ovary sex cord
description: structures that develop from sex cords in the female. After further development they become the ovarian follicles.

name: buccal mucosa
description: The inner lining of the cheeks and lips.

name: subarcuate fossa
description: The irregular depression found on the posterior inner surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone just below its crest and above and lateral to the internal acoustic meatus[MP].

name: rhombomere 7
description: the seventh transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

name: incisor enamel organ
description: A tooth enamel organ that is part of a incisor tooth.

name: superior frontal sulcus
description: The superior frontal sulcus is a sulcus between the superior frontal gyrus and the middle frontal gyrus. [WP,unvetted].

name: forelimb zeugopod
description: The middle limb segment of the pectoral free limb, between the autopod and stylopod segments. Includes as parts the forelimb zeugopodial skeleton, which includes as parts the radius and ulna, or their cartilage precursors, or evolutionary variants.

name: sulcus for Meckels cartilage
description: A groove on the palatoquadrate that is occupied by the Meckel's cartilage.

name: posterior auricular vein
description: The posterior auricular vein begins upon the side of the head, in a plexus which communicates with the tributaries of the occipital vein and superficial temporal veins. It descends behind the auricula, and joins the posterior division of the posterior facial vein to form the external jugular. It receive the stylomastoid vein, and some tributaries from the cranial surface of the auricula.

name: clavicle blade
description: Expanded and flattened ventral region of clavicle bone.

name: cerebellum globose nucleus
description: The two or three small masses of gray matter that is located medial to the emboliform nucleus and lateral to the fastigial nucleus; it receives axons from the intermediate area of the cerebellar hemispheres and its afferents exit through the superior cerebellar peduncle.

name: fissura sagittalis
description: Medial groove in the longitudinal ridge of the urostyle formed by the incomplete dorsal fusion of the caudal neural arches.

name: smooth muscle tissue layer of ejaculatory duct
description: A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a ejaculatory duct.

name: cerebral hemisphere white matter
description: White matter that is part of a cerebral hemisphere.

name: lacrimal nerve
description: The lacrimal nerve is the smallest of the three branches of the ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve.

name: posterior lateral line system
description: The posterior lateral line system develops from cranial ectodermal placodes, situated behind the ear, that give rise to both the neuromasts and the posterior lateral line sensory nerves that innervate the neuromasts. The posterior lateral line system consists of small sensory patches (neuromasts) located superficially on the skin or just under the skin in fluid-filled canals on the head of all fishes and most amphibians. The neuromasts are innervated by several lateral line nerves, which project primarily to the hindbrain. The posterior mechanosensory lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance.

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between digits 3 and 4
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between digits 3 and 4.

name: respiratory system
description: Functional system which consists of structures involved in respiration.

name: preputial gland
description: A aired, lobulated, modified sebaceous glands located in the inguinal region adjacent to the penis and vagina, with pheromonal functions in male rodents; in males, the preputial gland empties into the preputial cavity and in females, the preputial (aka clitoral) gland duct empties into the clitoral fossa.

name: procephalic segment
description: A segment that is anterior to the gnathal segments.

name: cuboidal oviduct epithelium
description: A cuboidal epithelium that is part of a oviduct.

name: Verson's gland
description: A gland found in the larvae of lepidoptera. Each gland is made of three cells: the secretory cell, the reservoir cell and the canal cell.

name: hypobranchial cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial cartilage or bone.

name: axilla
description: The axilla is the area directly under the joint where the forelimb connects to the shoulder.

name: white matter of forebrain
description: A white matter that is part of the forebrain.

name: eye
description: An organ that detects light.

name: anterior surface of prostate
description: The aspect of the prostate facing the pubic symphysis.

name: trigeminal nuclear complex
description: The sensory trigeminal nerve nuclei are the largest of the cranial nerve nuclei, and extend through the whole of the midbrain, pons and medulla. There is also a distinct trigeminal motor nucleus that is medial to the chief sensory nucleus[WP].

name: interarcual bone
description: Pharyngeal arch bone located between uncinate process of epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2.

name: body of fornix
description: Part of fornix adjacent to the crura where they join together at the midline underneath the corpus callosum

name: presumptive rhombomere 1
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 1.

name: pectoral fin distal radial cartilage
description: pectoral fin distal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: interdigital region between manual digits 3 and 4
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a manual digit 3 and adjacent_to a manual digit 4.

name: eye primordium
description: Portion of tissue that is part of the anterior neural keel and will form the optic vesicle[ZFA]. A paired ectodermal placode that becomes invaginated to form the embryonic lens vesicles.

name: atrium myocardial trabecula
description: The supporting bundles of muscular fibers lining the walls of the atrial myocardium

name: neuromere
description: A transverse unitary subdivision of the neural tube that shares a common dorsoventral structure (floor, basal, alar, and roof plates), but each having differential molecular identities and fates; they comprise the secondary prosencephalon, diencephalon (prosomeres), the midbrain (mesomeres), and the hindbrain (rhombomeres).

name: lacrimal canaliculus
description: The part of the lacrimal duct that connects the lacrimal punctum to the lacrimal sac.

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of pedal digit 4
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of pedal digit 4.

name: distal epiphysis
description: An epiphysis that is on the distal side of the bone.

name: azygos vein
description: An unpaired vein which in humans arises from the right ascending lumbar vein or the vena cava, enters the thorax through the aortic orifice in the diaphragm, and terminates in the superior vena cava; unlike humans, mice have a single and left-sided azygos vein that develops from the paired embryonic cardinal venous system and drains most of the right and left thoracic walls into the left anterior vena cava[MP].

name: mesocolic lymph node
description: A lymph node that located_in a colon.

name: pharyngeal arch artery 5
description: The vessels formed within the fifth pair of pharyngeal arches in embryogenesis.

name: medial precentral sulcus
description: A superficial feature of the frontal lobe that extends from the dorsal surface onto the medial surface of the superior frontal gyrus (Ono-90). (NN)

name: orifice
description: Anatomical conduit that connects two adjacent body spaces (or a body space with the space surrounding the organism)[FMA,modified].

name: rib 6
description: The sixth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: sebaceous gland
description: A holocrine gland that secretes sebum into the hair follicles, or in hairless areas into ducts.[MP].

name: trigeminal nerve
description: Cranial nerve that has three branches - the ophthalmic (supplying the skin of the nose and upper jaw), the maxillary and the mandibular (supplying the lower jaw).

name: fascia
description: A dense regular connective tissue that that connects muscles together[WP, modified].

name: parapophysis 3
description: Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the third centrum. Parapophysis 3 is bilaterally paired.[PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: calcaneocuboid joint
description: Calcaneocuboid Articulation (articulation of the calcaneus with the cuboid). The ligaments connecting the calcaneus with the cuboid are five in number, viz. , the articular capsule, the dorsal calcaneocuboid, part of the bifurcated, the long plantar, and the plantar calcaneocuboid.

name: sternoclavicular joint
description: The sternoclavicular articulation is a double arthrodial joint composed of two portions separated by an articular disc. The parts entering into its formation are the sternal end of the clavicle, the upper and lateral part of the manubrium sterni, and the cartilage of the first rib, visible from the outside as the suprasternal notch. The articular surface of the clavicle is much larger than that of the sternum, and is invested with a layer of cartilage, which is considerably thicker than that on the latter bone. The ligaments of this joint are: Articular capsule Anterior sternoclavicular ligament Posterior sternoclavicular ligament Interclavicular ligament Costoclavicular ligament Articular disk [WP,unvetted].

name: toilet claw
description: A specialized claw or nail on the foot of certain primates, used for personal grooming.

name: orbital foramen
description: Foramen in the bone or cartilage comprising the anterior wall of the orbit, and through which passes at least the deep ophthalmic branch of cranial nerve V (trigeminal).

name: secondary ovarian follicle
description: A maturing ovarian follicle that has two more more layers of granulosa cells, up to the onset of antrum formation.

name: laryngeal prominence
description: A zone of thyroid cartilage formed by fusion of the two plate-like laminae of the cartilages.

name: ossification center
description: The first step in ossification of the cartilage is that the cartilage cells, at the point where ossification is commencing and which is termed a ossification center, enlarge and arrange themselves in rows. The matrix in which they are imbedded increases in quantity, so that the cells become further separated from each other. A deposit of calcareous material now takes place in this matrix, between the rows of cells, so that they become separated from each other by longitudinal columns of calcified matrix, presenting a granular and opaque appearance. Here and there the matrix between two cells of the same row also becomes calcified, and transverse bars of calcified substance stretch across from one calcareous column to another. Thus there are longitudinal groups of the cartilage cells enclosed in oblong cavities, the walls of which are formed of calcified matrix which cuts off all nutrition from the cells; the cells, in consequence, atrophy, leaving spaces called the primary areolC&.

name: centrum 5
description: Centrum that is part of vertebra 5.

name: somite 23
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: cerebellopontine angle
description: Junction between the cerebellum and the pons.

name: precingulum
description: A shelf like ridge on the proximal (mesial) outside edge of the upper molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/)

name: cholinergic enteric nerve
description: nerve fibers that utilize acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter to the intestinal system

name: scute
description: A bony external plate or scale, as on the shell of a turtle, the skin of crocodilians, the feet of some birds. Scutes are similar to scales and serve the same function. Unlike the scales of fish and snakes, which are formed from the epidermis, scutes are formed in the lower vascular layer of the skin and the epidermal element is only the top surface. Forming in the living dermis, the scutes produce a horny outer layer, that is superficially similar to that of scales. Scutes will usually not overlap as snake scales (but see the pangolin). The outer keratin layer is shed piecemeal, and not in one continuous layer of skin as seen in snakes or lizards. The dermal base may contain bone and produce dermal armour. Scutes with a bony base are properly called osteoderms. Dermal scutes are also found in the feet of birds and tails of some mammals, and are believed to be the primitive form of dermal armour in reptiles. The term is also used to describe the heavy armour of the armadillo and the extinct glyptodon, and is occasionally used as an alternative to scales in describing snakes or certain fishes, such as sturgeons[WP].

name: interosseous muscle of pes
description: Any of the interosseous muscles of the pes (foot). Includes the plantar and dorsal interossei.

name: scaphium
description: Neural arch and Weberian ossicle that is reduced in size relative to other neural arches. Scaphium has a process which articulates with the first centrum.

name: parastyle
description: An anterior cusp on the stylar shelf of the tooth

name: osseus spiral lamina
description: The osseous spiral lamina is a bony shelf or ledge which projects from the modiolus into the interior of the canal, and, like the canal, takes two-and-three-quarter turns around the modiolus. It reaches about half-way toward the outer wall of the tube, and partially divides its cavity into two passages or scalae, of which the upper is named the scala vestibuli, while the lower is termed the scala tympani.

name: digit 7 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 7 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: limb connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a limb [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric cortical collecting duct
description: The metanephric cortical collecting duct is the portion of the metanephric collecting duct that resides in the renal cortex[GO].

name: exocrine system
description: Anatomical system that consists of the glands and parts of glands that produce exocrine secretions and help to integrate and control bodily metabolic activity. Exocrine glands are glands that secrete their products (hormones) into ducts (duct glands). They are the counterparts to endocrine glands, which secrete their products (hormones) directly into the bloodstream (ductless glands) or release hormones (paracrines) that affect only target cells nearby the release site. [Wikipedia].

name: lateral reticular nucleus
description: A nucleus of the lateral medullary nuclear complex.

name: oral cirrus
description: Small tentacle-like structure surrounding the mouth; they act as sensory devices and as a filter for the water passing into the body

name: upper vermilion
description: A vermilion that is part of a upper lip.

name: manual digit 4 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a hand digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: male urethral crest
description: narrow longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the male urethra, extending from the uvula of the bladder through the prostatic urethra; when distended, it may serve to prevent the passage of the semen backward into the bladder; on either side of the male urethral crest is a slightly depressed fossa, the prostatic sinus, the floor of which is perforated by the orifices of the prostatic ducts from the lateral lobes of the prostate; the ducts of the middle lobe open behind the crest; at the forepart of the crest, below its summit, is a median elevation, the colliculus seminalis, upon or within the margins of which are the orifices of the prostatic utricle and the slit-like openings of the ejaculatory ducts[MP]

name: lateral pretrosal artery
description: Part of the internal carotid which supplies blood to the ear and branches to two additional arteries.

name: manubrium of sternum
description: The cranial most segment of the sternum. Located ventrally with a quadrangular shape, wider superiorly and narrower inferiorly, it articulates with the clavicles and the first two ribs[MP,WP].

name: articular cartilage of joint
description: A thin layer of cartilage, usually hyaline, on the articular surface of bones in synovial joints.

name: epithelium of gall bladder
description: The simple columnar epithelial lining of the gall bladder.

name: hyolaryngeal complex
description: Complex formed by two units, the hyoid and laryngeal apparatuses, which are both derived from the larval hyobranchial skeleton.

name: rugal fold of stomach
description: A rugal fold that is part of a stomach.

name: autopod pad
description: pigmented, keratinised, hairless epidermis covering subcutaneous, collagenous, and adipose tissue.

name: gray matter of spinal cord
description: The ridge-shaped grey matter of the spinal cord that extends longitudunally through the center of each half of the spinal cord, and are largely or entirely composed of nerve cell bodies and their dendrites and some supportive tissue.

name: obsolete branchial arch skeleton
description: Skeletal and cartilaginous elements of the branchial arches; the last five of the set of seven pharyngeal arches; the numbering system can be confusing; generally branchial arch #1 is the first branchial arch, or the third pharyngeal arch, but some authors do not follow this convention.

name: muscle layer of infundibulum of uterine tube
description: A muscle layer that is part of a uterine tube infundibulum.

name: suspensory ligament of testis
description: The cranial atrophic portion of the urogenital ridge attached to the cranial pole of the intraabdominal embryonic testis

name: autopodial extension
description: A subdivision of the autopod that corresponds to one or more bones arranged in series branching from the main limb axis.

name: diastema between central incisors
description: A space or gap between the left and right central incisors, on either the upper or lower jaw.

name: articular process
description: Paired processes located on the anterior end of the cricoid cartilage.

name: eye trabecular meshwork
description: A pore-like structure surrounding the entire circumference of the anterior chamber of the eye through which aqueous humor circulates[MP].

name: bulb of hair follicle
description: Thickening of the proximal end of the hair follicle. Contains rapidly proliferating, rather undifferentiated matrix cells (transient amplifying cells), melanocytes and outer root sheath cells.

name: odontoid process of cervical vertebra 2
description: The toothlike process on the upper surface of the axis, which articulates with the atlas above[GAID].

name: accessory XI nerve nucleus
description: The spinal accessory nucleus lies within the cervical spinal cord (C1-C5) in the ventral horn. The nucleus ambiguus is classically said to provide the 'cranial component' of the accessory nerve. However, the very existence of this cranial component has been recently questioned and seen as contributing exclusively to the vagus nerve. The terminology continues to be used in describing both human anatomy, and that of other animals.

name: periolivary nucleus
description: A nucleus of the superior olivary complex that surrounds the primary superior olivary nuclei

name: frontal pole
description: Component of the frontal lobe. The rostral and caudal boundaries of the frontal pole are the superior frontal gyrus and the rostral division of the middle frontal gyrus respectively (Christine Fennama-Notestine).

name: obsolete principal cavity
description: The largest part of the nasal cavity, containing the olfactory epithelium.

name: vernix caseosa
description: An unctuous substance composed of sebum and desquamated epithelial cells, which covers the skin of the fetus.

name: middle phalanx of manual digit 5
description: A middle phalanx that is part of a hand digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: vestibulocerebellum
description: A phylogenetic subdivision of the cerebellum, the oldest part, which regulates balance and eye movements. It receives vestibular input from both the semicircular canals and from the vestibular nuclei, and sends fibres back to the medial and lateral vestibular nuclei. It also receives visual input from the superior colliculi and from the visual cortex (the latter via the pontine nuclei, forming a cortico-ponto-cerebellar pathway). Lesions of the vestibulocerebellum cause disturbances of balance and gait.

name: rostral ventrolateral medulla
description: Control of blood pressure is crucially dependent on the integrity of a small region of the brainstem called the ventrolateral medulla. Within this part of the brain are the cells that control the heart, blood vessels, swallowing, breathing and many other functions of the body that are not noticed at a conscious level; such unconscious activities are known as 'Autonomic'. One of these regions is the Rostral Ventrolateral Medulla (RVLM) is also known as the pressor area of the medulla (medulla pressor). It receives inhibitory GABAergic input from the caudal ventrolateral medulla (CVLM). The RVLM is the primary regulator of the sympathetic nervous system, sending excitatory fibers (catecholaminergic) to the sympathetic preganglionic neurons in the spinal cord, via reticulospinal tract[WP].

name: left renal artery
description: Renal artery that supplies the left kidney

name: fibular facet of the calcaneum
description: Articular surface on calcaneum for the fibula.

name: upper jaw symphyseal region
description: The region of the upper jaw on or near the midline. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: rib of vertebra 3
description: Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the third centrum.

name: agger limitans anterior of ischium
description: Shelf-like expansion of the ischium that forms the posterior border of the acetabulum.

name: brachial vein
description: A vein that accompanies the brachial artery between the shoulder and the elbow.

name: paraaortic body
description: A chromaffin paraganglion located at the bifurcation of the aorta or at the origin of the inferior mesenteric artery.

name: ethmoidomaxillary suture
description: A suture between the orbital surface of the body of the maxilla with the orbital plate of the ethmoid bone.

name: radial bone
description: radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: infranuchal scute
description: Scute that is an elongated plate associated with a ligament running between posterior nuchal plate and rib on vertebra 6. Infranuchal scute is paired and develops from its associated ligament and sensory canal tubular ossicle.

name: epipleural series
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of the epipleurals. [PHENOSCAPE:bf]

name: future facial nucleus
description: A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a facial nucleus.

name: ural vertebra 2
description: Ural vertebra that is the second vertebra posterior to preural centrum 1. It may bear a rudimentary neural arch and sometimes a rudimentary spine or the neural arch and spine are completely absent and it may articulate or fuse with hypural 2 (polyural terminology). Ural vertebra 2 is an unpaired median bone.

name: hyomandibular cartilage
description: Cartilage form of the hyomandibular element.

name: castoreum
description: A yellowish pungent liquid that is a mixture of the castor sacs (an anal gland in the taxon Castoreum) and urine.

name: intracranial diverticulum of swimbladder
description: An anterior extension of the swimbladder that passes through a foramen in the exoccipital; part of the otophysic connection between swimbladder and inner ear.

name: mural trophectoderm
description: Trophectoderm that surrounds blastocyst cavity.

name: vein of clitoris
description: A vein that is part of a clitoris [Automatically generated definition].

name: area X of basal ganglion
description: A nucleus in the basal ganglion of songbirds.

name: rectum smooth muscle tissue
description: Any portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of the rectum

name: Harderian gland duct
description: A duct that is part of a Harderian gland. opens into the conjunctival sac at the base of the nictitating membrane.

name: kidney pelvis urothelium
description: the epithelial lining of the luminal space of the kidney pelvis

name: forelimb skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a forelimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: epithelium of incisor
description: An epithelium that is part of a incisor tooth [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of cervical spinal cord dorsal horn
ventral liver lobe
description: Portion of the liver which develops on the fish's ventral side.

name: posterior pole of lens
description: the central point on the posterior surface of the lens.

name: ctenactinium
description: A curved rod-like clasper on the posterior side of the priapium in Phallostethidae.

name: lymph heart
description: A circulatory organ that is reponsible for pumping lymph throughout the body.

name: manual digit 2 phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit 2 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: male urethral meatus
description: A urethral meatus that is part of a male urethra[Automatically generated definition].

name: cartilage of respiratory system
description: A cartilage element that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: lobar bronchus of left lung upper lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a upper lobe of left lung.

name: median fin radial bone
description: median fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: anterior talofibular ligament
description: The anterior talofibular ligament is a ligament in the ankle. It passes from the anterior margin of the fibular malleolus, anteriorly and medially, to the talus bone, in front of its lateral articular facet. It is one of the lateral ligaments of the ankle and prevents the foot from sliding forward in relation to the shin.

name: muscle of digastric group
description: Either of the two muscles that comprise the digastric group (anterior or posterior).

name: habenular trigone
description: The habenular trigone is a small depressed triangular area situated in front of the superior colliculus and on the lateral aspect of the posterior part of the taenia thalami. It contains a group of nerve cells termed the ganglion habenulC&. Fibers enter it from the stalk of the pineal body, and others, forming what is termed the habenular commissure, pass across the middle line to the corresponding ganglion of the opposite side. Most of its fibers are, however, directed downward and form a bundle, the fasciculus retroflexus of Meynert, which passes medial to the red nucleus, and, after decussating with the corresponding fasciculus of the opposite side, ends in the interpeduncular ganglion.

name: prosencephalic artery
description: After the primitive prosencephalic artery forms it becomes disconnected from the cranial division of the internal carotid artery and instead it connects to the anterior mesencephalic central artery and the communicating vessels of the palatocerebral artery.

name: supraoptic nucleus
description: The supraoptic nucleus (SON) is a nucleus of magnocellular neurosecretory cells in the hypothalamus of the mammalian brain. The nucleus is situated at the base of the brain, adjacent to the optic chiasm. [WP,unvetted].

name: isla magna of Calleja
description: Regional part of telencephalon; the most prominent of the islands of Calleja located medially in the nucleus accumbens (adapted from Braininfo.org).

name: interhaemal bone
description: A small bone articulating distally with the haemal arch or a short haemal spine.

name: nutrient foramen conduit
description: Any of the passages admitting nutrient vessels to the medullary cavity of bone

name: obsolete myoblast
description: Embryonic (precursor) cell of the myogenic lineage that develops from the mesoderm.

name: obsolete trabecular plate
description: Ventral plate anterior to and confluent with ethmoid plate.

name: superficial epigastric artery
description: An artery that arises from the femoral artery and supplies the abdominal wall. It distributes branches to the superficial subinguinal lymph glands, the superficial fascia, and the integument; it anastomoses with branches of the inferior epigastric, and with its fellow of the opposite side.

name: carotid sinus nerve
description: A sensory branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) carrying signals from the baroceptors (blood pressure receptors) in the bifurcation of the carotid artery to the nucleus of the solitary tract (nucleus solitarius).

name: cervical vertebral arch
description: A neural arch that is part of a cervical vertebra.

name: oral subdivision of organism
description: A major subdivision of an organism that is the entire side of the organism oral to the plane that divides the organism in two, perpendicular to the oral-aboral axiom.

name: sacral region
description: A subdivision of an organism along the anterior-posterior axis in the pelvic region immediately posterior to the lumbar region and anterior to the caudal region. Sometimes an intermediate region is defined between the sacral and caudal.

name: testis sex cord
description: The testis cords are precursors to the rete testis. They play several different roles in the development of the male genitals[WP].

name: cortical intermediate zone
description: The region of the developing mammalian cortex that extends between the ventricular zone and the cortical plate (CP); normally, the IZ is a region of tangential migration of cells, and at midgestation, the lower part of the IZ develops into the subventricular zone

name: submandibular gland primordium epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a submandibular gland primordium.

name: upper jaw molar odontogenic papilla
description: An odontogenic papilla that is part of a upper jaw molar.

name: cervical vertebra 1 arcus anterior
description: The arch that connects the lateral masses of the atlas anteriorly and articulates with the anterior articular facet of the dens of the axis[MP].

name: ansiform lobule
description: A lobule comprising the greater part of the hemisphere of the cerebellum; its superior and inferior surfaces are separated by the horizontal fissure into major parts known as crus I (superior semilunar lobule) and crus II (inferior semilunar lobule).

name: vertebral column
description: Subdivision of skeletal system that consists of all the vertebra and associated skeletal elements and joints in the body[modified from VSAO].

name: midline nuclear group
description: The midline nuclear group (or midline thalamic nuclei) a region of the thalamus consisting of the following nuclei: paraventricular nucleus of thalamus (nucleus paraventricularis thalami) - not to be confused with paraventricular nucleus of hypothalamus paratenial nucleus (nucleus parataenialis) reuniens nucleus (nucleus reuniens) rhomboidal nucleus (nucleus commissuralis rhomboidalis) subfascicular nucleus (nucleus subfascicularis) [WP,unvetted].

name: cleithrum head
description: Expanded dorsal region of the cleithrum.

name: medial part of ventral lateral nucleus
glenoid end of clavicle
description: Lateral end of the clavicle, which usually lies in close proximity to the pars acromialis of the scapula, and occassionally may fuse to it.

name: main olfactory bulb
description: The main olfactory bulb has a multi-layered cellular architecture. In order from surface to the center the layers are: Glomerular layer, External plexiform layer, Mitral cell layer, Internal plexiform layer, Granule cell layer[WP].

name: nail of manual digit 1
description: A nail that is part of a manual digit 1.

name: anterior tegmental nucleus
description: A group of cells located ventral to the decussation of the superior cerebellar peduncle in the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ) and rat ( Swanson-1998 )

name: ventral tegmental nucleus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a ventral tegmental area.

name: lateral medullary reticular complex
description: A nuclear complex of the medullary reticular formation that can be divided into three subnuclei: the parvocellular, magnocellular and the subtrigeminal[WP,modified].

name: anterior lateral line neuromast
description: Neuromast that is part of the anterior lateral line. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)

name: prearticular coronoid process
description: Point of insertion of the masticatory musculature.

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between digits 4 and 5
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between digits 4 and 5.

name: respiratory airway
description: An airway through which respiratory air passes in organisms.

name: thermoreceptor
description: Cellular receptors which mediate the sense of temperature. Thermoreceptors in vertebrates are mostly located under the skin. In mammals there are separate types of thermoreceptors for cold and for warmth and NOCICEPTORS which detect cold or heat extreme enough to cause pain.

name: jugal ramule
description: This ramule innervates the jugal line of neuromasts and is the dorsal branch of the ramus mandibularis externus.

name: labral segment
description: Procephalic segment anterior to the antennal segment. In the adult it bears the clypeo-labrum.

name: submucosal gland
description: Gland of the lamina epithelialis mucosae which perforate the lamina muscularis, with their adenomeres located in the submucosal connective tissue.

name: hypobranchial 4 cartilage
description: Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.

name: white matter of myelencephalon
description: A white matter that is part of the myelencephalon.

name: ligamentum arteriosum
description: A small ligament attached to the superior surface of the pulmonary trunk and the inferior surface of the aortic arch. It is a nonfunctional vestige of the ductus arteriosus, and is formed within three weeks of birth. The ligamentum arteriosum is closely related to the left recurrent laryngeal nerve, a branch of the left vagus nerve. After splitting from the left vagus nerve, the left recurrent laryngeal loops around the aortic arch posterior to the ligamentum arteriosum, after which it ascends to the larynx[WP].

name: labial disc primordium
description: Primordium that will form the labial disc.

name: premaxilla maxillary process
description: Process of the premaxilla that extends upward, and often lies against the medial surface of the maxillary.

name: vestibular system
description: The sensory system for the sense of balance.

name: optic cup
description: Multi-tissue structure that is comprised of neural and non-neural epithelial layers which will form the retina and retinal pigmented epithelium of the mature eye[ZFA]. double walled structured formed by expansion and invagination of the distal end of the optic vesicle that develops into the pigmented and sensory layers of the retina while the mouth of the optic cup eventually forms the pupil of the eye[MP].

name: atrioventricular septum
description: The wall of the heart that separates the right atrium and left ventricle; and is located just above the septal cusp of the tricuspid valve

name: segmental subdivision of nervous system
description: Any segmental subdivision of a nervous system. Includes metameric developmental segments, such as vertebrates neuromeres.

name: pupil
description: the central circular aperture of the iris through which light rays enter the eye

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of pedal digit 5
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of pedal digit 5.

name: auricular muscle
description: A muscle that is part of the pinna and is attached to the auricular cartilage

name: thoracic wall
description: The thoracic wall (or chest wall) is the boundary of the thoracic cavity. The bony portion is known as the thoracic cage. However, the wall also includes muscle, skin, and fascia.

name: pharyngeal arch artery 6
description: The vessels formed within the sixth pair of branchial arches in embryogenesis

name: extraembryonic venous system
description: A venous system that overlaps a umbilical cord and is part of a entire extraembryonic component.

name: transverse parietal sulcus
description: A sulcus in the human parietal lobe that branches dorsally from the intraparietal sulcus (Savel'ev-96). (NN)

name: postorbital process
description: The Postorbital Process marks the rear, upper edge of the eye socket and is a projection from the frontal bone.

name: rib 7
description: The seventh rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: orbital septum
description: A membranous sheet that acts as the anterior boundary of the orbit. It extends from the orbital rims to the eyelids[WP].

name: principal neuronal circuit
