description: A neuronal circuit bearing a principal projection neuron whose axon extends beyond the region where its soma is located to synapse on the dendrites of cells in other regions of the nervous system (BB).

name: abducens nerve
description: Cranial nerve that runs to the eye muscles.

name: saddle joint
description: In a saddle joint (sellar joint, articulation by reciprocal reception) the opposing surfaces are reciprocally concave-convex.

name: manual digit 6 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 6 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: obsolete regional part of thoracic spinal cord
lateral ethmoid-frontal joint
description: Joint that articulates the lateral ethmoid and frontal. lateral ethmoid-frontal joint is paired.

name: tertiary ovarian follicle
description: A follicle that has reached the most mature stage of folliculogenesis, characterized by the presence of the antrum

name: vocal organ
description: Any organ that is the primary organ of vocalization behavior. Examples: The laryngeal vocal cord (humans), the syrinx (birds).

name: primary ossification center
description: A primary ossification center is the first area of a bone to start ossifying. It usually appears during prenatal development in the central part of each developing bone. In long bones the primary centers occur in the diaphysis/shaft and in irregular bones the primary centers occur usually in the body of the bone. Most bones have only one primary center (e.g. all long bones) but some irregular bones such as the os coxa (hip) and vertebrae have multiple primary centers.

name: centrum 6
description: Centrum that is part of vertebra 6.

name: somite 27
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: premolar 1
description: First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the jaw.

name: inguinal ring
description: An entrance or exit of the inguinal canal

name: obsolete apical ectodermal ridge forelimb
description: A forelimb that is part of an apical ectodermal ridge [Automatically generated definition].

name: stylar shelf
description: The stylar shelf is an an expansion of the cingulum; it often bears small cusps (each with its own name...).

name: otolith
description: Acellular structure composed of calcium carbonate located in the otolith organ.

name: statolith
description: Acellular mineralized structure located in the statocyst (balance organ) of some aquatic invertebrates[WP,CJM].

name: immature otolith
description: Brightly refractile stone-like organ within the otic vesicle and positioned over a sensory macula; two form in each vesicle during the late segmentation period. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for otolith by T. Whitfield.)

name: spiral ligament
description: A spiral thickening of the fibrous lining of the cochlear wall. Spiral ligament secures the membranous cochlear duct to the bony spiral canal of the cochlea. Its spiral ligament fibrocytes function in conjunction with the stria vascularis to mediate cochlear ion homeostasis.

name: mole
description: A benign tumor on the skin, usually with darker pigment.

name: digit 8 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 8 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: forelimb connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a forelimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric descending thin limb
description: It extends to the tip of the metanephric loop of Henle[GO].

name: connecting stalk
description: A bridge of mesoderm connecting the caudal end of the young embryo with the trophoblastic tissues; the precursor of the umbilical cord.

name: umbilical cord
description: The connecting cord from the developing embryo to the placenta.

name: caudal anterior cingulate cortex
description: Component of the cingulate cortex. The rostral boundary was the first appearance of the genu of the corpus callosum whereas the caudal boundary was established as the first appearance of the mammillary bodies. The medial boundary was the medial aspect of the cortex. The supero-lateral boundary was the superior frontal gyrus whereas the infero-lateral boundary was the corpus callosum (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: obsolete regional part of dentate nucleus
gastroduodenal junction
description: A anatomical junction that connects a stomach and connects a duodenum.

name: gigantocellular nucleus
description: Nucleus located in the rostral ventrolateral medulla. The PGL was originally identified by cytoarchitectural criteria in the human medulla (Olszewski and Baxter, 1954). In humans, the PGL is located in the ventrolateral quadrant of the rostral medullary tegmentum between the nucleus subtrigeminalis caudally, trapezoid body and the superior olive rostrally, nucleus gigantocellularis medially, spinothalamic tract fibers laterally, inferior olive ventrally, and the nucleus ambiguous dorsally (Olszewski and Baxter, 1954). In the rat, the PGL has been further subdivided into retrofacial PGL (caudal to the facial nucleus), and more rostrally located juxtafacial PGL (medial to the facial nucleus), based upon different connectivity.

name: hepatic cecum
description: A ventral evagination extending anteriorly in the mid-portion of the intestine in Amphioxi.

name: ramule palatonasalis
description: Descends and branches to the buccal roof where it anastomoses with the palatine ramus of the facial nerve.

name: lower vermilion
description: A vermilion that is part of a lower lip.

name: manual digit 5 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a hand digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: female urethral crest
description: The conspicuous longitudinal fold of mucosa on the posterior wall of the female urethra[MP]

name: ceratobranchial 4 bone
description: Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone.

name: ramus palatinus
description: Sensory branch of facial nerve from palatal region.

name: digital pad
description: A thick spongy structure at the base of the autopod, centred over the flexor surfaces of the distal interphalangeal joints.

name: cuneate fasciculus
description: An axon tract in the spinal cord and medulla which primarily transmits information from the forelimb and trunk. It is part of the dorsal column-medial lemniscus pathway.

name: gubernaculum testis
description: The fetal ligament attached to the inferior end of the epididymis and testis and, at its other end, to the bottom of the scrotum; it is present during, and is thought to guide, the descent of the testis into the scrotum and then atrophies.

name: neural tube alar plate
description: The mantle layer of the neural tube that lies dorsal to the sulcus limitans and contains primarily sensory neurons and interneurons involved in communication of sensory impulses.

name: panniculus adiposus
description: The panniculus adiposus is the fatty layer of the subcutaneous tissues, superficial to a deeper vestigial layer of muscle, the panniculus carnosus. An example is the Fascia of Camper. Another example is the superficial cervical fascia[WP]

name: diastema between upper central incisors
description: A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the upper jaw.

name: cartilaginous joint suture
description: A cranial suture that is part of a cartilaginous joint [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior nucleus of hypothalamus dorsal part
tympanic canal
description: A minute canal that passes from the petrous portion of the temporal bone between the jugular fossa and carotid canal to the floor of the tympanic cavity and transmits the tympanic branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve

name: centromedian nucleus of thalamus
description: In the anatomy of the brain, the centromedian nucleus, also known as the centrum medianum, (CM or Cm-Pf) is a part of the intralaminar nucleus (ILN) of the thalamus. There are two centromedian nuclei arranged bilaterally. It contains about 2000 neurons per cubic millimetre and has a volume of about 310 cubic millimetres with 664,000 neurons in total. [WP,unvetted].

name: obsolete intercalar
description: Small membrane bone homologous with a cartilage bone in more basal fishes (Patterson, 1977). Situated between the exoccipital and the pterotic at point of attachment of short ligament that originates on the ventral arm of the posttemporal.

name: pelvic fin bud mesenchyme
description: Mesechyme that is part of a pelvic fin bud.

name: skeletal muscle tissue of deltoid
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a deltoid [Automatically generated definition].

name: meconium
description: A dark greenish mass that accumulates in the bowel during fetal life and is discharged shortly after birth.

name: middle phalanx of pedal digit 2
description: A middle phalanx that is part of a foot digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: spinocerebellum
description: A phylogenetic subdivision of the cerebellum, the intermediate part, which regulates body and limb movements. It receives proprioception input from the dorsal columns of the spinal cord (including the spinocerebellar tract) and the trigeminal nerve, as well as from visual and auditory systems. It sends fibres to deep cerebellar nuclei which in turn project to both the cerebral cortex and the brain stem, thus providing modulation of descending motor systems.

name: cardiac vein
description: Vein of heart that drains the myocardium

name: great saphenous vein
description: The great saphenous vein (GSV), also greater saphenous vein, is the large (subcutaneous) superficial vein of the leg and thigh. The terms 'safaina' (Greek) and 'el safin' (Arabic) have both been claimed as the origin for the word 'saphenous'. [WP,unvetted].

name: bone tissue of long bone
description: A bone tissue that is part of a long bone.

name: obsolete predominantly gray part of ventral cochlear nucleus
testicular artery
description: One of a pair of arteries that is a branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to a male gonad.

name: spermatic artery
description: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies oxygenated blood to the testis.

name: lateral commissure
description: Region of the braincase which bears the facets for the hyomandibula in fishes. This region disappears in the origin of tetrapods and the space it occipied comes to contribute to the fenestra vestibulii. Clack, JA, 2001. Ch. 23, The otoccipital region. In Major Events in Early Vertebrate Evolution. Per Ahlberg editor.

name: rib of vertebra 4
description: Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fourth centrum.

name: obsolete supra-acetabular expansion
description: Dorsal portion of the ilial corpus, located above the acetabulum.

name: median basilic vein
description: A vein between the biceps and pronator radii teres muscles that unites with the common ulnar vein to form the basilic vein within the forearm.

name: lamina propria of small intestine
description: Lamina propria that is part_of the small intestine.

name: sphenomaxillary suture
description: an inconstant suture between the pterygoid process of the sphenoid bone and the body of the maxilla.

name: sensory canal tubular ossicle
description: Dermal bone that is ring-shaped or cylindrical and surrounds a sensory canal.

name: future inferior salivatory nucleus
description: A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a inferior salivatory nucleus.

name: paracentral lobule
description: The junction of the precentral gyrus and postcentral gyrus on the medial surface of the cerebral cortex. It lies across the boundary between the frontal lobe and the parietal lobe.

name: hyomandibular element
description: The upper paired deep bone or cartilage of the hyoid region, sometimes taking part in jaw suspension and which supports the opercle. Dorsally it articulates with the otic capsule at the hyomandibular fossa, ventrally with the quadrate and symplectic. In most Teleostei it has a foramen for the hyomandibular branch of the facial nerve (VII).

name: prothoracic tarsal segment
description: Tarsal segment of the adult prothoracic leg.

name: preepiotic fossa
description: Fossa that is a concavity on the dorsolateral surface of the skull roof found at least partially on the epiotic (epioccipital).

name: tract of spinal cord
description: An axon tract that is part of a spinal cord.

name: nasolacrimal groove
description: Groove between maxillary prominence and lateral nasal process.

name: tail vein
description: A vein that is part of a tail [Automatically generated definition].

name: robust nucleus of arcopallium
description: A specialized nucleus within the intermediate archistriatum of songbirds, required for and active during the production of learned song.

name: left kidney interstitium
description: A kidney interstitium that is part of a left kidney.

name: gland of ocular region
description: A gland that is typically found in or near the orbital region, in or around either the medial or lateral canthi, and is typically associated with secretions onto the eyeball or associated ducts. Includes the Harderian, nictitans and lacrimal glands.

name: larynx mucous gland
description: A mucous gland that is part of a larynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: hindlimb skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a hindlimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: supplemental motor cortex
description: The supplementary motor area (SMA) is a part of the sensorimotor cerebral cortex (perirolandic, i.e. on each side of the Rolando or central sulcus). It was included, on purely cytoarchitectonic arguments, in area 6 of Brodmann and the Vogts. It is located on the medial face of the hemisphere, just in front of primary motor cortex. This is an element that appeared late in evolution, in monkeys, linked to the appearance of a true medial pallidum.

name: epithelium of nasal septum
description: An epithelium that is part of a nasal septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: proctodeum
description: Inward fold on the surface of the embryonic ectoderm that develops into an ectodermal terminal part of the digestive tract.

name: obsolete CoPA
description: An interneuron in the spinal cord. CoPA are bipolar with 'T' shaped dorsal dendrites, have contralateral longitudinal axons that crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner neuron and ascends in the dorsal cord.

name: toxactinium
description: A long curved projection from the anterior end of the priapium in some Phallostethidae

name: pelvic complex muscle
description: Muscles of the pelvic girdle, hindlimb or pelvic fin.

name: cochlear ganglion
description: The group of nerve cell bodies that conveys auditory sensation from the organ of Corti to the hindbrain and resides on the cochlear part of the vestibulocochlear nerve (eighth cranial nerve)[MP]. distributed to the hair cells of the spiral organ. The cochlear fibers arise in bipolar cells in the spiral ganglion in the modiolus.

name: non-connected functional system
description: An anatomical group whose component structures share a common function.

name: manual digit 3 phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit 3 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: internal urethral orifice
description: the usually crescent-shaped opening of the urinary bladder into the urethra, placed at the anteroinferior angle (apex) of the urinary bladder trigone

name: nucleus of diagonal band
description: A brain structure that is part of the septal nuclear complex. It is connected with the hippocampus, hypothalamus and amygdala.

name: cartilage of nasal septum
description: A cartilage that is part of a nasal septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: lobar bronchus of left lung lower lobe
description: A lobar bronchus that is part of a lower lobe of left lung.

name: median fin proximal radial bone
description: median fin proximal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: posterior talofibular ligament
description: The posterior talofibular ligament, runs almost horizontally from the depression at the medial and back part of the fibular malleolus (lateral malleolus) to a prominent tubercle on the posterior surface of the talus immediately lateral to the groove for the tendon of the flexor hallucis longus.

name: septum of telencephalon
description: Gray matter structure located on the midline of the forebrain consisting of the septum pellucidum (in some species) and the septal nuclei (Heimer, 1996).

name: septum
description: A wall, dividing a cavity or structure into smaller ones[WP].

name: M. tibialis anticus longus
description: Originates on the ventro-lateral surface of the medial condyle of the femur. Its tendon extends in a groove over the knee in the lateral surface of the tibiofibular head, and penetrates the M. peroneus tendon. Insertion is by a lateral and medial head on the dorso-lateral surface of the fibulare and the medial border of the proximal end of the tibiale respectively.

name: obsolete body membrane
description: Part of body that takes the form of a thin sheet of cells or fibrous material, e.g., the meningeal coverings of the brain[NIFSTD].

name: gular plate
description: Dermal bone located on the ventral surface of the skull and positioned between the two rami of the lower jaw. Anteriorly the gular attaches to the symphysis of the lower jaw through fibrous connective tissue. The gular is an unpaired median bone.

name: lumen of nutrient foramen
description: An anatomical space that is part of a nutrient foramen conduit, leading to the medullary cavity of the bone.

name: obsolete abdominal myoblast
description: The myoblast that forms the muscles of the anterior abdominal walls.

name: pars interarticularis of vertebra
description: The part of vertebra located between the inferior and superior articular processes of the facet joint.

name: trabecular horn
description: Anterior extensions.

name: middle thyroid vein
description: The middle thyroid vein collects the blood from the lower part of the thyroid gland, and after being joined by some veins from the larynx and trachea, ends in the lower part of the internal jugular vein.

name: ischial cartilage
description: Paired cartilaginous element forming the posterior portion of the pelvic girdle. [D.F. Markle, BULLETIN OF MARINE SCIENCE. 30(1): 45-53. 1980]

name: vertebral arch of sacral segment
description: A neural arch that is part of a sacral vertebra.

name: pedal digit 3 epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a pedal digit 3.

name: sclerotome somite 9
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: aboral subdivision of organism
description: A major subdivision of an organism that is the entire side of the organism aboral to the plane that divides the organism in two, perpendicular to the oral-aboral axiom.

name: induseum griseum
description: Thin layer of cortex lying on the dorsal surface of the corpus callosum. It has been debated whether it is more related to the hippocampus or the olfactory bulb (Shipley et al., Olfactory System In Paxinos The Rat Nervous System, 2nd ed)

name: skin of clitoris
description: A zone of skin that is part of a clitoris [Automatically generated definition].

name: spleen primary B follicle
description: The nodules of small undifferentiated B lymphocytes and follicular dendritic cells located in the spleen white pulp

name: great vein of heart
description: The Great Cardiac Vein (left coronary vein) begins at the apex of the heart and ascends along the anterior longitudinal sulcus to the base of the ventricles. It then curves to the left in the coronary sulcus, and reaching the back of the heart, opens into the left extremity of the coronary sinus. It receives tributaries from the left atrium and from both ventricles: one, the left marginal vein, is of considerable size, and ascends along the left margin of the heart.

name: lower jaw molar odontogenic papilla
description: An odontogenic papilla that is part of a lower jaw molar.

name: postzygapophysis
description: Paired processes at the caudal end of the neural arch. The articular facets of the postzygapophyses face lateroventrally and articulate with the dorsomedially facing facets of the prezygapophyses of the succeeding vertebra.

name: hyoid bone greater horn
description: The larger and more lateral of the paired processes on either side of the hyoid bone[MP]

name: posterior cingulate gyrus
description: The posterior cingulate cortex is the backmost part of the cingulate cortex, lying behind the anterior cingulate cortex. This is the upper part of the 'limbic lobe'. The cingulate cortex is made up of an area around the midline of the brain. Surrounding areas include the retrosplenial cortex and the precuneus. Cytoarchitectonically posterior cingulate cortex is associated with Brodmann areas 23 and 31. [WP,unvetted].

name: paramedian lobule
description: The anterior portion of the posteroinferior lobule of the cerebellum, the posterior portion being the semilunar lobule inferior; the two are continuous with the tuber of the vermis.

name: greater sciatic notch
description: On the dorsal border of the wing of the ilium , at it's junction with the shaft is a cut away. This forms the Greater sciatic notch. The sciatic nerve runs over the notch in passage to the hindlimb.

name: vertebral foramen
description: A foramen within a vertebral element through which the spinal cord runs. It is formed by the anterior segment, and the posterior part, the vertebral arch.

name: postaxial process of the femur
description: A projection on the postaxial region of the femur.

name: cnemial crest
description: Longitudnal bony ridge on tibia, attachment site of the major extensor muscle of the hind limb.

name: dentate gyrus subgranular zone
description: A narrow layer of cells located between the granule cell layer and hilus of the dentate gyrus, where adult neurogenesis occurs.

name: nail of manual digit 2
description: A nail that is part of a manual digit 2.

name: myenteric nerve plexus
description: One of two ganglionated neural networks which together form the enteric nervous system. The myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus is located between the longitudinal and circular muscle layers of the gut. Its neurons project to the circular muscle, to other myenteric ganglia, to submucosal ganglia, or directly to the epithelium, and play an important role in regulating and patterning gut motility.

name: matrix compartment
description: The larger of two chemoarchitectural compartments identified in the neostriatum through differential staining for various biochemical markers. It usually is identified through differentially high staining for acetylcholinesterase and calbinin D28K.

name: obsolete deep blastomere
description: Cells (completely cleaved), located underneath the superficial blastomeres and internal to the marginal blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: obsolete spiracle
description: OBSOLETE: The mostly slit-like opening on the body surface through which air is taken into the respiratory system.

name: nerve of clitoris
description: Any nerve that innervates the clitoris.

name: pharyngeal nerve plexus
description: The pharyngeal plexus is a network of nerve fibers innervating most of the palate, larynx, and pharynx. It is located on the surface of the middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle.

name: median fin
description: Fin that is an unpaired fin located in the sagittal plane of the organism.

name: median fin fold
description: Surface structure that will develop into one of the median fins. Extends from dorsal surface of fish, caudal to the 8th somite, to the ventral surface ending at the caudal side of the vent.

name: antennal segment
description: Segment anterior to the intercalary segment. In the adult it bears the antennae.

name: caudal-fin stay
description: Dermal bone that is located anterior to the caudal fin procurrent rays. Caudal fin stays are unpaired median bones.

name: right subcostal vein
description: A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the right side of the body.

name: ciliated columnar epithelium
description: Simple columnar epithelium in which the luminal side of the cells bears cilia. Examples: epithelium of trachea, epithelium of uterine tube.[FMA]

name: Marshall's gland
description: A paired hollow organ in the genito-urinary apparatus of Raja (and probably other skates and rays) whose cavity is fluid filled.

name: hypobranchial 1 cartilage
description: Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone.

name: tuberculum sellae
description: An elevated zone of the sella turcica behind the chiasmatic groove[WP,modified].

name: node of ligamentum arteriosum
description: An inconstant lymph node of the anterior mediastinal group located adjacent to the ligamentum arteriosum.

name: corona radiata of neuraxis
description: Fan shaped white matter mass comprised of afferent and efferent fibers from the cerebral cortex arranged in radially arrayed bundles, converging towards the internal capsule (Carpenter, Core Text of Neuroanatomy, 3rd ed, 1985, pg. 30; Heimer, The Human Brain and Spinal Cord, 2nd ed., 1995, pg 84).

name: lens placode
description: A thickened portion of ectoderm which serves as the precursor to the lens. SOX2 and Pou2f1 are involved in its development[WP].

name: segmental subdivision of hindbrain
description: An organ subunit that is part of a hindbrain [Automatically generated definition].

name: hyoid arch skeleton
description: A subdivision of skeleton that supports pharyngeal arch 2.

name: corneal epithelium
description: the smooth stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea

name: roof plate of telencephalon
description: A roof plate that is part of a telencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of pedal digit
intrinsic auricular muscle
description: Auricular muscle attached only to the cartilage of the ear and not to the epicranial aponeurosis

name: cervical vertebral arch joint
description: A vertebral arch joint that is part of a cervical region of vertebral column.

name: embryonic cloaca
description: endoderm-lined chamber that develops as pouch-like dilation of the caudal end of the hindgut and receives the allantois ventrally and two mesonephric ducts laterally; caudally it ends blindly at the cloacal membrane formed by the union of proctodeal (anal pit) ectoderm and cloacal endoderm, with no intervening mesoderm[MP].

name: rib 9
description: The ninth rib counting from the top of the rib cage down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: nasal cartilage
description: One of the cartilage structures in the nose that provide form and support[WP].

name: intrinsic neuronal circuit
description: A neuronal circuit where all the participating neurons are bounded within a defined and limited region of the nervous system.(BB).

name: facial nerve
description: Cranial nerve that branches into the supraorbital (supplying the skin of the eye region and the lateral line organs here), the palatine (to the roof of the buccal cavity), and the hyomandibular (dividing into the jugular and mental branches).

name: manubriosternal joint
description: The early union, by hyaline cartilage, of the manubrium and the body of the sternum, which later becomes a symphysial type of joint.

name: manual digit 7 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 7 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: prootic-pterosphenoid joint
description: Joint that articulates the prootic and pterosphenoid. prootic-pterosphenoid joint is paired.

name: metanephros cortex
description: The metanephric cortex is the outer region of the metanephros[GO].

name: follicular fluid
description: The fluid surrounding the ovum and granulosa cells in the ovarian follicle.

name: secondary ossification center
description: A secondary ossification center is the area of ossification that appears after the primary ossification center has already appeared - most of which appear during the postnatal and adolescent years. Most bones have more than one secondary ossification center. In long bones, the secondary centres appear in the epiphyses.

name: mandibular-hyoid median cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is a spherical mass of cartilage located between the mandibular symphysis and ventral hyoid arch. Mandibular-hyoid median cartilage is unpaired.

name: somite 3
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: obsolete cervical artery
description: An artery that is part of a uterine cervix [Automatically generated definition].

name: renal cortex peritubular capillary
description: A peritubular capillary that is part of a cortex of kidney.

name: commissural nucleus of the solitary tract
preprotocrista
description: An enamel ridge joining the protocone and the paracone on the occlusal surface of a maxillary molar.

name: ocular angle artery
description: The angular artery is the terminal part of the facial artery; it ascends to the medial angle of the eye's orbit, imbedded in the fibers of the angular head of the Quadratus labii superioris, and accompanied by the angular vein.

name: venous valve
description: A valve that is part of a vein.

name: Mullerian duct
description: paired ducts of the embryo that run down the lateral sides of the urogenital ridge and terminate at the mullerian eminence in the primitive urogenital sinus. In the female, they will develop to form the fallopian tubes, uterus, and the upper portion of the vagina; in the male, they are lost. These ducts are made of tissue of mesodermal origin[WP]. develops either by lengthwise splitting of the archinephric duct (in chondrichthyans and some amphibians) or by a elongated invagination of the coelomic epithelium (other vertebrates) In males, the oviducts regress. The cranial end of the oviduct maintains an opening into the coelom (which primitively may have been the anteriormost coelomic funnels connecting the nephrocoel with the coelom). This opening is the ostium tubae[USM].

name: pelvic cavity
description: The part of the ventral body cavity that is within the pelvis.

name: obsolete ventral rhombencephalic commissure brain stem
dorsal pes interosseous muscle
description: the most superior muscles in the sole of the foot that abduct the second to fourth toes. These four muscles also act through the dorsal expansions to resist extension of the metatarsophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints.

name: obsolete apical ectodermal ridge hindlimb
description: A hindlimb that is part of an apical ectodermal ridge [Automatically generated definition].

name: parietal notch
description: A pronounced notch or cavity in the lateral face of the parietal.

name: vestibular membrane of cochlear duct
description: A membrane inside the cochlea of the inner ear. It separates scala media from scala vestibuli. Together with the basilar membrane it creates a compartment in the cochlea filled with endolymph, which is important for the function of the organ of Corti. It primarily functions as a diffusion barrier, allowing nutrients to travel from the perilymph to the endolymph of the membranous labyrinth. Histologically, the membrane is composed of two layers of flattened epithelium, separated by a basal lamina. Its structure suggests that its function is transport of fluid and electrolytes.

name: outer canthus
description: A corner of the outer (lateral) part of an eye.

name: cerebellum anterior vermis
description: The anterior portion of the narrow middle zone between the two hemispheres of the cerebellum that is located anterior to the primary fissure

name: labial commissure
description: Anatomical structure consisting of either corner of the mouth.

name: trochanter
description: A bony prominence near the extremity of the femur that normally serves as attachment points for hip and thigh muscles[MP,modified]

name: hindlimb connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a hindlimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric distal convoluted tubule
description: The metanephric distal convoluted tubule is a portion of the metanephric nephron tubule that connects the metanephric loop of Henle to the collecting duct[GO].

name: intertragic incisure
description: A surface structure that is the narrowed downward continuation of the conchal space bounded anteriorly by the borders of the tragus, posteriorly by theantitragus, and along its lower lateral margins and inferior boundary by the connection between the first two.

name: mucosa of gastroduodenal junction
description: A mucosa that is part of a gastroduodenal junction.

name: nucleus raphe magnus
description: The nucleus raphe magnus, located directly rostral to the raphe obscurus, is afferently stimulated from axons in the spinal cord and cerebellum. This makes the magnus a likely candidate for part of the motor system; however, it seems to participate in the endogenous analgesia system. The magnus receives descending afferents from the periaqueductal gray, the paraventricular hypothalamic nucleus, central nucleus of the amygdala, lateral hypothalamic area, parvocellular reticular nucleus and the prelimbic, infralimbic, medial and lateral precentral cortices . All of these brain areas influence the main function of the raphe magnus. The main function of the magnus is mostly pain mediation; in fact it sends projections to the dorsal horn of the spinal cord to directly inhibit pain. The periaquiductal gray, the epicenter of analgesia, sends efferent connections to the nucleus raphe magnus in when it is stimulated by opiates (endogenous or otherwise). Electrical stimulation of the PAG produces analgesia, as well as administration of morphine to the PAG or n.r. magnus. The antinociceptic effects of electrical stimulation of the PAG can be blocked by administering naloxone, an opiate antagonist, to the n.r. magnus. All of this seems to indicate that the magnus is part of the endogenous opiate system, and acts to inhibit pain in the spinal cord. [WP,unvetted].

name: Weberian vertebra
description: Vertebra that is part of the Weberian apparatus.

name: skeleton of pectoral complex
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in a pectoral complex - i.e. the combination of free limb or fin plus pectoral girdle.

name: mucosa of urethra
description: A mucosa that is part of a urethra.

name: mandibular artery
description: Part of lateral pretrosal artery which supplies blood to the roof of the mouth.

name: ceratobranchial 3 bone
description: Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone.

name: striosome
description: One of two compartments identified in the neostriatum, particularly the caudate nucleus, on the basis of differential staining for several biochemical markers such as acetylcholinesterase and calbindin. In individual sections, the striosomes appear as small patches of differentially high or low staining activity. In three dimensions, they form a 3D labyrinth extending throughout the caudate nucleus and in the putamen.

name: gubernaculum (female)
description: A gubernaculum that is part of a female reproductive system.

name: neural tube lateral wall mantle layer
diastema between lower central incisors
description: A space or gap between the left and right central incisors on the lower jaw.

name: gastric vein
description: A laterally paired vein that drains blood away from the lesser curvature of the stomach.

name: lateral ventricle choroid plexus epithelium
description: A choroid plexus epithelium that is part of a lateral ventricle [Automatically generated definition].

name: parahippocampal gyrus
description: Component of the temporal lobe on the mesial surface, posterior to the entorhinal cortex. The rostral and caudal boundaries are the posterior end of the netorhinal cortex and the caudal portion of the hippocampus, respectively. The medial boudnary is designated as the medial aspect off the temporal lobe and the lateral boundary is the collateral sulcus (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: skeletal muscle tissue of teres major
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a teres major [Automatically generated definition].

name: dorsal trigeminal tract
description: The dorsal trigeminal tract (dorsal trigeminothalamic tract, or lemniscus) is a tract which receives signals from Meissner's corpuscles and Pacinian corpuscles. this tract arises from Principal trigeminal nucleus and terminates in the VPM nucleus of the thalamus. [WP,unvetted].

name: middle phalanx of pedal digit 3
description: A middle phalanx that is part of a foot digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: peroneal artery
description: An artery that supplies blood to the lateral compartment of the leg and is typically a branch of posterior tibial artery. [WP,unvetted].

name: ventriculo bulbo valve
description: A heart valve located between the ventricle and bulbus arteriosus.

name: cortex of manus bone
description: The outer or sperficial part of a bone of the manus.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of superior olivary complex
ansoparamedian fissure of cerebellum
description: Fissure between cerebellar hemispheric lobules VIIBi and VIIBii.

name: adductor mandibulae
description: An adductor muscle that acts on the jaw. In some species, this is subdivided into segments based on attachment.

name: right testicular artery
description: A testicular artery that supplies a right testicle.

name: cerumen gland
description: A specialized sudoriferous gland (sweat glands) located subcutaneously in the external auditory canal.

name: upper jaw symphyseal tooth
description: Tooth of the upper jaw that is adjacent to the upper jaw symphysis. [PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: middle meningeal artery
description: The middle meningeal artery is typically the third branch of the first part (retromandibular part) of the maxillary artery; one of the two terminal branches of the external carotid artery. After branching off the maxillary artery in the infratemporal fossa, it runs through the foramen spinosum to supply the dura mater and the calvaria. The middle meningeal artery is the largest of the three (paired) arteries which supply the meninges, the others being the anterior meningeal artery and the posterior meningeal artery. In approximately half of subjects it branches into an accessory meningeal artery. The middle meningeal artery runs beneath the pterion. It is vulnerable to injury at this point, where the skull is thin. Rupture of the artery may give rise to an epidural hematoma.

name: ilial protuberance
description: Small, dorsolaterally projecting knob located just anterior to the supra-acetabular expansion and about the level of the anterior border of the acetabulum.

name: skin of pelvis
description: A zone of skin that is part of a pelvis [Automatically generated definition].

name: chromaffin system
description: Organ system subdivision that consists primarily of chromaffin cells and their supporting structures.

name: muscularis mucosae of large intestine
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a large intestine.

name: lacrimomaxillary suture
description: A suture between the lacrimal bone and the maxilla.

name: sensory canal tubule
description: Sensory canal that is a side branch between a sensory canal proximally and a pore at its distal end. Sensory canal tubule is bilaterally paired although often imperfectly so.

name: future superior salivatory nucleus
description: A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a superior salivatory nucleus.

name: facial foramen
description: Foramen through which cranial nerve VII (facial) exits.

name: notochordal plate
description: The notochordal plate is the dorsal part of the notochordal process when the ventral portion breaks down. It is continuous laterally with the endoderm that composes the roof of the primitive foregut and is in contact dorsally with the neural tube. The folding off of the notochordal plate gives rise to the notochord.

name: vein of trabecular bone
description: A portion of vein that is part of a trabecular bone tissue [Automatically generated definition].

name: mucosa of neck of urinary bladder
description: A mucosa that is part of a neck of urinary bladder [Automatically generated definition].

name: right kidney interstitium
description: A kidney interstitium that is part of a right kidney.

name: Ongur, Price, and Ferry (2003) area Iam
medial gland of ocular region
description: A gland that is located in the ocular region, nearer the inner canthi. Typically associated with or part of the nictitating membrane, when present

name: Harderian gland
description: The Harderian gland is an anterior orbital gland usually associated with the nictitating membrane, and produces and secretes a variety of substances to the eye, depending upon the species[GO].

name: orbitalis muscle
description: An orbitalis muscle is a rudimentary nonstriated muscle (smooth muscle) that crosses from the infraorbital groove and sphenomaxillary fissure and intimately united with the periosteum of the orbit. It is often called Muller's muscle. One characteristic of Horner's Syndrome is enophthalmos (retraction of the eyeball into the orbit due to paralysis of the orbitalis muscle that spans the inferior orbital fissure). Its function is eyeball protrusion.

name: manual digit skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a finger [Automatically generated definition].

name: lateral periolivary nucleus
description: Lateral component of the periolivary nucleus

name: epithelium of tongue
description: An epithelium that is part of a tongue [Automatically generated definition].

name: trunk
description: Organism subdivision which is the part of the body posterior to the cervical region (or head, when cervical region not present) and anterior to the caudal region. Includes the sacrum when present.

name: obsolete CoSA
description: An interneuron of the spinal cord. CoSA, have contralateral longitudinal axons that crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner neuron and ascends in the dorsal cord.

name: aproctal bone of priapium
description: The ventral element in the priapium of the Phallostethidae on which articulate the ctenactinia (q.v.). Also called aproctal or pelvic bone

name: pectoral complex muscle
description: A muscle of a pectoral girdle, pectoral fin or anterior limb.

name: vallate papilla
description: Any of the large papillae, which have multiple taste buds in the trough surrounding the papillae, located near the base and on the dorsal side of the tongue

name: glandular system
description: A non-connected functional system that is composed primarily of a gland.

name: obsolete dense connective tissue
description: Also known as fibrous connective tissue. Forms ligaments and tendons and is characterized by densely packed collagen fibers that have great tensile strength.

name: manual digit 4 phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit 4 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: nuptial pad
description: Raised calluses of cornified epidermis used by the male to hold the female during mating.

name: gland of digestive tract
description: A gland that is part of a digestive tract [Automatically generated definition].

name: primary bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that arises from a segmental bronchus and does not contain cartilage.

name: notochordal fluid
description: Fluid contained within the notochordal canal

name: infraspinatus tendon
description: The infraspinatus muscle inserts at this tendon to the distal greater tubercle of the humerus. This tendon stretches across the shoulder joint to attach to the humerus and in doing so acts as a very strong ligament to hold the joint surface in apposition. This structure restricts the movement of the shoulder joint to flexion and extension (together with the suscapularis tendon and the supraspinatus tendon). A bursa lies under this tendon at the greater tubercle of the humerus. The bursa is lined by a synovial membrance and filled with synovial fluid and protects the infraspinatus tendon and the shoulder joint by allowing the transmissions of tension and sheer forces around an angle.

name: obsolete neuron
description: Cell that is the basic unit of nervous tissue, each consisting of a body, an axon, and dendrites, and the purpose of which is to receive, conduct, and transmit impulses in the nervous system.

name: myocardial compact layer
description: outer dense layer of the myocardium uniting the epicardium and myocardium[MP].

name: muscle of pelvic diaphragm
description: A muscular partition formed by the levatores ani and coccygei, with which may be included the parietal pelvic fascia on their upper and lower aspects. It separates the pelvic cavity above from the perineal region below.

name: paired fin radial bone
description: paired fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: thoracic vertebral arch
description: A neural arch that is part of a thoracic vertebra.

name: pedal digit 4 epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a pedal digit 4.

name: sigmoid sinus
description: A portion of the lateral venous sinus, bulging prominently into the mastoid cavity, that serves as a principal conduit by which blood leaves the cranium[EPIC]. The sigmoid is drained by the internal jugular vein

name: left lung lobar bronchus epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a lobar bronchus of left lung.

name: prepuce of clitoris
description: A retractable double-layered fold of skin and mucous membrane that covers the clitoral glans.

name: spleen secondary B follicle
description: The nodules of antigen-activated, differentiating B cells, follicular dendritic cells, antigen-presenting T cells and macrophages in the spleen white pulp

name: mandible angular process
description: A process which protrudes from the ventral caudal angle of the mandible, and acts as the attachment of the digastric muscle.

name: optic eminence mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a optic eminence.

name: endocardium of ventricle
description: Endocardium that is part of the cardiac ventricle.

name: mesomere (fin)
description: The median series of bones supporting the pectoral fin of sarcopterygian fish. See Dipnomorpha. In the pectoral fin, the first mesomere is the humerus, the second the ulna, and the third probably the intermedium. The radius is the first preaxial radial. All other homologies are suspect. from http://palaeos.com/vertebrates/glossary

name: hyoid bone lesser horn
description: shorter and more medial of the paired processes on either side of the hyoid bone[MP]

name: diagonal band of Broca
description: A white fibre bundle descending in the precommissural septum toward the base of the forebrain, immediately rostral to the lamina terminalis; at the base, the bundle turns in the caudolateral direction; traveling through the ventral substantia innominata alongside the optic tract, it fades before reaching the amygdala.

name: olivary pretectal nucleus
description: Small distinct nucleus in the pretectum of mammals involved in the pupillary light reflect. In rats, it is an olive shaped (anterior) nucleus lying ventral to the brachium of the superior colliculus (Paxinos, The rat nervous system, 2nd ed, 1995, pg. 862). Physiologically, it is identified by neurons sensitive to luminance changes.

name: epicoracoid
description: Paired, flat cartilaginous arches that compose the central portion of the zonal area, unites the clavicle and coracoid of each half of the pectoral girdle, and form the medial margins of the pectoral fenestrae.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of Parahippocampal gyrus
superior prenasal cartilage
description: Paired, elongate cartilages that extend anteroventrally to abut the dorsomedial margin of the posterior face of the alary process of the premaxilla. The function of these cartilages is to transmit the movement of the premaxilla to the alary cartilages during the closure of the apertura nasalis externa.

name: parathyroid gland
description: The parathyroid gland is an endocrine gland for secretion of parathyroid hormone, usually found as a pair, embedded in the connective tissue capsule on the posterior surface of the thyroid gland. Parathyroid regulates calcium and phosphorous metabolism.

name: postaxial process of the fibula
description: A projection on the postaxial region of the fibula.

name: regional part of brain
description: Anatomical divisons of the brain according to one or more criteria, e.g. cytoarchitectural, gross anatomy. Parts may be contiguous in 3D or not, e.g., basal ganglia.

name: sulcus pro cartilagine praecoracoidealis
description: Canal on the posterior aspect of the clavicle that accomodates the anterior margin of the procoracoid cartilage.

name: post-embryonic organism
description: A multicellular organism that existence_starts_with a post-embryonic stage.

name: nail of manual digit 3
description: A nail that is part of a manual digit 3.

name: pharyngobranchial 2 tooth plate
description: Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 2 bone.

name: intermediate reticular nucleus
description: A nucleus of brain that is part of a intermediate reticular formation.

name: sublingual dorsal and ventral separate
description: Anatomical cluster consisting of the paired sublingual dorsal ossification and sublingual ventral ossification.

name: digestive system
description: Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs devoted to the ingestion, digestion, and assimilation of food and the discharge of residual wastes.

name: superior laryngeal nerve
description: The superior laryngeal nerve is a branch of the vagus nerve. It arises from the middle of the ganglion nodosum and in its course receives a branch from the superior cervical ganglion of the sympathetic. It descends, by the side of the pharynx, behind the internal carotid artery, and divides into two branches: external laryngeal nerve internal laryngeal nerve A superior laryngeal nerve palsy changes the pitch of the voice and causes an inability to make explosive sounds. If no recovery is evident three months after the palsy initially presents, the damage is most likely to be permanent. A bilateral palsy presents as a tiring and hoarse voice.

name: basibranchial 5 bone
description: Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7). Develops in posterior copula cartilage or basibranchial 5 cartilage.

name: hypobranchial 2 cartilage
description: Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone.

name: accessory nasal cartilage
description: small cartilages of the nose connecting the greater alar cartilage and lateral nasal cartilage.

name: superficial fibular nerve
description: A branch of the common fibular nerve that innervates the fibularis longus and brevis muscles, and via branches innervates parts of the dorsal part of the pes.

name: thoracic lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a thorax. Includes lymph nodes of the lungs and mediastinal lymph nodes

name: eye-antennal disc primordium
description: Primordium from which the eye-antennal disc develops.

name: nucleus of the brachium of the inferior colliculus
parasubiculum
description: A transitional zone between the presubiculum and the entorhinal area in the mouse (Paxinos-2001), the rat (Swanson-1998) and the primate (Zilles-1990). Defined on the basis of cytoarchitecture, it is more similar to the presubiculum than to the entorhinal area (Zilles-1990). (from Brain Info)

name: buccopharyngeal membrane
description: The thin bilaminar membrane derived from the prechordal plate that is devoid of mesoderm and formed by the apposition of the stomodeal ectoderm with the foregut endoderm; after the embryonic head fold has evolved it lies at the caudal limit of the stomodeum, forming a septum between the primitive mouth and pharynx; the membrane eventually disappears, and thus a communication is established between the mouth and the future pharynx.

name: meibum
description: an oily substance that prevents evaporation of the eye's tear film

name: parietal cortex
description: Gray matter of the parietal region of the neocortex, located in the parietal lobe of gyrencephalic animals. It is continuous anteriorly with the frontal cortex, posteriorly with the occipital cortex and medially with the insular cortex and with the temporal cortex on the posterior/inferior border.

name: interdigital region between manual digits 4 and 5
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a manual digit 4 and adjacent_to a manual digit 5.

name: rectus capitis lateralis muscle
description: A muscle that arises from the upper surface of the transverse process of the atlas and inserts into the under surface of the jugular process of the occipital bone.

name: epithelium of male gonad
description: An epithelium surrounding a testis.

name: mesonephric duct
description: Paired organ that connects the primitive kidney Wolffian body (or mesonephros) to the cloaca and serves as the anlage for certain male reproductive organs. the Wolffian duct is what remains of the pronephric duct after the atrophy of the pronephros[WP]. In Zebrafish: Duct of the adult kidney (mesonephros), present bilaterally ventral to the somites and leading to the cloacal chamber[ZFA].

name: renal duct
description: A tube in the kidney that collect and transport urine.

name: gastrula
description: Organism at the gastrula stage.

name: dorsal fin proximal radial cartilage 1
description: dorsal fin proximal radial 1 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: sclera
description: Opaque fibrous outer layer of the eyeball[ZFA,Kardong,WP].

name: roof plate of diencephalon
description: A roof plate that is part of a diencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: masseter muscle
description: Pharyngeal arch 1 muscle that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors, is innervated by masseteric nerve branches of the trigeminal nerve (CN V), and attaches to mandible and zygomatic arch.

name: pulmonary capillary
description: A capillary that is part of a lung.

name: lower primary molar tooth
description: A primary molar tooth that is part of a lower jaw region.

name: primitive urogenital sinus
description: the ventral part of the cloaca remaining after septation of the rectum, which further develops into part of the bladder, part of the prostatic part of the male urethra and the urethra and vestibule in females

name: rib 10
description: The tenth rib has only a single articular facet on its head. [WP,unvetted].

name: mucosa of larynx
description: The mucous lining of the larynx, which is composed of squamous epithelium in the upper larynx and ciliated columnar epithelium in the lower larynx.

name: vestibulocochlear nerve
description: Cranial nerve that transmits sound and equilibrium (balance) information from the inner ear to the brain.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of inferior colliculus
M. semitendinosus
description: Originates by two tendons: one on the postero-ventral aspect of the pelvic rim, the other, a dorsal tendon from the postero-dorsal pelvic rim under the ventral edge of M. semimembranosus. Inserts on the ventral surface of the tibiofibula.

name: costotransverse joint
description: The facet of the tubercle of the rib forms an articulation with the adjacent transverse process of a thoracic vertebra. This is a plane type synovial joint called the costotransverse joint. This articulation is present in all but the eleventh and twelfth ribs. Ribs 1 to 10 have two joints in close proximity posteriorly; the costovertebral joints and the costotranseverse joints. This arrangement restrains the motion of the ribs allowing them to work in a parallel fashion during breathing. If a typical rib had only one joint posteriorly the resultant swivel action would allow a rib to be non-parallel with respect to the neighboring ribs making for a very inefficient respiratory mechanism. The ventral rami innervate the costotransverse joints. Therefore, therapeutic medial branch blocks are ineffectual. The ligaments of the joint are: Articular capsule Posterior costotransverse Anterior costotransverse Ligament of the neck of the rib Ligament of the tubercle of the rib

name: pectoral fin skeleton
description: Paired fin skeleton that consists of the supporting endochondral proximal and distal radials and the dermal fins rays or lepidotrichia. The pectoral fin skeleton is located in the thoracic region of the body and articulates with the scapula and coracoid.

name: manual digit 8 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 8 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: prootic-exoccipital joint
description: Joint that articulates the prootic and exoccipital. Prootic-exoccipital joint is paired.

name: primitive mesonephric nephron
description: Anatomical cluster which give rise to mature mesonephric nephrons. Zebrafish continously generate new mesonephric nephrons.

name: follicular antrum
description: Region of ovarian follicle filled with follicular fluid.

name: arch of centrum of vertebra
description: An arch-shaped structure of the vertebra that extends dorsally (neural arch) or ventrally (hemal arch) from the vertebral centrum

name: somite 7
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: preural 1 vertebra
description: Last caudal vertebra identified as the point at which the caudal vessels bifurcate, leaving the protection of the haemal arches of the caudal vertebrae and running laterally to the hypurals. This vertebra bears, commonly, a well-developed haemal arch and its spine (parhypural).

name: deferent duct artery
description: An artery in males that provides blood to the vas deferens. The artery usually arises from the anterior trunk of the superior vesical artery. It accompanies the vas deferens into the testis, where it anastomoses with the testicular artery. In this way it also supplies blood to the testis and epididymis. A small branch supplies the ureter[WP].

name: medial olfactory stria
description: The medial olfactory stria turns medialward behind the parolfactory area and ends in the subcallosal gyrus; in some cases a small intermediate stria is seen running backward to the anterior perforated substance.

name: ocular surface region
description: The integrated unit (of the eye) that consists of the conjunctiva, the corneal surface, and the ocular mucosal adnexa including the lid margins and the meibomian gland openings, the lacrimal glands and the lacrimal drainage system, all which are critical to maintain ocular surface integrity and provide protection from external antigens and pathogenic microorganisms.

name: replacement tooth
description: Tooth (often obscured from view) in a 'waiting' position that will replace an existing tooth (i.e. a tooth that is well visible in the jaw)

name: muscularis mucosa
description: A the thin layer of smooth muscle found in most parts of the gastrointestinal tract, located outside the lamina propria mucosae and separating it from the submucosa[WP].

name: stroma
description: Connective, non-functional supportive framework of a biological cell, tissue, or organ. Contrast with parenchyma.

name: interventricular septum endocardium
description: An endocardium that is part of a interventricular septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: amphid sensory organ
description: Amphid sensory organs are the sensory organs of nematodes[GO].

name: stria vascularis of cochlear duct
description: The upper portion of the spiral ligament contains numerous capillary loops and small blood vessels, and is termed the stria vascularis. It produces endolymph for the scala media, one of the three fluid-filled compartments of the cochlea. [WP,unvetted].

name: somatic sensory system
description: The sensory system for the sense of touch and pain.

name: nose anterior margin
description: Subdivision of the head consisting of the area along the front edge of the external nose.

name: zygapophysis
description: Paired processes at the cephalic and caudal ends of the neural arch. They function as interlocking structures between adjacent vertebrae, and limit dorsoventral flexion and lateral movement of the column in the trunk region[AAO]. The articular processes or zygapophyses of a vertebra, in human anatomy contain two superior and two inferior, spring from the junctions of the pedicles and laminae. These stick out of an end of a vertebra to lock with a zygapophysis on the next vertebra, to make the backbone more stable. The superior processes project upward from a lower vertebra, and their articular surfaces are directed more or less backward. The inferior processes project downward from a higher vertebra, and their articular surfaces are directed more or less forward and outward. The articular surfaces are coated with hyaline cartilage.

name: pyramidal decussation
description: Part of medulla comprising a white matter structure containing nerve fibers of the pyramidal tract crossing from one side of the brain to the other (MM)

name: metanephric early distal convoluted tubule
description: The metanephric early distal convoluted tubule contains metanephric DCT cells and is vasopressin-insensitive[GO].

name: pulmonary trunk
description: An arterial trunk which is continuous with the heart and branches into the pulmonary arteries.

name: rectal lumen
description: An anatomical space that surrounded_by a rectum.

name: colorectum
description: The subdivision of the digestive tract that consists of the colon and the rectum.

name: nucleus raphe pallidus
description: The nucleus raphe pallidus receives afferent connections from the periaqueductal gray, the paraventricular hypothalamic nucleus, central nucleus of the amygdala, lateral hypothalamic area, and parvocellular reticular nucleus. Also, the pallidus receives afferents from the medial preoptic area, median preoptic nucleus and lateral paragigantocellular reticular nuclei . The pallidus has recently been shown to be involved in the activation of a fever as an immunoreaction. It has been implied that the preoptic area is constantly inhibiting the raphe pallidus, especially the rostral portion, with GABA. When the preoptic area receives immune signals from the body, the inhibition stops and the rostral portion of the raphe pallidus excites the intermediolateral cell column, which induces a fever . The raphe pallidus has also been known to mediate the tachycardia response, an extremely high heart rate known to be incited by emotional or psychological stress. Microinjections of a GABA-a antagonist into the raphe pallidus, induces an increased heart rate. Conversely, microinjections of muscimol, a GABA-a agonist, inhibit tachycardia in rats under air-stress stimuli. In both of these cases, GABA is mediating two different sympathetic responses, so clearly the nucleus raphe pallidus is a far more a complex nucleus than previously thought. [WP,unvetted].

name: pharyngeal arch mesenchymal region
description: A portion of mesenchymal tissue associated with an individual pharyngeal arch.

name: skeleton of pelvic complex
description: The collection of all skeletal elements in a pelvic complex - i.e. the combination of free limb or fin plus pelvic girdle.

name: supraneural 2 bone
description: Supraneural bone located dorsal to vertebra 2.

name: m. rhomboideus anterior
description: Muscle which originates on the posterior surface of the frontoparietal and the anterior part of the dorsal fascia. Inserts on the ventral surface of the anteromedial corner of the suprascapula.

name: footplate of pars media plectri
description: Independent, horizontal bar of cartilage located on the anterior part of the fenestra ovalis in front of the pars interna plectri.

name: embryonic/larval sensillum
description: Any sensillum (UBERON:6007152) that is part of some larva (UBERON:6001727).

name: obturator muscle
description: One of: obturator externus or obturator internus

name: sternebra
description: one of the bony segments of the sternum[TFD].

name: ceratobranchial 2 bone
description: Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 2 cartilage or bone.

name: levator quadrati
description: Responsible for the closing of the jaw.

name: crus of penis
description: the continuation of each corpus cavernosum of the penis, diverging posteriorly to be attached to the pubic arch.

name: anal sinus
description: Furrows, with pouchlike recesses at the lower end, separating the rectal columns.

name: ruminant reticulum
description: The second stomach of ruminants. It lies almost in the midline in the front of the abdomen, in contact with the liver and diaphragm and communicates freely with the RUMEN via the ruminoreticular orifice. The lining of the reticulum is raised into folds forming a honeycomb pattern over the surface. (From Concise Veterinary Dictionary, 1988)

name: neural system
description: A set of neural structures that subserve a specific function, e.g., visual system

name: pericardio-peritoneal canal mesothelium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a pericardio-peritoneal canal.

name: nonskeletal ligament
description: A ligament that does not connect two skeletal elements.

name: midbrain raphe nuclei
description: Midline nuclei found in the midbrain, includes the dorsal raphe nucleus and the rostral linear nucleus of raphe.

name: material entity in digestive tract
description: Any material entity that is located in the digestive tract. This includes undigested food and liquid as well as unexcreted waste products. It also includes other entities such as ingested stones used to aid digestion. Any microbial cells or cell populations are also included.

name: trunk or cervical vertebra
description: A vertebra in the trunk or cervical region. Includes all cervical, thoracic and lumbar vertebrae, but excludes caudal vertebra.

name: palpebral artery
description: An artery that supplies blood to an eyelid.

name: third ventricle choroid plexus epithelium
description: A choroid plexus epithelium that is part of a third ventricle [Automatically generated definition].

name: elbow joint
description: A joint that connects the forelimb zeugopod and stylopod skeletons[Obol].

name: obsolete regional part of sacral spinal cord gray matter
joint space of elbow
description: Joint cavity shared by all the joints of the elbow. The elbow joint is a compound joint that actually comprises three separate joints: the joints connecting the upper and lower arm: 1) Articulatio humero-ulnaris and 2) Articulatio humero-radialis as well as the proximal joint connecting the forarm bones: 3) Articulatio radio-ulnaris proximalis. All three share a joint cavity which is highly sinuated/scalloped/coved. Joint spaces of the elbow summarizes the joint cavity shared by all three adjoining joints of the elbow joint.

name: molecular layer of cerebellar cortex
description: The molecular layer is the outermost layer of the cerebellar cortex. It contains the parallel fibers of the granule cells, interneurons such as stellate and basket cells, and the dendrites of the underlying Purkinje cells

name: skeletal muscle tissue of biceps brachii
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a biceps brachii [Automatically generated definition].

name: left lateral ventricle
description: A telencephalic ventricle that is in_the_left_side_of a telencephalon.

name: spinothalamic tract of pons
description: Part of spinothalamic tract that is in the pontine tegmentum

name: middle phalanx of pedal digit 4
description: A middle phalanx that is part of a pedal digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: medial plantar artery
description: The medial plantar artery (internal plantar artery), much smaller than the lateral, passes forward along the medial side of the foot. It is at first situated above the Abductor hallucis, and then between it and the Flexor digitorum brevis, both of which it supplies. At the base of the first metatarsal bone, where it is much diminished in size, it passes along the medial border of the first toe, anastomosing with the first dorsal metatarsal artery. Small superficial digital branches accompany the digital branches of the medial plantar nerve and join the plantar metatarsal arteries of the first three spaces. [WP,unvetted].

name: nucleus H of ventral tegmentum
description: A nucleus present in the ventral tegmentum of squalomorph sharks.

name: sacro-iliac joint
description: The joint in the bony pelvis between the sacrum and the ilium of the pelvis, which are joined by strong ligaments.

name: levator palatoquadrati
description: A muscle derivative of the mandibular levator that runs from the chondrocranium to the palatoquadrate cartilage. Found in sharks

name: left testicular artery
description: A testicular artery that supplies a left testicle.

name: anal sac gland secretion
description: A bodily secretion that is produced by a gland of anal sac.

name: parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3 + rib of vertebra 4
skin of abdomen
description: A zone of skin that is part of an abdomen [Automatically generated definition].

name: sacral neural crest
description: One of the 5 distinct and partially overlapping functional domains of the premigratory neural crest. The vagal and sacral neural crest cells develop into the ganglia of the enteric nervous system, also known as the parasympathetic ganglia.

name: maxillary-premaxillary suture
description: A suture between the maxilla and premaxilla.

name: amnioserosa
description: A single extraembryonic epithelium, which closes the germband dorsally.

name: rostral plate
description: Dermal bone that is located on midline of snout in skin above mesethmoid and lateral ethmoid bones. Rostral plate bears type 1 odontodes and is unpaired.

name: future nucleus ambiguus
description: A gray matter that has the potential to develop into a nucleus ambiguus.

name: Meyer's loop of optic radiation
description: part of the optic radiation which sweeps back on itself into the temporal lobe, just lateral to the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle.

name: pectoral fin ray 7
description: Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the seventh most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.

name: panniculus carnosus muscle
description: The skeletal muscle layer in the superficial fascia deep to the panniculus adiposus

name: trigeminal foramen
description: Foramen through which cranial nerve V (trigeminal) exits.

name: annulus fibrosus
description: A ring of fibrous or fibrocartilaginous tissue (as of an intervertebral disk or surrounding an orifice of the heart).

name: notochordal process
description: A midline cellular cord formed from the migration of mesenchymal cells from the primitive knot

name: thymus lymphoid tissue
description: A portion of lymphoid tissue that is part of a thymus [Automatically generated definition].

name: mucosa of right uterine tube
description: A mucosa that is part of a right uterine tube [Automatically generated definition].

name: left renal pelvis
description: A renal pelvis that is part of a left ureter.

name: embryonic structure
description: Anatomical structure that is part of an embryo.

name: vasa vasorum
description: Nutrient blood vessels which supply the walls of large arteries or veins.

name: Ongur, Price, and Ferry (2003) area Ial
description: Insula agranular lateral area

name: lateral gland of orbital region
description: A gland that is located in or around the ocular region, nearer the outer canthi.

name: tail skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a tail [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of thoracic spinal cord gray matter
phrenic vein
description: The veins that run parallel to the phrenic arteries which include the two superior and two inferior phrenic veins.

name: epithelium of soft palate
description: An epithelium that is part of a soft palate [Automatically generated definition].

name: mesethmoid element
description: An endochondral element of the nasal capsule that forms septum between nasal capsules and usually remains unossified in mammals

name: colonic epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a colon [Automatically generated definition].

name: coprodeum
description: Most proximal cloacal compartment, into which the large intestine empties[Kardong]

name: manual digit 5 phalanx endochondral element
description: A manual digit 5 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: stratum intermedium of epidermis
description: A temporary layer between old and new skin that is invalided by white blood cells[Kardong].

name: gland of tongue
description: Any of the mucous, serous, or mixed glands that empty their secretions onto the surface of the tongue.

name: alular digit plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of alular digit plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: right lung middle lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a middle lobe of right lung.

name: anterior digastric muscle
description: The anterior digastric is a pharyngeal arch I muscle that participates in oral/pharygeal behaviors and is innervated by the nerve to mylohyoid (a branch of the third division of the trigeminal nerve), is attached to the mandible and to the hyoid apparatus, and it is superficial to mylohyoid muscle.

name: M. extensor cruris brevis
description: Originates by a slender tendon from the ventral surface of the medial condyle of the femur and passes over the knee to insert as a fleshy belly on the ventro-lateral surface of the tibiofibula.

name: vinculum tendon of wing
description: A tendon which emerges from the distal end of the humerus and follows the posterior margin of the wing, attaching at the distal end of digit 2. The raches of the remiges (i.e., the stems of the flight feathers) are stabilized by passing through the vinculum.

name: rostral anterior cingulate cortex
description: Component of the cingulate cortex. The rostral boundary was the first appearance of the cingulate sulcus (inferior to the superior frontal sulcus) whereas the caudal boundary was the first appearance of the genu of the corpus callosum. The medial boundary was the medial aspect of the cortex. The supero-lateral boundary was the superior frontal gyrus whereas the infero-lateral boundary was defined as the medial division of the orbitofrontal gyrus (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: mesopterygium cartilage
description: The median, elongated basal cartilage of the pectoral fin.

name: posterior arch of atlas
description: In a cervical vertebra, the posterior arch forms about two-fifths of the circumference of the ring: it ends behind in the posterior tubercle, which is the rudiment of a spinous process and gives origin to the Recti capitis posteriores minores.

name: pedal digit 5 epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a pedal digit 5.

name: spinal nerve trunk
description: trunk part of spinal nerve, where dorsal and ventral roots meet to form the spinal nerve, before branching off to dorsal and ventral rami.

name: ventral tegmental area
description: Unpaired midbrain region situated in the ventromedial portion of the reticular formation. The VTA is medial to the substantia nigra and ventral to the red nucleus, and extends caudally from the posterior hypothalamus in the diencephalon. The VTA contains dopamine neurons that project to various limbic and cortical areas and is a critical component of the brain's reward circuitry.

name: right lung lobar bronchus epitheium
description: A epithelium that is part of a lobar bronchus of right lung.

name: semicircular canal ampulla
description: The spherical enlargement at the base of each semicircular canal where they connect with the utricle, containing the crista ampullaris which detects movement of the fluid within the canals

name: epicardium of ventricle
description: An epicardial layer that lines a cardiac ventricle

name: hyoid bone body
description: The main curve of the hyoid bone, from which the horns extend

name: rhombomere 8
description: the eighth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

name: lamina of septum pellucidum
description: One of two layers of both white and gray matter of the septum pellucidum. During fetal development there is a space between the two laminae called the cavum septum pellucidum which, in ninety per cent of cases, disappears during infancy.

name: incisor mesenchyme
description: A odontogenic mesenchyme that is part of a incisor tooth.

name: epicoracoid bridge
description: A pair of cartilaginous expansions (one from each epicoracoid cartilage) that project anteriorly. They articulate anteriorly with the omosternum.

name: obsolete supraangular
description: The suprangular or surangular is a jaw bone found in most land vertebrates, except mammals. It's usually in the back of the jaw, on the upper edge, and is connected to all other jaw bones: dentary, angular, splenial and articular. It is often a muscle attachment site.

name: cardiac muscle tissue
description: Muscle tissue composed of cardiac muscle cells, forming the muscles of the heart[ZFA,modified].

name: internal trochanter
description: A boney projection on the internal diaphysis of the femur anterior or medial to the intertrochanteric fossa, below the femoral head. Muscle attachment site for ventral muscle mass notably the puboischiofemoralis externus. Modified from Romer 1956

name: pars postrema of ventral lateral nucleus
glenoid head of coracoid
description: Lateral end of the coracoid, which forms the medial portion of the glenoid fossa.

name: vomeronasal system
