name: obsolete right lung caudal lobe lobar bronchus mesenchyme
pedal digit 2 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a foot digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal carpal bone 1 cartilage
description: A distal carpal bone 1 endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: obsolete chondrocranium bone
description: A bone that is part of a chondrocranium [Automatically generated definition].

name: subcupular meshwork of statoconial membrane
description: An acellular membrane in the inner ear that is part of the statoconial membrane and consists of long branching filaments cross-bridged to one another. The filaments are continuous with those of the otolithic membrane on one side and with the surface of the epithelium on the other.

name: meninx of telencephalon
description: A meninx that is part of a telencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: areola
description: Subdivision of breast which consists of skin, connective tissue and smooth muscle bundle and modified sebaceous glands and which surrounds the nipple.

name: submucosa of main bronchus
description: A submucosa that is part of a main bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: urachal lumen
description: A anatomical space that is enclosed by a urachus.

name: sphenoid cartilage element
description: A sphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: feces
description: Portion of semisolid bodily waste discharged through the anus[MW,modified]

name: excreta
description: A portion of organism substance that is the product of an excretion process that will be eliminated from the body. An excretion process is elimination by an organism of the waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity

name: hindlimb blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a hindlimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: spongiose tissue of corpus cavernosum maxillaris
description: A erectile tissue that is part of a corpus cavernosum maxillaris.

name: tracheal mucosa
description: A mucosa that is part of a respiratory airway.

name: small intestine smooth muscle longitudinal layer
description: A longitudinal muscle layer of muscular coat that is part of a small intestine smooth muscle.

name: obsolete head muscle
description: Muscle which is part of the head.

name: hypaxial region somite 23
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: median thyrohyoid ligament
description: The middle thicker part of the thyrohyoid membrane is termed the median thyrohyoid ligament (middle hyothyroid ligament, middle thyrohyoid ligament), its lateral thinner portions are pierced by the superior laryngeal vessels and the internal branch of the superior laryngeal nerve. Its anterior surface is in relation with the Thyreohyoideus, Sternohyoideus, and Omohyoideus, and with the body of the hyoid bone

name: interstitial nucleus of Cajal
description: The largest and most prominent of the cell groups of the medial longitudinal fasciculus

name: branchial basket
description: The network-like non-segmented cartilaginous skeleton of the gill region of Petromyzontiformes and Holocephali, connected to the heart and surrounding respiratory tissue.

name: alveolar ridge of premaxilla
description: The thickened ridge of bone that contains the tooth sockets on the premaxilla.

name: splenius cervicis
description: A muscle that arises from the spinous processes of the third to the sixth thoracic vertebrae and inserts into the posterior tubercles of the transverse processes of the upper two or three cervical vertebrae[WP,modified].

name: rhombomere 6 lateral wall
description: A rhombomere lateral wall that is part of a rhombomere 6.

name: Douglas' pouch
description: The rectouterine pouch (or rectouterine excavation, rectovaginal, Ehrhardt-Cole Recess or Pouch of Douglas) is the extension of the peritoneal cavity between the rectum and back wall of the uterus in the female human body. The rectouterine pouch is used in the treatment of end-stage renal failure in patients who are treated by peritoneal dialysis. The tip of the dialysis catheter is placed into the deepest point of the pouch. In women it is the deepest point of the peritoneal cavity, posterior to (behind) the uterus and anterior to (in front of) rectum. (The pouch on the other side of the uterus is the vesicouterine excavation. ) It is near the posterior fornix of the vagina. In men, the region corresponding to the rectouterine pouch is the rectovesical excavation, which lies between the urinary bladder and rectum. (There is no equivalent to the vesicouterine excavation.)

name: glial limiting membrane
description: The meshwork of astrocytic foot processes (glial end feet) covered by a basal lamina adjacent to the inner pial surface of the central nervous system.

name: coronary sinus valve
description: Vestigial cardiac valve which is continuous with the valve of the inferior vena cava[FMA].

name: cervical vertebra 1 anterior tubercle
description: The conical ventral projection on the arch of the atlas

name: flexor tubercle of ungual
description: Eminence on the proximo-dorsal surface of the ungual, for attachment of flexor muscles.

name: vestibular nuclear complex
description: Nuclear complex containing the vestibular nuclei.

name: preacetabular expansion
description: Ventral portion of the ilial corpus, located anteroventral to the acetabulum.

name: kidney outer medulla inner stripe
description: The inner stripe is a deep, centrally located portion of the renal outer medulla and is traversed by thick and thin portions of nephron tubules

name: digit 2 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 2 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: acromion
description: Region of the scapula where the latter meets with the clavicle: attachment point of the clavicle to the scapula in some taxa.

name: atlantal cotyle
description: Anterior, single or paired concave facets for articulation with the condyle(s) of the urostyle.

name: lateral ganglionic eminence
description: A distinct elevation of a transient proliferating cell mass of the fetal subventricular zone; this mass contributes most of its cells to the striatum; however, neocortex, thalamus, septum and olfactory bulb neurons are also partly derived from the LGE

name: muscularis mucosae of intestine
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a intestine.

name: transverse occipital sulcus
description: The transverse occipital sulcus is a structure in the occipital lobe. The transverse occipital sulcus is continuous with the posterior end of the occipital ramus of the intraparietal sulcus, and runs across the upper part of the lobe, a short distance behind the parietoC6ccipital fissure.

name: ventral pancreatic duct
description: A duct joining the pancreas to the common bile duct to supply pancreatic juices which aid in digestion provided by the exocrine pancreas. The pancreatic duct joins the common bile duct just prior to the ampulla of Vater, after which both ducts perforate the medial side of the second portion of the duodenum at the major duodenal papilla.

name: pancreatic duct
description: A duct that collects and carries secretions of the exocrine pancreas to the intestine.

name: limen of insula
description: The anterior basal part of the insular cortex, which separates the lateral surface of the insula from the anterior perforated substance (Heimer, The Human Brain and Spinal Cord, 2nd ed., 1995, pg 80).

name: element Y of hind mesopodium
description: Oval tarsal element that is located on the anteromedial side of the tibiale. Anteriorly, it articulates with the proximal prehallux, tarsals 1, 2, and 3.

name: inferior pancreaticoduodenal vein
description: A blood vessel running parallel to the inferior pancreatico-duodenal artery that drains blood from the pancreas and duodenum into the splenic vein.

name: webbing of bone in vertebral column
description: In anurans, pair of bony plates that connect the posteromedial margins of the sacral diapophyses with the lateral margins of the anterior portion of the urostyle.

name: interlobar artery
description: An artery that supplies a renal lobe.

name: solum nasi
description: Unpaired, horizontal plate that forms the floor of the nasal capsule.

name: left lobe of liver
description: The left lobe is smaller and more flattened than the right. It is situated in the epigastric and left hypochondriac regions. Its upper surface is slightly convex and is moulded on to the diaphragm; its under surface presents the gastric impression and omental tuberosity. [WP,unvetted].

name: dartos muscle
description: The dartos fascia is a fat-free layer of smooth muscular fiber outside the external spermatic fascia but below the skin. It is a continuation of Scarpa's Fascia which is a membranous layer of the subcutaneous tissue in the abdominal wall.

name: obsolete regional part of cingulate gyrus
lingual vein
description: The lingual veins begin on the dorsum, sides, and under surface of the tongue, and, passing backward along the course of the lingual artery, end in the internal jugular vein. The vena comitans of the hypoglossal nerve (ranine vein), a branch of considerable size, begins below the tip of the tongue, and may join the lingual; generally, however, it passes backward on the Hyoglossus, and joins the common facial.

name: calcaneal tuber
description: An enlargement of the distal region of the calcaneum that corresponds to the attachment site for the foot extensor muscles.

name: prothoracic metatarsus
description: First tarsal segment of the prothoracic leg. Proximally, it articulates with the tibia and distally with the second tarsal segment. Its surface is covered with eight longitudinal rows of bristles and with transverse rows of bristles (TR) in the anterior compartment, between proximo-distal rows 7 and 8. There is sexual dimorphism in the number of TRs (transverse row bristles, TR). In males, 2 TRs are replaced by the sex comb and one central bristle.

name: cell cluster organ
description: A small cluster of cells of various types which form a discrete structure, largely delimited by a morphological boundary and whose components work together to make the whole structure capable of a specific function.

name: entopterygoid tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to the entopterygoid bone.

name: postcranial axial cartilage
description: Cartilage which is part of the axial skeleton.

name: cuneus cortex
description: Component of the occipital lobe. The rostral boundary was the first coronal slice above the calcarine sulcus where the cuneus cortex becomes visible whereas the caudal boundary was the last slice where the calcarine sulcus was visualized. The medial boundary was the most medial portion of the occipital and parietal cortices. The superio-lateral boundary was the parieto-occipital fissure whereas the inferolateral boundary was the pericalcarine cortex (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: quadrant of breast
description: The part of the breast that is bordered by the intermammary line and a perpendicular line bisecting the nipple.

name: body of mandible
description: The zone of the mandible that carries the teeth.

name: embryonic/larval imaginal precursor
description: Imaginal precursor that is part of the embryo/larva.

name: substantia gelatinosa of lumbar spinal cord dorsal horn
description: A substantia gelatinosa that is part of a lumbar spinal cord dorsal horn.

name: thymus trabecula
description: the thymic connective tissue which extends into the parenchyma

name: trabecula communis
description: Cartilage formed via medial fusion between bilaterally paired trabecula crani.

name: periorbital skin
description: A zone of skin in the periorbital region of the face.

name: interventricular septum membranous part
description: The membranous portion of the wall between the two lower chambers of the heart

name: island of Calleja
description: One of the seven small groups of granule cells in the polymorph layer of the olfactory tubercle and one large group, the insula magna, which lies along the border between septum, nucleus accumbens and nucleus of the diagonal band.

name: cavity of left atrium
description: luminal space of the left atrium of the heart.

name: epithelium of shoulder
description: An epithelium that is part of a shoulder [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior mesencephalic central artery
description: Arteries that irrigate rostral regions of the midbrain. They extend between the Basial communicating artery to the anterior cerebral vein. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 21
description: Brodmann area 21, or BA21, is part of the temporal cortex in the human brain. The region encompasses most of the lateral temporal cortex, a region believed to play a part in auditory processing and language. Language function is left lateralized in most individuals. BA21 is superior to BA20 and inferior to BA40 and BA41. This area is also known as middle temporal area 21. It is a subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined temporal region of cerebral cortex. In the human it corresponds approximately to the middle temporal gyrus. It is bounded rostrally by the temporopolar area 38 (H), ventrally by the inferior temporal area 20, caudally by the occipitotemporal area 37 (H), and dorsally by the superior temporal area 22 (Brodmann-1909). [WP,unvetted].

name: chordal neural plate
description: The portion of neural plate posterior to the mid-hindbrain junction.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 29
description: Brodmann area 29, also known as granular retrolimbic area 29 or granular retrosplenial cortex, is a cytoarchitecturally defined portion of the retrosplenial region of the cerebral cortex. In the human it is a narrow band located in the isthmus of cingulate gyrus. Cytoarchitecturally it is bounded internally by the ectosplenial area 26 and externally by the agranular retrolimbic area 30 (Brodmann-1909).

name: arcuate nucleus of hypothalamus
description: The arcuate nucleus (or infundibular nucleus) is an aggregation of neurons in the mediobasal hypothalamus, adjacent to the third ventricle and the median eminence. The arcuate nucleus includes several important populations of neurons, including: Neuroendocrine neurons, Centrally-projecting neurons and Others. [WP,unvetted].

name: median caudal cartilage
description: Cartilage associated with hypurals.

name: middle ear
description: The middle ear is the air-filled cavity within the skull of vertebrates that lies between the outer ear and the inner ear. It is linked to the pharynx (and therefore to outside air) via the Eustachian tube and in mammals contains the three ear ossicles, which transmit auditory vibrations from the outer ear (via the tympanum) to the inner ear (via the oval window)[GO].

name: obsolete superficial feature part of telencephalon
suspensorium
description: (1) the arrangement of bones which supports the jaw from the braincase; (2) in teleost fish, a large, usually triangular, bone which supports the jaw. The teleost suspensorium is formed by fusion of various elements which vary among different taxa.

name: late embryo
description: An embryo that is at the late embryonic stage; this stage covers late steps of the embryogenesis with a fully formed embryo still developing before birth or egg hatching.

name: epimysium
description: Epimysium is a layer of connective tissue which ensheaths the entire muscle. It is composed of dense irregular connective tissue. It is continuous with fascia and other connective tissue wrappings of muscle including the endomysium, and perimysium. It is also continuous with tendons where it becomes thicker and collagenous.

name: occipital bun
description: A prominent bulge, or projection, of the occipital bone at the back of the skull[WP].

name: paravertebral ganglion
description: Trunk ganglion which is part of a bilaterally paired set of sympathetic ganglia located anterior and lateral to the spinal cord.

name: meningeal branch of mandibular nerve
description: The meningeal branch of the mandibular nerve (recurrent branch, nervus spinosus) is a branch of the mandibular nerve that supplies the dura mater.

name: pedicellaria
description: A small wrench or claw-shaped structure commonly found on Echinoderms, particularly in sea stars (class Asteroidea) and sea urchins (class Echinoidea). Pedicellariae are poorly understood but in some taxa, they are thought to keep the body surface clear of algae, encrusting organisms, and other debris in conjunction with the ciliated epidermis present in all echinoderms. Pedicellariae in some taxa, such as the deep-sea Brisingida, and the Antarctic Labidiaster are known to function in food capture. In forcipulate sea stars, each pedicellaria is typically composed three forceps-like valves. Other asteroids can have pedicellariae composed of only two components. In some asteroid sea stars pedicellariae are present around the base of a spine or on the surface of the animal's body. In other sea stars, they are present in pits on the abactinal, marginal, or actinal surface; oftentimes on the adambulacral plate adjacent to the tube foot furrow.

name: anterior limb of ceratobranchial 5 bone
description: Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 bone part of ceratobranchial 5 bone.

name: cephalic clasper
description: A mace-like spiny-headed rod found on the mid-dorsal surface of heads of male Holocephali. Thought to aid in holding the female during copulation.

name: afferent portion of pharyngeal arch artery
description: A section of a pharyngeal arch artery that delivers blood to the gills.

name: regurgitated pellet
description: A mass of undigested parts of a bird's food that some bird species occasionally regurgitate from their proventriculus.

name: chest organ
description: An organ that is part of a chest [Automatically generated definition].

name: hematopoietic system
description: Anatomical system that is involved in the production of hematopoietic cells.

name: integumental taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located external to the digestive tube, on the head or body, as found in species such as goldfish.

name: obsolete arthropod oviduct
description: A tube that connects ovary to the uterus.

name: hypoconid
description: The labial most of three cusps on the talonoid (posterior) end of lower molariform teeth. (modified from http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/collections/mammal_anatomy/cheek_teeth_structure/)

name: cruciate ligament of knee
description: One of a pair of ligaments arranged like a letter X.[1] They occur in several joints of the body, such as the knee. In a fashion similar to the cords in a toy Jacob's ladder, the crossed ligaments stabilize the joint while allowing a very large range of motion[WP].

name: philtrum
description: the vertical groove found on the median line of the upper lip, extending to the nose

name: pedal digit epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a toe [Automatically generated definition].

name: cervicothoracic ganglion
description: the group of neurons formed by the fusion of the inferior cervical and first thoracic ganglia

name: photoreceptor inner segment layer
description: Layer of the retina composed of the inner segments of the photoreceptor cells.

name: thoracodorsal vein
description: companion vein of the thoracodorsal artery, draining the apical part of the latissimus dorsi and merging with the circumflex scapular vein to form a subscapular vein

name: gnathal segment
description: The head segments that develop posterior to the embryonic/larval mouth.

name: cornea
description: the transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

name: jaw depressor muscle
description: A muscle whose action is to depress the lower jaw.

name: white matter
description: Neural tissue consisting of myelinated axons connecting grey matter areas of the central nervous system.

name: trachea basement membrane
description: A basement membrane that is part of a trachea.

name: pedal digit 3 digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 3 plus the associated metapodial element.

name: occipital segment
description: Metameric segment forming the back of the skull.

name: associated mesenchyme of otic placode
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a otic placode.

name: antler pedicle
description: Attachment point for antler on skull

name: urachus epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a urachus.

name: obsolete regional part of medial mammillary nucleus
presumptive rhombomere 6
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 6.

name: basibranchial 3 bone
description: Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 3 (pharyngeal arch 5). Typically develops in the anterior copula cartilage.

name: m. dorsalis scapulae
description: Muscle which originates on the lateral surface of the suprascapulae and inserts on the deltoid crest of the humerus.

name: hypaxial musculature
description: Musculature that is derived from the hypaxial myotome region, trunk muscles that lie ventral to the horizontal septum of the vertebrae. Hypaxial muscles include some vertebral muscles, the diaphragm, the abdominal muscles, and all limb muscles.

name: pulmonary valve cusp
description: The three fibrous triangular components and associated flap of the pulmonary valve

name: long head of biceps brachii
description: The long head originates on the supraglenoid tubercle just above the shoulder joint from where its tendon passes down along the intertubercular groove of the humerus into the joint capsule of the shoulder joint. [1] When the humerus is in motion, the tendon of the long head is held firmly in place in the intertubercular groove by the greater and lesser tubercles and the overlying transverse humeral ligament. During the motion from external to internal rotation, the tendon is forced medially against the lesser tubercle and superiorly against the transverse ligament.

name: epiphysis of tibia
description: An epiphysis that is part of a tibia [Automatically generated definition].

name: presphenoid bone
description: The anterior part of the body of the sphenoid bone in front of the basisphenoid. It is usually a separate bone in the young or fetus, but becomes a part of the sphenoid in the adult.

name: mandibular prominence
description: the paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip

name: ossified tendon
description: Sesamoid that develops within a tendon, distal to an articulation or joint.

name: rib 11
description: The eleventh rib has a single articular facet on the head, which is of rather large size. It has no necks or tubercles, and is pointed at its anterior ends. The eleventh has a slight angle and a shallow costal groove. [WP,unvetted].

name: epiphysial cluster
description: Early-developing neuronal cluster of the epiphysis. By 24 hpf the pioneer axon of the dorsoventral diencephalic tract (DVDT) has arisen from the ec and grown ventrally. As this axon encounters axons of the TPOC, it makes a near-90 rostral turn and grows rostrally among axons of the TPOC growing in the opposite direction. Ross et al., 1992.

name: obsolete ectepicondylar flange
description: Flange on the dorsal part of the humerus, associated with extensor musculature of the forelimb (manus. carpus).

name: proximal epiphysis of distal phalanx of manual digit 4
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manual digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: unbranched anal fin ray
description: Anal fin lepidotrichium that is not distally branched.[PHENOSCAPE:WD]

name: P3 area of pallium (Myxiniformes)
description: Area directly deep to the P2 area of pallium in hagfishes.

name: back blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a back [Automatically generated definition].

name: lymphatic vessel
description: A vessel that contains or conveys lymph, that originates as an interfibrillar or intercellular cleft or space in a tissue or organ, and that if small has no distinct walls or walls composed only of endothelial cells and if large resembles a vein in structure[BTO].

name: nervous system lemniscus
description: A bundle or band of sensory nerve fibers.

name: feather muscle
description: Similar to erector pili muscles of mammals; attached to the sides of the follicle; capable of elevating or lowering entire groups of feathers.

name: serosa of uterus
description: Outer serosa layer of the uterus.

name: Leydig's organ
description: A hemopoietic organ found in elasmobranchs. Along with the spleen and special tissue around the gonads, this structure produces red blood cells and it is nestled along the top and bottom of the esophagus.

name: obsolete notochordal cell
description: Cell of the notochord, often vacuolated or resembles a chondrocyte.

name: premaxillary tooth 3
description: Premaxillary tooth that is the third tooth in a premaxillary tooth series, and positioned adjacent to the second tooth.

name: lateral bone
description: Membrane bone extending between a transverse process of the second proximal dorsal-fin radial and the pleural rib of the sixth vertebra. Lateral bone is paired.

name: median nuchal line attachment site
description: Of the nuchal lines, the one that runs from the external occipital protuberance a ridge or crest is the median nuchal line, often faintly marked, descends to the foramen magnum, and affords attachment to the ligamentum nuchae.

name: extensor carpi radialis longus muscle
description: Extensor carpi radialis longus is one of the five main muscles that control movements at the wrist. This muscle is quite long, starting on the lateral side of the humerus, and attaching to the base of the second metacarpal bone (metacarpal of the index finger). [WP,unvetted].

name: Brodmann (1909) area 8
description: Brodmann area 8 is one of Brodmann's cytologically defined regions of the brain. It is involved in planning complex movements.

name: liver trabecula
description: A trabecula that is part of a liver

name: vestibular fissure of the cochlear canal
brown adipose tissue
description: A thermogenic form of adipose tissue that is composed of brown adipocytes[MP,modified]

name: pleural plate of carapace
description: One of eight pairs of plates on the carapace, forming two rows adjacent to the peripheral plates.

name: inguinal fat pad
description: encapsulated adipose tissue found in the groin

name: glenoid region
description: Region surrounding the glenoid fossa on the scapulocoracoid. [PHENOSCAPE:AD]

name: palatopharyngeus muscle
description: The palatopharyngeus or palatopharyngeal or pharyngopalatinus muscle is a long, fleshy fasciculus, narrower in the middle than at either end, forming, with the mucous membrane covering its surface, the palatopharyngeal arch.

name: basibranchial 5 cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7).

name: basibranchial 3 element
description: Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 3.

name: capitulum of humerus
description: A smooth, rounded eminence on the lateral portion of the articular surface of the humerus. It articulates with the cupshaped depression on the head of the radius, and is limited to the front and lower part of the bone.

name: premacula segment of distal straight tubule
lobar bronchus connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a lobar bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: pectoral fin proximal radial cartilage 2
description: pectoral fin proximal radial 2 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: presumptive mesoderm
description: Presumptive structure of the blastula that will develop into mesoderm.

name: right lung cranial lobe lobar bronchus mesenchyme
description: The right lung cranial lobe lobar bronchus mesenchyme is a type of tissue made up of loosely-packed mesenchymal cells in the right lung cranial lobe lobar bronchus

name: pedal digit 3 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a foot digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: perirhinal cortex of primate of Burwell et al 1995
description: Cortical region near the rhinal sulcus in primate encompassing Brodmann's areas 35 and 36

name: distal carpal bone 1 pre-cartilage condensation
description: A distal carpal bone 1 endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: forelimb zeugopod bone
description: A bone that is part of a lower arm [Automatically generated definition].

name: embryonic/larval central nervous system
description: Central nervous system of the embryo/larva.

name: arrector muscle of hair
description: A tiny smooth muscle that connects the hair follicle with the dermis.

name: mesangial matrix
description: Extracellular matrix secreted by intraglomerular mesangial cells

name: superior cervical ganglion
description: Trunk ganglion which is bilaterally paired and located at the anterior end of the sympathetic ganglion chain.

name: kidney blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a kidney [Automatically generated definition].

name: comb
description: A vascular, red cutaneous structure attached in a sagittal plane to the dorsum of the skull of domestic fowl. It consists of a base attached to the skull, a central mass called the body, a backward projecting blade and upward projecting points

name: obsolete hindbrain commissure
description: CNS white matter that crosses the midline within the hindbrain.

name: hypaxial region somite 26
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: lateral thyrohyoid ligament
description: The lateral thyrohyoid ligament (lateral hyothyroid ligament) is a round elastic cord, which forms the posterior border of the hyothyroid membrane and passes between the tip of the superior cornu of the thyroid cartilage and the extremity of the greater cornu of the hyoid bone. The recurrent laryngeal nerve typical lies lateral to this ligament

name: interanterodorsal nucleus of the thalamus
description: a group of nerve cells that bridges the midline of the thalamus between the anterodorsal nucleus of the thalamus of the left and right sides. According to Crosby (1962), it is more developed and consistently present in rodents than in primates (adapted from Brain Info).

name: urorectal septum
description: The ridge of mesoderm covered with endoderm that in the early developing embryo partitions the endodermal cloaca into the primary urogenital sinus (ventrally) and the anorectal canal of the hindgut (dorsally); the urorectal septum eventually fuses with the cloacal membrane, dividing it into a dorsal anal membrane and a larger ventral urogenital membrane - this area of fusion is represented in the adult by the perineal body[MP].

name: rhombomere 6 roof plate
description: A rhombomere roof plate that is part of a rhombomere 6.

name: hindlimb feather
description: A feather that is part of a hindlimb.

name: cardiac chamber
description: A cardiac chamber surrounds an enclosed cavity within the heart

name: ovarian artery
description: An artery that supplies an ovary.

name: left umbilical vein
description: An umbilical vein that is in the left side of a multicellular organism.

name: fossula tuberis superioris
description: Small depression dorsal to the proximal portion of the collum ilei and ventral to the ilial protuberance.

name: kidney outer medulla outer stripe
description: The outer stripe is the region of the kidney that lies distal to the line of termination of the straight renal tubules

name: deltopectoral crest
description: a rough elevation at the middle of the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus to which the deltoid muscle attaches

name: anterodorsal nucleus of medial geniculate body
caudal ganglionic eminence
description: The caudally located, distinct elevation of a transient proliferating cell mass of the fetal subventricular zone, located adjacent to the lateral ventricle

name: crypt of Lieberkuhn of small intestine
description: the tubular intestinal glands found in the mucosal membranes of the small intestine

name: parotid main excretory duct
description: The main excretory tubular canal that connects the parotid gland and the buccal mucosa and secretes a serous saliva into the vestibule of the oral cavity; it arises from the anterior surface of the gland, traversing the masseter muscle; the duct then pierces the buccinator muscle, moving medially, and opens out into the oral cavity near the second upper molar; saliva produced by acinar secretory cells in the glandular body flows sequentially through the intercalated ducts, striated ducts, and excretory ducts.

name: prehallux skeleton
description: One to three or four elements located ventral and medial to the metatarsal of digit I. When more than one elements are present, they are smaller than the proximal prehallux.

name: clavus
description: A rudder-like lobe formed from extensions of dorsal and anal fin rays.

name: ventral trigeminal tract
description: The Anterior trigeminothalamic tract (or ventral trigeminothalamic tract) serves as pain, temperature, and light touch pathway from the face, head and neck. It receives input from trigeminal nerve, facial nerve, glossopharyngeal nerve and vagus nerve. It receives discriminative tactile and pressure input from the contralateral principal sensory nucleus of CN V, which terminates in the ventral posteromedial nucleus of the thalamus. It then ascends to the contralateral sensory cortex via three neurons .

name: urostyle ridge
description: Longitudinal crest on the dorsal side of the urostyle formed by the caudal neural arches.

name: preural centrum 1+ ural centrum 1
description: Urostyle that is the result of fusion of preural centrum 1 with the first ural centrum (of polyural terminology).

name: quadrate lobe of liver
description: The quadrate lobe is an area of the liver situated on the under surface of the right lobe, bounded in front by the anterior margin of the liver; behind by the porta hepatis; on the right, by the fossa for the gall-bladder; and on the left, by the fossa for the umbilical vein. It is oblong in shape, its antero-posterior diameter being greater than its transverse. [WP,unvetted].

name: preacetabular process
description: Process on ilium located anteriorly to acetabulum.

name: anterior ectoderm
description: The region of the ectoderm anterior to the cephalic furrow.

name: supraorbital sensory canal
description: Sensory canal anterior to and in close proximity to the otic and infraorbital sensory canals. The supraorbital sensory canal is bilaterally paired.

name: pulmonary neuroendocrine body
description: corpuscular, organoid structures composed of PNECs, found as distinctive innervated clusters only within intrapulmonary airways, where they appear concentrated at airway branch points; NEBs reach from the basement membrane to the airway lumen and are thought to function as oxygen sensors.

name: pharyngobranchial 1 cartilage
description: Most anterior pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials.

name: metatarsophalangeal joint of pedal digit 2
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 2.

name: secretion of endocrine pancreas
description: A secretion that is part of a endocrine pancreas [Automatically generated definition].

name: inferior oblique extraocular muscle
description: thin, narrow muscle placed near the anterior margin of the floor of the orbit.

name: sclerotic ring
description: Sclerotic rings are rings of bone found in the eyes of several groups of vertebrate animals, except for mammals and crocodilians. They can be made up of single bones or small bones together. They are believed to have a role in supporting the eye, especially in animals whose eyes are not spherical, or which live underwater. Fossil sclerotic rings are known for a variety of extinct animals, including ichthyosaurs, pterosaurs, and dinosaurs, but are often not preserved[WP].

name: lateral septal complex
description: The lateral septal area; largest nuclear mass in this region, plays a pivotal role in various physiological processes, such as aggression, emotion, thermoregulation, water and food intake and sexual behaviour.

name: pedal digit phalanx endochondral element
description: A pedal digit phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: interventricular septum muscular part
description: The muscular portion of the wall between the two lower chambers of the heart

name: nucleus accumbens
description: A region of the brain consisting of a collection of neurons located in the forebrain ventral to the caudate and putamen. (caudoputamen in rodent) and continuous with these structures. There is no distinct boundary between the nucleus accumbens and the caudate/putamen, but in rodents, it can be identified by its lack of traversing fiber bundles in comparison to the dorsal striatum. Its principle neuron is the medium spiny neuron. Together with the neostriatum (caudate nucleus and putamen), the nucleus accumbens forms the striatum.

name: oropharyngeal gland
description: A gland that is part of a oropharynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: vibrissa follicle
description: one of the tubular invaginations of the epidermis enclosing the hair roots and from which grow the vibrissae located on the muzzle and face of many species

name: cavity of left ventricle
description: luminal space of the left ventricle of the heart.

name: interdigital region between digits 2 and 3
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a digit 2 and adjacent_to a digit 3.

name: extensor pollicis longus muscle
description: The Extensor pollicis longus is much larger than the Extensor pollicis brevis muscle, the origin of which it partly covers.

name: M. tibialis anticus brevis
description: Originates from the dorso-lateral surface of the tibiofibula and inserts on the proximo-medial surface of the tibiale dorsal to the medial head of M. tibialis anticus longus.

name: hypochord
description: The hypochord is a transient rod-like structure in the embryos of fish, lampreys and amphibians that is located immediately ventral to the notochord. The hypochord may play a role in positioning the dorsal aorta[GO].

name: rostral cartilage
description: Median chondrified cartilage bound to premaxillary ascending process by a rostro-premaxilla ligament.

name: vinculum of tendon
description: A tendinous band that connects the phalanges and the flexor muscles of the autopods.

name: pinna
description: The part of the ear that projects from the head, connecting to the external acoustic meatus.

name: parapophysis
description: Endochondral bone that forms from a lateral outgrowth of the basiventral arcualia and connects the rib with the vertebral centrum[TAO]. A lateral or ventrolateral projections of vertebrae to which ribs are attached in Danio rerio. ZFA: They can arise through replacement ossification of a basiventral or form directly in bone. They are separated from the centrum in basal teleosts, e.g., Leptolepis coryphaenoides, Megalops and Elops.

name: ophryon
description: The ophryon is the point in the forehead just above the optic foramen, or eyesocket, and glabella.

name: white fibrocartilage
description: fibrocartilage in which strong bundles of white fibrous tissue predominate.

name: parasympathetic ganglion
description: Ganglion containing neurons that receive innervation from parasympathetic neurons in the central nervous system and subserves parasympathetic functions through innervation of smooth muscle, cardiac muscle and glands.

name: dental follicle
description: A sac containing the developing tooth and its odontogenic organ. The dental follicle (DF) differentiates into the periodontal ligament. In addition, it may be the precursor of other cells of the periodontium, including osteoblasts, cementoblasts and fibroblasts. They develop into the alveolar bone, the cementum with Sharpey's fibers and the periodontal ligament fibers respectively.

name: incisive duct
description: an infrequent rudimentary duct, or protrusion of the mucous membrane into the incisive canal, on either side of the anterior extremity of the nasal crest

name: superior colliculus stratum zonale
description: Most superficial layer of the superior colliculus consisting primarily of thin fibers derived primarily from the occipital cortex (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 2nd 3d, 1981, pg. 544)

name: anterior limb of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage
description: Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage.

name: pelvic fin clasper
description: The rod-like extension of the medial portion of the pelvic fin in male Elasmobranchii and Holocephali. Claspers are used as intromittent organs (not in clasping), the grooves on their facing surfaces together forming a tube for the transmission of sperm when the claspers are held together. The anterior proximal opening is called the apopyle, the posterior distal opening the rhipidion

name: obsolete regional part of lumbar spinal cord dorsal horn
gray matter layer of superior colliculus
description: A central nervous system gray matter layer that is part of a superior colliculus.

name: apical ectodermal ridge median fin fold
description: Apical ectodermal ridge that is part of the median fin fold.

name: spermatic cord
description: The cord-like structure in males comprising the vas deferens and associated tissue that runs from the abdomen down to each testis[MP].

name: tooth enamel organ
description: A circumscribed mass of ectodermal cells which bud off from the dental lamina; it becomes cup-shaped and develops on its internal face the ameloblast layer of cells that produces the enamel cap of a developing tooth.

name: lymph
description: Lymph is the fluid that is formed when interstitial fluid enters the conduits of the lymphatic system through lymph capillaries[WP].

name: barbel taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located on a barbel.

name: medial tibial tarsal bone
description: Endochondral tarsal bone that is medially located and between the intermedium and centralia.

name: ventral striatum
description: A composite structure of the telencephalon that is defined in the striatopallidal system by connectivity and neurochemical staining. It includes the nucleus accumbens, the most ventral portions of the caudate nucleus and the putamen, the rostrolateral portion of the anterior perforated substance, the islands of Calleja and a rostral subcommissural portion of substantia innominata. The boundary between the ventral striatum and dorsal striatum is indistinct in sections stained for Nissl substance (Heimer-1995; adapted from Brain Info).

name: pubic symphysis
description: The firm fibrocartilaginous joint in the median plane between the two opposing surfaces of the pubic bones, which are united by an interpubic disc of fibrocartilage as well as the superior and arcuate pubic ligaments.

name: manual digit epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a finger [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of transverse frontopolar gyri complex
anterior olfactory nucleus
description: Laminated structure lying caudal to the olfactory bulb

name: lens of camera-type eye
description: Transparent part of camera-type eye that helps to refract light to be focused on the retina.

name: white matter of cerebellum
description: Regional part of cerebellum consisting of the myelinated axons lying deep to the granule cell layer, excluding the deep cerebellar nuclei and the cerebellar peduncles.

name: alveolar artery
description: A branch of the maxillary artery that is found in the gingiva, premolars, and molars.

name: pedal digit 4 digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 4 plus the associated metapodial element.

name: associated mesenchyme of midgut
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing midgut.

name: subhyoideus
description: Deep, visceral muscle associated with tongue movement.

name: urachus mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing urachus.

name: presumptive rhombomere 7
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 7.

name: basibranchial 4 bone
description: Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 4 (pharyngeal arch 6). Develops in posterior copula cartilage or basibranchial 4 cartilage.

name: levator mandibulae articularis
description: Muscle which is responsible for the closing of the jaw.

name: epaxial musculature
description: Musculature that is derived from the epaxial myotome region, ventral to the horizontal septum of the vertebrae. Epaxial muscles include other (dorsal) muscles associated with the vertebrae, ribs, and base of the skull.

name: pulmonary valve anulus
description: The fibrous ring of the pulmonary valve that attaches the cusps of pulmonary valve to the wall of right ventricle, and which consists of portions of the fibrous scallops of the anterior, right posterior and left posterior cusps

name: hypophysial artery
description: An artery that supplies the pituitary gland.

name: smooth muscle sphincter
description: A ring of smooth muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.

name: short head of biceps brachii
description: Proximally (towards the body), the short head of the biceps attaches to (originates from) the coracoid process at the top of the scapula.

name: epiphysis of femur
description: An epiphysis that is part of a femur [Automatically generated definition].

name: cerebellum external granule cell layer
description: transient layer of the cerebellar cortex present during development which is composed of dividing and migrating granule cells[MP]

name: maxillary prominence
description: the paired dorsal prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo that unite with the ipsilateral medial nasal process to form the upper jaw

name: rib 12
description: In humans: The twelfth rib has a single articular facet on the head, which is of rather large size. It has no necks or tubercles, and is pointed at its anterior ends. The twelfth has angle nor costal groove; it is much shorter than the eleventh rib, and its head is inclined slightly downward. Sometimes the twelfth rib is even shorter than the first rib. [WP,unvetted].

name: hemal prezygapophysis
description: Hemal prezygapophyses are paired, anteromedially directed processes arising from the bases of hemal arches, ligamentously joined to the hemal postzygapophyses of the preceding vertebra. Posterior caudal vertebrae close to the caudal fin lack hemal prezygopophyses.

name: articular surface
description: Anatomical surface that is part of a skeletal element and articulates with another skeletal element. [NI]

name: perivascular space
description: The space between a blood vessel and the pia mater.

name: proximal epiphysis of distal phalanx of manual digit 5
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manual digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: hypoglossal nerve
description: Cranial nerve that innervates the muscles of the tongue.

name: photophore
description: A light-emitting organ which appears as luminous spots on various marine animals, including fish and cephalopods.

name: P4 area of pallium (Myxiniformes)
description: Area directly deep to the P3 area of pallium in hagfishes.

name: lower arm blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a lower arm [Automatically generated definition].

name: bone element
description: Skeletal element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: medial lemniscus
description: Fiber tract arising predominantly from neurons in the nucleus gracilis and nucleus cuneatus in the medulla, projecting to thalamus. Fibers cross in the decussation of the medial lemniscus.

name: supreme nasal concha
description: A thin bony plate occasionally found projecting from the inner wall of the ethmoid labyrinth, above the bony superior nasal concha, and the mucous membrane covering the plate.

name: psoas major muscle
description: The psoas major is a long fusiform muscle placed on the side of the lumbar region of the vertebral column and brim of the lesser pelvis. It joins the iliacus muscle to form the iliopsoas. In less than 50 per cent of subjects the psoas major is accompanied by the psoas minor. [WP,unvetted].

name: medial lemniscus of pons
description: Part of medial lemniscus located within the pons

name: glossopharyngeal ganglion
description: The group of neuron cell bodies associated with the ninth cranial nerve.

name: pharyngeal arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a entire pharyngeal arch associated mesenchyme.

name: branched anal fin ray
description: Anal fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched.

name: inferior nuchal line attachment site
description: Of the nuchal lines, the one running from the middle of the median line is the inferior nuchal line. Attached are the Obliquus capitis superior muscle, Rectus capitis posterior major muscle, and Rectus capitis posterior minor muscle.

name: extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle
description: The Extensor carpi radialis brevis is shorter and thicker than the extensor carpi radialis longus. The longus muscle can be found above the distal end of the Extensor carpi radialis brevis. [WP,unvetted].

name: terminal part of the cochlear canal
externally connecting tube lumen
description: Anatomical cavity that connects an organ cavity, organ cavity subdivision or cavity of body part subdivision to the exterior, completely or partially surrounded by organs or organ parts that are lined by epithelium. Examples: preputial cavity, vestibule of vagina.[FMA]

name: retroperitoneal fat pad
description: encapsulated adipose tissue found on the dorsal side of the peritoneum

name: perichondral bone
description: Bone element that is located on the surface of a cartilage element.

name: post-ceratobranchial cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and at or posterior to the juncture of the bilaterally paired ceratobranchial 5 cartilage or bone.

name: vertical myoseptum
description: Connective tissue partitions developing between the myotomes. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: caudal vertebra
description: Any vertebral bone that is part of the caudal region of the vertebral column (tail or coccyx).

name: basibranchial 4 element
description: Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 4.

name: bronchus connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric late distal convoluted tubule
description: The metanephric late distal convoluted tubule contains metanephric DCT cells and intercalated (IC) alpha and beta cells and is vasopressin-sensitive[GO].

name: external yolk syncytial layer
description: The portion of the YSL that is outside of the blastoderm margin during epiboly. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: superficial pretectal nucleus
description: Any nucleus found in the superficial pretectum.

name: pectoral fin proximal radial cartilage 3
description: pectoral fin proximal radial 3 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: lamina orbitonasalis
description: Cranial cartilage which is bilaterally paired and develops as a dorsal plate-like projection of the anterolateral ethmoid plate, which are oriented perpendicular to the ethmoid plate. It fuses dorsally to the taenia marginalis anterior, and it joins the ethmoid cartilage medially.

name: preductal region of aortic arch
description: Area of aorta proximal to the ductus arteriosus.

name: basisphenoid bone
description: part of the base of the cranium between the basioccipital and the presphenoid, which usually ossifies separately in the embryo or in the young, and becomes a part of the sphenoid in the adult; in many animals it persists as a separate bone between the basioccipital bone and the presphenoidal bone

name: respiratory system arterial blood vessel
description: An arterial blood vessel that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: sesamoid bone of gastrocnemius
description: A small sesamoid bone situated behind a condyle of the femur.

name: syndesmosis
description: Fibrous joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages of the vertebral column and the limbs as well as articulating ossicles, are connected by skeletal ligaments or membranes. Examples: Intervertebral syndesmosis, inferior tibiofibular joint.[FMA]

name: suprachiasmatic nucleus
description: * An ovoid densely packed collection of small cells of the anterior hypothalamus lying close to the midline in a shallow impression of the optic chiasm. (MSH) * small group of nerve cell bodies in the supraoptic region of the hypothalamus, just above the optic chiasm; influences rhythmic aspects of hypothalamic functions in many vertebrate species. (CSP)

name: fin skeleton
description: Skeletal subdivision consisting of all the skeletal elements in a single fin.

name: anal membrane
description: The dorsal part of the cloacal membrane following its partition by the urorectal septum.

name: main bronchus blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a main bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: skin apocrine gland
description: An apocrine gland that is part of a skin of body.

name: fauces
description: lateral walls of the oropharynx that are located medial to the palatoglossal folds

name: hypaxial region somite 29
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: thyroepiglotticus muscle
description: fibers of the thyroarytenoid muscle that continue to the margin of the epiglottis; it closes the inlet to the larynx.

name: iliocostalis cervicis muscle
description: The iliocostalis cervicis (cervicalis ascendens) arises from the angles of the third, fourth, fifth, and sixth ribs, and is inserted into the posterior tubercles of the transverse processes of the fourth, fifth, and sixth cervical vertebrae..

name: rhombomere 7 floor plate
description: A rhombomere floor plate that is part of a rhombomere 7.

name: venom
description: Poisonous animal secretions forming fluid mixtures of many different enzymes, toxins, and other substances. These substances are produced in specialized glands and secreted through specialized delivery systems (nematocysts, spines, fangs, etc.) for disabling prey or predator.

name: crural feather
description: A feather that is part of a hindlimb zeugopod.

name: intergeniculate leaflet of the lateral geniculate complex
bulbus arteriosus
description: The bulbus arteriosus is an elastic heart chamber[GO]. Multi-tissue structure that consists of three layers and through which the blood exits the heart. The bulbus arteriosus is a pear shaped chamber that functions as a capacitor, maintaining continuous blood flow into the gill arches[ZFA].

name: primary fissure of cerebellum
description: The monticulus of the cerebellum is divided by the primary fissure (or preclival fissure) into an anterior, raised part, the culmen or summit, and a posterior sloped part, the clivus; the quadrangular lobule is similarly divided.

name: common iliac artery
description: The common iliac arteries are two large arteries, about 4cm long in adults but more than a centimetre in diameter, that originate from the aortic bifurcation. The arteries run inferolaterally, along the medial border of the psoas muscles to the pelvic brim, where they bifurcate into the external iliac artery and internal iliac artery. The common iliac artery, and all of its branches, exist as paired structures (that is to say, there is one on the left side and one on the right). The distribution of the common iliac artery is basically the pelvis and lower limb on the corresponding side. Both common iliac arteries are accompanied along their course by common iliac veins. [WP,unvetted].

name: caecum epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a caecum.

name: inner digits of hand
description: The medial most digit of the manus skeleton.

name: collum ilei
description: Cyllindrical pillar that originates anterior to the acetabulum and extends to the ilial shaft.

name: cortical collecting duct
description: The cortical collecting duct is the portion of the collecting duct that resides in the renal cortex

name: cochlear labyrinth
description: The labyrinth is a system of fluid passages in the inner ear, including both the cochlea, which is part of the auditory system, and the vestibular system, which provides the sense of balance. It is named by analogy with the mythical maze that imprisoned the Minotaur, because of its appearance. The bony labyrinth, or osseous labyrinth, is the network of passages with bony walls lined with periosteum. The bony labyrinth is lined with the membranous labyrinth. There is a layer of perilymph between them. The three parts of the bony labyrinth are the vestibule of the ear, the semicircular canals, and the cochlea. The vestibular system is the region of the inner ear where the semicircular canals converge, close to the cochlea (the hearing organ). The vestibular system works with the visual system to keep objects in focus when the head is moving. Joint and muscle receptors also are important in maintaining balance. The brain receives, interprets, and processes the information from these systems that control our balance. [WP,unvetted].

name: posterior intervertebral notch
description: Indentation on the anterior margin of the pedicel. When two vertebrae articulate, the anterior notch of one vertebra and the posterior notch of the other create a bilateral intervertebral space.

name: chorionic plate
description: That portion of the chorionic wall in the region of its uterine attachment, which gives rise to chorionic villi; it consists of the mesoderm that lines the chorionic vesicle and, on the maternal side, of the trophoblast that lines the intervillous spaces; in the last half of gestation, the mesodermal connective tissue is largely replaced by fibrinoid material, and the amnionic membrane is adherent to the fetal side of the plate.

name: intestinal mucosa
description: Mucosal layer that lines the intestine.

name: occipital pole
description: The anterior end of the hemisphere is named the frontal pole. The posterior end is named the occipital pole. The anterior end of the temporal lobe, the temporal pole. [WP,unvetted].

name: intervertebral disk
description: A pad of fibrocartilage between the articular surfaces of two successive vertebral centra which has nucleus pulposus at its core.

name: blastula
description: Organism at the blastula stage - an early stage of embryonic development in animals. It is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum and consists of a spherical layer of around 128 cells surrounding a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel. The blastula follows the morula and precedes the gastrula in the developmental sequence.

name: parotidoauricular muscle
description: Is one of the numerus muscles of the external ear and is of importance since it is encountered in the operation for drainage of infections of the external ear of the dog. As its name suggests, it arises from the fascia over the parotid gland and approaches the auricle from the ventrolateral direction. This muscle is supplied by the facial nerve.The muscles of the external ear with their scattered origins and precisely located insertions provide for displacement and rotation of the ear in all directions. These muscles also have a collective function in communication both within and between species.

name: interlobar vein
description: The interlobar veins are veins of the renal circulation which drain the renal lobes.

name: caudal procurrent ray
description: Caudal fin lepidotrichium that form part of the anterior dorsal and ventral series of lepidotrichia of the caudal fin that may be associated with a neural spine or an epural or an uroneural (dorsal series) and with a haemal spine of a preural vertebra (ventral series). Caudal procurrent rays are shorter than the caudal principal rays. A caudal procurrent ray is an unpaired median bone.

name: caudate lobe of liver
description: The caudate lobe (posterior hepatic segment I, Spigelian lobe) is situated upon the postero-superior surface of the liver on the right lobe of the liver, opposite the tenth and eleventh thoracic vertebrae. It is bounded on the left side by the physiological division of the liver called the ligamentum venosum. It is bounded, below, by the porta; on the right, by the fossa for the inferior vena cava; and, on the left, by the fossa for the ductus venosus. It looks backward, being nearly vertical in position; it is longer from above downward than from side to side, and is somewhat concave in the transverse direction. The caudate process is a small elevation of the hepatic substance extending obliquely and laterally, from the lower extremity of the caudate lobe to the under surface of the right lobe. It is situated behind the porta, and separates the fossa for the gall-bladder from the commencement of the fossa for the inferior vena cava. Budd-Chiari syndrome, caused by occlusion of hepatic venous outflow, can lead to hypertrophy of the caudate lobe due to its own caval anastomosis that allows for continued function of this lobe of the liver. [WP,unvetted].

name: Brodmann (1909) area 23
description: The term area 23 of Brodmann-1909 refers to a subdivision of the cerebral cortex of the guenon defined on the basis of cytoarchitecture. Brodmann regarded it as topographically and cytoarchitecturally homologous to the combined ventral posterior cingulate area 23 and dorsal posterior cingulate area 31 of the human (Brodmann-1909). Distinctive Features (Brodmann-1905): the cortex is relatively thin; smaller cells predominate; the cell density of the multiform layer (VI) is great, producing a distinct boundary with the subcortical white matter; the internal granular layer (IV) is rather well developed; the internal pyramidal layer (V) contains a dense population of round, medium-sized ganglion cells concentrated at the border with layer IV; layers V and VI are narrow with a distinct mutual boundary.nn* Definition Source NeuroNames

name: infraorbital sensory canal
description: Sensory canal lateral or ventral to and in close proximity to the otic and supraorbital sensory canals at their union. The infraorbital sensory canal is bilaterally paired and associated with the infraorbital bones.

name: pharyngobranchial 1 bone
description: Most anterior pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials.

name: optic pit
description: A small indentation in the central part of the optic placode.

name: efferent portion of pharyngeal arch artery
description: A section of a pharyngeal arch artery that carries blood away from the gills.

name: dorsal nerve of clitoris
description: The deep terminal division of the pudendal nerve that runs along the dorsum of the clitoral shaft and innervates the the glans clitoris.

name: secretion of exocrine pancreas
description: A secretion that is part of a exocrine pancreas [Automatically generated definition].

name: superior oblique extraocular muscle
description: The superior oblique muscle, or obliquus oculi superior, is a fusiform muscle in the upper, medial side of the orbit whose primary action is downward, lateral rotation of the eye. One of the extraocular muscles, the superior oblique is the only muscle innervated by the trochlear nerve (the fourth cranial nerve).

name: thoracic spinal cord
description: The thoracic nerves are the spinal nerves emerging from the thoracic vertebrae. [WP,unvetted].

name: dorsal digital artery of pes
description: The dorsal digital arteries of foot are small arteries which supply the toes.

name: synsacrum
description: A region of the lower vertebral column formed from the fusion of vertebrae.

name: dorsum of nose
description: The midline prominence of the nose, extending from the nasal root to the tip.

name: lesser sac cavity
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a lesser sac [Automatically generated definition].

name: anal fin proximal radial cartilage
description: anal fin proximal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: medial septal complex
description: A septal nuclear complex that consists of the nucleus of the diagonal bands and the septal medial nuclei

name: pedal digit 1 phalanx endochondral element
description: A pedal digit 1 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: fourth ventricle aperture
description: One of: the 4th ventricle median or lateral apertures.

name: palatal tooth
description: A tooth that is on the roof of the mouth.

name: muscular layer of prostatic urethra
description: A muscular coat that is part of a prostatic urethra.

name: obsolete CoBL
description: A bifurcate interneuron where the axon projects ventrally, crossing the spinal cord ventral to the Mauthner axons before bifurcating and extending dorsally.

name: mycetome
description: A specialized organ that is linked to the gut in beetles and host to a symbiotic yeast. The yeast cells assist in the digestion of less nutritious foods, supply needed B-vitamins and sterols, and provide resistance to certain toxins.

name: epithelium of upper jaw
description: An epithelium that is part of a upper jaw [Automatically generated definition].

name: corpus albicans
description: White fibrous tissue that replaces the regressing corpus luteum in the human ovary in the latter half of pregnancy, or soon after ovulation when pregnancy does not supervene.

name: presomitic mesoderm
description: Unsegmented field of paraxial mesoderm present posterior to the most recently formed somite pair, from which somites will form.

name: kidney arcuate vein
description: Any of the veins that parallel the arcuate arteries, receive blood from the interlobular veins and straight venules, and terminate in the interlobar veins.

name: dorsomedial nucleus of hypothalamus
description: The Dorsomedial hypothalamic nucleus is a nucleus of the hypothalamus. It is involved in feeding, drinking, and body weight regulation. [WP,unvetted].

name: respiratory velum
description: A respiratory pump found in basal craniates

name: epihyoideum
description: an elastic ligament lying between the lateral pharyngeal muscles and the thyroglossus muscle

name: occipital arch
description: Posterior chondrocranium forming ventral and lateral margins of foramen magnum, medial to otic capsules.

name: optic radiation
description: The optic radiation (also known as the geniculo-calcarine tract or as the geniculostriate pathway) is a collection of axons from relay neurons in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus carrying visual information to the visual cortex (also called striate cortex) along the calcarine fissure. There is one such tract on each side of the brain.

name: obsolete anterior catecholaminergic tract
description: CNS white matter, an axonal tract between ventral diencephalon and ventral telencephalon. At 3 d, the anterior catecholaminergic tract includes noradrenergic projections from the hindbrain and dopaminergic projections from ventral dopaminergic neurons. During later development, other catecholaminergic projections may also contribute to the anterior catecholaminergic tract.

name: lower back skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a lower back.

name: pedal digit digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit plus the associated metapodial element.

name: glymphatic system
description: macroscopic waste clearance system that utilizes a unique system of perivascular tunnels, formed by astroglial cells, to promote efficient elimination of soluble proteins and metabolites from the central nervous system.

name: pterotic-posttemporal-supracleithrum
description: Bone that is a fusion of the pterotic, posttemporal, and supracleithrum bones.

name: tail electric organ
description: An electric organ that is part of a tail.

name: white matter of superior colliculus
description: A central nervous system white matter layer that is part of a superior colliculus.

name: epaxial region somite 27
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: spleen perifollicular zone
description: The compartment located between the marginal zone and the red pulp harboring scattered B and T lymphocytes[MP].

name: trunk region element
description: An organ or element that part of the trunk region. The trunk region can be further subdividied into thoracic (including chest and thoracic cavity) and abdominal (including abdomen and pelbis) regions.

name: nasolacrimal duct
description: the paired channels leading from the lacrimal sacs to the inferior meatus of the nose, through which tears are conducted through the nasal cavity

name: lip taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located on a lip.

name: tegmen tympani
description: The Tegmental Wall or Roof (paries tegmentalis) is formed by a thin plate of bone, the tegmen tympani, which separates the cranial and tympanic cavities. It is situated on the anterior surface of the petrous portion of the temporal bone close to its angle of junction with the squama temporalis; it is prolonged backward so as to roof in the tympanic antrum, and forward to cover in the semicanal for the Tensor tympani muscle. Its lateral edge corresponds with the remains of the petrosquamous suture[Grays] .

name: hippocampal field
description: a part or parts of the hippocampus that have a particular function

name: frontonasal suture
description: A suture between frontal and nasal bones

name: foramen of nasal bone
description: A vascular foramen opening on the outer surface of a nasal bone.

name: upper arm epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a forelimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: choroidal blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a choroid [Automatically generated definition].

name: arcus praeoccipitalis
description: Skeletal structure that separates the inferior and superior perilymphatic foramina.

name: cardiac muscle tissue of left auricle
description: A cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a left atrium auricular region.

name: laterodorsal tegmental nucleus
description: The laterodorsal tegmental nucleus (or lateroposterior tegmental nucleus) is a nucleus situated in the brainstem, spanning the midbrain tegmentum and the pontine tegmentum. [WP,unvetted].

name: diaphysis of ulna
description: The body of the ulna at its upper part is prismatic in form, and curved so as to be convex behind and lateralward; its central part is straight; its lower part is rounded, smooth, and bent a little lateralward. It tapers gradually from above downward, and has three borders and three surfaces.

name: obsolete macula lagena
description: This term was obsoleted as it was previously defined midleadingly as 'A macula that is part of a cochlea'.

name: m. oblique externus
description: Originates on the posterior margin of the suprascapula and the epaxial fascia and inserts ventrally on the lateral fascia of the M. rectus abdominus and the ilial shaft.

name: maxillopalatine
description: A compound bone consisting of maxilla and palatine, can also contain a prefrontal and/or lacrimal; present in adult Gymnophiona.

name: retina
description: The retina is the innermost layer or coating at the back of the eyeball, which is sensitive to light and in which the optic nerve terminates.

name: white matter of spinal cord
description: The regions of the spinal cord that are largely or entirely composed of myelinated nerve cell axons and contain few or no neural cell bodies or dendrites.

name: auricular artery
description: An artery that supplies oxygenated blood to the ear.

name: pedal digit 5 digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of pedal digit 5 plus the associated metapodial element.

name: ectoderm of buccopharyngeal membrane
description: An ectoderm that is part of a buccopharyngeal membrane.

name: supraethmoid
description: Dermal bone that first appears as paired ossifications in the membrane (dermis) dorsolateral to the ethmoid cartilage and anterolateral to the lateral ethmoids, later having the appearance of one butterfly-shaped element. Fused to the anterodorsal margin of the mesethmoid. Bordered anteriorly by the kinethmoid and posteriorly by the frontal.

name: abdominal part of esophagus
description: Clinical esophageal segment composed of smooth muscle. It corresponds to the inferior part of the lower third topographic segment of the esophagus.

name: presumptive rhombomere 8
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a rhombomere 8.

name: levator mandibulae lateralis
description: Responsible for the closing of the jaw.

name: amygdalohippocampal area
description: A cytoarchitecturally defined portion of the periamygdalar area and the cortical amygdalar nucleus at the caudal extreme of the amygdala.

name: subclavius
description: The Subclavius is a small triangular muscle, placed between the clavicle and the first rib. Along with the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor muscles, the subclavius muscle makes up the anterior wall of the axilla.

name: chorda tendineae
description: The tendinous strands that connect the papillary muscles on the wall of the ventricles to the leaflets of the atrioventricular valves; the chordae tendineae serve to prevent the AV valves from prolapsing back into the atria

name: superior hypophysial artery
description: The superior hypophysial artery is an artery supplying the pars tuberalis,the infundibulum of the pituitary gland and the median eminence. It is a branch of the posterior communicating artery which branches from the internal carotid artery in the circle of Willis..

name: striated muscle sphincter
description: A ring of striated muscle cells whose contraction closes the opening of the ring.

name: tonsillar fossa
description: Between the plica triangularis and the surface of the palatine tonsils is a space known as the tonsillar fossa (or tonsillar sinus); in many cases, however, this sinus is obliterated by its walls becoming adherent.

name: epiphysis of radius
description: An epiphysis that is part of a radius [Automatically generated definition].

name: maxillary process of inferior nasal concha
description: From the lower border of the inferior nasal concha, a thin lamina, the maxillary process, curves downward and lateralward; it articulates with the maxilla and forms a part of the medial wall of the maxillary sinus.

name: obsolete direct ossification
description: Ossification that does not require the replacement of pre-existing tissues, most often a cartilaginous model.

name: mammalian cervical vertebra 3
description: The third of the seven cervical vertebrae[ncit,modified].

name: ischial peduncle
description: Bony projection (peduncle) that is located on the posterior portion of the ilium, posterior to the acetabulum.

name: periungual skin
description: A zone of skin adjacent to a nail or claw.

name: proximal epiphysis of middle phalanx of manual digit 2
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a middle phalanx of manual digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: right pulmonary artery
description: The pulmonary artery that supplies the right lung.

name: rostral tubule
description: Consists of a set of tubuli occupying the space between the external dermal bones above the dorsal and anterior wal of the nasal capsule below. Thomson and Campbell (1971). [PHENOSCAPE:AD].

name: P5 area of pallium (Myxiniformes)
description: Most deep of the areas of the pallium in the enlarged evaginated telencephalon of hagfishes.

name: talofibular ligament
description: A skeletal ligament that connects the fibula to the talus. Examples: anterior and posterior talofibular ligament

name: rectrix feather
description: A flight feather that lies along a single horizontal row on the rear margin of the anatomical tail. Only the central pair are attached (via ligaments) to the tail bones; the remaining rectrices are embedded into the rectricial bulbs, complex structures of fat and muscle that surround those bones. Rectrices are always paired, with a vast majority of species having six pairs. They are absent in grebes and some ratites, and greatly reduced in size in penguins

name: glans penis
description: the conic expansion of the corpus spongiosum that forms the head of the penis

name: serous membrane
description: multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

name: eyelash
description: Any of the hairs that grow at the edge of the upper or lower eyelid.

name: dentary tooth 2
description: Dentary tooth that is the second tooth in a dentary tooth series, and positioned adjacent to the symphyseal tooth.

name: synostosis
description: Nonsynovial joint in which the articulating bones are connected by bone. Examples: epiphyseal junction, manubriosternal synostosis.

name: branched pectoral fin ray
description: Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched and segmented.

name: extensor carpi ulnaris muscle
description: Extensor carpi ulnaris is a muscle located in the forearm that acts to extend and adduct the wrist. Being an extensor muscle, extensor carpi ulnaris is on the posterior side of the forearm. [WP].

name: rete ovarii
description: A structure formed from the primary sex cords in females, counterpart of the rete testis in males.

name: duct of sebaceous gland
description: A duct that is part of a sebaceous gland.

name: neural plate of carapace
description: One of a series of plates on the dorsal midline of the turtle shell, posterior to the nuchal bone.

name: levator arcus palatini
description: Jaw muscle that connects the sphenotic to the metapterygoid and hyomandibula and promotes the elevation/abduction of the suspensorium.

name: epididymal fat pad
description: encapsulated adipose tissue associated with the epididymis

name: anterior neuropore
description: The neuropore at the anterior (rostral) end of the neural tube.

name: mandibular lateral line
description: One of eight distinct lateral lines in the 4-day larva. A sensory system on the surface of the fish, consisting of small sensory patches (neuromasts) distributed in discrete lines over the body surface.
