It courses to the right between the head of the pancreas and duodenum, and then ascends to anastomose with the anterior and posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal artery. It distributes branches to the head of the pancreas and to the descending and inferior parts of the duodenum. [WP,unvetted].

name: ischial foot
description: Expansion of the distal region of the ischium.

name: internal carotid foramen
description: Foramen for the passage of the internal carotid artery.

name: spina pelvis anterior
description: Small, rounded process on the anteroventral margin of the preacetabular expansion of the ilial corpus.

name: frontonasal process epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a frontonasal prominence.

name: prebend segment of loop of Henle
description: The prebend segment is a part of the descending thin limb that lies before the bend and exhibits robust sodium chloride reabsorption

name: facial lymphatic vessel
description: A lymphatic vessel that is part of a face [Automatically generated definition].

name: future common hepatic duct
description: An extrahepatic bile duct that has the potential to develop into a common hepatic duct.

name: anterior limb of internal capsule
description: Portion of internal capsule lying between the lenticular nucleus and the head of the caudate nucleus.

name: interlobular bile duct
description: The canals that carry bile in the liver between the intralobular ducts and the biliary ductules; interlobular bile ducts are part of the interlobular portal triad.

name: vertebra 4-vertebra 5 joint
description: Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 4 and vertebra 5.

name: bulbospongiosus muscle
description: The bulbospongiosus is the thick extrapelvic continuation of the urethralis. It originates from the perineal body (and midline raphe over corpus spongiosum in male) and inserts at the superficial perineal membrane and dorsal penile or clitoral aponeurosis. In males, the bulbospongiosus muscles are united and surround the base of the penis. They aid in emptying of urine and ejaculate from urethra. In females, these muscles are separated in the middle by the vagina and act to constrict the vaginal introitus. They can also stop the flow of blood into veins, which maintains an erection in the penis of the male and the clitoris of the female. Its nerve connection is the perineal branch of the pudendal nerve (S2, 3, 4).

name: rostrodermethmoid
description: Dermal bone formed by the fusion of dermethmoids and rostral bones.  [Fink, W L Weitzman, S H. 1982. Relationships of the stomiiform fishes (Teleostei), with a description of Diplophos Bulletin of The Museum of Comparative Zoology 150:31-93. http://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/part/28697]

name: gastroduodenal artery
description: A small blood vessel in the abdomen that supplies blood directly to the pylorus (distal part of the stomach) and proximal part of the duodenum, and indirectly to the pancreatic head (via the anterior and posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal arteries).

name: tela choroidea
description: A structure found in the walls of the ventricles of the brain, consisting of part of the meninges (pia mater in mammals) plus ependyma[cjm].

name: Kimura membrane
description: The thickening of the lower surface of the tectorial membrane into which the hair bundles of the outer hair cells are embedded.

name: pectoral fin distal radial bone
description: pectoral fin distal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: subsegmental lymph node
description: The lymph nodes around the subsegmental bronchi.

name: nuchal plate
description: Dermal bone that is a bony expansion in the integument anterior to or flanking the dorsal fin that is part of and at the distal end of a supraneural or dorsal fin proximal radial.

name: placenta fetal blood space
description: The spaces of the placenta occupied by fetal blood, primarily within the fetal labyrinth villi

name: basal nuclear complex
description: The deep nuclei of telencephalic origin found in the basal region of the forebrain

name: Ongur, Price, and Ferry (2003) area AON
supraorbital artery
description: The supraorbital artery is an artery of the head. It springs from the ophthalmic artery as that vessel is crossing over to the medial side of the optic nerve.

name: eye-antennal disc
description: Imaginal disc that, in the adults, gives rise to the eye, antenna, head capsule (including all bristles and external membranes) and the maxillary palps (Cohen, 1993).

name: blood vessel layer
description: Any of the tissue layers that comprise a blood vessel. Examples: tunica media, tunica adventitia.

name: right lung terminal bronchiole
description: A terminal bronchiole that is part of a right lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: epithelium of right lung
description: An epithelium that is part of a right lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: fascia of Camper
description: The superficial layer (fascia of Camper) is a thick superficial layer of the anterior abdominal wall. It is areolar in texture, and contains in its meshes a varying quantity of adipose tissue. It is found superficial to Scarpa's fascia.

name: left dorsal thalamus
description: A dorsal thalamus that is in_the_left_side_of a diencephalon.

name: respiratory system arterial endothelium
description: An endothelium of artery that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: pedal digit 5 phalanx endochondral element
description: A pedal digit 5 phalanx bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: cervix glandular epithelium
description: A glandular epithelium that is part of a uterine cervix.

name: inner medulla vasa recta ascending limb
internal capsule of telencephalon
description: White matter regional part of brain which is flanked by nuclear masses, consisting of both afferent and efferent fibers projecting between the cerebral cortex and the brainstem and spinal cord. It consists of three distinct parts: an anterior limb, posterior limb, and genu. (Adapted from MSH by Maryann Martone).

name: pars inferior ear
description: The ventral portion of the ear. It contains the saccule and the laguena which are the primary auditory organs.

name: mesenchyme of nasal septum
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing nasal septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: bony part of hard palate
description: A subdivision of skeletal system that subdivision_of a hard palate.

name: obsolete CoLA
description: A spinal interneuron with a dorsal dendrite that extends caudally. CoLA also has midlateral process that extend rostrally and caudally, the axon crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner cell and ascends, extending dorsally. Axon has minor descending branch.

name: muscularis mucosae of jejunum
description: A muscularis mucosa that is part of a jejunum.

name: rostral linear nucleus
description: Nucleus of the medial ventral tegmental area, originally identified in the rat but also in cat, monkey and human, comprising an average of 7% volume of the VTA across the different species, with the largest being present in the cat.

name: epithelium of posterior semicircular canal
description: An epithelium that is part of a posterior semicircular canal [Automatically generated definition].

name: cerebral subcortex
description: The layer located below the cerebral cortex that includes the forebrain, midbrain and hindbrain.

name: ctenoid scale
description: Scale that possesses cteni (discrete spines).

name: Brodmann (1909) area 4
description: The term area 4 of Brodmann-1909 refers to a cytoarchitecturally defined portion of the frontal lobe of the guenon. It is located predominantly in the precentral gyrus. Brodmann-1909 regarded it as topographically and cytoarchitecturally homologous to the human gigantopyramidal area 4 and noted that it occupies a much greater fraction of the frontal lobe in the monkey than in the human. Distinctive features (Brodmann-1905): the cortex is unusually thick; the layers are not distinct; the cells are relatively sparsely distributed; giant pyramidal (Betz) cells are present in the internal pyramidal layer (V); lack of an internal granular layer (IV) such that the boundary between the external pyramidal layer (III) and the internal pyramidal layer (V) is indistinct; lack of a distinct external granular layer (II); a gradual transition from the multiform layer (VI) to the subcortical white matter.

name: female membranous urethra
description: A membranous urethra of male or female that is part of a female urethra.

name: alary process of premaxilla
description: Dorsal process that extends toward the nasal bone. The posterior (inner) face of each alary process is concave and is invested dorsomedially by the superior prenasal cartilage and ventromedially by the inferior prenasal cartilage.

name: sensory canal pore series
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one sensory canal pore.

name: dermatological-muscosal system
description: Anatomical system that consists of the integumental system plus all mucosae and submucosae.

name: obsolete stem cell
description: A relatively undifferentiated cell that retains the ability to divide and proliferate throughout life to provide progenitor cells that can differentiate into specialized cells.

name: tonsillar pillar
description: The anterior and posterior borders of the tonsillar fossa. They are composed of muscle tissue.

name: lacrimal
description: Investing bone in non-teleosts associated with nasolacrimal duct and lying between pars facialis of maxilla and prefrontal and sometimes nasal.

name: hair root
description: The enlarged basal part of a hair within the skin[BTO]. The root of the hair ends in an enlargement, the hair bulb, which is whiter in color and softer in texture than the shaft, and is lodged in a follicular involution of the epidermis called the hair follicle. [Wikipedia].

name: planum temporale
description: The planum temporale is the cortical area just posterior to the auditory cortex within the Sylvian fissure. It is a triangular region which forms the heart of Wernicke's area, one of the most important functional areas for language. The planum temporale shows a significant asymmetry. In 65% of all individuals the left planum temporale appears to be more developed, while the right planum temporale is more developed in only 10%. In some peoplebs brains, the planum temporale is more than five times larger on the left than on the right, making it the most asymmetrical structure in the brain. This greater size of the left planum temporale compared with the right is already present in the foetus, where it can be observed starting from the 31st week of gestation. This observation strengthens the hypothesis of a genetic predisposition for brain asymmetry.

name: postrhinal cortex of rodent of Burwell et al 1995
description: Cortical region lying caudal to the perirhinal cortex in the rat. It encompasses the caudal levels of area 35 and the caudal portion of area 36 (ectorhinal cortex). It is bordered medially by agranular retrosplenial cortex and ventrally by the entorhinal cortex (with the exception of the caudomedial portion). The authors note that the ventral portion of the postrhinal cortex in rat may by homologous with the parahippocampal cortex in the monkey.

name: webbed digit
description: A digit that is part of a webbed autopod.

name: suprapubic skin
description: Area of skin in the hypoastric region of the abdomen.

name: left supracardinal vein
description: The left thoracic supracardinal vein loses its connection with the left posterior cardinal veins and left sinus horn and subsequently drains into the right supracardinal system.

name: lateral geniculate nucleus parvocellular layer
description: Layer of the lateral geniculate nucleus characterized by small cells (adapted from Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_geniculate_nucleus)

name: cleaving embryo
description: Organism at the cleavage stage.

name: coronary capillary
description: A capillary that is part of the coronary system.

name: narwhal tusk
description: A upper jaw incisor that protrudes prominently from the mouth as a single median tusk, found in narwhals.

name: brain ependyma
description: the ependymal cell layer that lines the brain ventricles

name: renal collecting system
description: The collecting duct system of the kidney consists of a series of tubules and ducts that connect the nephrons to the ureter. It participates in electrolyte and fluid balance through reabsorption and excretion, processes regulated by the hormones aldosterone and antidiuretic hormone.

name: vomer
description: the triangular flat bone of the nasal septum

name: brevis shelf
description: Anatomical projection on the ilium, anchoring caudal muscles.

name: circumventricular organ
description: Any of any of the secretory or sensory organs located in the brain region around or in relation to the ventricular system that are characterized by extensive vasculature and a lack of a normal blood brain barrier (BBB) and allow for the linkage between the central nervous system and peripheral blood flow.

name: cerebral peduncle
description: Synonym for macrodissected adult human tegmentum (Vicq d'Azyr, 1784; Swanson, 2000); pp. 555-556. Later used thus by for example His (1893b, p. 178), Herrick (1915, p. 160), Strong & Elwyn (1943, p. 17), Carpenter (1976, p. 367), Williams & Warwick (1980, p. 935).

name: margo posterior of scapula
description: Posterior margin of the scapula.

name: nail of pedal digit 5
description: A nail that is part of a pedal digit 5.

name: palatine gland
description: The palatine glands form a continuous layer on its posterior surface and around the uvula. They are primarily mucous secreting glands, as opposed to serous or mixed secreting glands. [WP,unvetted].

name: processus lingularis of nasal skeleton
description: Rod-shaped process that extends caudally from the inferior edge of the planum terminale.

name: ventral anterior lateral line nerve
description: Nerve fibers originating from the ventral anterior lateral line ganglion. These rami innervate the mandibular and opercular neuromasts.

name: prothoracic segment
description: The first (most anterior) segment of the thorax.

name: anterior cingulate cortex
description: The frontal part of the cingulate cortex that resembles a collar form around the corpus callosum. It includes both the ventral and dorsal areas of the cingulate cortex. Wikipedia:File:Gray727.svg

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of medial mammillary nucleus
cuneiform cartilage
description: The cuneiform cartilages of the larynx are two small, elongated pieces of yellow elastic cartilage, placed one on either side, in the aryepiglottic fold, where they give rise to small whitish elevations on the surface of the mucous membrane, just in front of the arytenoid cartilages.

name: sublingual dorsal cartilage
description: Sublingual cartilage that is the dorsal element paired with the sublingual ventral cartilage.

name: anterolateral supplementary element
description: A muscle slip arising from the lingual surface of the mandible on the anterior portion of the bone. The fibers pass anteriorly, parallel to the mandible, and attach upon the ventral surface of the m. submentalis (Tyler, 1971).

name: anatomical junction
description: An anatomical structure that connects two structures

name: matrix-based tissue
description: A tissue whose predominant feature is extracellular matrix which may or may not be highly hydrated or calcified.

name: infraorbital 2
description: Infraorbital that is the second bone of the infraorbital series.

name: choroid plexus of tectal ventricle
description: A choroid plexus that is part of a cerebral aqueduct.

name: adult labral segment
description: Any labral segment (UBERON:6000008) that is part of some adult head (UBERON:6003007).

name: tract of brain
description: An axon tract that is part of a brain.

name: lateral plate mesoderm
description: Portion of the middle of the three primary germ layers of the embryo that resides on the periphery of the embryo, is continuous with the extra-embryonic mesoderm, splits into two layers enclosing the intra-embryonic coelom, and gives rise to body wall structures[MP].

name: tricuspid valve cusp
description: The three fibrous triangular components and associated flaps of the tricuspid valve

name: cleithrum
description: Dermal bone on the margin of the scapula. The cleithrum is attached to the skull in fishes, but free from the latter in amphibians and disappears early in the evolution of reptiles.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 48
description: Retrosubicular area 48 is a subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined hippocampal region of the cerebral cortex. In the human it is located on the medial surface of the temporal lobe. Cytoarchitectually it is bounded rostrally by the perirhinal area 35 and medially by the presubiculum. While described by Brodmann (Brodmann-1909), it was not included in his areal maps of human cortex (Brodmann-1909; Brodmann-1910).

name: spinal nerve
description: the any of the paired peripheral nerves formed by the union of the dorsal and ventral spinal roots from each spinal cord segment[MP,modified]

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of manual digit 4
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manual digit 4.

name: epiphysis of metatarsal bone
description: An epiphysis that is part of a metatarsal bone [Automatically generated definition].

name: central part of body of bony vertebral centrum
respiration organ
description: Organ that functions in gaseous exchange between an organism and its environment. In plants, microorganisms, and many small animals, air or water makes direct contact with the organism's cells or tissue fluids, and the processes of diffusion supply the organism with dioxygen (O2) and remove carbon dioxide (CO2). In larger animals the efficiency of gaseous exchange is improved by specialized respiratory organs, such as lungs and gills, which are ventilated by breathing mechanisms.

name: mammalian cervical vertebra 7
description: Vertebra prominens is the proper name for the seventh cervical vertebra. The most distinctive characteristic of this vertebra is the existence of a long and prominent spinous process which is palpable from the skin surface, hence the name. This spinous process is thick, nearly horizontal in direction, not bifurcated, but terminating in a tubercle to which the lower end of the ligamentum nuchae is attached. The seventh cervical vertebra (C7) has the most prominent spinous process only in about 70% of people; in the remainder, either C6 or T1 (the first thoracic vertebra) will be the most prominent. The transverse processes are of considerable size, their posterior roots are large and prominent, while the anterior are small and faintly marked; the upper surface of each has usually a shallow sulcus for the eighth spinal nerve, and its extremity seldom presents more than a trace of bifurcation. The foramen transversarium may be as large as that in the other cervical vertebrae, but is generally smaller on one or both sides; occasionally it is double, sometimes it is absent. On the left side it occasionally gives passage to the vertebral artery; more frequently the vertebral vein traverses it on both sides; but the usual arrangement is for both artery and vein to pass in front of the transverse process, and not through the foramen. Sometimes the anterior root of the transverse process attains a large size and exists as a separate bone, which is known as a cervical rib.

name: parotid gland
description: The parotid gland is the largest of the salivary glands. It is found wrapped around the mandibular ramus, and it secretes saliva through Stensen's duct into the oral cavity, to facilitate mastication and swallowing. [WP,unvetted].

name: pedal claws
description: Claws on the pes.

name: cerebral cortex marginal layer
description: developing superficial cortical layer located just under the pia matter, develops from the marginal layer of the neural tube and becomes cortical layer I

name: submental vein
description: A vein in the chin that is connected to the sublingual and anterior jugular veins and drains into the facial vein.

name: postsplenial
description: Dermal bone of the lower jaw.

name: entopallium
description: The major telecephalic thalamorecipient zone of the tectofugal visual system in Aves.

name: visceral fat
description: Any fat deposit surrounding a visceral organ.

name: epiphysis of proximal phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a proximal phalanx of pes.

name: sesamoid bone
description: A sesamoid element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: 5th arch mesenchyme
description: A mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 5.

name: lateral parabrachial nucleus
description: The lateral parabrachial nucleus induces thirst by stimulating the median preoptic nucleus. It gets its name from its location relative to the superior cerebellar peduncles, which is also known as the 'brachia conjunctiva'. [WP,unvetted].

name: tertial remex feather
description: A remex feather that is connected to the humerus.

name: parapophysis 6
description: Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the sixth centrum.

name: tarsus cartilage element
description: A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a tarsal bone.

name: stemma
description: eye-spots which may be set into a pit to reduce the angles of light that enters and affects the eyespot, to allow the organism to deduce the angle of incoming light

name: nasal septum
description: The nasal septum separates the left and right airways in the nose, dividing the two nostrils. It is depressed by the Depressor septi nasi muscle. [WP,unvetted].

name: external spermatic fascia
description: A thin membrane, prolonged downward around the surface of the spermatic cord and testis. It is separated from the dartos tunic by loose areolar tissue. It is derived from the aponeurosis of the abdominal external oblique muscle.

name: odontoid tissue
description: Skeletal tissue that is part of the exoskeleton and derived from an odontogenic papilla.

name: parietal-supraoccipital
description: Compound dermal and endochondral bone that results from the fusion of the paired dermal parietal bones and the median endochondral supraoccipital. Forms the dorso-posterior element of the dermatocranium.

name: epaxial region somite 5
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: lymph node B cell domain
description: A part of the lymph node cortex in which B lymphocytes home to primary follicles to survey follicular dendritic cells (FDCs); antigen stimulated B cells proliferate and differentiate within the follicles forming distinctive germinal centers

name: ampulla of Lorenzini
description: The ampullae of Lorenzini are special sensing organs called electroreceptors, forming a network of jelly-filled pores. Each ampulla consists of a canal opening to the surface by a pore in the skin and ending blindly in a cluster of small pockets full of special jelly. The ampullae are mostly clustered into groups inside the body, each cluster having ampullae connecting with different parts of the skin, but preserving a left-right symmetry. The canal lengths vary from animal to animal, but the distribution of the pores is generally specific to each species. The ampullae pores are plainly visible as dark spots in the skin. They provide fish with a sixth sense capable of detecting electromagnetic fields as well as temperature gradients[WP].

name: male inguinal ring
description: A inguinal ring that is part of a male reproductive system.

name: stomatodeum gland
description: A gland that is part of a stomodeum.

name: recessus vena jugularis
description: As defined here, this refers to a depression on the lateral surface of the braincase posterior to the Vidian canal as opposed to the carotid fossa...(Conrad 2008)

name: lymphatic part of lymphoid system
description: An organ system subdivision that is a network of vessels capable of removing accumulating protein and fluid from the interstitial space and returning it to the vascular space. In some species, this network is connected to the immune system via lymph nodes and lymphocyte-producing organs, with the whole being the lymphoid system.

name: male preputial gland
description: One of the sebaceous glands of the corona and neck of the glans penis.

name: digit 7 digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of digit 7 plus the associated metapodial element.

name: manual digit connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a finger [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric proximal straight tubule
description: The metanephric proximal straight tubule is the part of the metanephric descending limb that extends from the metanephric proximal convoluted tubule to the metanephric descending thin tubule[GO].

name: epithelium of main bronchus
description: An epithelium that is part of a main bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: tectobulbar tract
description: A long process of a CNS neuron, that carries efferent (outgoing) action potentials from the cell body in the optic tectum towards target cells in the premotor reticulospinal system in the hindbrain.

name: nerve of thoracic segment
description: A nerve that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].

name: serosa of cloaca
description: A serous membrane that is part of a cloaca [Automatically generated definition].

name: metaphysis of fibula
description: A metaphysis that is part of a fibula.

name: metacarpal bone of digit 4
description: A metacarpal bone that distally_connected_to a proximal phalanx of manual digit 4.

name: thoracic vertebra 8
description: The eighth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: synchondrosis
description: Cartilaginous joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by hyaline cartilage. Examples: spheno-occipital synchondrosis, first sternocostal joint.[FMA]

name: distal segment of manual digit
description: A segment of the manual digit containing the distal phalanx

name: inferior phrenic vein
description: The Inferior Phrenic Veins drain the diaphragm and follow the course of the inferior phrenic arteries; the right ends in the inferior vena cava; the left is often represented by two branches, one of which ends in the left renal or suprarenal vein, while the other passes in front of the esophageal hiatus in the diaphragm and opens into the inferior vena cava. [WP,unvetted].

name: M. coracobrachialis brevis
description: Muscle which originates on the dorsal surface of the coracoid and scapula and inserts on the deltoid crest of the humerus.

name: organismal segment
description: One of the repeated divisions of the whole organism.

name: manual digitopodium bone
description: A bone that is part of a the manual digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the fingers or the metacarpal skeleton.

name: obsolete endodermal cell
description: A cell of the inner of the three germ layers of the embryo.

name: superficial circumflex iliac artery
description: The superficial iliac circumflex artery (or superficial circumflex iliac), the smallest of the cutaneous branches of the femoral artery, arises close to the superficial epigastric artery, and, piercing the fascia lata, runs lateralward, parallel with the inguinal ligament, as far as the crest of the ilium. It divides into branches which supply the integument of the groin, the superficial fascia, and the superficial subinguinal lymph glands, anastomosing with the deep iliac circumflex, the superior gluteal and lateral femoral circumflex arteries.

name: inner fin tissue
description: Part of the fin consisting of a supporting core of mesenchyme and extracellular matrix.

name: right lung associated mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing right lung.

name: visceral yolk sac
description: extraembryonic tissue membrane, formed from the visceral endoderm and the extraembryonic mesoderm, which is located ventral to the embryonic disc and is connected to the presumptive midgut of the embryo; the yolk that it contains is the site of embryonic hematopoiesis and vitelline circulation is involved in early embryonic circulation; it is the origin of the primordial germ cells

name: yolk sac
description: A sac-like expansion of the ventral wall of the intestine, narrowed into a yolk stalk near the body[Hyman's]. Membranous sac attached to an embryo, providing early nourishment in the form of yolk in bony fishes, sharks, reptiles, birds, and primitive mammals. It functions as the developmental circulatory system of the human embryo, before internal circulation begins. In the mouse, the yolk sac is the first site of blood formation, generating primitive macrophages and erythrocytes[WP].

name: obsolete dorsal fin skeleton
description: Median fin skeleton located on the dorsal surface of the organism.

name: tunica media of vein
description: A tunica media that is part of a vein.

name: ventral nerve root of cervical spinal cord
description: A ventral root of spinal cord that overlaps a cervical spinal cord.

name: hair outer root sheath
description: A stratified epithelium that surrounds the hair follicle that merges proximally with the basal layer of the interfollicular epidermis and distally with the hair bulb.

name: pulvinar nucleus
description: One of a set of nuclei located in the posterior thalamus, that projects to all or nearly all extra-striate visual areas.

name: cingulum of upper jaw molar
description: A ridge that girdles the base of a upper molar tooth

name: umbilicus
description: The pit in the center of the abdominal wall marking the point where the umbilical cord entered in the fetus.

name: proximal phalanx of pedal digit 2
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a pedal digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: pelvic fin distal radial cartilage 1
description: pelvic fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: psoas minor muscle
description: The psoas minor is a long, slender skeletal muscle that, when present, is placed in front of the psoas major muscle. [WP,unvetted].

name: neuraxis flexure
description: An anatomical structure that is regional part of the central nervous system where there is a significant bend of the axis.

name: manual digit 3 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 3 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: middle colic artery
description: The middle colic artery is a branch of the superior mesenteric artery that mostly supplies the transverse colon. It arises just below the pancreas, and, passing downward and forward between the layers of the transverse mesocolon, divides into two branches: right and left. The right branch anastomoses with the right colic artery The left branch anastomoses with the left colic artery, a branch of the inferior mesenteric artery. The arches thus formed are placed about two fingers' breadth from the transverse colon, to which they distribute branches. [WP,unvetted].

name: lateral extrascapular
description: The most lateral of the paired series of extrascapular bones and is the bone where the intersection of the otic, postotic and extrascapular or supratemporal canals occur.

name: intumescentia bilateralis inferior
description: Small protuberance on the ischium, located close to its posteroventral margin.

name: anal membrane ectodermal component
description: A unilaminar epithelium that develops_from a ectoderm and is part of a anal region.

name: nephrogenic mesenchyme
description: Nephrogenic mesenchyme is the tissue made up of loosely connected mesenchymal cells in the nephron

name: radius bone
description: The major preaxial endochondral bone in the anterior zeugopod[Phenoscape].

name: obsolete predominantly gray part of medulla oblongata
posterior limb of internal capsule
description: Portion of internal capsule lying between the globus pallidus and the thalamus (Nolte, The Human Brain, 6th ed., 2009, pg 409, modified by MM)

name: aortic valve leaflet
description: A cardiac valve leaflet that is part of a aortic valve.

name: falciform ligament
description: A ligament that attaches the liver to the anterior body wall. It is a broad and thin antero-posterior peritoneal fold, falciform in shape, its base being directed downward and backward and its apex upward and backward. It is a remnant of the ventral mesentery of the fetus. It is situated in an antero-posterior plane but lies obliquely, so that one surface faces forward and is in contact with the peritoneum behind the right rectus and the diaphragm, while the other is directed backward and is in contact with the left lobe of the liver. It is attached by its left margin to the under surface of the diaphragm and the posterior surface of the sheath of the right Rectus as low down as the umbilicus; by its right margin it extends from the notch on the anterior margin of the liver, as far back as the posterior surface. It is composed of two layers of peritoneum closely united together. Its base or free edge contains between its layers the round ligament and the paraumbilical veins[WP].

name: lumen of esophagus
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a esophagus.

name: obsolete hair cell posterior macula
description: Specialized neuronal receptor cells of the lateral line and acoustico-vestibular systems. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for hair cells by T. Whitfield.)

name: orbitosphenoid-lateral ethmoid joint
description: Joint that articulates the orbitosphenoid cartilage or bone and lateral ethmoid cartilage or bone. Orbitosphenoid-lateral ethmoid joint is paired.

name: ventral marginal cartilage
description: In the clasper skeleton, a flat semicylindrical cartilage that is partially fused to the lateral edge of the axial cartilage, and forms the lateral wall of the clasper groove. [Compagno, L. 2001. Sharks of the World: An Annotated and Illustrated Catalogue of Shark Species Known to Date. Volume 2]

name: neuroendocrine gland
description: any of the organized aggregations of cells that function as secretory or excretory organs and that release hormones in response to neural stimuli

name: pectoral fin ray 5
description: Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the fifth most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.

name: space between upper and lower jaws
description: The space between the upper jaw skeleton and lower jaw skeleton (including teeth) that is formed when when biting.

name: propterygium cartilage
description: The propterygium is the lateralmost or anteriormost basal cartilage that originates from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc. The bases of the pectoral lepidotrichium 1 plus the propterygium articulates with the scapula.

name: pharyngeal arch artery
description: One of a series of paired embryological vascular structures formed within a pharyngeal arch; in the adult, some of these vessels give rise to the great vessels[MP]

name: loose connective tissue
description: Irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a sparse irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, neuroglial tissue, mucoid tissue.

name: median lobe of prostate
description: The upper, smaller part of the prostate between the ejaculatory ducts and the urethra.

name: somite 20
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: anterior nuchal plate
description: Nuchal plate that is unpaired and part of the supraneural and in contact, or not, with the supraoccipital crest anteriorly and middle nuchal plate posteriorly.

name: placental cotyledon
description: Round structure consisting of chorionic villi[PMID]. A separation of the decidua basalis of the placenta, separated by placental septa. Each cotyledon consists of a main stem of a chorionic villus as well as its branches and subbranches. The cotyledons receive fetal blood from chorionic vessels, which branch off cotyledon vessels into the cotyledons, which, in turn, branch into capillaries. The cotyledons are surrounded by maternal blood, which can exchange oxygen and nutrients with the fetal blood in the capillaries[WP].

name: pericardio-peritoneal canal
description: Each of the canals that connects the pericardial cavity with the peritoneal cavity and becomes a pleural cavity.

name: respiratory system reticular lamina
description: A reticular lamina that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of globus pallidus
metatarsophalangeal joint of pedal digit 4
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metatarsal bone and connects a distal phalanx of pedal digit 4.

name: plantar interosseous muscle of pes
description: Any of three muscles with origin from the third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal bones, with insertion to the proximal phalanx of the same toes, with nerve supply from the lateral plantar nerve, and whose action adducts the three lateral toes.

name: inferior branch of oculomotor nerve
description: The inferior branch of the oculomotor nerve or the inferior division, the larger, divides into three branches. One passes beneath the optic nerve to the medial rectus. Another, to the inferior rectus. The third and longest runs forward between the inferior recti and lateralis to the inferior oblique. From the last a short thick branch is given off to the lower part of the ciliary ganglion, and forms its short root. All these branches enter the muscles on their ocular surfaces, with the exception of the nerve to the inferior oblique, which enters the muscle at its posterior border.

name: antennal disc
description: Posterior portion of the eye-antennal disc. It gives rise to the adult antennal segments and the maxillary palp, as well as contributing to the head capsule.

name: respiratory system basal lamina
description: A basal lamina that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: left lung terminal bronchiole
description: A terminal bronchiole that is part of a left lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: epithelium of left lung
description: An epithelium that is part of a left lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: right dorsal thalamus
description: A dorsal thalamus that is in_the_right_side_of a diencephalon.

name: lateral structure
description: Any structure that is placed on one side of the left-right axis of a bilaterian.

name: respiratory system venous endothelium
description: An endothelium of vein that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: pedal digit metatarsal endochondral element
description: A pedal digit metatarsal bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: ectocervical epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a ectocervix.

name: outer medulla vasa recta ascending limb
mesenchyme of tongue
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing tongue [Automatically generated definition].

name: replacement bone
description: Bone that forms as a replacement of another structural tissue.

name: obsolete asexual organism
description: Multi-cellular organism that does not produce gametes.

name: styloauricular muscle
description: An occasional small muscle extending from the root of the styloid process to the cartilage of the meatus of the ear

name: transforming ctenoid scale
description: Ctenoid scale with two or three alternating rows of cteni marginally and truncated cteni submarginally. (Roberts 1993).

name: male membranous urethra
description: the shortest, least dilatable, and, with the exception of the external orifice, the narrowest part of the male urethral canal located in the deep perineal pouch and lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium; it extends downward and forward, with a slight anterior concavity, between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the urethra, perforating the urogenital diaphragm below and behind the pubic symphysis; the membranous portion of the urethra is completely surrounded by the fibers of the sphincter urethrae membranaceae; on either side near its termination are the bulbourethral glands

name: obsolete hematopoietic stem cell
description: A stem cell from which all cells of the lymphoid and myeloid lineages develop, including blood cells and cells of the immune system.

name: mammary gland
description: A specialized accessory gland of the skin of mammals that secretes milk. The gland is typically only developed in females, and regresses in males.

name: vertebral element 9
description: Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 8.

name: anlage in statu nascendi
description: "anlagen in statu nascendi" are domains that do not yet coincide 1:1 with a later organ. Anlagen in statu nascendi are typically defined for the early blastoderm by the expression domains of genes which, in the late blastoderm or later, are expressed in specific anlagen, but initially come on in larger domains.

name: webbed manual digit
description: A digit that is part of a webbed manus.

name: right supracardinal vein
description: The right supracardinal vein loses its connection with the posterior cardinal vein and makes a new anastomosis with the segments of the superior vena cava derived from the anterior cardinal vein, becoming the azygos vein.

name: thymus lobe
description: Either of the two lateral lobes that constitute the thymus.

name: subarachnoid cistern
description: The widening portions of the subarachnoid space within the cranium where the arachnoid bridges over a depression on the surface of the brain

name: horn
description: A pointed projection of the skin on the head of various animals, consisting of a covering of horn (keratin and other proteins) surrounding a core of living bone.

name: lower jaw incisor epithelium
description: A dental epithelium that is part of a lower jaw incisor.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 32
description: The Brodmann area 32, also known in the human brain as the dorsal anterior cingulate area 32, refers to a subdivision of the cytoarchitecturally defined cingulate region of cerebral cortex. In the human it forms an outer arc around the anterior cingulate gyrus. The cingulate sulcus defines approximately its inner boundary and the superior rostral sulcus (H) its ventral boundary; rostrally it extends almost to the margin of the frontal lobe. Cytoarchitecturally it is bounded internally by the ventral anterior cingulate area 24, externally by medial margins of the agranular frontal area 6, intermediate frontal area 8, granular frontal area 9, frontopolar area 10, and prefrontal area 11-1909. (Brodmann19-09). Dorsal region of anterior cingulate gyrus is associated with rational thought processes, most notably active during the Stroop task.

name: dental pulp of median incisor tusk
description: A dental pulp that is part of a narwhal tusk.

name: ventricle of nervous system
description: A layer in the central nervous system that lines system of communicating cavities in the brain and spinal cord.

name: pontine reticular formation
description: The reticular formation is a part of the brain that is involved in actions such as awaking/sleeping cycle, and filtering incoming stimuli to discriminate irrelevant background stimuli. It is essential for governing some of the basic functions of higher organisms, and is one of the phylogenetically oldest portions of the brain. [WP,unvetted].

name: obsolete predominantly gray dorsal regional part of thalamus
maxilla
description: The bone which normally forms the lateral upper jaw in osteichthyans, including tetrapods.

name: renal vein
description: Either of the pair of major vessels which arise from the renal hilus and return blood from the kidneys, suprarenal gland and the ureter to the inferior vena cava.

name: brevis fossa
description: Fossa located on the brevis shelf.

name: alimentary part of gastrointestinal system
description: The part of the digestive system that excludes the hepatobiliary system.

name: orbital part of inferior frontal gyrus
description: Component of the inferior frontal gyrus.defined as the first gyrus from the precentral gyrus.the remainder of the inferior frontal gyrus once the pars opercularis and triangularis have been defined (Christine Fennema-Notestine)., NeuroNames

name: margo suprascapularis
description: Superior margin of the scapula, which articulates with the suprascapula.

name: epoophoron
description: A remnant of the Mesonephric duct that can be found next to the ovary and fallopian tube.

name: fungiform papilla
description: Any of the mushroom-shaped papillae, which have a single taste bud at the tip, located mostly on the dorsal anterior portion of the tongue

name: middle lateral line nerve
description: Nerve fibers originating from the middle lateral line ganglion. These fibers innervate the middle lateral line.

name: cloacal bursa
description: An evagination of the cloaca. In Testudines these are hypothesized to function in different physiological roles, primarily in respiration.

name: musculature
description: A subdivision of the muscular system corresponding to a subdisivision of an organism.

name: mesothoracic segment
description: The second (middle) segment of the thorax.

name: left suprarenal vein
description: A vein that drains blood from the left adrenal gland into the left renal artery.

name: primary subdivision of skull
description: The skull can be divided into two: the neurocranium and the facial skeleton

name: pharyngobranchial cartilage
description: Paired cartilages that project medially from the medial tips of epibranchials.

name: bulbourethral gland secretion
description: A bodily secretion that is produced by a bulbourethral gland.

name: infraorbital 3
description: Infraorbital that is the third bone of the infraorbital series.

name: adult antennal segment
description: Any antennal segment (UBERON:6000009) that is part of some adult head (UBERON:6003007).

name: myotome
description: A transitional population of migrating mesenchymal cells that derive from somites and that will become muscle cells.

name: dentary
description: The dentary is a dermal bone that forms the antero-lateral part of the lower jaw in fishes and amphibians, extending to the whole lower jaw in mammals[VHOG,modified].

name: layer of retina
description: Any of the layers that make up the retina[MP].

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of manual digit 5
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manual digit 5.

name: reproductive organ
description: An organ involved in reproduction

name: vomit
description: A bodily fluid consisting of the expulsed contents of the stomach disgorged through the mouth or nose that happens as a result of a vomit reflex.

name: lumbar vertebra 1
description: The first lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: sublingual gland
description: the small mucin-producing salivary glands in the floor of the mouth beneath the tongue, anterior to the submandibular gland

name: pedal digit 7 phalanx
description: Phalanx of the 7th pedal digit. [AD]

name: retromandibular vein
description: The retromandibular vein (temporomaxillary vein, posterior facial vein), formed by the union of the superficial temporal and maxillary veins, descends in the substance of the parotid gland, superficial to the external carotid artery but beneath the facial nerve, between the ramus of the mandible and the sternocleidomastoideus muscle. It divides into two branches: an anterior, which passes forward and unites with the anterior facial vein to form the common facial vein. a posterior, which is joined by the posterior auricular vein and becomes the external jugular vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: habenular nucleus
description: Either of the two neural nuclei within the habenula.

name: epiphysis of middle phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a middle phalanx of pes.

name: caudal vertebra cartilage element
description: A caudal vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: dorsal longitudinal fasciculus of hypothalamus
description: Part of dorsal longitudinal fasciculus located within the hypothalamus

name: cavity of feather shaft
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a feather shaft.

name: parapophysis 5
description: Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the fifth centrum.

name: simple eye
description: An eye with one concave chamber. Note that 'simple' does not imply a reduced level of complexity or acuity.

name: nasal cavity
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of the olfactory apparatus. This includes the space bounded anteriorly by the nares and posteriorly by the choanae, when these structures are present.

name: conjunctival vasculature
description: A vasculature that is part of a conjunctiva.

name: posttemporal-supracleithrum
description: Dermal bone that results from the fusion of the dermal posttemporal and the dermal supracleithrum. Forms the upper skeletal element of the pectoral girdle between the cleithrum and neurocranium. Posttemporal-supracleithrum is paired.

name: epaxial region somite 14
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: swim bladder
description: A thin membranous, sometimes alveolated sac in the dorsal portion of the abdominal cavity. Contains a varying mixture of gases, not identical to the composition of air. May be one, two or three chambered. May be connected to the gut by a tube, the ductus pneumaticus (then called physostomous) or unconnected (then called physoclistous).

name: lymph node T cell domain
description: The paracortex and interfollicular cortex of the lymph node in which T lymphocytes home to survey dendritic cells

name: female superficial inguinal ring
description: A deep inguinal ring that is part of a female reproductive system.

name: yolk sac cavity
description: An anatomical cavity that is part of a yolk sac [Automatically generated definition].

name: rictal bristle
description: Rictal bristles project from the beak of many insect-eating birds, including flycatchers, nightjars and even the American Robin. They are believed to provide protection for the bird's eyes as it consumes its wriggly prey. The bristles may also provide tactile feedback, like the whiskers on a dog or cat. from http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/studying/feathers/feathers/document_view

name: forebrain-midbrain boundary
description: An anatomical boundary that adjacent_to a forebrain and adjacent_to a midbrain.

name: choroid plexus of fourth ventricle
description: Choroid plexus of the fourth ventricle

name: collection of hair on snout
description: A collection of hairs that grows on the snout.

name: inner ear canal
description: The tubular ducts of the inner ear

name: female preputial gland
description: The paired, lobulated, modified sebaceous glands located on the side of the clitoris in female rodents; in contrast to the preputial glands in male rodents, clitoral glands are a minor source of olfactory stimuli contributing to sexual attractivity; unlike other sebaceous glands, they undergo progressive atrophy of the glandular portion with marked ductal ectasia as rodents age.

name: digit 8 digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of digit 8 plus the associated metapodial element.

name: manus connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a hand [Automatically generated definition].

name: mental nerve
description: Mental nerve is a general somatic afferent (sensory) nerve which provides sensation to the anterior aspects of the chin and lower lip as well as the buccal gingivae of the mandibular anterior teeth and the premolars. It is a branch of the posterior trunk of the inferior alveolar nerve, which is itself a branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V). The nerve emerges at the mental foramen in the mandibula, and divides beneath the Depressor anguli oris muscle into three branches: one descends to the skin of the chin. two ascend to the skin and mucous membrane of the lower lip. These branches communicate freely with the facial nerve.

name: metanephric S1
description: The S1 portion is the initial portion of the metanephric proximal convoluted tubule and is responsible for avid reabsorption of water and solutes[GO].

name: epithelium of segmental bronchus
description: An epithelium that is part of a segmental bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of substantia nigra pars reticulata
anterior lingual gland duct
description: A duct that is part of a anterior lingual gland.

name: endocardium
description: The endocardium is an anatomical structure comprised of an endothelium and an extracellular matrix that forms the innermost layer of tissue of the heart, and lines the heart chambers[GO].

name: nerve of abdominal segment
description: A nerve that is part of an abdominal segment of trunk [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of adenohypophysis
lingual cusp of tooth
description: A medially (towards the tongue)) raised feature found on crown of a tooth.

name: metacarpal bone of digit 5
description: A metacarpal bone that distally_connected_to a proximal phalanx of manual digit 5.

name: histaminergic system
description: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to histamine.

name: symphysis
description: Cartilaginous joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by fibrocartilage. Examples: pubic symphysis, intervertebral symphysis, manubriosternal joint.[FMA]

name: obsolete pars palatina of maxilla
description: Lingual ledge on the inner surface of the maxilla.

name: distal segment of pedal digit
description: A segment of the pedal digit containing the distal phalanx. Note this class represents a digit segment and thus includes tissues in addition to bone.

name: pharyngobranchial 2 bone
description: Pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.

name: infrarostral cartilage
description: Larval lower jaw lies anterior to Meckels cartilage.

name: thoracic segment of trunk
description: Subdivision of trunk that lies between the head and the abdomen.

name: pedal digitopodium bone
description: A bone that is part of a the pedal digitopodium skeleton - i.e. the toes or the metatarsal skeleton.

name: obsolete mesodermal cell
description: A cell of the middle germ layer of the embryo.

name: orbital gyrus
description: The inferior or orbital surface of the frontal lobe is concave, and rests on the orbital plate of the frontal bone. It is divided into four orbital gyri by a well-marked H-shaped orbital sulcus. These are named, from their position, the medial, anterior, lateral, and posterior orbital gyri. The medial orbital gyrus presents a well-marked antero-posterior sulcus, the olfactory sulcus, for the olfactory tract; the portion medial to this is named the straight gyrus, and is continuous with the superior frontal gyrus on the medial surface.

name: parietal yolk sac
description: tissue that consists of two cellular layers (parietal endoderm and trophoblast) separated by a relatively thick nonvascular basement membrane (Reichert's membrane), and acts as a protective layer to supports and facilitates transport of nutrients between the uterine tissue and the yolk sac cavity.

name: organizer inducing center
description: The dorsal marginal region of the YSL where maternal dorsal determinants localize. Participates in positioning the shield. Ho et al, 1999.

name: mesonephric early distal tubule
description: The mesonephric equivalent of the ascending limb, or straight distal segment, of metanephric nephrons.

name: turbinate bone
description: the small curved bones that extends horizontally along the lateral wall of the nasal passage

name: transverse palatine suture
description: the line of junction between the processes of the maxilla and the horizontal parts of the palatine bones that form the hard palate.

name: inferior pulvinar nucleus
description: One of four subdivisions recognized in the primate pulvinar based on initially on topography, located ventrally between the medial and lateral geniculate bodies (Carpenter, A core text of neuroanatomy, 3rd ed., 1985, pg 238)

name: skeletal muscle tissue of pectoralis major
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a pectoralis major [Automatically generated definition].

name: neck of femur
description: The femur neck or neck of the femur is a flattened pyramidal process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft, and forming with the latter a wide angle opening medialward.

name: proximal phalanx of pedal digit 3
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a pedal digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: sartorius muscle
description: The Sartorius muscle - the longest muscle in the human body - is a long thin muscle that runs down the length of the thigh. Its upper portion forms the lateral border of the femoral triangle.

name: cephalic midbrain flexure
description: A sharp, ventrally concave bend in the developing midbrain of the embryo[MP].

name: ileocolic artery
description: The Ileocolic Artery is the lowest branch arising from the concavity of the superior mesenteric artery. It passes downward and to the right behind the peritoneum toward the right iliac fossa, where it divides into a superior and an inferior branch; the inferior anastomoses with the end of the superior mesenteric artery, the superior with the right colic artery. Supplies the cecum, ileum, and appendix. [WP,unvetted].

name: manual digit 4 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 4 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: foramen of Panizza
description: A hole with that connects the left and right aorta in animals of the order Crocodilia.

name: tensor tympani
description: The larger of the two muscles of the tympanic cavity, is contained in the bony canal above the osseous portion of the auditory tube. Its role is to dampen sounds produced from chewing. It arises from the cartilaginous portion of the auditory tube and the adjoining part of the great wing of the sphenoid, as well as from the osseous canal in which it is contained. Passing backward through the canal, it ends in a slender tendon which enters the tympanic cavity, makes a sharp bend around the extremity of the septum, known as the processus cochleariformis[1], and is inserted into the manubrium of the malleus, near its root[WP].

name: obsolete regional part of transverse temporal cortex
profundus foramen
description: Foramen for the profundus or ophthalmic nerve [PHENOSCAPE:AD]

name: intumescentia bilateralis superior
description: Small protuberance on the ischium, located at the level of the superior margin of the acetabulum and close to its posterior margin.

name: pleuroperitoneal canal lumen
description: A anatomical space that is enclosed by a pleuroperitoneal canal.

name: renal vesicle
description: The renal vesicle is the primordial structure of the nephron epithelium, and is formed by the condensation of mesenchymal cells.

name: ulna
description: The major postaxial endochondral bone in the anterior zeugopod[Phenoscape].

name: future dermis
description: Mesenchyme that has the potential to develop into a dermis.

name: extreme capsule
description: Thin band of fibers separating the claustrum from the insular cortex

name: hilum of spleen
description: The splenic hilum is a location on the surface of the spleen. It is the point of attachment for the gastrosplenic ligament, and the point of insertion for the splenic artery and splenic vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: nictitating membrane lamina
description: thin cartilage element that stiffens the nictitating membrane.

name: autopalatine-maxillary joint
description: Joint that articulates the autopalatine cartilage or bone and maxilla.

name: manual digit digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of manual digit plus the associated metapodial element.

name: vertical limb of the diagonal band
dorsal fin basal cartilage (elasmobranchs)
description: The large cartilage of the dorsal fin, on which the radials articulate distally. [Compagno 2001. Sharks of the World: An Annotated and Illustrated Catalogue of Shark Species Known to Date. Volume 2]

name: secretory circumventricular organ
description: A circumventricular organ that is capable of secreting substances into the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: life cycle temporal boundary
description: A temporal boundary connecting two life cycle stages that follow in immediate succession. A temporal boundary is an abstract, instantaneous entity.

name: somite 30
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: middle nuchal plate
description: Nuchal plate that is unpaired and part of dorsal fin proximal radial 1 and usually in contact with the anterior nuchal plate and paired posterior nuchal plates.

name: aggregate regional part of brain
description: A regional part of brain consisting of multiple brain regions that are not related through a simple volummetric part of hierarchy, e.g., basal ganglia[NIF].

name: superior branch of oculomotor nerve
description: The superior branch of the oculomotor nerve or the superior division, the smaller, passes medialward over the optic nerve. It supplies the Superior rectus and Levator palpebrae superioris.

name: trachea basal lamina
description: A basal lamina that is part of a respiratory airway [Automatically generated definition].

name: right lung respiratory bronchiole
description: A respiratory bronchiole that is part of a right lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: epithelium of uterine horn
description: An epithelium that is part of a uterine horn [Automatically generated definition].

name: rostrum of corpus callosum
description: The part of the corpus callosum that projects posteriorly and inferiorly from the anteriormost genu.

name: barnacle cement gland
description: Typical barnacles, common name of the sedentary crustacean marine animals constituting the subclass Cirripedia, attach to the substrate by means of an exceedingly adhesive cement, produced by a cement gland, and secrete a shell, or carapace, of calcareous (limestone) plates, around themselves.

name: obsolete predominantly gray part of basolateral nuclear complex
pedal digit 1 metatarsal endochondral element
description: A pedal digit 1 metatarsal bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: endocervical epithelium
description: The glandular epithelium that lines the endocervix.

name: transverse canal
description: Duct that crosses the midline connecting the sacculi.

name: mesenchyme of soft palate
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing soft palate [Automatically generated definition].

name: tibiotalar joint
description: A skeletal joint that connects a tibia and connects a talus.

name: obsolete cell space
description: Anatomical space that is part of a cell.

name: interscutular muscle
description: A muscle that attaches to the base of the ear and to the middle of the skull

name: secretion of exocrine gland
description: A portion of organism substance that is produced by exocrine glands.

name: M. tarsalis posticus
description: Originates on the medial border of the ligamentum calcanei and inserts along the ventral surface of the tibiale.

name: Jakubowski's organ
description: Neuromast of the supraorbital sensory canal in the nasal bone. It is innervated by the buccal nerve rather than by the supraorbital nerve, which invariably innervates neuromasts of the supraorbital canal. (Johnson and Patterson 1993).

name: ureteral orifice
description: The slit-like opening of either ureter into the bladder; normally, the two ureteral orifices are placed at the posterolateral angles of the urinary bladder trigone while the internal urethral orifice is placed at its anteroinferior angle (apex); wide gaping usually indicates vesicoureteral reflux

name: gastrico-linealis
description: Major branch which supplies blood to the spleen and dorsal wall of the stomach.

name: lateral line scale series
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one lateral line scale.

name: feather barbicel
description: A minute hook that projects off of a feather barbule, holding barbules together

name: obsolete zygote
description: Diploid cell produced by the fusion of sperm cell nucleus and egg cell.

name: somite 10
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: webbed pedal digit
description: A digit that is part of a webbed pes.

name: 2nd arch ectoderm
description: An ectoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 2.

name: spleen lymphoid follicle
description: The area of the white pulp where the affinity maturation of B cells and the generation of memory B cells and plasma cells occur

name: nacre
description: An organic-inorganic composite material produced by some mollusks as an inner shell layer; it is also what makes up pearls. It is very strong, resilient, and iridescent. Nacre is found in some ancient lineages of bivalve gastropod and cephalopod. The inner layer in the great majority of mollusk shells is porcellaneous, not nacreous, frequently resulting in a non-iridescent shine or less commonly in non-nacreous iridescence such as flame structure (e.g. conch pearl). Pearls and the inside layer of pearl oyster and freshwater pearl mussel shells are made of nacre. Many other families of mollusk also have a nacreous inner shell layer, including marine gastropods such as the Haliotidae, the Trochidae and the Turbinidae. Nacre is composed of hexagonal platelets of aragonite (a form of calcium carbonate) 10-20 ¬µm wide and 0.5 ¬µm thick arranged in a continuous parallel lamina. These layers are separated by sheets of organic matrix composed of elastic biopolymers (such as chitin, lustrin and silk-like proteins)[WP].

name: elastic cartilage tissue
description: Cartilage tissue that is flexible and contains abundant elastic fibers.

name: lateral cerebellomedullary cistern
description: The space between the cerebellum and the lateral aspect of the medulla

name: foregut duodenum mesentery
description: A mesentery of duodenum that is part of a foregut.

name: extrastriate cortex
description: A group of cortical areas related by direct or indirect connectivity to the striate area 17 and functionally involved primarily in vision. They include the parastriate area 18, the peristriate area 19 and adjacent areas in the parietal lobe and temporal lobe (Adapted from BrainInfo and Zilles-1990).

name: synovial fluid
description: Joint fluid is a transudate of plasma that is actively secreted by synovial cells.

name: medial longitudinal fasciculus of medulla
description: A medial longitudinal fasciculus that is part of a medulla [Automatically generated definition].

name: interpedicular line
description: An anatomical line that connects two successive vertebral pedicles. The length of this line is known as the interpedicular distance.

name: spinal cord ependyma
description: the ependymal cell layer that lines the spinal cord

name: obsolete regional part of inferior olivary complex
description: A regional part of brain that is part of a inferior olivary complex [Automatically generated definition].

name: acetabular depression
description: The central, most concave portion of the acetabulum, which remains open.

name: right renal vein
description: A renal vein that drains the right kidney

name: stratum zonale of thalamus
description: The thalamus consists chiefly of gray substance, but its upper surface is covered by a layer of white substance, named the stratum zonale.

name: articular surface for the calcaneum on the astragalus
description: Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the astragalus.

name: median preoptic nucleus
description: The median preoptic nucleus is located along the midline in a position significantly dorsal to the other 3 preoptic nuclei, at least in the macaca fascicularis brain. It wraps around the top (dorsal), front, and bottom (ventral) surfaces of the anterior commissure. The median preoptic nucleus generates thirst. Drinking decreases noradrenaline release in the median preoptic nucleus.

name: pars suprascapularis
description: Superior portion of the scapula, which is thinner than the rest of the shaft.

name: excretory gland
description: A gland that discharges its secretion through a duct opening on an internal or external surface of the body, as a lacrimal gland.

name: margo libera
description: Anterior, rounded portion of the corpus of the septomaxilla.

name: middle lateral line ganglion
description: The middle lateral line ganglion develops from a cranial ectodermal placode and contains sensory neurons that innervate the middle lateral line.

name: iliococcygeus muscle
description: The Iliococcygeus arises from the ischial spine and from the posterior part of the tendinous arch of the obturator fascia, and is attached to the coccyx and anococcygeal raphC); it is usually thin, and may fail entirely, or be largely replaced by fibrous tissue. It is part of the levator ani group of muscles. An accessory slip at its posterior part is sometimes named the Iliosacralis.

name: nervous system
description: The nervous system is an organ system containing predominantly neuron and glial cells. In bilaterally symmetrical organism, it is arranged in a network of tree-like structures connected to a central body. The main functions of the nervous system are to regulate and control body functions, and to receive sensory input, process this information, and generate behavior [CUMBO].

name: metathoracic segment
description: The third (most posterior) segment of the thorax.

name: opercle-interopercle joint
description: Joint that articulates the opercle and interopercle. Opercle-interopercle joint is paired.

name: obsolete superficial feature part of frontal lobe
primary subdivision of cranial skeletal system
pharyngobranchial 3 cartilage
description: Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.

name: capillary loop nephron
description: Developing nephron where the developing glomerular capsule has been invaded by a glomerular capillary loop called the glomerular tuft.

name: skeletal muscle tissue of eye
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a eye [Automatically generated definition].

name: genital disc primordium
description: Primordium from which the genital disc develops.

name: external naris epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of an external naris [Automatically generated definition].

name: infraorbital 4
description: Infraorbital that is the fourth bone of the infraorbital series.

name: intraorbital lacrimal gland
description: A lacrimal gland located superficially at the lateral canthus, where both the lacrimal gland and Harderian gland ducts open.

name: interdigital region between pedal digits 3 and 4
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a pedal digit 3 and adjacent_to a pedal digit 4.

name: trunk neural crest
description: Trunk portion of the neural crest. The trunk neural crest lies between the vagal and sacral neural crest and gives rise to two groups of cells. One group migrates dorsolateral and populates the skin, forming pigment cells and the other migrates ventrolateral through the anterior sclerotome to become the epinephrine-producing cells of the adrenal gland and the neurons of the sympathetic nervous system. Some cells remain in the sclerotome to form the dorsal root ganglia [Wikipedia].

name: coracoid bone
description: Endochondral bone that is paired and forms part of the socket for the humerus in tetrapods and acts as base of the pectoral fin in fish.

name: pigmented layer of retina
description: A monolayer of pigmented epithelium covering the neural retina; develops from the outer of the two layers of the optic cup[ZFA]. the pigmented cell layer just outside the neurosensory retina that nourishes retinal visual cells, and is firmly attached to the underlying choroid and overlying retinal visual cells[WP].

name: floor plate of metencephalon
description: A floor plate that is part of a metencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of manual digit
female reproductive organ
description: A female organ involved in reproduction

name: amniotic fluid
description: Amniotic fluid is a bodily fluid consisting of watery liquid surrounding and cushioning a growing fetus within the amnion. It allows the fetus to move freely without the walls of the uterus being too tight against its body. Buoyancy is also provided. The composition of the fluid changes over the course of gestation. Initially, amniotic fluid is similar to maternal plasma, mainly water with electrolytes. As the fetus develops, proteins, carbohydrates, lipids, phospholipids originating from the lungs, fetal cells, and urea are deposited in the fluid.

name: lumbar vertebra 2
description: The second lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: lip
description: One of the two fleshy folds which surround the opening of the mouth.

name: remnant of processus vaginalis
description: incompletely obliterated remnants of the vaginal process of the peritoneum remaining in the spermatic cord.

name: superficial temporal vein
description: The superficial temporal vein is a vein of the side of the head. [WP,unvetted].

name: equine glandular stomach
description: Stomach found in horses; includes cardiac, proper gastric and pyloric glandular zones.

name: jejunal epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a jejunum.

name: epiphysis of distal phalanx of pes
description: An epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of pes.

name: supraorbital bone
description: Dermal bone that is part of the dorsal or upper border or antero-dorsal border of the orbit. The supraorbital bone may contact the orbital margin of the frontal bone medially, the antorbital antero-ventrally and the dermosphenotic posteriorly. The supraorbital bone does not carry sensory canals. The supraorbital bone is paired.

name: caudal vertebra pre-cartilage condensation
description: A caudal vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: posterior limb of parapophysis 4
description: Process that arises and projects posterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Posterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.

name: acropodial skeleton
description: The subdivision of the skeleton that consists of all the skeletal elements at the distalmost end of the autopodium - i.e. the bones of the digits or their cartilaginous precursors[VSAO,modified].

name: pinhole eye
description: Simple eye that has a small aperture (which may be adjustable) and deep pit. It is only found in the nautiloids.

name: jaw skeleton
description: Subdivision of skeleton which includes upper and lower jaw skeletons.

name: conjunctival vein
description: A vein that is part of a conjunctiva.

name: posterior cleithral process
description: Process arising from the posterior or postero-dorsal margin of the cleithrum dorsally adjacent to the insertion of the pectoral fin. Posterior cleithral process is paired.

name: epaxial region somite 17
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: inferior longitudinal fasciculus
description: The inferior longitudinal fasciculus connects the temporal lobe and occipital lobe, running along the lateral walls of the inferior and posterior cornua of the lateral ventricle. The existence of this fasciculus independent from the occipitotemporal fasciculus has been questioned for the human being, such that it has been proposed that the term inferior longitudinal fasciculus be replaced by the term "occipitotemporal projection".

name: diaphysis proper
description: Subdivision of long bone which forms the part of the bone between two metaphyses. Note that the diaphysis includes the metaphyses, but the diaphysis proper excludes these.

name: urethral opening
description: An orifice that is part of a lower urinary tract.

name: pharyngeal tubercle
description: On the lower surface of the basilar part of occipital bone, about 1 cm. in front of the foramen magnum, is the pharyngeal tubercle which gives attachment to the fibrous raphC) of the pharynx, also known as the pharyngeal raphe. This is the point of attachment for the superior pharyngeal constrictor muscle.

name: female deep inguinal ring
description: A deep inguinal ring that is part of a male reproductive system.

name: urinary bladder muscularis mucosa
description: A thin layer of smooth muscle within the bladder lamina propria.

name: rostral entotympanic element
description: An entotympanic that arises in forward part of tympanic floor. It may be intimately fused witA cartilage of tube during development(MacPhee (1981: 62)) in contrast to a caudal entotympanic arising in the rear tympanic floor. From O'Leary et al. 2012

name: hindbrain-spinal cord boundary
description: An anatomical boundary that adjacent_to a hindbrain and adjacent_to a spinal cord.

name: central canal of spinal cord
description: Spinal cord structure that is part of the ventricular system and is filled with cerebral-spinal fluid and runs the length of the spinal cord.

name: ocular fundus
description: The posterior concave interior of the eye, consisting of the retina, the choroid, the posterior segment of the sclera, the optic disk, and blood vessels, visible by an ophthalmoscope

name: skin of face
description: A zone of skin that is part of the face.

name: reproductive system
description: Anatomical system that has as its parts the organs concerned with reproduction.

name: hypogastric nerve
description: The transition between the superior hypogastric plexus and the inferior hypogastric plexus.

name: future central nervous system
