description: Primordium that develops into the central nervous system

name: tail connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a tail [Automatically generated definition].

name: infra-orbital foramen of maxilla
description: A foramen on the exterior of the maxilla that is continuous with the infra-orbital canal and is the conduit for the passage of the infraorbital nerve and artery.

name: metanephric thick ascending limb
description: At the macula densa, the thick ascending limb connects to the distal convoluted tubule[GO].

name: neural crest
description: A specialized region of ectoderm found between the neural ectoderm (neural plate) and non-neural ectoderm and composed of highly migratory pluripotent cells that delaminate in early embryonic development from the dorsal neural tube and give rise to an astounding variety of differentiated cell types[MP].

name: endocardium of atrium
description: Endocardium that is part of the atrium.

name: upper leg bone
description: A bone that is part of a hindlimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: proximal-most prepollical element
description: Is the proximal-most prepollical element.

name: catecholamine system
description: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to the catecholamines.

name: synovial joint
description: Joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by an articular capsule which encloses a synovial membrane and a synovial cavity. Examples: Temporomandibular joint, knee joint.[FMA]

name: obsolete pars palatina of premaxilla
description: Lingual ledge on the inner surface of the premaxilla.

name: obsolete coffin bone
description: The bottommost bone in the equine leg and is encased by the hoof capsule. The distal phalanx articulates with both the middle phalanx and the distal sesamoid, forming the distal interphalangeal joint

name: pharyngobranchial 4 cartilage
description: Most posterior pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials.

name: abdomen
description: The subdivision of the vertebrate body between the thorax and pelvis. The ventral part of the abdomen contains the abdominal cavity and visceral organs. The dorsal part includes the abdominal section of the vertebral column.

name: left subcostal vein
description: A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the left side of the body.

name: parotid gland myoepithelium
description: epithelium that consists of stellate-shaped contractile cells with long dendritic processes that surround the secretory acini and intercalated ducts of the parotid gland, usually found in the glandular epithelium as a thin layer above the basement membrane but generally beneath the luminal cells; they display features of both smooth muscle and epithelium, such as numerous microfilaments with focal densities in the cytoplasmic processes, and desmosomes which attach them to the epithelial cells; their functions include contraction when the gland is stimulated to secrete, compressing or reinforcing the underlying parenchymal cells, thus aiding in the expulsion of saliva and preventing damage to the other cells

name: root of molar tooth
description: The part of a molar tooth that is implanted in the gum; mandibular and maxillary molars usually have two and three roots, respectively.

name: noninvoluting endocytic marginal cell cluster
description: The NEM cell cluster lies in a superficial position of the dorsal blastoderm margin encompassing EVL cells and one or two layers of underlying deep cells. Unlike other marginal blastomeres, cells in this cluster do not participate in involution. Cooper et al, 1996.

name: leg bone
description: A bone that is part of the region of the hindlimb that includes the zeugopod and stylopod. Examples: patella, femur, tibia. Counter-examples: any pes phalanx

name: anocleithrum
description: Dermal bone of pectoral girdle that is dorsal to and articulates with the cleithrum.

name: suture of hard palate
description: Any of the sutures of the hard palate

name: nuclear complex of neuraxis
description: Gray matter of the central nervous system which is a collection of clustered nuclei.

name: axial skeleton plus cranial skeleton
description: Subdivision of skeleton which consists of cranial skeleton, set of all vertebrae, set of all ribs and sternum[FMA, modified].

name: skeletal muscle tissue of rectus abdominis
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a rectus abdominis [Automatically generated definition].

name: cricoarytenoid ligament
description: Laryngeal ligament that connects the cricoid and arytenoid cartilages[WP,modified]

name: vomerine dentition
description: A set of teeth in which each tooth that attaches to a vomer.

name: proximal phalanx of pedal digit 4
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a pedal digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: medial marginal vein
description: a continuation of the Dorsal venous arch of the foot and is the origin of the long saphenous vein

name: biceps femoris
description: The biceps femoris is a muscle of the posterior (the back) thigh. As its name implies, it has two parts, one of which (the long head) forms part of the hamstrings muscle group. [WP,unvetted].

name: cervical flexure
description: A ventrally concave flexure of the embryonic brain occurring at the junction of hindbrain and spinal cord[MP].

name: obsolete regional part of paraventricular nucleus of hypothalamus magnocellular division
rib skeletal system
description: Subdivision of skeletal system that consists of all ribs and rib joints in an organism. In many vertebrates this consists of the combination of the rib cage and all rib joints, but some vertebrates have ribs outside the thoracic rib cage.

name: superior suprarenal artery
description: Each (left and right) superior suprarenal artery is a branch of the inferior phrenic artery on that side of the body. The left and right phrenic arteries supply the diaphragm, and come off the aorta. [WP,unvetted].

name: manual digit 5 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of manual digit 5 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: caudofemoralis
description: The caudofemoralis (from the latin cauda, tail and femur, thighbone) is a muscle found in the pelvic limb of mostly all animals possessing a tail, since it is a synapomorphy appeared on the Archosauria clade. It is thus found in felids (cats) and Mustela ('Weasels'), but also on crocodiles and birds.

name: extra-ocular muscle
description: Skeletal muscle derived from cranial mesoderm and controls eye movements.

name: umbilical blood vessel
description: One of the three blood vessels, usually one large umbilical vein and two small umbilical arteries, buried within Wharton's jelly, that transport blood to and from the placenta, where exchange between the mother and fetus takes place; the umbilical vein carries oxygenated, nutrient-rich blood from the placenta to the fetus, and the umbilical arteries carry deoxygenated, nutrient-depleted blood from the fetus to the placenta.

name: interhyal element
description: Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.

name: incisura terminalis
description: Small indentation on the posterior margin of the ischium, ventral to the intumescentia bilateralis superior.

name: median lingual swelling epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a median lingual swelling.

name: future diaphragm
description: A structure that will develop into a diaphragm.

name: scleral sesamoid bone
description: A sesamoid bone that lies adjacent to the tendon of one of the muscles responsible for adducting the nictitating membrane (the pyramidal nictitating muscle)

name: metapterygoid-autopalatine ligament
description: Ligament that connects the metapterygoid to the autopalatine.

name: sensory circumventricular organ
description: A circumventricular organ that is capable of monitoring the levels of substances to the cerebrospinal fluid.

name: life-death temporal boundary
description: A life cycle temporal boundary that marks the end of the life cycle of the organism.

name: stylohyoid bone
description: This is the paired bone that makes up the segment of the mammalian hyoid apparatus connecting the epihyoids with the skull via the tympanohyoid cartilages on each side. Ventrally, it defines the medial and lateral compartments of the guttural pouch in the horse.

name: coccygeal nerve plexus
description: The coccygeal plexus is a plexus of nerves near the coccyx bone.

name: dorsal fin proximal radial bone 1
description: dorsal fin proximal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: bronchus reticular lamina
description: A reticular lamina that is part of a bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: upper canine 1
description: first canine (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

name: mucosa of tongue
description: A mucosa that is part of a tongue [Automatically generated definition].

name: abdominopelvic cavity
description: The part of the ventral body cavity that is within the abdominal segment of the trunk, which encompasses the abdomen proper plus pelvic cavity.

name: left lung respiratory bronchiole
description: A respiratory bronchiole that is part of a left lung [Automatically generated definition].

name: epithelium of vomeronasal organ
description: An epithelium that is part of a vomeronasal organ [Automatically generated definition].

name: gall bladder
description: An organ that aids digestion and stores bile produced by the liver[WP].

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of inferior frontal gyrus
obsolete CoB
description: A bifurcate interneuron. It is a commissural neuron with both ascending and descending axons in the ventrolateral cord contralateral to its cell body.

name: anatomical conduit space
description: An anatomical space which is the lumen of some anatomical conduit and connects two or more spaces together[FMA,modified].

name: arcuate ligament
description: A ligament that is part of a diaphragm.

name: dilatatio alaris
description: Flange that extends ventrally from about the middle portion of the margo mandibularis.

name: pedal digit 2 metatarsal endochondral element
description: A pedal digit 2 metatarsal bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: cervical squamo-columnar junction
description: Region of cervical epithelium where columnar epithelium of endocervic and the stratified non-keratinising squamous epithelium of the ectocervic meet

name: mesenchyme of submandibular gland
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing submandibular gland [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete epithelial cell
description: Cell which has as its part a cytoskeleton that allows for tight cell to cell contact and which has apical-basal cell polarity.

name: frontalis muscle belly
description: A belly of the occipitofrontalis muscle that is near the frontal bone

name: cavernous artery
description: Any of several small branches of the internal carotid artery that supply the trigeminal ganglion and the walls of the cavernous and petrosal sinuses.

name: M. plantaris profundus
description: Originates on the medial half of the ligamentum calcanei and inserts along the dorsal surface of the aponeurosis plantaris and extends to the level of the base of the prehallux.

name: obsolete median fin
description: Fin that is an unpaired fin located in the sagittal plane of the organism.

name: nasal diverticulum
description: Caudally blind-ending cutaneous pouch lined with skin that occupies the nasoincisive notch. It's ventral and medial walls is formed by the alar fold. It's lateral wall is formed by the external nares and it's dorsal wall is formed by the straight fold. Lined by pigmented predominantly hairless skin. It has an external opening located on the dorsolateral aspect of the "true nostril". When the horse is exercising, obliteration of the nasal diverticulum greatly widens the nostrils increasing air intake[MURDOCH].

name: duodeno-pancreatic artery
description: Major branch which supplies blood to pancreas and duodenum.

name: alveolar foramen
description: Foramen for the R. alveolaris of Nerve VII and the alveolar artery.

name: suprahyoid muscle
description: A muscle in the region above the hyoid bone in the neck. The suprahyoid muscles include digastric, stylohyoid, geniohyoid, and mylohyoid.

name: nose tip
description: Outermost point on an external nose or snout

name: somite 13
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: tooth crown
description: The portion of the tooth covered by enamel.

name: scalenus anterior
description: The Scalenus anterior (Scalenus anticus), also known as anterior scalene muscle, lies deeply at the side of the neck, behind the Sternocleidomastoideus. It arises from the anterior tubercles of the transverse processes of the third, fourth, fifth, and sixth cervical vertebrC&, and descending, almost vertically, is inserted by a narrow, flat tendon into the scalene tubercle on the inner border of the first rib, and into the ridge on the upper surface of the rib in front of the subclavian groove.

name: spinal nerve plexus
description: an intermingling of fiber fascicles from adjacent spinal nerves to form a network.

name: flexor pollicis longus muscle
description: A muscle in the forearm and hand that flexes the thumb. It lies in the same plane as the flexor digitorum profundus.

name: 3rd arch ectoderm
description: An ectoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 3.

name: valve of inferior vena cava
description: the semicircular fold of endocardium located on the right atrium at the point of attachment of the inferior vena cava; during development this valve helps direct the flow of oxygen-rich blood through the right atrium into the left cardiac atrium via the foramen ovale (preventing blood flowing into the right ventricle)

name: quadrigeminal cistern
description: The enclosed space extending forward between the corpus callosum and the thalamus that contains the internal cerebral veins

name: cranial appendage
description: An anatomical projection that is part of and protrudes from the head

name: midgut duodenum mesentery
description: A mesentery of duodenum that is part of a midgut.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of median eminence
future telencephalon
description: Embryonic structure that gives rise to the telencephalon.

name: calcareous tooth
description: Skeletal element within the mouth (or in some species, upper part of the digestive tract) that is composed of dentine and is used in procuring or masticating food.

name: process 3
description: Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle (see Coates 1996)

name: inferior temporal gyrus
description: Component of the temporal lobe, lateral aspect. The rostral boundary is the rostral extent of the inferior temporal sulcus whereas the caudal boundary is designated as the temporo-occipital incisure on the cortical surface. The occipitotemporal sulcus is the medial boundary and the inferior temporal sulcus is the lateral boundary (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: ventral ectodermal ridge
description: A thickening of the surface ectoderm on the ventral side of the embryonic tail which resembles the apical ectodermal ridge of the limb bud.

name: alveolar ridge
description: one of the two jaw ridges either on the roof of the mouth between the upper teeth and the hard palate or on the bottom of the mouth behind the lower teeth[WP]. The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth[HP].

name: lesser omentum
description: The double layer of peritoneum that extends from the liver to the lesser curvature of the stomach and the start of the duodenum. [WP,unvetted].

name: left renal vein
description: A renal vein that drains the left kidney

name: growth line
description: Distinct layer that indicate the growth of an organism.

name: left parietal lobe
description: Parietal lobe of the left hemisphere of the brain

name: articular surface for the astragalus on the calcaneum
description: Contact surface between the calcaneum and the astragalus located on the calcaneum.

name: head of caudate nucleus
description: Largest part of the caudate nucleus lying lateral to and protruding into the anterior of the lateral ventricle

name: sinus interglenoidalis
description: Notch or indentation between the pars glenoidalis and pars acromialis of the scapula.

name: antennal gland
description: Excretory gland situated in the basal article of the antennal peduncle. It functions to rehulate ionic balance

name: basibranchial tooth
description: Tooth that is part of the basibranchial tooth plate.

name: crista interna
description: Sharp ridge that extends medially from the basal part of the processus infrafenestralis; it separates the diverticulum proncipale from the diverticulum medium.

name: obsolete superficial blastomere
description: Cells (completely cleaved), located at the surface of the blastodisc, above the deep blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: puborectalis muscle
description: The fibers which form a sling for the rectum are named the Puborectalis or Sphincter recti. They arise from the lower part of the symphysis pubis, and from the superior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm. They meet with the corresponding fibers of the opposite side around the lower part of the rectum, and form for it a strong sling. Relaxation reduces the angle between rectum and anus, allowing defecation in conjunction with relaxation of the internal and external sphincters. Puborectalis is part of the levator ani group of muscles.

name: central nervous system
description: The central nervous system is the core nervous system that serves an integrating and coordinating function. In vertebrates it consists of the neural tube derivatives: the brain and spinal cord. In invertebrates it includes central ganglia plus nerve cord.

name: frontal-pterotic joint
description: Joint that articulates the frontal and pterotic. Frontal-pterotic joint is paired.

name: mesonephric capsule
description: The mesonephric capsule is the tough fibrous layer surrounding the mesonephros, covered in a thick layer of perinephric adipose tissue.

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of posterior hypothalamic region
pelvic girdle bone/zone
description: A bone element or fused bone that is part of pelvic girdle.

name: dorsal fin fold
description: Region of the median fin fold that develops into the dorsal fin.

name: body of gallbladder
description: The middle portion of the gallbladder which is distal to the gallbladder neck and proximal to the gallbladder fundus.

name: male genital disc primordium
description: Primordium from which the male genital disc derives.

name: Peyer's patch epithelium
description: the specialized epithelium of the Peyer's patch

name: endoderm of hindgut
description: An endoderm that is part of a hindgut [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete mesoderm of gonad
description: A mesoderm that is part of a gonad [Automatically generated definition].

name: heart primordium
description: Bilateral groups of cells consisting of three rows: one row of endocardial precursors medially and two rows of myocardical precursors laterally. The two populations fuse at the midline to form the heart rudiment or cone.

name: loose mesenchyme tissue
description: Mesenchyme whose cells are embedded in obvious amounts of extracellular matrix.

name: optic disc
description: The optic disc or optic nerve head is the location where ganglion cell axons exit the eye to form the optic nerve. There are no light sensitive rods or cones to respond to a light stimulus at this point. This causes a break in the visual field called 'the blind spot' or the 'physiological blind spot'. The optic nerve head in a normal human eye carries from 1 to 1.2 million neurons from the eye towards the brain. [WP,unvetted].

name: floor plate of medulla oblongata
description: A floor plate that is part of a medulla oblongata [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of fornix
distal epiphysis of distal phalanx of digit
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx.

name: short bone
description: Short bones are designated as those bones that are as wide as they are long. Their primary function is to provide support and stability with little to no movement. They are one of five types of bones: long, short, flat, irregular and sesamoid. Examples of these bones include the tarsals in the foot and the carpals in the hand.

name: male reproductive organ
description: A male organ involved in reproduction

name: spheno-maxillary fossa
description: The speno-maxillary fossa is a small triangular space situated at the angle of the junction of the spheno-maxillary and pterygo-maxillary fissures, and placed beneath the apex of the orbit. It is formed above by the under surface of the body of the sphenoid and by the orbital process of the palate bone.

name: lumbar vertebra 3
description: The third lumbar vertebra counting from the top down. Note that members of this class are not necessarily homologous[ncit,modified].

name: upper lip
description: Lip that covers the upper portion of the mouth.[TAO].

name: canal of Nuck
description: A patent pouch of peritoneum extending into the labia majora of women. It is analogous to the processus vaginalis in males. The pouch accompanies the gubernaculum during development of the urinary and reproductive organs, more specifically during the descent of the ovaries, and normally obliterates.

name: middle temporal vein
description: A temporal vein that arises near the lateral angle of the eye; joins the superficial temporal veins to form the retromandibular vein.

name: nucleus of cerebellar nuclear complex
description: Four accumulations of gray substance embedded in the white substance of the cerebellum, comprising the nucleus dentatus, nucleus emboliformis, nucleus globosus, and nucleus fastigii.

name: mandibular ramus
description: the upturned perpendicular extremity of the mandible

name: piriform cortex layer 2a
description: Superficial region of layer 2 of the piriform cortex characterized by a less dense packing of cells and a concentration of semilunar cell bodies

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 1
description: dorsal fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: protogynous hermaphroditic organism
description: Sequential hermaphroditic organism that produces gametes first of the female sex, and then later of the male sex.

name: epiphysis of proximal phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a proximal phalanx of manus.

name: symplectic
description: Replacement bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with the hyomandibula and the quadrate.

name: cervical vertebra cartilage element
description: A cervical vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: hindlimb zeugopod skeleton
description: Subdivision of skeleton consisting of all skeletal elements in an hindlimb zeugopod region. Typically consists of the tibia and the fibula.

name: anterior paraventricular nucleus of thalamus
description: The anterior of the two nuclei paraventriculares thalami.

name: obsolete regional part of frontal lobe
anterior limb of parapophysis 4
description: Process that arises and projects anterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Anterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.

name: metacarpus skeleton
description: The metacarpus is the intermediate part of the manus skeleton that is located between the phalanges (bones of the fingers) distally and the carpus which forms the connection to the forearm. The metacarpus consists of metacarpal bones. The metacarpals form a transverse arch to which the rigid row of distal carpal bones are fixed. The peripheral metacarpals (those of the thumb and little finger) form the sides of the cup of the palmar gutter and as they are brought together they deepen this concavity. The index metacarpal is the most firmly fixed, while the thumb metacarpal articulates with the trapezium and acts independently from the others. The middle metacarpals are tightly united to the carpus by intrinsic interlocking bone elements at their bases. The ring metacarpal forms a transitional element of the semi-independent last metacarpal. [WP,unvetted].

name: spherical lensed eye
description: simple eye that consists of a lens of one refractive index

name: upper jaw region
description: Subdivision of head that consists of the upper jaw skeletal elements plus associated soft tissue (skin, lips, muscle)[cjm].

name: cremasteric artery
description: The cremasteric artery (external spermatic artery) is a branch of the Inferior epigastric artery which accompanies the spermatic cord, and supplies the Cremaster and other coverings of the cord, anastomosing with the testicular artery (internal spermatic artery in older texts). (In the female, the cremesteric artery is very small and accompanies the round ligament.)

name: obsolete regional part of granular layer of cerebellar cortex
pulmonary lobule
description: The smallest anatomical unit of the lung, measuring 0.50 to 2.00 cm in diameter. Each lobule is composed of 4-8 terminal bronchioles and their distal alveolar ducts and sacs. The lobules are separated by fibrous interlobular septa.

name: epaxial region somite 2
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: diaphysis of femur
description: A diaphysis that is part of a femur[Automatically generated definition].

name: spinal vein
description: A vein that is part of a vertebral column.

name: obsolete ansulate commissure
description: A brainstem commissure that contains major crossed descending projections from both tectal lobes.

name: crus of penis or clitoris
description: the continuation of each corpus cavernosum of the penis or clitoris, diverging posteriorly to be attached to the pubic arch.

name: head mesenchyme
description: Portion of primordial embryonic connective tissue of the developing head, consisting of mesenchymal cells supported in interlaminar jelly, that derive mostly from the mesoderm and contribute to head connective tissue, bone and musculature in conjunction with cranial neural crest cells.

name: lip epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a lip.

name: neuropore
description: A temporary opening leading from the central canal of the embryonic neural tube to the exterior.

name: costovertebral joint
description: The costovertebral joints are the articulations that connect the heads of the ribs with the bodies of the thoracic vertebrae. Joining of ribs to the vertebrae occurs at two places, the head and the tubercle of the rib. Two convex facets from the head attach to two adjacent vertebrae. This forms a trochoid joint, which is strengthened by the ligament of the head and the intercapital ligament. Articulation of the tubercle is to the transverse process of the adjacent vertebrae. This articulation is reinforced by the dorsal costotransverse ligament. [WP,unvetted].

name: anterior stroma of cornea
description: The anterior segment of the lamellated connective tissue layer of the cornea

name: Zymbal's gland
description: A multilobulated modified sebaceous gland that is located at the base of the external ear, lined by stratified squamous epithelium, and secretes into the auditory canal

name: gonad
description: Reproductive organ that produces and releases eggs (ovary) or sperm (testis).

name: submucous nerve plexus
description: the gangliated plexus of unmyelinated nerve fibers that ramify the stomach and intestinal submucosa

name: obsolete matrix part of body of caudate nucleus
abdomen musculature
description: Set of all muscles in abdomen.

name: recessus vaginiformis
description: Is a space on the interior surface of the pars facialis of the maxilla

name: set of upper jaw teeth
description: A tooth row that is part of a skeleton of upper jaw.

name: right lung
description: Lung which consists of the right upper lobe, middle lobe and right lower lobe.[FMA]

name: otic plate of pterygoid
description: Osseous expansion of the posterior and medial rami of the pterygoid.

name: thoracic segment bone
description: A bone that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].

name: muscle layer of cloaca
description: A muscular coat that is part of a cloaca.

name: distal-most prepollical element
description: Is the distal-most prepollical element.

name: sublaminar layers S3 or S4
description: One of sublaminar layers S3 or S4.

name: tympanic ring
description: A C-shaped membranous bone that provides physical support to the tympanic membrane. The tympanic ring develops sequentially from an initial primordium in the first branchial arch growing in a circumferential fashion around the first pharyngeal cleft into the second branchial arch (Mallo and Gridley, 1996). In most mammals, the tympanic ring exists only during embryonic life, when it coordinates proper development and positioning of the eardrum (see below), and then becomes integrated into the temporal bone[PMID].

name: short pastern bone
description: The middle phalanx of digit 3 in a horse

name: pharyngobranchial 3 bone
description: Pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.

name: M. flexor carpi ulnaris
description: Muscle which originates from the medial condyle of the humerus and inserts on the carpus.

name: intestinal bulb
description: This anteriormost portion of the intestine has the most digestive enzymes and the greatest epithelial surface area. Wallace et al, 2005.

name: epiphysis of fifth metacarpal bone
description: An epiphysis that is part of a metacarpal bone of digit 5.

name: wing hair
description: The posteriorly oriented trichome of a cell of the wing blade. Each cell makes one of these trichomes at its posterior vertex.

name: superior surface of tongue
description: The upper (superior) side of the tongue.

name: lateral nasal gland
description: Any of the lateral nasal glands (the largest nasal secretory glands in rodents) which surround the maxillary sinus located in the lateral wall adjacent to each nasal passage and are characterized by cytologic features similar to those described for the major serous salivary glands; secretory contents of the LNG drain into the nasal vestibule; the LNG is a major site for the synthesis and secretion of odorant-binding proteins that serve as odorant carriers in nasal mucus; it also, synthesizes large amounts of immunoglobulin A, which is important for immune defense of the upper respiratory tract, and testosterone and salivary androgen-binding proteins, which are likely important in olfaction and reproductive behavior

name: stroma of bone marrow
description: The stroma of the bone marrow is all tissue not directly involved in the primary function of hematopoiesis. The yellow bone marrow belongs here, and makes the majority of the bone marrow stroma, in addition to stromal cells located in the red bone marrow. Yellow bone marrow is found in the Medullary cavity. Still, the stroma is indirectly involved in hematopoiesis, since it provides the hematopoietic microenvironment that facilitates hematopoiesis by the parenchymal cells. For instance, they generate colony stimulating factors, affecting hematopoiesis.

name: placenta metrial gland
description: A group of granular epithelial cells in the uterine muscle beneath the placenta that develops during pregnancy in rodents and some other species.

name: obsolete locomotive weight-bearing appendage
description: OBSOLETE: A leg is a limb on which an animal walks and stands (GO:0035110).

name: skeletal musculature of head
description: Any collection of skeletal muscles that is part of a head [Automatically generated definition].

name: palatine aponeurosis
description: Attached to the posterior border of the hard palate is a thin, firm fibrous lamella called the palatine aponeurosis, which supports the muscles and gives strength to the soft palate. It is thicker above than below, where it becomes very thin and difficult to define. Laterally it is continuous with the pharyngeal aponeurosis. It serves as the insertion for the Tensor veli palatini and Levator veli palatini, and the origin for the Musculus uvulae, Palatopharyngeus, and Palatoglossus. It provides support for the soft palate.

name: basement membrane of epithelium
description: An acellular membrane that is part of the epithelium, lies adjacent to the epithelial cells, and is the fusion of the the basal lamina and the reticular lamina.

name: lateral dorsal nucleus
description: The lateral dorsal nucleus is a nucleus of the thalamus. It acts in concert with the anterior nuclei of thalamus. It receives significant input from several subdivisions of visual cortex, and has a primary output to parietal cortex on the dorsolateral cortical convexity, giving it access to limbic forebrain nuclei important for emotion and behavior functions.

name: skeletal muscle tissue of supraspinatus
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a supraspinatus [Automatically generated definition].

name: cricothyroid ligament
description: This attaches the caudal border of the thyroid cartilage to the ventral arch of the cricoid cartilage. Its sheetlike ventral portion is sometimes referred to as the cricothyroid membrane. Being elastic, it 'balances' movement at the hinge-like cricothyroid joint and determines the resting position of the larynx when the muscles are relaxed[MURDOCH]. The cricothyroid ligament is the larger part of the laryngeal membrane, continuing inferiorly as a median or anterior part and twin lateral ligaments. The median cricothyroid ligament is a flat band of white tissue joining the cricoid and thyroid cartilages, while the lateral cricothyroid ligament is also known as the cricothyroid membrane (also called conus elasticus).

name: afferent spiracular artery
description: A section of a pharyngeal arch artery that carries blood away from the spiracle.

name: proximal phalanx of pedal digit 5
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a pedal digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: semitendinosus
description: The semitendinosus is a muscle in the back of the thigh; it is one of the hamstrings. [WP,unvetted].

name: elephant trunk
description: An appendage formed by the fusion of the nose and upper lip.

name: embryo portion of umbilical artery
description: Each of the two arteries arising from the hypogastric arteries of the fetus and passing throught the umbilical cord to the placenta.

name: mucosa of stomach
description: The mucosal layer that lines the stomach.

name: otic notch
description: Otic notches are invagination in the posterior margin of the skull roof, one behind each orbit. Such notches are found in labyrinthodonts and some of their immediate ancestors, but not their reptilian descendants. The presence or absence of the otic notches is one of the traits used to separate the amniotes from the amphibian grade tetrapods.

name: medial rectus extraocular muscle
description: The medial rectus muscle is a muscle in the orbit. As with most of the muscles of the orbit, it is innervated by the inferior division of the oculomotor nerve (Cranial Nerve III). This muscle shares an origin with several other extrinsic eye muscles, the anulus tendineus, or common tendon. It is the largest of the extraocular muscles and its only action is adduction of the eyeball. [WP,unvetted].

name: hypobranchial element
description: Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial element.

name: pulmonary valve leaflets
description: A cardiac valve leaflet that is part of a pulmonary valve.

name: adipose fin actinotrichium
description: Actinotrichium that is part of the adipose fin.

name: subopercle
description: Dermal bone that is part of the opercular series, lying below the opercle. The subopercle is paired and is typically a thin bone.

name: immature eye
description: Developing anatomical structure that develops into the eyeball and associated structures.

name: lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament
description: Lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the autopalatine.

name: epithelial sheet
description: An epithelial sheet is a flat surface consisting of closely packed epithelial cells.

name: retractor tentaculi
description: Bilaterally paired dorsal hyoid arch muscle that retracts the maxillary barbel.

name: start of life cycle
description: A life cycle temporal boundary that marks the start of the life cycle of the organism.

name: left atrium auricular region
description: A muscular pouch connected to the left atrium of the heart

name: dorsal fin proximal radial bone 2
description: dorsal fin proximal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: pleuropericardial folds
description: Each of the folds that grow out from the lateral part of the body wall. They fuse and meet with the dorsal and ventral mesentery of the foregut, separating the pleural cavities from the pericardial cavity.

name: trachea reticular lamina
description: A reticular lamina that is part of a trachea [Automatically generated definition].

name: upper deciduous premolar 5
description: Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the upper jaw.

name: mucosa of sphenoidal sinus
description: A mucosa that is part of a sphenoidal sinus [Automatically generated definition].

name: femoral artery
description: The femoral artery is a large artery in the muscles of the thigh. It is a continuation of external iliac artery where it enters the femoral triangle at the mid inguinal point behind the inguinal ligament. It leaves femoral triangle through apex beneath the sartorius muscle. It enters the popliteal fossa by passing through the 5th osseo-aponeurotic(adductor hiatus) opening of adductor magnus where it becomes the Popliteal Artery. [WP,unvetted].

name: palmar interosseous muscle of manus
description: Any of three muscles, the first with its origin from the second metacarpal, and the second and the third with origin from the fourth and fifth metacarpals; the first with insertion into the index finger, and the second and the third with insertion into the ring and little fingers; with nerve supply from the ulnar nerve, and whose action adducts the fingers toward the axis of the middle finger.

name: anterior cranial fossa
description: The floor of the anterior fossa is formed by the orbital plates of the frontal, the cribriform plate of the ethmoid, and the small wings and front part of the body of the sphenoid; it is limited behind by the posterior borders of the small wings of the sphenoid and by the anterior margin of the chiasmatic groove. The lesser wings of the sphenoid separate the anterior and middle fossae.

name: superior pharyngeal constrictor
description: The superior pharyngeal constrictor muscle is a quadrilateral muscle, thinner and paler than the inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscle and middle pharyngeal constrictor muscle. [WP,unvetted].

name: brain white matter
description: The regions of the brain that are largely or entirely composed of myelinated nerve cell axons and contain few or no neural cell bodies or dendrites.

name: epithelium of hard palate
description: An epithelium that is part of a hard palate [Automatically generated definition].

name: artery smooth muscle tissue
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an artery [Automatically generated definition].

name: pericranium
description: Periosteum that is part of a skull.

name: median arcuate ligament
description: The median arcuate ligament is a ligament under the diaphragm that connects the right and left crura of diaphragm.

name: tunica fibrosa of eyeball
description: The sclera and cornea form the fibrous tunic of the bulb of the eye; the sclera is opaque, and constitutes the posterior five-sixths of the tunic; the cornea is transparent, and forms the anterior sixth.

name: pedal digit 3 metatarsal endochondral element
description: A pedal digit 3 metatarsal bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: abdominal aorta artery
description: An artery that originates from the abdominal aorta

name: mesenchyme of parotid
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing parotid gland [Automatically generated definition].

name: fovea capitis of femur
description: The surface of the head of the femur is smooth, coated with cartilage in the fresh state, except over an ovoid depression, the fovea of head of femur, which is situated a little below and behind the center of the head, and gives attachment to the ligamentum teres.

name: obsolete obsolete single cell organism
description: Cell that is an individual member of a species.

name: parabrachial pigmental nucleus
description: Nucleus identified in the medial ventral tegmental area that borders the red nucleus and superior cerebellar peduncle dorsally, the medial lemniscus laterally, the subtantia nigra pars compacta and paranigral nucleus ventrally and the rostral linear nucleus and interfascicular nucleus medially. Generally, the largest nucleus in the ventral tegmental area, occupying an average of 50% of the total volume as measured in rat, cat, monkey and human.

name: nasalis muscle
description: The nasalis (compressor naris) is a sphincter-like muscle of the nose whose function is to compress the nasal cartilage. It consists of two parts, transverse and alar: The transverse part arises from the maxilla, above and lateral to the incisive fossa; its fibers proceed upward and medially, expanding into a thin aponeurosis which is continuous on the bridge of the nose with that of the muscle of the opposite side, and with the aponeurosis of the Procerus. The alar part is attached at one end to the greater alar cartilage, and at the other to the integument at the point of the nose. Other sources divide it into 'Compressor nasalis' and 'Dilator nasalis'.

name: endocervix
description: The region of the opening of the uterine cervix into the uterine cavity.

name: obsolete musculus rectus superior
description: Cranial nerve III innervated; dorsal in the rectus group.

name: pectoral fin distal radial bone 1
description: pectoral fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: marginal cutaneous pouch of ear
description: A fold of skin at the caudal border of the auricle.

name: myotome somite 30
description: Portion of the somite giving rise to body wall muscle masses. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: duodeno-hepatic artery
description: Major branch supplying blood via many smaller branches to the liver, duodenum, ventral wall of the stomach, and gall bladder.

name: posterior crico-arytenoid
description: The posterior cricoarytenoid muscles are extremely small, paired muscles that extend from the posterior cricoid cartilage to the arytenoid cartilages in the larynx. By rotating the arytenoid cartilages laterally, these muscles abduct the vocal cords and thereby open the rima glottidis. Their action opposes the lateral cricoarytenoid muscles. The posterior cricoarytenoid muscles receive innervation from the recurrent laryngeal branch of the vagus nerve (CN X). Paralysis of the posterior cricoarytenoid muscles may lead to asphyxiation as they are the only laryngeal muscles to open the true vocal folds, allowing inspiration and expiration.

name: radial head of humerus
description: Hemispherical ball located at the lower end of the humerus that stands out prominently from the surrounding structures toward the flexor surface of the forelimb

name: obsolete blastocoel anlage
description: The first appearance of the antomical space that will become the blastocoel.

name: somite 16
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: ventral medial complex of thalamus
description: A group of nuclei located in the medial portion of the ventral thalamic nuclei.

name: intermetatarsal joint
description: A joint that connects two adjacent metatarsals

name: 4th arch ectoderm
description: An ectoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 4.

name: external male genitalia
description: The external masculine genital organs, including the penis and scrotum

name: exoccipital-atlas joint
description: A synovial joint that connects a vertebral bone 1 and connects a exoccipital bone.

name: fibroelastic membrane of larynx
description: A layer of fibrous and elastic fibers, taking the place of the submucosa in the larynx. It is divided by the laryngeal ventricle into two parts: the quadrangular membrane superiorly and the conus elasticus inferiorly.

name: vertebral bone 1
description: The first vertebral bone in the vertebral column.

name: process 4
description: Process on the humerus of basal tetrapods, anterior to the entepicondyle (see Coates 1996)

name: olivocerebellar tract
description: The olivocerebellar tract (olivocerebellar fibers) leaves the olivary nucleus and pass out through the hilum and decussate with those from the opposite olive in the raph√©, then as internal arcuate fibers they pass partly through and partly around the opposite olive and enter the inferior peduncle to be distributed to the cerebellar hemisphere of the opposite side from which they arise. They terminate directly on Purkinje cells as the climbing fiber input system. [WP,unvetted].

name: temporal pole
description: Anterior component of the temporal lobe (rostral boundary) extends caudally to the entorhinal cortex. The medial and lateral boundaries are the medial aspect of the temporal lobe and the superior or inferior temporal sulci, respectively (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: ilial ridge
description: Longitudinal crest on the dorsal side of the shaft of the ilium.

name: hairline
description: Anatomical line demarcating the boundary between forehead and scalp.

name: hepatic vein
description: Vein that carries blood away from the liver[ZFA].

name: distal groove of humerus
description: Groove along the distal margin of the humerus, ventral to the radial and ulnar condyle.

name: right parietal lobe
description: Parietal lobe of the right hemisphere of the brain

name: astragalo-calcaneal canal
description: The astragalo-calcaneal canal forms a foramen between the articulated astragalus and calcaneum when the canal is ossified (Nesbitt, 2011).

name: piriformis muscle
description: The piriformis is a muscle in the gluteal region that originates from the anterior (front) part of the sacrum, the part of the spine in the gluteal region, and from the superior margin of the greater sciatic notch (as well as the sacroiliac joint capsule and the sacrotuberous ligament). It exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen to insert on the greater trochanter of the femur. Its tendon often joins with the tendons of the superior gemellus, inferior gemellus, and obturator internus muscles prior to insertion[WP,modified].

name: tenuitas cristaeformis
description: Leading (anterior) portion of the scapula, which is thinner than the rest of the shaft.

name: crustacean maxillary gland
description: Excretory organ in maxillary segment with duct opening on maxilla.

name: basibranchial tooth plate
description: Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchials 1-3.

name: crista praeopercularis
description: Synchondrotic or synostotic connection between the footplate of the pars media plectri and the ventral margin of the fenestra ovalis.

name: axon tract
description: A group of axons linking two or more neuropils and having a common origin, termination[FBbt].

name: exudate
description: Fluids that is discharged from blood vessels usually arising from inflammation or injury.

name: dorsal actinotrichium
description: Actinotrichium which is part of the dorsal fin fold.

name: pharyngobranchial 2 cartilage
description: Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.

name: renal sinus
description: A hollowed out area on the medial margin of the kidney. The renal sinus opens at the renal hilum; it contains the renal aa. and vv., major calyces and renal pelvis, perirenal fat

name: pectoral girdle skeleton
description: A subdivision of a limb or fin skeleton consisting of bones which connects the upper limb or fin to the axial skeleton on each side. It consists of the clavicle and scapula in humans and, in those species with three bones in the pectoral girdle, the coracoid. Some mammalian species (e.g. the dog and the horse) have only the scapula. In humans, the only joints between the shoulder girdle and axial skeleton are the sternoclavicular joints on each side. No joint exists between each scapula and the rib cage; instead the muscular connection between the two permits relatively great mobility of the shoulder girdle in relation to the pelvic girdle. In those species having only the scapula, no joint exists between the forelimb and the thorax, the only attachment being muscular[WP]. Examples: There are only two instances, right and left pectoral girdle skeletons.

name: uncinate fasciculus of the forebrain
description: A fiber pathway in the cerebral white matter that connects anterior portions of the temporal lobe with the inferior frontal gyrus and the middle frontal gyrus. It is not readily distinguished in myelin-stained cross-sections (adapted from Brain Info).

name: supramaxilla
description: Dermal bone that is located on the dorsal margin of the maxilla, usually at the dorso-posterior region of maxilla. The supramaxilla is a paired bone.

name: superficial cervical lymph node
description: A group of nodes lying along the external jugular vein; they drain the skin and superficial structures over the region of the sternocleidomastoid muscle and anterior cervical regions. Efferent vessels drain to the deep cervical lymph nodes. Lymph nodes can be further subdivided into anterior and lateral groupings.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of lateral geniculate body
female genital disc primordium
description: Primordium from which the female genital disc derives.

name: Harderian gland epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a Harderian gland [Automatically generated definition].

name: future diencephalon
description: The foremost region of the future forebrain that develops into the diencephalon.

name: lobe of lacrimal gland
description: An anatomical lobe that is part of a lacrimal gland

name: thyroid primordium endoderm
description: An endoderm that is part of a thyroid primordium.

name: subdivision of digestive tract
description: A proximal-distal subdivision of the digestive tract.

name: anterior mesenteric artery
description: Unpaired artery departing from dorsal aorta, typically supplying the small intestine

name: ventral aorta
description: The ventral aorta is a blood vessel in a single-pass circulatory system that carries de-oxygenated blood from the heart to the gills. In a single-pass circulatory system blood passes once through the heart to supply the body once[GO].

name: parasphenoid
description: A tooth- or denticle-covered plate which is attached to the sphenoid stem[Palaeos].

name: periarterial lymphatic sheath
description: The area of the spleen in which T cells surround the central arteriole

name: mesenchyme of testis
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing testis [Automatically generated definition].

name: iliotibialis muscle
description: A muscle in amphibians that connects originates in the ilium and inserts in the tibia.

name: anterior chest
description: Subdivision of thorax which is anterior to the plane of the posterior boundary of the middle mediastinum.

name: sesamoid element
description: Ossicle that develops within bands of dense, regular connective tissue (e.g., tendons and ligaments). Sesamoids are generally located proximate to a bony prominence, over which the dense regular connective tissue wraps, and/or a joint or articulation.

name: nuchal ligament
description: A fibrous membrane, which, in the neck, represents the supraspinal ligaments of the upper vertebrae.

name: spheno-petrosal fissure
description: The sphenopetrosal fissure (or sphenopetrosal suture) is the cranial suture between the sphenoid bone and the petrous portion of the temporal bone. It is in the middle cranial fossa.

name: pleural effusion
description: Pleural effusion is a bodily fluid that is produced in exess and accumulates in the pleural cavity, the fluid-filled space that surrounds the lungs. Excessive amounts of such fluid can impair breathing by limiting the expansion of the lungs during inhalation.

name: deep circumflex iliac artery
description: The deep circumflex iliac artery (or deep iliac circumflex artery) is an artery in the pelvis that travels along the iliac crest of the pelvic bone.

name: lower lip
description: Lip that covers the lower portion of the mouth.[TAO].

name: diaphysis of fibula
description: A diaphysis that is part of a fibula[Automatically generated definition].

name: transverse facial vein
description: a tributary of the superficial temporal or retromandibular veins, anastomosing with the facial vein.

name: nasal vestibule
description: The nasal vestibule is the most anterior part of the nasal cavity. It's enclosed by the cartilages of nose and lined by the same epithelium of the skin. The other part of the nasal cavity, which is lined by the respiratory epithelium, is called nasal cavity proper. [WP,unvetted].

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 2
description: dorsal fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: piriform cortex layer 2b
description: Deeper of two subdivisions of piriform layer 2 characterized by more densely packed cell bodies dominated by pyramidal cell bodies.

name: epiphysis of middle phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a middle phalanx of manus.

name: cervical vertebra pre-cartilage condensation
description: A cervical vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: distal tarsal bone
description: There are three cuneiform bones in the human foot: the medial cuneiform the intermediate cuneiform also known as the middle the lateral cuneiform. They are located between the navicular bone and the first, second and third metatarsal bones and are medial to the cuboid bone[WP, unvetted, human specific].

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of inferior colliculus
metatarsus skeleton
description: Limb segment that consists of the long bones of the pes. The metatarsals are analogous to the metacarpal bones of the manus.

name: gubernacular bulb, intra-abdominal part
description: The portion of the gubernacular bulb that is located within the abdomen.

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of hypothalamus
nasal bridge
description: A saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose. It lies between the glabella and the inferior boundary of the nasal bone, and extends laterally to the inner canth[WP].

name: secondary pulmonary lobule
description: A unit of lung supplied by three to five terminal bronchioles and contained by fibrous septa.

name: epaxial region somite 22
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: multi organ part structure
description: An multicellular anatomical structure that has subparts of multiple organs as a part.

name: proximal metaphysis of femur
description: A proximal metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: median sacral vein
description: The median sacral vein (or middle sacral veins) accompany the corresponding artery along the front of the sacrum, and join to form a single vein, which ends in the left common iliac vein; sometimes in the angle of junction of the two iliac veins.

name: ansa cervicalis
description: A loop of nerves that are part of the cervical plexus that lies superficial to the internal jugular vein in the carotid sheath. Branches from the ansa cervicalis innervate three of the four infrahyoid muscles, including the sternohyoid muscle, the sternothyroid muscle, and the omohyoid muscle.

name: upper leg mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing hindlimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: gustatory nucleus
description: The gustatory nucleus is the enlarged rostral portion of the solitary nucleus, which receives taste afferents from the glossopharyngeal nerve and the intermediate nerve ( Carpenter-1983 ).

name: squamous epithelium
description: An epithelium characterised by its most superficial layer consisting of squamous epithelial cells.

name: spina externa
description: A median bony point projecting from the anterior and ventral margin of the sternum of a bird. From http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/spina%20externa

name: lamina terminalis of neural tube
description: The anterior-most (rostral) portion of the wall of the neural tube, formed by closure of the anterior neuropore; the median strip of the anterior wall of the prosencephalon, which persists in a relatively unchanged state as the cerebral hemispheres grow out forward beyond the original anterior end of the prosencephalon.

name: costochondral joint
description: A bars of hyaline cartilage located between the distal part of a rib and a costal cartilage, connecting the ribs to the sternum .

name: posterior stroma of cornea
description: The posterior segment of the lamellated connective tissue layer of the cornea

name: spleen pulp
description: The parenchyma of the spleen, consisting of lymphocytes and macrophages. It lies between the splenic trabecula. Red pulp is the part suffused with blood and white pulp consists of areas of lymphatic tissue where there are sleeves of lymphocytes and macrophages.

name: ovary
description: the gonad of a female organism which contains germ cells

name: taenia tectum of brain
description: A continuation ventrally of the supracallosal gyrus beyond the rostrum of the corpus callosum. It is demonstrated histologically by Nissl stain. In the human ( Anthoney-1994 ) and the macaque ( Paxinos-2004 ) it lies on the rostral surface of the lamina terminalis and is considered identical to or part of the paraterminal gyrus. In the rat ( Swanson-1998 ) and the mouse ( Paxinos-2001 ) it is located similarly in relation to the supracallosal gyrus, however, it is a more prominent layered structure that extends rostrally on the medial surface overlying the anterior olfactory nucleus. It is considered part of the olfactory areas (rodent) of the cerebral cortex. In rodents it consists of two parts, the dorsal tenia tecta and the ventral tenia tecta. Note that some authors use the term 'tenia tecta' or 'taenia tecta' as a synonym for the lateral longitudinal stria ( Riley-1943 ).

name: thyroid follicle
description: Discrete, cystlike units of the thyroid gland that are lined with cuboidal epithelium and are filled with a colloid substance, about 30 to each lobule[BTO].

name: submandibular lymph node
description: The submandibular lymph nodes (submaxillary glands in older texts), three to six in number, are placed beneath the body of the mandible in the submaxillary triangle, and rest on the superficial surface of the submaxillary salivary gland. One gland, the middle gland of Stahr, which lies on the external maxillary artery as it turns over the mandible, is the most constant of the series; small lymph glands are sometimes found on the deep surface of the submaxillary salivary glands. The afferents of the submaxillary glands drain the medial palpebral commissure, the cheek, the side of the nose, the upper lip, the lateral part of the lower lip, the gums, and the anterior part of the margin of the tongue. Efferent vessels from the facial and submental glands also enter the submaxillary glands. Their efferent vessels pass to the superior deep cervical glands. [WP,unvetted].

name: striosomal part of body of caudate nucleus
infra-orbital groove of maxilla
description: A groove on the interior of the maxilla that is continuous with the infra-orbital canal and is the conduit for the passage of the infraorbital nerve and artery.

name: metanephric distal tubule
description: The metanephric distal tubule is a metanephric nephron tubule that begins at the metanephric macula densa and extends to the metanephric connecting tubule[GO].

name: thoracic spinal cord lateral horn
description: A spinal cord lateral horn that is part of a thoracic spinal cord.

name: left lung
description: Lung which consists of the left upper lobe and left lower lobe.[FMA]

name: abdominal segment bone
description: A bone that is part of an abdominal segment of trunk [Automatically generated definition].

name: vaginal sphincter
description: A sphincter muscle that is part of a vagina.

name: sublaminar layers S1 or S2 or S5
description: One of sublaminar layers S1, S2, or S5.

name: subfornical organ
description: Group of neurons situated on the ventral surface of the fornix at the level of the foramen of Monro in the third ventricle (adapted from Wikipedia via NIF).

name: long pastern bone
description: The proximal phalanx of digit 3 in a horse

name: neural arch 2
description: Neural arch that is the second after the neurocranium.

name: ramus anterior of CN VIII
description: Formed by fibers from the anterior semicircular canal and sacculus.

name: lateral border of scapula
description: The lateral border (or axillary border, or margin) is the thickest of the three borders of the scapula. It begins above at the lower margin of the glenoid cavity, and inclines obliquely downward and backward to the inferior angle. Immediately below the glenoid cavity is a rough impression, the infraglenoid tuberosity, about 2.5 cm. in length, which gives origin to the long head of the Triceps brachii; in front of this is a longitudinal groove, which extends as far as the lower third of this border, and affords origin to part of the Subscapularis. The inferior third is thin and sharp, and serves for the attachment of a few fibers of the Teres major behind, and of the Subscapularis in front.

name: obsolete yolk
description: The nutritive substance contained in the egg.

name: anal fin radial cartilage
description: anal fin radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: parotid gland interlobular duct
description: Any of the excretory ducts of the parotid gland which are found in the connective tissue septa i.e. between lobules

name: tracheobronchial tree
description: The structure from the trachea, bronchi, and bronchioles that forms the airways that supply air to the lungs. The lining of the tracheobronchial tree consists of ciliated columnar epithelial cells.

name: stomach muscularis externa
description: The smooth muscle layer of the stomach wall that functions to churn and mix food and gastric secretions as well as to move food along the digestive tract to the intestines

name: insect leg
description: The walking appendages of each segment of the ventral adult external thorax[FBbt]. A leg derived from an imaginal disc[GO].

name: nucleus of superior olivary complex
description: Any of the nuclei that comprise the superior olivary complex (superior olive). This includes both the primary nuclei such as the lateral and medial nuclei, as well as periolivary nuclei.

name: musculature of body wall
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a body wall [Automatically generated definition].

name: outflow tract of atrium
description: An outflow tract that is part of a cardiac atrium.

name: ventral nucleus of medial geniculate body
description: Ventral division of medial geniculate body, first described by Morest (1964) in the cat, but found in primate, mouse and rat as well. It begins midway in the posterior third of the medial geniculate in the cat and is prominant anteriorly. The boundary between the dorsal and ventral divisions is demarcated in rat by a thick horizontally oriented axon bundle, the midgeniculate bundle (Webster, 1995, fig 16).

name: skeletal muscle tissue of internal intercostal muscle
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a internal intercostal muscle [Automatically generated definition].

name: cricotracheal ligament
description: The cricotracheal ligament connects the cricoid cartilage with the first ring of the trachea[WP]. The caudal border of the cricoid cartilage is joined to the first ring of the trachea by this ligament. It is an extrinsic laryngeal ligament. It resembles the fibrous membrane which connects the cartilaginous rings of the trachea to each other.

name: efferent spiracular artery
description: A section of a pharyngeal arch artery that drains the spiracle.

name: distal phalanx of manual digit 1
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 1 [Automatically generated definition].

name: kidney arcuate artery
description: One of the curved arteries at the corticomedullary border of the kidney that arise from the interlobar arteries and give rise to the interlobular arteries.

name: anal fin pterygiophore 1
description: Anal fin pterygiophore that is the anteriormost of the series.

name: nasomaxillary suture
description: A cranial suture that connects a nasal bone and connects a maxilla.

name: tensor fasciae latae muscle
description: The tensor fasciae latae or tensor fasci√¶ lat√¶ is a muscle of the thigh. [WP,unvetted].

name: embryonic cardiovascular system
description: A cardiovascular system that is part of a conceptus.

name: alveolar gland
description: In contrast to tubular glands, in the second main variety of gland, the secretory portion is enlarged and the lumen variously increased in size. These are termed alveolar glands (or saccular glands, or acinar glands, or acinous glands). Some sources draw a clear distinction between acinar and alveolar glands, based upon the shape of the lumen. A further complication in the case of the alveolar glands may occur in the form of still smaller saccular diverticuli growing out from the main sacculi. These are termed alveoli. The term 'tubulo-alveolar' (or 'tubulo-acinar', or 'compound tubulo-acinar', or 'compound tubulo-alveolar') is used to describe glands that start out as branched tubular, and branch further to terminate in alveoli. This type of gland is found in the salivary glands, esophagus, and mammary glands. The term 'racemose gland' is used to describe a 'compound alveolar gland' or 'compound acinar gland'.

name: lateral rectus extra-ocular muscle
description: The lateral rectus muscle is a muscle in the orbit. It is one of six extraocular muscles that control the movements of the eye (abduction in this case) and the only muscle innervated by the abducens nerve, cranial nerve VI. [WP,unvetted].

name: parietal ganglion
description: A lateral ganglion that innervates pallial cavity, gills and skin of a snail[BTO,modified].

name: pectoral fin base
description: Subdivision of organism that is the basal region of the pectoral fin. [PHENOSCAPE:WD].

name: operculum of brain
description: The most posterior portion of the inferior frontal gyrus of the frontal lobe in the brain. In an axial plane, the Sylvian fissure extends from the operculum posteriorly to divide the frontal from the temporal lobe. Broca's area is a notable part of the operculum, which plays a key role in conversation or speech production, reading and writing. Its vascular supply comes from the M3 branches of the middle cerebral artery[WP].

name: hypobranchial 1 element
description: Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 1 element laterally.

name: pituitary fossa
description: Anatomical cavity that is part of the sella turcica and contains the pituitary gland.

name: hyoplastron
description: A paired plastron element that is in the anterior part of the plastron, anterior to the hypoplastron, posterior to the epiplastron and adjacent to the median entoplastron.

name: cochlear basement membrane
description: The the continuous basement membrane found within the membranous labyrinth of the cochlea, known to extend from the limbus, down to the inner sulcus, across the basilar membrane, up to the external sulcus to the spiral prominence and radiating into the spiral ligament ensheathing the root cell processes

name: Weberian ossicle
description: Bone that is an element associated with a Weberian vertebra.

name: pectoral fin radial element
description: Pectoral fin radial elements are the internal skeletal supports of the pectoral fin which develop from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, supports the pectoral lepidotrichia or fin rays and connects the lepidotrichia with the primary pectoral girdle.

name: neural crest-derived structure
description: An anatomical structure that develops from the neural crest.

name: mesethmoid-premaxillary ligament
description: Mesethmoid-premaxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the premaxilla.

name: mantle cavity
description: Within the shell is a fleshy layer of tissue called the mantle; there is a cavity (the mantle cavity) between the mantle and the body wall proper.

name: polarized epithelium
description: A polarized epithelium is an epithelium where the epithelial sheet is oriented with respect to the planar axis.

name: start of neonate stage
description: A life cycle temporal boundary that marks the start of the neonate stage of the organism.

name: preopercle vertical limb
description: A dermal bone that is the upper, vertical portion of the preopercle bone.

name: meningeal vein
description: One of the veins draining a meninix.

name: right atrium auricular region
description: A small conical muscular pouch attached to the right atrium of the heart.

name: smegma
description: A combination of exfoliated (shed) epithelial cells, transudated skin oils, and moisture. It occurs in both female and male mammalian genitalia[WP].

name: pleuroperitoneal canal
description: Each of the canals that links the peritoneal cavity and the caudal part of a pleural cavity.

name: respiratory system venule
description: A venule that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: upper molar 1
description: first molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the upper jaw.

name: mucosa of nasopharynx
description: A mucosa that is part of a nasopharynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: truncus arteriosus
description: The truncus arteriosus and bulbus cordis are divided by the aorticopulmonary septum. The truncus arteriosus gives rise to the ascending aorta and the pulmonary trunk. The bulbus cordis gives rise to the smooth parts (outflow tract) of the left and right ventricles.

name: lingual nerve
description: The lingual nerve is a branch of the mandibular nerve (CN V3), itself a branch of the trigeminal nerve, which supplies sensory innervation to the tongue. It also carries fibers from the facial nerve, which return taste information from the anterior two thirds of the tongue.

name: multi-unit eye
description: An eye consisting of multiple light-sensing organs

name: fossa ovalis of heart
description: Found in the right atrium of the heart, the fossa ovalis is an embryonic remnant of the foramen ovale, which normally closes shortly after birth. In a heart specimen of a neonate, the fossa ovalis is translucent, but later in life the membrane thickens.

name: smooth muscle of esophagus
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

name: tonsil germinal center
description: A germinal center that is part of a tonsil.

name: gravid organism
description: An organism containing a developing embryo, fetus, or unborn offspring within the body.

name: inner ear foramen
description: Foramen in the inner ear.

name: metapterygial axis
description: proximodistal trajectory through a metapterygium[Wagner]

name: periotic mesenchyme
description: Anatomical region that surrounds the otic vesicle.

name: base of crypt of Lieberkuhn
description: The basal portion (further from lumen) of an intestinal crypt. Contains multipotent stem cells. Stem cells in the crypts divide to form daughter cells. One daughter cell from each stem cell division is retained as a stem cell. The other becomes committed to differentiate along one of four pathways to become an enterocyte, enteroendocrine cell, goblet cell or Paneth cell.

name: ceratohyoideus muscle
description: The ceratohyoideus is a muscle of Pharyngeal Arch III that participates in oral/pharyngeal behaviors and is innervated by the glossopharyngeal n. , and attaches to the ceratohyal part of the hyoid apparatus and also to a non-ceratohyal part of the hyoid apparatus.[FEED]

name: uterine wall
description: An anatomical wall that is part of a uterus [Automatically generated definition].

name: metapterygium cartilage
description: The posterior and innermost of the three principal basal cartilages in the fins of fishes.

name: myotome somite 6
description: Portion of the somite giving rise to body wall muscle masses. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: lateral cervical lymph node
description: A cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to an internal or external jugular vein.

name: oviduct artery
description: One of three arteries which are part of the renal artery supplying blood to the anterior, middle, and posterior parts of the oviduct.

name: lateral crico-arytenoid
description: The lateral cricoarytenoid (also anterior cricoarytenoid) muscles extend from the lateral cricoid cartilage to the ipsilateral arytenoid cartilage. By rotating the arytenoid cartilages medially, these muscles adduct the vocal cords and thereby close the rima glottidis, protecting the airway. (Their action is antagonistic to that of the posterior cricoarytenoid muscles. ) The lateral cricoarytenoid muscles receive innervation from the recurrent laryngeal branch of the vagus nerve (CN X).

name: somite 19
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: tracheobronchial epithelium
description: Epithelium pertaining to the trachea and bronchi.

name: parietal mesothelium
description: Mesothelium overs the body walls is called the parietal mesothelium

name: parietal endoderm
description: primitive endoderm-derived tissue that lines the luminal surface of the mural trophectoderm[MP]

name: paraganglion (generic)
description: A cluster of neuroendocrine cells derived from neural crest. Paraganglia may be chromaffin or nonchromaffin

name: urinary bladder neck smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a neck of urinary bladder [Automatically generated definition].

name: internal male genitalia
description: The internal masculine genital organs, including the testes, epididymides, deferent ducts, seminal vesicles, prostate, ejaculatory ducts, and bulbourethral glands

name: vertebral bone 2
description: The second vertebral bone in the vertebral column.

name: posterior spinocerebellar tract
description: It ascends the dorsal part of the lateral funiculus and enters the cerebellum via the restiform body. Within the cerebellum, its axons terminate in the ipsilateral hindlimb area of the anterior lobe and in the pyramis and the paramedian lobule predominantly ipsilaterally. Rostrally, it extends to lobules I and II. Afferents from the upper trunk, forelimbs, and the neck to the cerebellum.

name: os triangulare
description: Small, broadly triangular bar of bone lying across the ventral side of the pharynx at the junction of the M. genio-hyoideus and the M. rectus cervicis superficialis.

name: papillary layer of dermis
description: The upper layer of the dermis beneath the epidermis, composed of dense irregular connective tissue[ncit,modified].

name: parotid lymph node
description: A lymph node found near the parotid gland.

name: ilial shaft
description: Anterior rod that articulates with the sacrum.

name: subungual region
description: Region beneath a nail or claw.

name: iliolumbar vein
description: The iliolumbar vein is the vena comitans of the iliolumbar artery. The obturator nerve crosses superficial to it. A single vein is found more commonly than a double vein. It drains vertebral segments four and five. It is closely related to the ascending lumbar vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: testicular vein
description: A vein that carries deoxygenated blood from a single male gonad. It is the male equivalent of the ovarian vein, and is the venous counterpart of the testicular artery. It is a paired vein, with one supplying each testis.

name: foramen C
description: Foramen located on the scapulocoracoid, located just behind the cleithral anteroventral process(the articulation with the cleithrum). Modified from Coates 1996

name: left limbic lobe
description: A limbic lobe that is part of a left cerebral hemisphere.

name: attachment site
description: Morphological struture denoting the exent of an attachment site for a soft tissue on a skeletal element.

name: tail of caudate nucleus
description: Narrowest part of the caudate nucleus, roughtly defined as that portion that curves ventrally from the body of the caudate nucleus, following the temporal horn of the lateral ventricle

name: crista longitudinalis scapula
description: Longitudinal ridge on the medial (inner) face of the scapula.

name: coxal gland
description: A gland found in some arthropods, for collecting and excreting urine. The gland comprises an end sac (saccule), a long duct (labyrinth) and a terminal bladder (reservoir). There is generally only one pair (two in some spiders), and they open on the coxae of the walking legs[WP].

name: rostral organ
description: A putative electroreceptor organ located in the medial rostral cavity in the ethmoid portion of the chondrocranium of Coelacanths. It is surrounded by an insulating layer of adipose tissue and innervated by the superficial ophthalmic nerve.

name: basibranchial 4 tooth plate
description: Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 4 bone.

name: anterior process of vomer
description: Process that extends anterolaterally toward the maxilla-premaxilla articulation.

name: caudal principal ray 1
description: Caudal principal ray that is the dorsalmost caudal principal ray of the caudal fin.

name: mesocoracoid cartilage
description: Pectoral fin cartilage that is part of the embryonic primary pectoral girdle from which the mesocoracoid bone will ossify endochondrally.

name: rectal diverticulum
description: The rectal diverticulum is an outgrowth of the cloaca and links the pronephric kidney to the exterior
