name: suprapreopercle
description: Dermal bone that is located dorsal to the preopercle or lies on the antero-dorsal corner of the opercle, and encloses the upper section of the preopercular canal. The suprapreopercle is paired.

name: vertebral centrum element
description: Skeletal element that functionally replaces the notochord[VSAP,modified].

name: lateral recess of fourth ventricle
description: The lateral recess is a projection of the fourth ventricle which extends into the inferior cerebellar peduncle of the brainstem. The lateral aperture, an opening in each extremity of the lateral recess, provides a conduit for cerebrospinal fluid to flow from the brain's ventricular system into the subarachnoid space.

name: somatic layer of lateral plate mesoderm
description: Layer of lateral plate mesoderm that forms the future body wall - underlies the ectoderm[WP].

name: embryonic/larval circulatory system
description: Tubular system of the embryo/larva through which hemolymph flows.

name: arterial system smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an arterial system [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of basilar membrane
orbital lobe of lacrimal gland
description: Larger of the two lacrimal gland lobes located superficially.

name: interdigital region between pedal digits 4 and 5
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a pedal digit 4 and adjacent_to a pedal digit 5.

name: amniotic mesoderm
description: A mesenchyme that is part of a amnion.

name: superior cerebellar peduncle of midbrain
description: Regional part of superior cerebellar peduncle, located in the midbrain, consisting of a large bundle of fibers largely projecting from the deep cerebellar nuclei to the midbrain and thalamus. It is continuous with the superior cerebellar peduncle of the pons. (MM).

name: metapodium bone 1
description: A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 1 plus metapodial segment.

name: caudal artery
description: Extension of the dorsal aorta in the tail.

name: prootic bone
description: Paired, endochondral bones forming the anterior, and lateral walls of the otic capsules.

name: mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue
description: diffuse system of small concentrations of lymphoid tissue found in various sites of the body such as the gastrointestinal tract, thyroid, breast, lung, salivary glands, eye, and skin[WP]. Mucosal-associated lymphoid tissue is typically found as nodules associated with mucosal epithelia with distinct internal structures including B- and T-zones for the activation of lymphocytes[GO].

name: cranial nerve
description: Cranial nerves are nerves that emerge directly from the brain, in contrast to spinal nerves, which emerge from segments of the spinal cord.

name: left hemisphere of cerebellum
description: A cerebellar hemisphere that is in_the_left_side_of a cerebellum.

name: sesamoid cartilage
description: A sesamoid element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: oronasal secretion
description: A bodily fluid secreted from the body via the mouth or nose.

name: saliva
description: A fluid produced in the oral cavity by salivary glands, typically used in predigestion, but also in other functions.

name: obsolete orbital region
description: An anatomical cluster that is part of the cranium and structurally supports the eye.

name: epaxial region somite 26
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: palmaris brevis
description: The Palmaris brevis is a thin, quadrilateral muscle, placed beneath the integument of the ulnar side of the hand. It arises by tendinous fasciculi from the transverse carpal ligament and palmar aponeurosis; the fleshy fibers are inserted into the skin on the ulnar border of the palm of the hand. The muscle is innervated by the superficial branch of the ulnar nerve, containing fibers from the eighth cervical and first thoracic nerves.

name: scalp
description: The outer covering of the calvaria. It is composed of several layers: SKIN; subcutaneous connective tissue; the occipitofrontal muscle which includes the tendonous galea aponeurotica; Loose connective tissue; and the pericranium (the PERIOSTEUM of the SKULL).

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 3
description: dorsal fin distal radial 3 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: epiphysis of distal phalanx of manus
description: An epiphysis that is part of a distal phalanx of manus.

name: ceratobranchial 5 tooth
description: Tooth that forms on ceratobranchial 5 cartilage or bone.

name: thoracic vertebra cartilage element
description: A thoracic vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: obsolete periventricular nucleus of ventral telencephalon
accessory bone
description: A bone which does not occur frequently in the body but is still present in a significantly large number of organisms

name: metapodial skeleton
description: Subdivision of skeleton that corresponds to metapodium region, between acropodial skeleton and mesopdoial skeleton.

name: gubernacular bulb, extra-abdominal part
description: The portion of the gubernacular bulb that is located external to the abdomen.

name: columella nasi
description: The tissue that links the nasal tip to the nasal base, and separates the nares. It is the inferior margin of the nasal septum[EoM].

name: epaxial region somite 25
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: olfactory bulb subependymal zone
description: the region of mitotically active layer of cells surrounding the lateral brain ventricles that consists of migrating neuroblasts, astrocytes and transitory amplifying progenitor cells, that produce neurons that migrate to the olfactory bulb

name: cell cluster
description: A cluster of cells, largely surrounded by a morphological boundary.

name: distal metaphysis of femur
description: A distal metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: sublingual caruncle
description: The sublingual caruncle is a site on either side of the frenulum linguae on the sublingual surface of the tongue. There it denotes the site at which the submandibular gland empties into the oral cavity.

name: anterior spinal artery
description: A blood vessel that supplies the anterior portion of the spinal cord. It arises from branches of the vertebral arteries and is supplied by the anterior segmental medullary arteries, including the artery of Adamkiewicz, and courses along the anterior aspect of the spinal cord.

name: forelimb feather
description: A feather that is part of a forelimb.

name: pedal digit mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing toe [Automatically generated definition].

name: autopod region
description: Terminal segment of free limb, immediately distal to the zeugopod region. The fully developed autopod consists of the autopod skeleton plus associated structures such as integument, muscle tissue, vasculature etc. The autopod is divided into mesopodial, metapodiual, and acropodial segments. Examples: human hand, mouse paw, human foot

name: stratified squamous epithelium
description: Multilaminar epithelium which consists of more than one layer of squamous cells only one layer of which is in contact with a basement membrane. Examples: keratinized stratified squamous epithelium, epithelium of wall of esophagus.[FMA]

name: subolfactory process
description: The ventral portion of the frontals which forms part of the lateral wall of the braincase. Modified from Lee and Caldwell 1998

name: eggshell
description: A product of the somatic follicle cell epithelium and a structure that supports the egg in a hostile environment, minimizing water loss whilst allowing gas exchanges essential for embryonic respiration[GO].

name: biliary system
description: Organ system subdivision that consists of the organs and ducts that are involved in the production and transportation of bile. In most species this is the gallbladder and the bile ducts (biliary tree).

name: flexor cruris lateralis pars accessoria muscle
squamoparietal suture
description: The articulation of the squamous portion of the temporal bones with the parietal bones[MP]. The squamosal suture arches backward from the pterion and connects the temporal squama with the lower border of the parietal: this suture is continuous behind with the short, nearly horizontal parietomastoid suture, which unites the mastoid process of the temporal with the region of the mastoid angle of the parietal[WP].

name: parenchyma of spleen
description: A parenchyma that is part of a spleen.

name: oviduct
description: A tube or collection of tubes in an animal from the ovaries to the outside of the body.

name: blastema
description: A blastema is a mass of cells capable of growth and regeneration into organs or body parts. Historically blastema have been thought to be composed of undifferentiated pluripotent cells, but recent research indicates that in some organisms blastema may retain memory of tissue origin.[1] Blastemata are typically found in the early stages of an organism's development such as in embryos, and in the regeneration of tissues, organs and bone[WP]. A regenerating tissue composed of a proliferative mass of undifferentiated progenitor cells from which new differentiated structures arise[ZFA].

name: elastic tissue
description: Connective tissue composed of elastic fibers.

name: descending thoracic aorta
description: The part of the aorta that extends from the arch of the aorta to the diaphragm, and from which arises numerous branches that supply oxygenated blood to the chest cage and the organs within the chest.

name: alveolar sac
description: The small terminal dilation of the alveolar ducts around which the alveoli form pocket-like clusters

name: urethra muscle tissue
description: Any muscle tissue that is part of the urethra.

name: muscle layer of duodenum
description: A muscular coat that is part of a duodenum.

name: branch of anterior cerebral artery
description: An arterial branch arising from the anterior cerebral artery. It includes the callosomarginal artery, frontopolar artery, medial orbitofrontal artery, pericallosal artery, and recurrent artery of Heubner.

name: sublaminar layers S1 or S2 or S3
description: One of sublaminar layers S1, S2, or S3.

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of anterior hypothalamic region
pneumatic duct
description: A duct connecting the esophagus to the posterior chamber of the swim bladder. Finney et al, 2006.

name: ramus posterior of CN VIII
description: Composed of two rami: a short ventral ramus innervating the cochlea (lagena and papille basilar), and a long dorsal ramus innervating the posterior semicircular canal.

name: mediastinal pleura
description: The parietal pleura that lines the mediastinum.

name: cruciate ligament of atlas
description: A cruciate ligament in the neck forming part of the atlanto-axial joint. It consists of the transverse ligament of the atlas, along with additional fibers above and below.

name: inferior surface of tongue
description: The lower (inferior) side of the tongue.

name: dorsal fin radial cartilage
description: dorsal fin radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: deep intraparotid lymph node
description: The intraglandular deep parotid lymph nodes are a group of lymph nodes found inside the parotid gland.

name: internal surface of cranial base
description: internal (endosteal) surface of the base of skull

name: hermaphroditic organism
description: multicellular organism that can produce both male and female gametes.

name: stomach smooth muscle circular layer
description: The middle layer of the muscularis; it is continuous with the circular layer of the esophagus, but is absent in the fundus and lies concentric to the longitudinal axis of the stomach; the circular layer is normally tonically constricted forming a functional pyloric sphincter, which controls the movement of chyme into the duodenum

name: obsolete jointed/prehensile appendage
description: A jointed or prehensible appendage used for locomotion or manipulation. Examples: human arm, human leg, octopus tentacle, insect limb[Wikipedia]. A limb is an appendage of an animal used for locomotion or grasping. For example a leg, arm or some types of fin[GO].

name: anal fin
description: Median fin that is located posterior to the anus.

name: musculature of hindlimb stylopod
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a hindlimb stylopod (upper leg / thigh)[Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete preameloblast
description: Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into an ameloblast.

name: skeletal muscle tissue of transversus thoracis
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a transversus thoracis [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior part of tympanic bone
description: The anterior aspect of the tympanum.

name: extensor pollicis brevis muscle
description: The Extensor pollicis brevis lies on the medial side of, and is closely connected with, the Abductor pollicis longus.

name: proximal phalanx of manual digit 1
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 1 [Automatically generated definition].

name: medial tarsal artery
description: The medial tarsal arteries are two or three small branches which ramify on the medial border of the foot and join the medial malleolar net-work.

name: anal fin spine 1
description: Anal fin spine that is the anteriormost element of the series.

name: quadriceps femoris
description: One of the muscles belong to the group consisting of the rectus femoris and the three heads of the vastus (lateralis, medialis, intermedius).

name: blood brain barrier
description: Cell layer consisting of lining cells that separates the central nervous system and the bloodstream. The BBB may consist of endothelial cells or glial cells. An endothelial barrier may have arisen independently several times during evolution. In bichir and lungfish the barrier is formed by brain endothelial cells, while in sturgeon it is formed by a complex perivascular glial sheath, but with no detectable tight junctions.

name: Ciaccio's gland
description: Ciaccio's glands are small tubular accessory lacrimal glands (glandulae lacrimales accessoriae) found in the lacrimal caruncle of the eyelid. They are located in the upper border of the tarsus, approximately in the middle between the extremities of the tarsal glands. Sometimes they are situated slightly above the tarsus. There are usually 2 to 5 of these glands in the upper eyelid, and their function is to produce tears which are secreted onto the surface of the conjunctiva. They are named after Italian anatomist Giuseppe Vincenzo Ciaccio (1824b1901), who described these glands in 1874. They are sometimes called Wolfring's glands after Polish ophthalmologist Emilj von Wolfring (1832-1906), who described them during the same time period as did Ciaccio. Another type of accessory lacrimal gland are Krause's glands, which are smaller, more numerous than Ciaccio's glands and are found along the superior and inferior fornices of the conjunctival sac.

name: levator palpebrae superioris
description: The levator palpebrae superioris (or levator muscle of upper eyelid) is the muscle in the orbit that elevates the superior (upper) eyelid. [WP,unvetted].

name: pleural ganglion
description: A knot of nerves in The pallial cavity that innervates the mantle of a snail[BTO,modified].

name: obsolete embryoid body
description: Embryoid bodies are structures resembling embryos, occurring in several types of germ cell tumors.

name: hypobranchial 2 element
description: Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 2 element laterally.

name: costal plate of carapace
description: One of a series of plates on each side of the carapace, forming two rows between the peripheral plates and the median neural plates.

name: pectoral fin proximal radial element
description: Pectoral fin radial element which develops from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, supports a few pectoral lepidotrichia or fin rays and connects the lepidotrichia and distal radial elements with the primary pectoral girdle (scapula and coracoid).

name: structure with developmental contribution from neural crest
description: An anatomical structure that has some part that develops from the neural crest.

name: mesethmoid-maxillary ligament
description: Mesethmoid-maxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the maxilla.

name: mantle muscle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a mantle.

name: basioccipital posterodorsal region
description: Endochondral bone which is the posterodorsal region of the basioccipital bone.

name: internal pudendal vein
description: Accompanying vein of internal pudendal artery.

name: musculo-phrenic artery
description: An artery with its origin in the lateral terminal branch of the internal thoracic artery, with distribution to the diaphragm and the intercostal muscles, and with anastomoses to the branches of the pericardiacophrenic and inferior phrenic.

name: anterior cruciate ligament of knee joint
description: A major stabilizing ligament in the knee that attaches the surfaces of the femur and tibia.

name: respiratory system arteriole
description: An arteriole that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: adrenal tissue
description: Tissue that is part of some adrenal gland

name: mucosa of oropharynx
description: A mucosa that is part of a oropharynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: endocardial cushion
description: The endocardial cushion is a specialized region of mesenchymal cells that will give rise to the heart septa and valves[GO]. Swellings of tissue present between the endocardial and myocardial cell layers that will give rise to the interstitial cells of the cardiac valves[ZFA].

name: middle cranial fossa
description: The compartment containing the anterior extremities and half the inferior surface of the temporal lobes (TEMPORAL LOBE) of the cerebral hemispheres. Lying posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa (CRANIAL FOSSA, ANTERIOR), it is formed by part of the TEMPORAL BONE and SPHENOID BONE. It is separated from the posterior cranial fossa (CRANIAL FOSSA, POSTERIOR) by crests formed by the superior borders of the petrous parts of the temporal bones[MESH]. The middle fossa, deeper than the anterior cranial fossa, is narrow medially and widens laterally to the sides of the skull. It is separated from the posterior fossa by the clivus and the petrous crest. It is bounded in front by the posterior margins of the lesser wings of the sphenoid bone, the anterior clinoid processes, and the ridge forming the anterior margin of the chiasmatic groove; behind, by the superior angles of the petrous portions of the temporal bones and the dorsum sellC&; laterally by the temporal squamC&, sphenoidal angles of the parietals, and greater wings of the sphenoid. It is traversed by the squamosal, sphenoparietal, sphenosquamosal, and sphenopetrosal sutures[WP].

name: postcleithrum
description: Dermal bone placed postero-medially to the supracleithrum and/or cleithrum.

name: distal convoluted tubule macula densa
description: A macula densa that is part of a distal convoluted tubule [Automatically generated definition].

name: kidney
description: A paired organ of the urinary tract which has the production of urine as its primary function.

name: appendix lymphoid tissue
description: Lymphoid tissue located in the appendix.

name: gravid uterus
description: The uterus in pregnancy

name: metatarsus of male prothoracic leg
description: First tarsal segment of the male prothoracic leg. In contrast to females, it has a sex comb, central bristle and 5 to 6 transverse rows of bristles (TR).

name: obsolete regional part of body system
obsolete tip
description: Anatomical point that is the apex of a projection or anything long and tapered; can be bony or cartilage.

name: mesenchyme of fronto-nasal process
description: The embryonic connective tissue made up of loosely aggregated mesenchymal cells, supported by interlaminar jelly, that gives rise to the frontonasal region of the head

name: pectoral fin distal radial bone 2
description: pectoral fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.

name: ceratotrichium
description: Elastoidin fin ray that is thickened, generally unbranched and found in the fins of Chondrichthyes.

name: anterior cervical lymph node
description: The anterior cervical lymph nodes are a group of nodes found on the anterior part of the neck.

name: myotome somite 9
description: Portion of the somite giving rise to body wall muscle masses. immel et al, 1995.

name: foramen primum
description: opening in the septum primum between the two atria of the embryonic heart[TMD].

name: transverse arytenoid
description: The tranverse arytenoid crosses transversely between the two cartilages. It is an unpaired muscle running from one arytenoid to another to pull the arytenoids together.

name: somite 22
description: Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: visceral mesothelium
description: Mesothelium that covers the internal organs is called visceral mesothelium

name: mammary gland fat
description: The mammary fat is an adipose structure in the gland that is invaded by the mammary ducts

name: nonchromaffin paraganglion
description: A cluster of chemoreceptive and support cells associated with blood vessels and nerves.

name: sacral spinal cord dorsal column
description: A subdivision of spinal cord dorsal column that is part of a sacral spinal cord.

name: trochlear notch
description: The semilunar notch of the ulna (trochlear notch of ulna, greater sigmoid cavity) is a large depression, formed by the olecranon and the coronoid process, and serving for articulation with the trochlea of the humerus. About the middle of either side of this notch is an indentation, which contracts it somewhat, and indicates the junction of the olecranon and the coronoid process. The notch is concave from above downward, and divided into a medial and a lateral portion by a smooth ridge running from the summit of the olecranon to the tip of the coronoid process. The medial portion is the larger, and is slightly concave transversely; the lateral is convex above, slightly concave below.

name: 2nd arch endoderm
description: An endoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 2.

name: superior mesenteric plexus
description: The superior mesenteric plexus is a continuation of the lower part of the celiac plexus, receiving a branch from the junction of the right vagus nerve with the plexus. It surrounds the superior mesenteric artery, accompanies it into the mesentery, and divides into a number of secondary plexuses, which are distributed to all the parts supplied by the artery, viz. , pancreatic branches to the pancreas; intestinal branches to the small intestine; and ileocolic, right colic, and middle colic branches, which supply the corresponding parts of the great intestine. The nerves composing this plexus are white in color and firm in texture; in the upper part of the plexus close to the origin of the superior mesenteric artery is the superior mesenteric ganglion.

name: anal region smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an anal region [Automatically generated definition].

name: pyramidal layer of CA3
description: A layer of hippocampal field that is part of a hippocampus pyramidal layer and is part of a CA3 field of hippocampus.

name: primitive pit
description: The small depression in the primitive streak that is caudal to the primitive node where the cells of the epiblast initially begin to invaginate during early embryogenesis

name: bony pelvis
description: A ring of bone formed by the sacrum and the first few coccygeal vertebrae as the roof, the pubis and ischia as the floor and the ilia and the acetabular part of the ischia as the walls.

name: embryoid body
description: Embryoid bodies (EBs) are three-dimensional aggregates of pluripotent stem cells.

name: sacral vertebra
description: A vertebra bone that is part of the sacral region of the vertebral column.

name: anterior radial
description: Paired, horn-like processes of basibranchial I that protrude in an antero-dorso-lateral direction, being more or less embedded in the tongue musculature. These elements contitute the hypohyals.

name: obsolete ilial corpus
description: Posterior body of the ilium that forms the anterior half of the acetabulum.

name: crus of ear
description: horizontal piece of cartilage located outside the ear canal that divides the upper and lower parts of the ear.

name: obturator vein
description: The obturator vein begins in the upper portion of the adductor region of the thigh and enters the pelvis through the upper part of the obturator foramen, in the obturator canal. It runs backward and upward on the lateral wall of the pelvis below the obturator artery, and then passes between the ureter and the hypogastric artery, to end in the hypogastric vein. It has an anterior and posterior branch (similar to obturator artery). [WP,unvetted].

name: taenia tecti marginalis
description: Cartilaginous connection between the orbital cartilage and otic capsules.

name: palatoglossal arch
description: A fold that lies between the mouth and pharynx and marks the posterior border of the mouth

name: ovarian vein
description: A vein that carries deoxygenated blood from its corresponding ovary to inferior vena cava or one of its tributaries.

name: columnar area
description: Modified from Garvey et al. 2005. " Between the dorsal ridge and the caput humeri is a futher recessed area......that clearly separates the two structures and is slightly separted from the dorsal surface of the entepicondyle, and more specifically from the unfinished bone of the entepicondyle, by a narrow ridge."

name: right limbic lobe
description: A limbic lobe that is part of a right cerebral hemisphere.

name: levator nasolabialis muscle
description: Is a principal muscle of the lips which arises over the dorsum of the nose. It runs cranioventrally to insert partly on the wing of the nostril and partly into the lateral part of the upper lip. This muscles function includes dilation of the nostril, elevation and retraction of the upper lip. Branches of the facial nerve supply innervation to this muscle.

name: bicipital crest
description: Anatomical projection that is an expansion on the proximal region of the humerus.

name: triangular part of inferior frontal gyrus
description: Component of the inferior frontal gyrus.defined as the second gyrus from the precentral gyrus (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: internodal tract
description: A conducting pathway in the conducting tissue of heart through which electrical activity spreads from the SA node to the AV node.

name: stomochord
description: A flexible, unpaired, hollow tube found in hemichordates that arises in embryonic development as an outpocketing from the roof of the embryonic gut anterior to the pharynx. In adults, they extend dorsally from the pharynx into the probiscis, and serve to communicate with the oral cavity.

name: 6th arch mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a pharyngeal arch 6.

name: basibranchial 4 tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 4 tooth plate.

name: esophagogastric junction muscularis mucosa
description: muscularis mucosa from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

name: histoblast nest
description: One of several groups of cells in the larval abdomen that gives rise to the adult external abdomen.

name: caudal principal ray 2
description: Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 1.

name: pelvic radial cartilage
description: Small cartilage that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium.

name: osseus semicircular canal
description: the organ of balance composed of three long bony tubes of the labyrinth

name: foramen spinosum of sphenoid bone
description: A foramen in the sphenoid bone through which the middle meningeal artery, middle meningeal vein, and the meningeal branch of the mandibular nerve pass.

name: esophageal artery
description: Any of several arteries that arise from the aorta and supply blood to the esophagus.

name: anular ligament of radius
description: The anular ligament (orbicular ligament) is a strong band of fibers, which encircles the head of the radius (bone), and retains it in contact with the radial notch of the ulna

name: splanchnic layer of lateral plate mesoderm
description: Layer of lateral plate mesoderm that forms the circulatory system and future gut wall - overlies endoderm[WP].

name: venous system smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a venous system [Automatically generated definition].

name: palpebral lobe of lacrimal gland
description: Smaller of the two lacrimal gland lobes located at the eyelid.

name: organ component layer
description: A part of a wall of an organ that forms a layer.

name: metapodium bone 2
description: A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 2 plus metapodial segment.

name: anterior cardinal vein
description: One of the the two paired cardinal veins draining the cephalic part of the body.

name: distal tarsal bone 3 pre-cartilage condensation
description: A distal tarsal bone 3 endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: supraoccipital bone
description: Endochondral bone that is located at the dorsal part of the occipital region of the cranium or the dorso-posterior part of the skull[TAP,modified].

name: gut-associated lymphoid tissue
description: Mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue in digestive tract. includes Peyer's patches, appendix, and solitary lymph nodules[GO].

name: obsolete regional part of basolateral nuclear complex
fovea centralis
description: A depression in the inner retinal surface within the macula lutea, the photoreceptor layer of which is entirely cones and which is specialized for maximum visual acuity

name: eye mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing camera-type eye.

name: nasion
description: The intersection of the frontal and two nasal bones of the human skull. Its manifestation on the visible surface of the face is a distinctly depressed area directly between the eyes, just superior to the bridge of the nose.

name: intertrochanteric crest
description: The intertrochanteric crest is a bony ridge located on the posterior side of the head of the femur, stretching obliquely downward and medially from the summit of the greater trochanter to the lesser trochanter.

name: parenchyma
description: functional part of an organ in the body. This is in contrast to the stroma, which refers to the structural tissue of organs, being exactly, connective tissues.

name: pus
description: Pus is a bodily fluid consisting of a whitish-yellow or yellow substance produced during inflammatory responses of the body that can be found in regions of pyogenic bacterial infections. Pus is produced from the dead and living cells which travel into the intercellular spaces around the affected cells.

name: anterior intercostal vein
description: The anterior intercostal veins are the veins which drain the anterior intercostal space.

name: pudendal venous plexus
description: The pudendal plexus (vesicoprostatic plexus) lies behind the arcuate pubic ligament and the lower part of the pubic symphysis, and in front of the bladder and prostate. Its chief tributary is the deep dorsal vein of the penis, but it also receives branches from the front of the bladder and prostate. It communicates with the vesical plexus and with the internal pudendal vein and drains into the vesical and hypogastric veins.

name: prostatic venous plexus
description: The prostatic veins form a well-marked prostatic plexus which lies partly in the fascial sheath of the prostate and partly between the sheath and the prostatic capsule. It communicates with the pudendal and vesical plexuses.

name: duct of salivary gland
description: The duct of a salivary gland.

name: teres minor muscle
description: A narrow, elongated muscle of the rotator cuff

name: vasculature of brain
description: System pertaining to blood vessels in the brain.

name: down feather
description: A feather lacking a vane and having a rudimentary rachis and a tuft of non-interlocked barbs with elongated barbules extending from the calamus

name: obsolete regional part of longitudinal fissure
dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 4
description: dorsal fin distal radial 4 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: centrale 1
description: Distal-most centrale when two are present.

name: thoracic vertebra pre-cartilage condensation
description: A thoracic vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: os vesalianum pedis
description: An accessory bone located proximal to the base of the fifth metatarsal. Its prevalence has been reported to be from 0.1% to 1.0%. This bone is found within the peroneus brevis tendon and is considered to be asymptomatic in the majority of people

name: obsolete cytoarchitectural part of the cerebellum
pedal digit 1 metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pedal digit metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a pedal digit 1 mesenchyme.

name: corticobulbar and corticospinal tracts
description: The corticobulbar and corticospinal tracts combined.

name: intestinal villus of duodenum
description: An intestinal villus in the duodenum.

name: epaxial region somite 28
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: dentate gyrus granule cell layer
description: Granule cell layer is also called the DG principal cell layer. This one of the three layers of dentate gyrus that lies deep to the molecular layer and is made of densely packed layer that is four to eight granule cells thick.

name: disconnected anatomical group
description: Material anatomical entity consisting of multiple anatomical structures that are not connected to each other.

name: metaphysis of femur
description: A metaphysis that is part of a femur.

name: frenulum of tongue
description: A small fold of mucous membrane extending from the floor of the mouth to the midline of the underside of the tongue.

name: aortic sac
description: The dilated structure that is lined by endothelial cells and located at the arterial pole of the heart just above (distal to) the truncus arteriosus in mammalian embryos; it is the primordial vascular channel from which the aortic arches (and eventually the dorsal aortae) arise; the aortic sac is homologous to the ventral aorta of gill-bearing vertebrates

name: wing feather
description: A feather that is part of a forelimb wing.

name: inferior tarsal muscle
description: A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a inferior eyelid tarsus.

name: trunk mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing trunk.

name: zeugopod
description: The middle free limb segment, between the autopod and stylopod segments. Includes as parts the zeugopodial skeleton. Examples: There are two types of zeugopod: forelimb zeugopod (aka forearm), hindlimb zeugopod (aka crus).

name: non-keratinized epithelium of tongue
description: A non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium that is part of a tongue.

name: processus infrafenestralis
description: Posterior part of the corpus of the septomaxilla; the posterior surface of the processus infrafenestralis is in contact with the oblique cartilage.

name: molar crown
description: The part of a molar that is covered by enamel

name: spermathecum
description: An organ of the female reproductive tract that functions to receive and store sperm from the male, and can sometimes be the site of fertilization when the oocytes are ready.

name: chorion-containing eggshell
description: An eggshell that contains chorion. An example of this is found in Drosophila melanogaster.

name: tunica media
description: The middle layer of an artery or vein. [WP,unvetted].

name: neurectoderm
description: Embryonic ectoderm that gives rise to nervous tissue.

name: retroarticular process
description: Bony process that is part of the articular and is the point of insertion of the m. interhuoideus posterior.

name: obsolete regional part of basal part of pons
otic ramus of squamosal
description: Ramus (process) that extends medially toward the otic capsule.

name: muscle layer of colon
description: A muscular coat that is part of a colon.

name: sublaminar layers S2 or S3 or S4
description: One of sublaminar layers S2, S3, or S4.

name: pastern bone
description: A bone that is part of the pastern region of a horse limb. i.e. proximal or middle (P1 or P2) phalanges in digit 3.

name: M. palmaris longus
description: Originates from the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts on the palmar aponeurosis.

name: synovial joint of pelvic girdle
description: A synovial joint that is part of a pelvic girdle region.

name: incus cartilage element
description: A incus endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: hermaphrodite anatomical structure
description: An anatomical structure present only in hermaphrodites.

name: digit 1 or 5
description: Either of the outermost digits in a five-digit autopod, or their phylogenetic equivalent.

name: pyloric canal
description: The short narrow part of the stomach extending from the pyloric antrum to the pyloric sphincter

name: ciliated epithelium
description: Epithelium bearing vibratile cilia on the free surface.

name: manus bone
description: A bone that is part of the manus skeleton. Note that this includes the carpal bones.

name: caudal fin
description: The caudal fin is the most posterior median fin. It is composed of a complex of modified centra and modified neural and hemal arches and spines.

name: decussation of diencephalon
description: A neural decussation that is part of a diencephalon.

name: renal efferent arteriole
description: the blood vessels that convey blood from the glomerulocapillary network to the capillary bed of the proximal convoluted tubule

name: dorsal accessory inferior olivary nucleus
description: The inferior olivary nucleus that is the smallest, and appears on transverse section as a curved lamina behind the primary olivary nucleus

name: musculature of thorax
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a thorax [Automatically generated definition].

name: cloacal muscle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a cloaca.

name: skeleton
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of all the skeletal elements (eg., bone, cartilage, and teeth) of the body.

name: submedial nucleus of thalamus
description: Thalamic nucleus separated from the ventromedial part of the mediodorsal nucleus of the thalamus by the internal medullary lamina (Paxinos The rat nervous system 2nd ed, Academic Press, 1995).

name: obsolete regional part of paraventricular nucleus of hypothalamus magnocellular division - posterior magnocellular part
pupal stage
description: A life cycle stage of holometabolous insects in which the organism is a pupa and starts with the larval-pupal apolysis and ends with pupal-adult apolysis.

name: anterior spinocerebellar tract
description: Runs through the ventrolateral surface of the spinal cord. It enters the cerebellum through the superior cerebellar peduncle. It crosses the midline at the segmental level and recrosses in the cerebellum. Its terminals are distributed in the cerebellar anterior lobe, preferentially in the ipsilateral intermediate cortex. Rostrally, it extends to lobule II.

name: obsolete chordoblast
description: Skeletogenic cell that is derived from the notochordal mesoderm and produces notochordal tissue (and cartilage tissue in some taxa).

name: smooth muscle tissue of bronchiole
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a bronchiole [Automatically generated definition].

name: adipose fin ray
description: Soft ray that is part of the adipose fin.

name: sigmoid process of tympanic bone
description: A wavy crest externally on the tympanic bone of cetaceans.

name: vasa efferentia
description: Sperm travel through these 4 or 5 fine ducts which pass through the mesorchium from the testis to the sexual kidney.

name: vault of skull
description: Upper part of skull, consisting of parietals, frontals, post-parietals, and in some species the squamosal and a portion of the alisphenoid

name: skin of hip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a hip region.

name: anal fin spine 2
description: Anal fin spine that is located posteriorly adjacent to the first anal fin spine.

name: synarthrosis
description: A synarthrosis is a type of joint which permits very little or no movement under normal conditions. Most synarthrosis joints are fibrous. Suture joints and synchondroses are synarthroses.

name: rectus femoris
description: The Rectus femoris muscle is one of the four quadriceps muscles of the human body. (The others are the vastus medialis, the vastus intermedius, and the vastus lateralis. All four combine to form the quadriceps tendon, which inserts into the patella and continues as the patellar ligament. ) The Rectus femoris is situated in the middle of the front of the thigh; it is fusiform in shape, and its superficial fibers are arranged in a bipenniform manner, the deep fibers running straight down to the deep aponeurosis. [WP,unvetted].

name: perineurium
description: A layer of thin, concentrically arranged cells with interspersed collagen that lies within the epineurium. (Nolte, J., The Human Brain 3rd edition)

name: ciliary muscle
description: The ciliary muscle is a ring of smooth muscle in the middle layer of the eye that controls the eye's accommodation for viewing objects at varying distances and regulates the flow of aqueous humour through Schlemm's canal. [WP,unvetted].

name: gastropod cerebral ganglion
description: The cerebral ganglia are primarily sensual centres, that compute information from the eyes as well as from the tactile and position sensors (statocystes). Besides coordination they also serve the locational memory of a snail.

name: hepatopancreas
description: An organ of the digestive tract of arthropods and molluscs. It provides the functions which in mammals are provided separately by the liver and pancreas, including the production of digestive enzymes, and absorption of digested food.

name: hypobranchial 3 element
description: Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 3 element laterally.

name: carapace primordium
description: A primordium that gives rise to a carapace.

name: postganglionic autonomic fiber
description: Nerve fibers which project from cell bodies of autonomic ganglia to synapses on target organs.

name: pisiform
description: A laterally positioned sesamoid bone found in close proximity with and occasionally fused to the ulnare.

name: pectoral fin distal radial element
description: Pectoral fin radial element that sometimes ossifies, develops from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, and is located at the proximal region of a lepidotrichium, between its hemitrichia. Pectoral fin distal radial element is paired.

name: hyomandibular-otic region joint
description: Joint that articulates the hyomandibular cartilage or bone and otic region cartilage or sphenotic bone, and often pterotic bone and prootic bone. Hyomandibular-otic region joint is paired.

name: external pudendal vein
description: One of the veins of the pelvis which drain into the great saphenous vein.

name: coracoid process of scapula
description: A process of the scapula in most mammals representing the remnant of the coracoid bone of lower vertebrates thas has become fused with the scapula.

name: dentition
description: A collection of teeth arranged in some pattern in the mouth or other part of the body. The arrangement may be a simple row, a collection of rows, or a more elaborate structure, such as a toooth whorl.

name: thoracic mammary gland
description: A lactiferous gland that is located in the thoracic region/breast.

name: head blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a head [Automatically generated definition].

name: post-axial region of pectoral appendage
description: Anatomical region lying to the posteiror or ventral side of the metapterygial axis.

name: mucosa of soft palate
description: A mucosa that is part of a soft palate [Automatically generated definition].

name: sinus venosus
description: The sinus venosus is a large cardiac chamber at the inflow tract that receives venous blood from systemic circulation. precedes the atrium on the venous side of the chordate heart.

name: lamina nariochoanalis
description: Free, dorsal margin of the lamina inferior.

name: interosseous muscle of autopod
description: Any of the muscles of the autopod region that lie between metacarpal or metatarsal bones.

name: vestibular nerve
description: The vestibular nerve is one of the two branches of the Vestibulocochlear nerve (the cochlear nerve being the other). It goes to the semicircular canals via the vestibular ganglion. It receives positional information. Axons of the vestibular nerve synapse in the vestibular nucleus on the lateral floor and wall of the fourth ventricle in the pons and medulla. It arises from bipolar cells in the vestibular ganglion, ganglion of Scarpa, which is situated in the upper part of the outer end of the internal auditory meatus. [WP,unvetted].

name: dorsal paramedian reticular nucleus
description: Small nucleus in the brainstem of human, located adjacent and medial to the nucleus prepositus in the dorsal medulla, described in several atlases of human brain stem. In transverse sections, it is oval with its long axis aligned with the dorsal border of the brainstem. It begins at about the same A-P level as the nucleus prepositus, just rostral to the hypoglossal nucleus. It includes calretinin immunoreactive large cells with oval or polygonal cell bodies. Cells are not immunoreactive for either calbindin or parvalbumin, but a few fibers immunoreactive to each protein are found within its central region. Cells in PMD are also immunoreactive to nNOS, and immunoreactivity to a neurofilament protein shows many labeled cells and fibers. According to Baizer et al., no equivalent structure was observed in the cat, rat, mouse or monkey atlas although they did not look at the brains of the great apes.

name: brain meninx
description: A meninx that is part of a brain [Automatically generated definition].

name: duodenum
description: The first part of the small intestine. At the junction of the stomach and the duodenum the alimentary canal is inflected. The duodenum first goes anteriorly for a short distance, turns dorsally, and eventually caudally, thus it is a U-shaped structure with two horizontal sections (a ventral and a dorsal one).

name: typhlosole
description: An invagination of the intestinal epithelium that emanates from a lamina of mesenchymal cells located between the dorsal aorta and the upper intestine and constitute one of the two principal hematopoietic organs at the ammocoete stage of development.

name: ventral mesentery of mesentery of foregut-midgut junction
pterygopharyngeal part of superior pharyngeal constrictor
superficial lateral cervical lymph node
description: The superficial lateral cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to the external jugular vein.

name: epaxial region somite 19
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: oblique arytenoid
description: The oblique arytenoid, the more superficial Arytenoid muscle, forms two fasciculi, which pass from the base of one cartilage to the apex of the opposite one, and therefore cross each other like the limbs of the letter X; a few fibers are continued around the lateral margin of the cartilage, and are prolonged into the aryepiglottic fold; they are sometimes described as a separate muscle, the Aryepiglotticus. The aryepiglottic muscle together with the transverse arytenoid and the thyroarytenoid work as a sphincter and close the larynx as we swallow or cough. Its innervation is by the recurrent laryngeal nerve (from vagus) just like all the intrinsic muscles of the larynx except the cricothyroid muscle.

name: hypaxial region somite 24
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: left internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a left common carotid artery plus branches.

name: cheek pouch
description: A pocketlike fold of skin in the cheeks of various animals, such as squirrels, gophers, and monkeys, that functions as a means of carrying food.

name: cervical spinal cord dorsal column
description: A subdivision of spinal cord dorsal column that is part of a cervical spinal cord.

name: 3rd arch endoderm
description: An endoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 3.

name: anterior interventricular sulcus
description: The ventricles of the heart are separated by two grooves, one of which, the anterior longitudinal sulcus (or anterior interventricular sulcus), is situated on the sternocostal surface of the heart, close to its left margin. The other groove separating the ventricles is the posterior interventricular sulcus.

name: lymphatic vessel smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a lymphatic vessel [Automatically generated definition].

name: primitive groove
description: The shallow valley that extends along the length of the primitive streak[MP]

name: pelvic girdle region
description: The organism subdivision that includes the pelvic girdle skeleton and associated soft tissue. Note that this includes both the skeletal elements and associated tissues (integument, muscle, etc). Examples: There are only two instances in an organism, right and left pectoral girdle regions.

name: intrinsic muscle of manus
description: Any of the intrinsic muscles of the manus (hand)

name: commissure of diencephalon
description: A commissure that is part of a diencephalon.

name: distal condyle of humerus
description: The area encompassing the radial and ulnar condyles of the humerus.

name: posterior radial
description: Paired, horn-like processes of basibranchial I that protrude in an antero-dorso-lateral direction, being more or less embedded in the tongue musculature. They arise secondarily during metamorphosis, and are therefore not strictly part of the visceral skeleton.

name: non-connected developing system
description: The sum of all the anlagen and primordia that will develop into a single system.

name: hepatic lymph node
description: Any of the lymph nodes adjacent to the stomach and duodenum.

name: obsolete regional part of medullary reticular formation
description: A regional part of brain that is part of a medullary reticular formation [Automatically generated definition].

name: glenoid foramen
description: Opening on the glenoid fossa.

name: odontogenic mesenchyme of molar
description: An odontogenic papilla that is part of a molar tooth [Automatically generated definition].

name: suprarenal vein
description: A vein that drains the adrenal gland.

name: scapulohumeralis muscle
description: Muscle found primarily in basal sarcopterygians that runs between teh scapulocoracoid and the humerus. Its exact homologies with more derived shoulder muscles in Tetrapoda is unclear.

name: left occipital lobe
description: An occipital lobe that is part of a left cerebral hemisphere.

name: longissimus atlantis muscle
description: A muscle that runs beneath the longissimus capitis and inserts on the wing of the atlas

name: cartilago sesamoides
description: A sesamoid found in the found in the ligamentum calcanei of a wide variety of frogs. (based on Nussbaum, R. A. 1982

name: tip
description: Anatomical point that is the apex of a projection or anything long and tapered; can be bony or cartilage

name: margo anterior of cleithrum
description: Anterior margin of the anterior ramus of the cleithrum.

name: pharyngobasilar fascia
description: The pharyngeal aponeurosis (or pharyngobasilar fascia, or fibrous coat), is situated between the mucous and muscular layers. It is thick above where the muscular fibers are wanting, and is firmly connected to the basilar portion of the occipital and the petrous portions of the temporal bones. As it descends it diminishes in thickness, and is gradually lost. It is strengthened posteriorly by a strong fibrous band, which is attached above to the pharyngeal spine on the under surface of the basilar portion of the occipital bone, and passes downward, forming a median raphe, which gives attachment to the Constrictores pharyngis.

name: anterior part of tongue
description: The portion of the tongue in front of the terminal sulcus. At the apex, thin and narrow, it is directed forward against the lingual surfaces of the lower incisor teeth. It is derived primarily from the first pharyngeal arch.

name: basibranchial 2 tooth plate
description: Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 2 bone.

name: esophagogastric junction muscularis propria
description: muscularis propria from the lowest portion of the esophagus, just proximal to the stomach.

name: caudal principal ray 3
description: Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 2.

name: basipterygium cartilage
description: Bilaterally paired small, rodlike cartilages on the ventral surface of the abdomen (present at 7.9 mm). Their posterior tips expand laterally, forming L-shaped cartilages. Medially, a posterior spur of cartilage develops, which will later ossify as the ischiac process (Weitzman 1962).

name: pronephric sinus
description: The pronephric sinus is an ill-defined capillary network that lies between the pronephric tubules

name: lumbar spinal cord ventral commissure
description: A spinal cord ventral commissure that is part of a lumbar spinal cord.

name: extension
description: The posterior elongated region of the yolk cell that forms during the segmentation period. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: palmaris longus muscle
description: The palmaris longus is seen as a small tendon between the flexor carpi radialis and the flexor carpi ulnaris, although it is not always present. The muscle is absent in about 14 percent of the population, however this varies greatly with ethnicity. Absence of palmaris does not have any known effect on grip strength. Palmaris longus can be palpated by touching the pads of the fifth and first fingers and flexing the wrist. The tendon, if present, will be very visible.

name: splanchnopleure
description: A structure created during embryogenesis when the lateral mesoderm splits into two layers - the inner (or splanchnic) layer adheres to the endoderm, and with it forms the splanchnopleure[WP].

name: sphenoid endochondral element
description: A sphenoid bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: Peyer's patch germinal center
description: Area of the Peyer's patch where B cells proliferate and differentiate into plasma cells

name: limb nerve
description: A nerve that is part of a limb [Automatically generated definition].

name: adult thorax
description: Thorax of the adult.

name: submucosa of pharynx
description: The tissue underlying the tunica mucosa of the pharynx.

name: metapodium bone 3
description: A metapodial bone that is associated with digit III.

name: bronchial-associated lymphoid tissue
description: A diffuse collection of lymphpoid cells that participate in airway immune responses

name: skeleton of digitopodium
description: A subdivision of the autopod skeleton consisting of both acropodial skeleon and metapodial skeleton, but excluding the mesopodial/basopodial skeleton.

name: photoreceptor layer of retina
description: The layer within the retina where the photoreceptor cell receptor segments reside.

name: mesenchyme of ovary
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing ovary [Automatically generated definition].

name: obsolete regional part of anterior commissure
intertrochanteric line
description: The intertrochanteric line (or spiral line of the femur) is a line located on the anterior side of the proximal end of the femur that stretches between the lesser trochanter and the greater trochanter forming the base of the neck of the femur, roughly following the direction of the shaft of the femur.

name: obsolete regional part of olfactory cortex
reproductive gland secretion
description: A portion of organism substance that is secreted by a reproductive gland.

name: blood
description: A fluid that is composed of blood plasma and erythrocytes.

name: sublingual duct
description: A duct of a sublingual gland.

name: epaxial region somite 29
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: hoof lamina
description: The tissues which attach the third phalanx to the hoof wall.

name: flexor digiti minimi brevis of hand
description: The flexor digiti minimi brevis is a muscle in the hand that flexes the little finger. It lies in the same plane as the abductor digiti minimi, on its radial side.

name: tarsometatarsus cartilage element
description: A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a tarsometatarsus.

name: vaned feather
description: A feather that has_part a feather vane.

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 5
description: dorsal fin distal radial 5 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: lumbar vertebra cartilage element
description: A lumbar vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: lateral tubercle of talus
description: An accessory bone tubercle which if present lies posterior to the talus

name: bodily gas
description: Any substance in the body or expelled from the body that is in a gaseous state.

name: pedal digit 2 metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pedal digit metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a pedal digit 2 mesenchyme.

name: respiratory system gland
description: Any gland that is part os the respiratory system.

name: intestinal villus of jejunum
description: An intestinal villus in the jejunum.

name: epaxial region somite 30
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: aligned anatomical group
description: An anatomical group whose members are arranged in a line.

name: terminal part of digestive tract
description: The distalmost portion of the digestive tract, derived from the hindgut, and terminating with the anus.

name: obsolete peripheral part of autonomous nervous system
tail feather
description: A feather that is part of a tail.

name: manual digit mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing finger [Automatically generated definition].

name: tarsal gland acinus
description: A sac-like structure comprising a sebaceous gland.

name: aqueous drainage system
description: The structures associated with drainage of the aqueous humor from the eye, that include the trabecular meshwork, Schlemm's canal, the uveoscleral network, and the aqueous veins

name: nephrostome
description: The nephrostome is the opening of the pronephros into the body cavity[GO].

name: tunica intima
description: The innermost layer of a blood vessel which is a lining of endothelial cells facing the lumen[Kardong].

name: stegochordal
description: Vertebral centrum that is depressed dorsoventrally and solid. All traces of the notochord dissapear.

name: obsolete striosomal part of tail of caudate nucleus
thoracic vertebra
description: A thoracic vertebra endochondral element that is composed primarily of a bone tissue.

name: otoccipital
description: Fused prootic and exoccipital bones.

name: synovial membrane of synovial tendon sheath
description: Synovial sac which surrounds parts of one or more tendons. Examples: synovial tendon sheath of manual digit 2, radial bursa.

name: sublaminar layers S1 or S3 or S4
description: One of sublaminar layers S1, S3, or S4.

name: anterior sclerotic bone
description: Sclerotic bone that is located anterior to the eye.

name: metacarpal/tarsal-phalangeal joint
description: A skeletal joint that connects a mesopodium bone and connects a proximal phalanx.

name: M. palmaris profundis
description: Originates on the ulnar aspect of the radioulna and inserts on the palmar aponeurosis.

name: synovial joint of pectoral girdle
description: A synovial joint that is part of a pectoral girdle region.

name: sphincter muscle
description: A structure, usually a circular muscle, that normally maintains constriction of a natural body passage or orifice and which relaxes as required by normal physiological functioning.

name: digit 2, 3 or 4
description: Any of the three medial digits in a five-digit autopod, or their phylogenetic equivalent.

name: cardiac gastric gland
description: A gastric gland in the cardiac region of the stomach; cardiac glands are fewer in number than in the fundus and body, and secrete mucin which coats the stomach and protects it[MP]

name: stratified columnar epithelium
description: Stratified columnar epithelia is a rare type of epithelial tissue composed of column shaped cells arranged in multiple layers. Stratified columnar epithelia are found in the ocular conjunctiva of the eye, in parts of the pharynx and anus, the female's uterus, the male urethra and vas deferens. Also found in intralobular ducts in salivary glands.[WP]

name: spleen capsule
description: the connective tissue that surrounds the spleen

name: musculature of neck
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a neck [Automatically generated definition].

name: transverse cloacal muscle
description: a very prominent superficial muscle and with its almost transverse course it forms the boundary between the abdomen and the tail.

name: radula
description: An anatomical structure found in mollusks and used for feeding. It is a minutely toothed, chitinous ribbon. It is typically used for scraping or cutting food before the food enters the esophagus. The radula is unique to the molluscs, and is found in all classes of mollusks except for the bivalves.

name: death stage
description: End of the life of an organism.

name: smooth muscle tissue of terminal bronchiole
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a terminal bronchiole [Automatically generated definition].

name: cavity of pharynx
description: A anatomical space that is enclosed by a pharynx.

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of tectum
nasal air sac
description: An air sac opening into the passage of the blowhole that is hypothesized to be involved in echolocation

name: lumen of urethra
description: An organ cavity that is part of a urethra.

name: digestive tract
description: A tube extending from the mouth to the anus.

name: amphiarthrosis
description: Amphiarthrosis is a type of continuous, slightly movable joint.

name: vastus lateralis
description: The Vastus lateralis (Vastus externus) is the largest part of the Quadriceps femoris. It arises by a broad aponeurosis, which is attached to the upper part of the intertrochanteric line, to the anterior and inferior borders of the greater trochanter, to the lateral lip of the gluteal tuberosity, and to the upper half of the lateral lip of the linea aspera; this aponeurosis covers the upper three-fourths of the muscle, and from its deep surface many fibers take origin. A few additional fibers arise from the tendon of the Glut√¶us maximus, and from the lateral intermuscular septum between the Vastus lateralis and short head of the Biceps femoris. The fibers form a large fleshy mass, which is attached to a strong aponeurosis, placed on the deep surface of the lower part of the muscle: this aponeurosis becomes contracted and thickened into a flat tendon inserted into the lateral border of the patella, blending with the Quadriceps femoris tendon, and giving an expansion to the capsule of the knee-joint. [WP,unvetted].

name: neuron projection bundle
description: A fasciculated bundle of neuron projections (GO:0043005), largely or completely lacking synapses.

name: midgut loop
description: Portion of midgut after it bends around the superior mesenteric artery

name: headfoot
description: The head-foot is the part you see most easily in slugs and snails. It is mostly a muscular organ covered in cilia and rich in mucous cells, which the mollusc uses to move around, it normally tapers to a tail at one end and has a head incorporated in the front. The head includes a mouth, eyes and tentacles, the last two may be much reduced or even absent. In those species with shells the head-foot can be drawn into the shell.

name: hypobranchial 4 element
description: Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 4 element laterally.

name: preganglionic autonomic fiber
description: Nerve fibers which project from the central nervous system to autonomic ganglia. In the sympathetic division most preganglionic fibers originate with neurons in the intermediolateral column of the spinal cord, exit via ventral roots from upper thoracic through lower lumbar segments, and project to the paravertebral ganglia; there they either terminate in synapses or continue through the splanchnic nerves to the prevertebral ganglia. In the parasympathetic division the fibers originate in neurons of the brain stem and sacral spinal cord. In both divisions the principal transmitter is acetylcholine but peptide cotransmitters may also be released.

name: otic lateral line
description: One of eight distinct lateral lines in the 4-day larva. A sensory system on the surface of the fish, consisting of small sensory patches (neuromasts) distributed in discrete lines over the body surface. The lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance. (See Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)

name: anal-fin hook
description: Process that is part of the anal fin lepidotrichium.

name: statocyst
description: A balance sensory receptor present in some aquatic invertebrates[WP].

name: olecranon
description: The olecranon is a large, thick, curved bony eminence of the forearm that projects behind the elbow. It is situated at the upper (proximal) end of the ulna, one of the two bones in the forearm. When the hand faces forward the olecranon faces towards the back (posteriorly). It is bent forward at the summit so as to present a prominent lip which is received into the olecranon fossa of the humerus in extension of the forearm. Its base is contracted where it joins the body and the narrowest part of the upper end of the ulna. Its posterior surface, directed backward, is triangular, smooth, subcutaneous, and covered by a bursa. Its superior surface is of quadrilateral form, marked behind by a rough impression for the insertion of the Triceps brachii; and in front, near the margin, by a slight transverse groove for the attachment of part of the posterior ligament of the elbow-joint. Its anterior surface is smooth, concave, and forms the upper part of the semilunar notch. Its borders present continuations of the groove on the margin of the superior surface; they serve for the attachment of ligaments, viz. , the back part of the ulnar collateral ligament medially, and the posterior ligament laterally. From the medial border a part of the Flexor carpi ulnaris arises; while to the lateral border the anconeus muscle is attached.

name: abdomen blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of an abdomen [Automatically generated definition].

name: bicipital surface
description: region of the humerus associated with the biceps attachment areas

name: mucosa of uvula
description: A mucosa that is part of a uvula [Automatically generated definition].

name: spinal cord
description: Part of the central nervous system located in the vertebral canal continuous with and caudal to the brain; demarcated from brain by plane of foramen magnum. It is composed of an inner core of gray matter in which nerve cells predominate, and an outer layer of white matter in which myelinated nerve fibers predominate, and surrounds the central canal. (CUMBO)

name: epaxial myotome region
description: Portion of myotome that is dorsal to the horizontal septum

name: common cardinal vein
description: Either of a pair of large transverse venous sinuses that conduct blood from the cardinal veins to the sinus venosus of the vertebrate embryo[BTO].

name: musculocutaneous nerve
description: a large branch of the brachial plexus supplying various parts of the upper arm (as flexor muscles) and forearm (as the skin).

name: cavum inferius
description: Accessory cavity located ventral to the cavum principale and cavum medius.

name: forebrain meninges
description: A meninx that is part of a forebrain [Automatically generated definition].

name: jejunum
description: the portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum

name: middle nasal meatus
description: The middle meatus is a nasal opening or canal situated between the middle and inferior conchae, and extends from the anterior to the posterior end of the latter. The lateral wall of this meatus can be satisfactorily studied only after the removal of the middle concha. On it is a curved fissure, the hiatus semilunaris, limited below by the edge of the uncinate process of the ethmoid and above by an elevation named the bulla ethmoidalis; the middle ethmoidal cells are contained within this bulla and open on or near to it. Through the hiatus semilunaris the meatus communicates with a curved passage termed the infundibulum, which communicates in front with the anterior ethmoidal cells and in rather more than fifty percent of skulls is continued upward as the frontonasal duct into the frontal air-sinus; when this continuity fails, the frontonasal duct opens directly into the anterior part of the meatus. Below the bulla ethmoidalis and hidden by the uncinate process of the ethmoid is the opening of the maxillary sinus (ostium maxillare); an accessory opening is frequently present above the posterior part of the inferior nasal concha.

name: obsolete Stiftchenzellen
description: Possibly chemoreceptor cells in anuran larvae.

name: mesenchyme of hindgut
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing hindgut.

name: corpuscles of Stannius
description: Islands of eosinic cells found on the lateroventral surface of the kidney. Function is thought to be that of the parathyroid gland in other vertebrates, which are lacking in fishes. These cells secrete hypocalcin (teleocalcin) to regulate calcium metabolism.

name: superficial anterior cervical lymph node
description: The superficial anterior cervical lymph nodes are found in proximity to the anterior jugular vein.

name: postcaval vein
description: One of three major veins which enter the sinus venosus.

name: thyro-arytenoid
description: The Thyroarytenoid is a broad, thin, muscle which lies parallel with and lateral to the vocal fold, and supports the wall of the ventricle and its appendix. It functions in fine tonal control of the vocal cords.

name: gastrocolic ligament
description: A major portion of the greater omentum between the stomach and the transverse colon.

name: right internal carotid artery
description: An internal carotid artery that branching_part_of a right common carotid artery plus branches.

name: skin of cheek
description: A zone of skin that is part of a cheek.

name: mammary gland cord
description: The solid cord of epithelial cells that emerges from the mammary bud and grows down from the primary mammary mesenchyme and into a second stromal compartment, the fat pad precursor, beneath the dermis.

name: lumbar spinal cord dorsal column
description: A subdivision of spinal cord dorsal column that is part of a lumbar spinal cord.

name: 4th arch endoderm
description: An endoderm that is part of a pharyngeal arch 4.

name: sublingual nucleus
description: In the substance of the formatio reticularis are two small nuclei of gray matter. The one near the dorsal aspect of the hilus of the inferior olivary nucleus is called the Sublingual nucleus (inferior central nucleus, nucleus of Roller.) [WP,unvetted].

name: lower respiratory tract smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a lower respiratory tract [Automatically generated definition].

name: skeletal muscle fiber triad
description: The skeletal muscle fiber structure comprised of the transverse tubule and the two associated terminal cisternae; each fiber normally has thousands of triads

name: trapezoid body
description: Bundles of axons traversing the pontine tegmentum oriented in the mediolateral direction. These fibers are related to the auditory pathway. Nuclei are embedded within these fibers.

name: tract of diencephalon
description: An axon tract that is part of a diencephalon.

name: wall of esophagus
description: An anatomical wall that is part of a esophagus [Automatically generated definition].

name: ceratobranchials II--IV
description: Paired bars that articulate with hypobranchial II. Reduction of loss of these elements is common in salamanders.

name: dorsal fin spine 2
description: Dorsal-fin lepidotrichium 2 with co-ossified and unsegmented hemitrichia that form a stiff shaft and enlarged base that moveably articulates with second dorsal-fin pterygiophore.

name: epicoracoid horn
description: A pair of cartilaginous expansions (one from each epicoracoid cartilage) that project posteriorly. They articulate with the sternum by means of grooves, pouches or fossae in the dorsal surface of the sternum and provide a site for the insertion of a pair of muscles derived from the m. rectus abdominis.

name: clivus of occipital bone
description: Part of the cranium, the clivus is a shallow depression behind the dorsum sellC& that slopes obliquely backward. It forms a gradual sloping process at the anterior most portion of the basilar occipital bone at its junction with the sphenoid bone. On axial planes, it sits just posterior to the sphenoid sinuses. Just lateral to the clivus bilaterally is the foramen lacerum which contains the internal carotid artery, proximal to its anastamosis with the Circle of Willis. Posterior to the clivus is the basilar artery. The clivus supports the upper part of the pons.

name: tibial nerve
description: The tibial nerve is a branch of the sciatic nerve. The tibial nerve passes through the popliteal fossa to pass below the arch of soleus. In the popliteal fossa the nerve gives off branches to gastrocnemius, popliteus, soleus and plantaris muscles, an articular branch to the knee joint, and a cutaneous branch that will become the sural nerve. The sural nerve is joined by fibres from the common peroneal nerve and runs down the calf to supply the lateral side of the foot. Below the soleus muscle the nerve lies close to the tibia and supplies the tibialis posterior, the flexor digitorum longus and the flexor hallucis longus. The nerve passes into the foot running posterior to the medial malleolus. Here it is bound down by the flexor retinaculum in company with the posterior tibial artery. [WP,unvetted].

name: oral epithelium from ectoderm
description: An epithelium that develops_from a ectoderm and is part of a oral epithelium.

name: anteroventral process of cleithrum
description: A ramus of the celithrum that descend along the girdle. Its rounded outer surface forms the articulation surface for the clavicle while its anterior surface overlaps with the anterior process of the scapulocoracoid.

name: right occipital lobe
description: An occipital lobe that is part of a right cerebral hemisphere.

name: interhyal-epihyal joint
description: Joint that articulates the interhyal and epihyal bones, or interhyal and ceratohyal cartilages. Interhyal-epihyal joint is paired.

name: margo posterior of cleithrum
description: Posterior margin of the posterior ramus of the cleithrum.

name: posterior part of tongue
description: The Posterior tongue, or pharyngeal part, is the part of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus. At its root, it is directed backward, and connected with the hyoid bone by the Hyoglossi and Genioglossi muscles and the hyoglossal membrane; with the epiglottis by three folds (glossoepiglottic) of mucous membrane; with the soft palate by the glossopalatine arches; and with the pharynx by the Constrictores pharyngis superiores and the mucous membrane. It is derived primarily from the third pharyngeal arch. (The second arch has a substantial contribution during fetal development, but this later atrophies. The fourth arch may also contribute, depending upon how the boundaries of the tongue are defined.)

name: basibranchial 2 tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 2 tooth plate.

name: extensor digitorum brevis manus
description: An accessory extensor muscle of the hand found in some humans and other animals.

name: scapholunate
description: The combined scaphoid and lunate bones.

name: caudal principal ray 4
description: Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 3.

name: principal vein of forelimb
description: A prinicipal vein of limb that is part of a forelimb.

name: mesothelium of pleural cavity
description: A mesothelium that is part of a pleural cavity [Automatically generated definition].

name: sacral spinal cord ventral commissure
description: A spinal cord ventral commissure that is part of a sacral spinal cord.

name: somatopleure
description: A structure created during embryogenesis when the lateral mesoderm splits into two layers - the outer (or somatic) layer becomes applied to the inner surface of the ectoderm, and with it forms the somatopleure.[WP].

name: limb endochondral element
description: A limb bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: vena cava endothelium
description: An endothelium that is part of a vena cava [Automatically generated definition].

name: forelimb nerve
description: A nerve that is part of a forelimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: adult thoracic segment
description: Any segment (UBERON:6000003) that is part of some adult thorax (UBERON:6003018).

name: pharyngeal ectoderm
description: The external part of the developing pharynx that is made of ectoderm. During vertebrate development, pockets form in pharyngeal ectoderm between the pharyngeal arches.

name: fenestrated capillary
description: Capillary that has pores in the endothelial cells (60-80 nm in diameter) that are spanned by a diaphragm of radially oriented fibrils and allow small molecules and limited amounts of protein to diffuse
