name: external cervical os
description: Opening of uterine cervix into the vagina.

name: anatomical group
description: Anatomical structure consisting of at least two non-overlapping organs, multi-tissue aggregates or portion of tissues or cells of different types that does not constitute an organism, organ, multi-tissue aggregate, or portion of tissue.

name: submucosa of laryngopharynx
description: A submucosa that is part of a hypopharynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: metencephalic artery
description: These arteies branch dorsally from both sides of the posterior communicating artery looping up to join with the opposite MtA as well as with both middle cerebral veins at the dorsal midline of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: metapodium bone 4
description: A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 4 plus metapodial segment.

name: sclerotome
description: Ventral somitic compartment that is a precursor of the axial skeleton[XAO]. Sclerotomes eventually differentiate into the vertebrae and most of the skull. The caudal (posterior) half of one sclerotome fuses with the rostral (anterior) half of the adjacent one to form each vertebra. From their initial location within the somite, the sclerotome cells migrate medially towards the notochord. These cells meet the sclerotome cells from the other side to form the vertebral body. From this vertebral body, sclerotome cells move dorsally and surround the developing spinal cord, forming the vertebral arch[WP].

name: distal tarsal bone 4 cartilage
description: A distal tarsal bone 4 endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: blastodisc
description: A small, circular, white spot (approximately 2-3 mm across) on the surface of the yellow yolk of an egg that has been laid. The nucleus of the egg is in the germinal disc.

name: least splanchnic nerve
description: A thoracic nerve that nerve travels into the abdomen, where its fibers synapse in the renal ganglia.

name: skeleton of manual digitopodium
description: A subdivision of the manus skeleton consisting of both manual acropodial skeleton and metacarpal skeleton, but excluding the carpal skeleton.

name: outer limiting layer of retina
description: The row of jucntional complexes between the plasma membranes of rod segments and the Muller glia cells; this barrier separates the layer of inner and outer segments of the rods and cones from the outer nuclear layer and forms a blood-retina barrier[MP].

name: pronephric glomerular capsule epithelium
description: Simple squamous epithelium that lines the capsule of the pronephric glomerulus.

name: mesenchyme of yolk sac
description: The portion of the yolk sac that is derived from mesoderm and consists of mesenchyme.

name: subarticular tubercles
description: Is a integumentary structure located on the ventral surface of the hand and/or foot. Found at the junction between, in the hand, the metacarpal and most proximal phalanx of the digit and between phalanges, and in the foot between the metatarsal and most proximal phalanx of the digit and between phalanges.

name: primary dental epithelium
description: Epithelium that surrounds a primary tooth. This epithelium is committed to formation of replacement teeth.

name: tibia pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a tibia.

name: pharyngeal mucosa
description: A mucosa that is part of a pharynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: morphological boundary
description: A two dimensional anatomical structure that corresponds to some structural discontinuity.

name: stephanion
description: The point where the upper temporal line cuts the coronal suture is named the stephanion.

name: octaval nerve motor nucleus
description: Hindbrain nucleus which consists of cell bodies whose axons exit the hindbrain via cranial nerve VIII and innervate hair cells of the lateral line and inner ear. The neurons of these nuclei are unusual in that they extend both contra- and ipsilateral dendrites.

name: haemolymphatic fluid
description: Circulating fluid that is part of the hemolymphoid system. Blood, lymph, interstitial fluid or its analogs.

name: bony labyrinth
description: A system of fluid passages in the inner ear, including both the cochlea, which is part of the auditory system, and the vestibular system, which provides the sense of balance. The bony labyrinth, or osseous labyrinth, is the network of passages with bony walls lined with periosteum. The bony labyrinth is lined with the membranous labyrinth. There is a layer of perilymph between them. The three parts of the bony labyrinth are the vestibule of the ear, the semicircular canals, and the cochlea. The vestibular system is the region of the inner ear where the semicircular canals converge, close to the cochlea (the hearing organ). The vestibular system works with the visual system to keep objects in focus when the head is moving. Joint and muscle receptors also are important in maintaining balance. The brain receives, interprets, and processes the information from these systems that control our balance. [WP,unvetted].

name: pseudostratified columnar epithelium
description: A simple columnar epithelium that looks stratified but is not, because its cells are arranged with their nuclei at different levels.

name: epaxial region somite 4
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: tarsometatarsus pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a tarsometatarsus.

name: urethra skeletal muscle tissue
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a urethra [Automatically generated definition].

name: filoplume feather
description: A hairlike feather that grows alongside the down feathers.

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 6
description: dorsal fin distal radial 6 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: M. quadratus femoris
description: Originates on the ventro-lateral border of the ischium and inserts on the ventro-medial surface of the femur at the base of caput femoris.

name: accessory navicular bone
description: An accessory bone of the pes that occasionally develops abnormally in front of the ankle towards the inside of the pes. This bone may be present in approximately 2.5% of the general population and is usually asymptomatic

name: air in respiratory system
description: Any portion of gas located in a part of the respiratory system that is composed primarily of air.

name: obsolete alarm substance cell
description: Epithelial cell that produces a chemical that triggers antipredator behavior.

name: pedal digit 3 metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pedal digit metatarsal pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a pedal digit 3 mesenchyme.

name: myotome somite 1
description: Portion of the somite giving rise to body wall muscle masses. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: intestinal villus of ileum
description: An intestinal villus in the ileum.

name: epaxial region somite 6
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: recessus basilaris
description: An opening of the otic duct within the inner ear. The recessus basilaris can open to the saccule (in frogs) or the lagena (in salamanders and caecilians). The sensory epithelium of the recessus basilaris is the basilar papilla (or papilla basilaris). Reference: Lewis, E.R. and R.E. Lombard. 1988. The amphibian inner ear. Pp. 93-123 in Fritszch, B., et al. (eds.), The Evolution of the Amphibian Auditory System. Wiley & Sons. [curated by D. Blackburn]

name: anatomical collection
description: A collection of anatomical structures that are alike in terms of their morphology or developmental origin.

name: anal part of perineum
description: The anal triangle is the posterior part of the perineum. It contains the anal canal. [WP,unvetted].

name: anal region
description: The anus and surrounding regions. Encompasses both internal and external regions, where present

name: iliac vein
description: Any of the three veins including the common, external and internal iliac veins.

name: breast feather
description: A feather that is part of a the upper ventral region of an animal's torso.

name: upper arm mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing forelimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: intercerebral commissure
description: A commissure that connects the two cerebral hemispheres. Examples: anterior commissure, corpus callosum.

name: parakeratinized epithelium of tongue
description: A parakeratinized epithelium that is part of a tongue.

name: cerumen
description: The yellow or brown waxy secretions produced by vestigial apocrine sweat glands in the external ear canal[MESH].

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of neostriatum
processus lingualis of pterygoid
description: Dorsolateral process of the of the medial ramus of the pterygoid.

name: Bruch's membrane
description: A transparent, nearly structureless innermost layer of the choroid in contact with the pigmented layer of the retina.

name: vagina
description: A fibromuscular tubular tract leading from the uterus to the exterior of the body in female placental mammals and marsupials, or to the cloaca in female birds, monotremes, and some reptiles[WP].

name: pronephric nephron
description: A pronephric nephron is the functional unit of the pronephros[GO].

name: mediastinal lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a mediastinum. Each consists of several lymph node groups, especially along the trachea (5 groups), along the esophagus and between the lung and the diaphragm. In the mediastinal lymph nodes arises lymphatic ducts, which draines the lymph to the left subclavian vein (to the venous angle in the confluence of the subclavian and deep jugular veins). The mediastinal lymph nodes along the esophagus are in tight connection with the abdominal lymph nodes along the esophagus and the stomach. That fact facilitates spreading of tumors cells through these lymphatics in cases of cancers of the stomach and particularly of the esophagus. Through the mediastinum, the main lymphatic drainage from the abdominal organs goes via the thoracic duct (ductus thoracicus), which drains majority of the lymph from the abdomen to the above mentioned left venous angle.

name: corpus spongiosum of penis
description: Corpus spongiosum (also known as corpus cavernosum urethrae in older texts) is the mass of spongy tissue surrounding the male urethra within the penis.

name: epibranchial bone uncinate process
description: Epibranchials 1-3 in adults are compound elements formed by the fusion of epibranchial cartilages and the so-called uncinate processes. Posteromedially directed uncinate processes develop on the posterior edge of epibranchials 1-3. These appear as separate centers of chondrification (6.2 mm) that later fuse laterally to the posterior edges of the epibranchial cartilages (6.8 mm).

name: anatomical lobe
description: A portion of an organ, such as the liver, lung, breast, or brain.

name: fibrous membrane of synovial tendon sheath
sublaminar layers S3 or S4 or S5
description: One of sublaminar layers S3, S4, or S5.

name: posterior sclerotic bone
description: Sclerotic bone that is located posterior to the eye.

name: hair canal
description: Tubular connection between the epidermal surface and the most distal part of the inner root sheath. Contains the hair shaft.

name: medial floor plate
description: The medial portion of the spinal cord floor plate, located adjacent to the notochord.

name: M. flexor antibrachii medialis
description: Originates on the medial epicondyle of the humerus and inserts on the radial aspect of the radioulna.

name: Brachet's cleft
description: The visible division between epiblast and hypoblast in the gastrula. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: clypeus
description: The anterior part of the head between the frons and the labrum, which occasionally may fuse with either one to form the frontoclypeus and the clypeolabrum. In the context of Drosophila refers to a round structure on the center of the frontal adult external head.

name: mons pubis
description: A structure composed of adipose tissue lying above the pubic bone of adult women, anterior to the symphysis pubis. The mons pubis forms the anterior portion of the vulva, and limits the perineal region proximally and anteriorly.

name: outer epithelium
description: The epidermis is the entire outer epithelial layer of an animal, it may be a single layer that produces an extracellular material (e.g. the cuticle of arthropods) or a complex stratified squamous epithelium, as in the case of many vertebrate species[GO].

name: stratified cuboidal epithelium
description: Stratified cuboidal epithelia is a rare type of epithelial tissue composed of cuboidally shaped cells arranged in multiple layers. They protect areas such as ducts of sweat glands, mammary glands, and salivary glands.

name: pes bone
description: A bone that is part of the pes skeleton

name: anal fin skeleton
description: Median fin skeleton that is located posterior to the anus.

name: third ventricle ependyma
description: An ependyma that is part of a third ventricle [Automatically generated definition].

name: musculature of leg
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a lower leg or upper leg [Automatically generated definition].

name: nasal bone
description: One of two small oblong bones, varying in size and form in different individuals; they are placed side by side at the middle and upper part of the face, and form, by their junction, 'the bridge' of the nose[WP]. Paired dermal bones, likened to a bone tube, positioned lateral to the supraethmoid. Nasal bones are transversed by the anterior most part of the supraorbital canals and bear one neuromast foramen in zebrafish[ZFA].

name: levator cloacae
description: a long narrow muscle arising from the underside of feather bulge of the lateral rectrices, inserting near the midline of the cloacal tubercle - phallus.

name: proximo-distal subdivision of respiratory tract
description: An section of a respiratory tract.

name: anconeus muscle
description: A small muscle on the posterior aspect of the elbow joint.

name: smooth muscle tissue of respiratory bronchiole
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a respiratory bronchiole [Automatically generated definition].

name: pharyngeal tonsil
description: the lymph tissue in the roof and posterior wall of the nasopharynx

name: obsolete predominantly gray posterior regional part of thalamus
parametrium
description: The subserous connective tissue of the pelvic floor of the supracervical portion of the uterus. The parametrium extends laterally between the layers of the broad ligament.

name: lower urinary tract
description: Subdivision of urinary system which consists of the urinary bladder and the urethra.

name: ligament of sternoclavicular joint
description: A skeletal ligament that is part of a sternoclavicular joint.

name: asterion of skull
description: The asterion is the point on the skull corresponding to the posterior end of the parietomastoid suture.

name: endoneurium
description: The loose connective tissue within the perineurium that continues into nerve fascicles and surrounds individual fibers. (Nolte, J. The Human Brain 3rd edition)

name: crypt of Henle
description: Crypts of Henle are microscopic pockets found in scattered sections of the conjunctiva around the eyeball. They are responsible for secreting mucin, a proteinous substance that makes up the inner layer of tears. It coats the cornea to provide a hydrophilic layer that allows for even distribution of the tear film. The layer of mucin allows tears to glide evenly across the eye's surface[WP].

name: albumen
description: Albumen is the clear liquid contained within an egg and consists of water and proteins, among which are ovomucin and ovomucoid. It protects the egg yolk and provides additional nutrition for the growth of the embryo.

name: presumptive prothoracic metatarsus
description: Region of the prothoracic leg disc that will develop into the prothoracic metatarsus.

name: arthropod hepatopancreas
description: Digestive gland of crustaceans with functions approximately analogous to liver and pancreas of vertebrates - enzyme secretion, food absorption and storage.

name: ceratobranchial element
description: Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and forms part of the ventral branchial arches.

name: preopercle horizontal limb
description: A dermal bone that is the lower, horizontal portion of the preopercle bone.

name: adrenergic system
description: any molecule, protein, cell, tissue or organ that is related to epinephrine (also known as adrenaline).

name: obsolete germ layer / neural crest derived structure
caudal-fin hook
description: Process that is part of the caudal fin lepidotrichium.

name: metanephric proximal tubule
description: The metanephric proximal tubule is a metanephric nephron tubule that connects Bowman's capsule to the descending thin limb of the loop of Henle in the metanephros. It has a brush border epithelial morphology[GO].

name: occipital condyle
description: The occipital condyles are undersurface facets of the occipital bone in vertebrates, which function in articulation with the superior facets of the atlas vertebra. The condyles are oval or reniform (kidney-shaped) in shape, and their anterior extremities, directed forward and medialward, are closer together than their posterior, and encroach on the basilar portion of the bone; the posterior extremities extend back to the level of the middle of the foramen magnum. The articular surfaces of the condyles are convex from before backward and from side to side, and look downward and lateralward. To their margins are attached the capsules of the atlantoC6ccipital articulations, and on the medial side of each is a rough impression or tubercle for the alar ligament. At the base of either condyle the bone is tunnelled by a short canal, the hypoglossal canal.

name: jejunal artery
description: A branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the jejunum.

name: subcutaneous adipose tissue
description: A portion of adipose tissue that is part of the hypodermis, beneath the dermis.

name: anterior abdominal wall
description: The abdominal wall represents the boundaries of the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall is split into the posterior (back), lateral (sides) and anterior (front) walls. There is a common set of layers covering and forming all the walls: the deepest being the extraperitoneal fat, the parietal peritoneum, and a layer of fascia which has different names over where it covers (eg transversalis, psoas fascia). Superficial to these, but not present in the posterior wall are the three layers of muscle, the transversus abdominis (transverse abdominal muscle), the internal (obliquus internus) and the external oblique (obliquus externus).

name: telencephalon neural crest
description: A neural crest that has_potential_to_developmentally_contribute_to a telencephalon.

name: cuspid
description: A tooth that is typically long and pointed and bearing a single cusp.

name: Hadjikhani et al. (1998) visuotopic area V1d
distal straight tubule macula densa
description: A macula densa that is part of an ascending limb of loop of Henle [Automatically generated definition].

name: hyoid bone
description: A horseshoe shaped bone situated in the anterior midline of the neck between the chin and the thyroid cartilage. The hyoid bone provides attachment to the muscles of the floor of the mouth and the tongue above, the larynx below, and the epiglottis and pharynx behind. [WP,modified].

name: heart blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a heart [Automatically generated definition].

name: mucosa of middle ear
description: A mucosa that is part of a middle ear [Automatically generated definition].

name: chondrocranium
description: Endoskeletal elements that encase the brain, nose, inner ear[cjm]. that part of the neurocranium formed by endochondral ossification and comprising the bones of the base of the skull[TFD].

name: horizontal septum
description: A logitudinal sheet of continuous connective tissue partition developing at the apex of the chevron-shaped myotome and separating dorsal (epaxial) and ventral (hypaxial) body wall muscle masses; each is destined to become, respectively, the epaxial and hyopaxial musculature.

name: posterior cardinal vein
description: One of two paired cardinal veins that return blood from the body of the embryo[Kardong]

name: brain pia mater
description: The fibrous membrane forming the innermost of the three coverings that surrounds the brain within the cranial cavity that is firmly attached to the glial capsule.

name: ileum
description: the portion of the small intestine that extends from the jejunum to the colon

name: tooth 2D
description: Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the dorsal tooth row.

name: obsolete ventral ramus of occulomotor nerve
description: Innervates m. rectus medialis, m. rectus inferior, m. obliquus inferior.

name: articular cartilage element
description: Cartilage of the lower jaw that give rise to a portion of the anguloarticular compound bone.

name: mesenchyme of main bronchus
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing main bronchus.

name: arytenoid muscle
description: A single muscle, filling up the posterior concave surfaces of the arytenoid cartilages. It arises from the posterior surface and lateral border of one arytenoid cartilage, and is inserted into the corresponding parts of the opposite cartilage. It consists of oblique and transverse parts.

name: occipital lateral line neuromast
description: A neuromast that is part of the occipital lateral line.

name: precaval vein
description: Either of a pair of veins which enter on either side of the sinus venosus.

name: vocalis muscle
description: The vocal muscle is the upper portion of the thyroarytenoid muscle which is primarily involved in producing speech.

name: nephric ridge
description: Nephric tubules (nephrons) form embryonically along the nephric ridge. The ridge comprises three regions; anterior, middle and posterior. The functional kidney uses nephrons from only one or two regions of the ridge. A pronephric kidney uses only the nephrons from the anterior region of the ridge. A mesonephric kidney uses only the middle region, a metanephric kidney uses only the posterior region and an opisthonephric kidney uses the middle and posterior regions.

name: embryonic post-anal tail
description: An embryonic structure that will either develop into a post-anal tail or recede into a vestigial remnant of the tail.

name: stylopharyngeus muscle
description: The stylopharyngeus is a muscle in the head that stretches between the styloid process and the pharynx.

name: placental labyrinth blood vessel
description: The embryonic vessels grow through the layer to come in close contact with the maternal blood supply

name: sacral spinal cord
description: A spinal cord segment that adjacent_to a sacral region.

name: distal epiphysis of fibula
description: A distal epiphysis that is part of a fibula [Automatically generated definition].

name: iris smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of a iris [Automatically generated definition].

name: ilium
description: Paired endochondral bone that is the dorsal-most of the pelvic bones, offering attachment areas for gluteal muscles on its main surface [PHENOSCAPE:ad].

name: embryonic/larval lymph gland
description: Hematopoietic organ of the larva, located along the dorsal vessel, behind the brain. It produces the plasmatocytes, crystal cells and lamellocytes which are released at the end of the larval instar and onset of metamorphosis. It is composed of 3 pairs of bilateral lobes: an anterior primary lobe, a posterior secondary lobe and the most posterior lobe (or multiple lobes), the tertiary lobe. Each lobe is separated by pericardial cells. In the late embryo, the lymph gland consists of a single pair of lobes (primary lobes) containing around 20 cells each that flank the dorsal vessel. By the second larval instar, the lymph gland is composed of two or three new pairs of posterior lobes, and the primary lobes have increased in size to contain around 200 cells. During the first and early second larval instars, the lymph gland comprises only the hematopoietic progenitor population. The lymph gland increases in size ten-fold by the late third instar, and at this stage the progenitor cells (prohemocytes) become restricted to the medial region (medullary zone) of the primary lobe and become quiescent. The differentiated hemocytes are found in the periphery (cortical zone) of the primary lobe and these cells proliferate extensively. The posterior signalling center is a group of about 30 cells at the posterior tip of the primary lobe that secretes several signalling molecules and functions as a stem-cell niche. The secondary and tertiary lobes contain prohemocytes, and rarely a differentiated cell. Lymph glands are eliminated at metamorphosis.

name: pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium
description: Epithelium composed of a single layer of cells, appearing as layered because the column-shaped cells vary in height so the nuclei are at different levels. The basal portions of all the cells are in contact with the basement membrane. It lines the respiratory system and the male reproductive tract. The cilia in the respiratory tract are motile, while the stereocilia in the male reproductive tract are immobile.

name: epaxial region somite 7
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. immel et al, 1995.

name: opponens digiti minimi of hand

It is of a triangular form, and placed immediately beneath the palmaris brevis, abductor minimi digiti, and flexor brevis minimi digiti. It arises from the convexity of the hamulus of the hamate bone, and contiguous portion of the transverse carpal ligament; it is inserted into the whole length of the metacarpal bone of the little finger, along its ulnar margin.

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 7

name: obsolete fascia dentata
description: OBSOLETE: The fascia dentata is the earliest stage of the hippocampal circuit. Its primary input is the perforant path from the superficial layers of entorhinal cortex. Its principal neurons are tiny granule cells which give rise to unmyelinated axons called the mossy fibers which project to the hilus and CA3. The fascia dentata of the rat contains approximately 1,000,000 granule cells. It receives feedback connections from mossy cells in the hilus at distant levels in the septal and temporal directions. The fascia dentata and the hilus together make up the dentate gyrus. As with all regions of the hippocampus, the dentate gyrus also receives GABAergic and cholinergic input from the medial septum and the diagonal band of Broca.

name: renal lobe

name: epineurium
description: A loose connective tissue sheath surrounding each peripheral nerve. Composed mainly of colagen and fibroblasts, it forms a substantial covering over nerve trunks, then thins to an incomplete layer around smaller branches near their terminations. The epineurium is continuous centrally with the dura. Peripherally, it usually ends near the termination of a nerve fiber, but it may continue as the capsule of Meissner corpuscles and a few other encapsulated endings. Nolte, J. The Human Brain 3rd edition

name: sweat gland of eyelid
description: Glands of Moll, also known as ciliary glands, are modified apocrine sweat glands that are found on the margin of the eyelid. They are next to the base of the eyelashes, and anterior to the Meibomian glands within the distal eyelid margin. These glands are relatively large and tubular-shaped. The glands of Moll are named after Dutch oculist Jacob Anton Moll (1832-1914). Glands of Moll empty into the adjacent lashes. Glands of Moll and Zeis secrete lipid that adds to the superficial layer of the tear film, retarding evaporation. The glands of Moll are prone to infection and blockage of its duct with sebum and cell debris. Blockage of the gland's duct causes swelling which can manifest itself as a stye.

name: dilatator pupillae

name: extraembryonic endoderm

name: lacrimal vein

name: subiculum

A molecular layer is present that is continuous with that of CA1, although the stratum radiatum is no longer present. The stratum oriens is also not present. adapted from Paxinos, G. The rat central nervous system, 2nd ed, Academic Press, San Diego, 1995, pg. 468)

name: thoracic nerve

name: cranial nerve II

Transmits visual information from the retina to the brain[ZFA].

name: cavum medius

name: root of thoracic nerve

name: tooth 4MD

name: obsolete flask cell

name: pelvic appendage musculature

name: mesenchyme of trachea

name: supraorbital lateral line neuromast

name: cauda epididymis

name: gingival groove

The depth of the sulcus (Latin for groove) is bounded by two entities: apically by the gingival fibers of the connective tissue attachment and coronally by the free gingival margin.

name: prostate gland stroma

name: proximal epiphysis of humerus

name: prepatagium

name: osteon

name: mammary gland smooth muscle

name: calcaneus

name: ischium

name: footplate apical ectodermal ridge

name: intrinsic muscle of pes

name: incisor tooth

name: right temporal lobe

name: granulation tissue

name: ceratohyal-dorsal hypohyal joint

name: polster

name: urogenital fold

name: exoccipital pre-cartilage condensation

name: thoracic cavity nerve

name: tooth of upper jaw

name: basal lamina of epithelium
description: Acellular anatomical structure that consists of a thin sheet of fibrous proteins that underlie and support the cells of an epithelium. It separates the cells of an epithelium from any underlying tissue.

name: celiac nerve plexus
description: A complex network of nerves located in the abdomen behind the stomach. The celiac plexus is located near where the celiac trunk, superior mesenteric artery, and renal arteries branch from the abdominal aorta. It is behind the stomach and the omental bursa and in front of the crura of the diaphragm, on the level of the first lumbar vertebra, L1. The plexus is formed (in part) by the greater and lesser splanchnic nerves of both sides, and also parts of the right vagus nerve. The celiac plexus proper consists of the celiac ganglia with a network of interconnecting fibers. The aorticorenal ganglia are often considered to be part of the celiac ganglia, and thus, part of the plexus. [WP,unvetted].

name: submucosa of cecum

name: fused metapodial bones 3 and 4

name: substantia nigra pars reticulata
description: Regional part of substantia nigra consisting of loosely packed cells, generally located ventral and lateral to the pars compacta. Many cells in this region use GABA as a neurotransmitter (MM).

name: mesenchyme of elbow

name: prostate gland lateral lobe

name: fibula pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that has the potential to develop into a fibula.

name: inferior palpebral branch of infra-orbital nerve

name: manual digit 2 phalanx cartilage element

name: nucleus recessus

name: tibiotarsus pre-cartilage condensation

name: vertebral ganglion

name: feather barbule

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage 8

name: dentate gyrus molecular layer inner

name: M. gemellus

name: entopterygoid vertical strut

name: sutural bone

name: future neurohypophysis

name: nasal muscle

description: An epithelium that is part of the respiratory segment of the nasal mucosa [Automatically generated definition].

name: arcuate artery of foot
description: The arcuate artery of the foot (metatarsal artery) arises a little anterior to the lateral tarsal artery; it passes lateralward, over the bases of the metatarsal bones, beneath the tendons of the Extensor digitorum brevis, its direction being influenced by its point of origin; and its anastomoses with the lateral tarsal and lateral plantar arteries. This vessel gives off the second, third, and fourth dorsal metatarsal arteries. It is not present in all individuals.

name: electric organ
description: A specialized tract of tissue (as in the electric eel) in which electricity is generated.

name: intercostal artery
description: One of a group of arteries that supply the area between the ribs ('costae'), called the intercostal space.

name: median fin spine
description: Fin spine that is part of a median fin.

name: embryonic metathoracic segment
description: Metathoracic segment of the embryo.

name: common hepatic artery
description: In anatomy, the common hepatic artery is a short blood vessel that supplies oxygenated blood to the liver, pylorus (a part of the stomach), duodenum (a part of the small intestine) and pancreas. It arises from the celiac artery and has the following branches:

name: anterior horn of lateral ventricle
description: Part of the lateral ventricle that extends anteriorly into the frontal lobes, bordered by the head of the caudate nucleus on the lateral side (Adapted from Heimer, 1996)

name: saphenous nerve
description: The largest cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve. [WP,unvetted].

name: posterolateral process
description: Paired processes that extend posterolaterally from the posterolateral margin of the hyoid plate. These processes are formed as a result of new cartilaginous growth lateral to the basibranchial and hypobranchial plate.

name: cerebellum hemisphere lobule
description: The region of a cerebellar lobule that resides in either of the lateral sections of the cerebellum outside the vermis; in mammals, the vermis portion of the cerebellum has a foliation pattern along the AP axis that is distinct from the lateral cerebellar hemispheres

name: alveolus
description: organ part that has the form of a hollow cavity[WP].

name: alveolus of lung
description: Spherical outcropping of the respiratory bronchioles and primary site of gas exchange with the blood. Alveoli are particular to mammalian lungs. Different structures are involved in gas exchange in other vertebrates[WP].

name: chordate pharynx
description: A portion of the respiratory and digestive tracts; its distal limit is the superior part of the esophagus and it connects the nasal and oral cavities with the esophagus and larynx; it contains the valleculae and the pyriform recesses; its upper limits are the nasal cavity and cranial base.[FEED].

name: puboischiotibialis muscle
description: A muscle that originates from the puboischaidic plate and inserts on the tibia. Acts to adduct the hindlimb. Is anterior to cloacal gland in males. Modified from De luliis and Pulera.

name: rete testis
description: An anastomosing network of delicate tubules located in the hilum of the testicle (mediastinum testis) that carries sperm from the seminiferous tubules to the vasa efferentia[WP].

name: middle frontal gyrus
description: Component of the frontal lobe, lateral aspect (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: seminal vesicle
description: Either of a pair of glandular pouches that lie one on either side of the male reproductive tract posterolateral to the urinary bladder and in the human male secrete a sugar- and protein-containing fluid into the ejaculatory duct.

name: lumbar lymph node
description: The lumbar lymph nodes (paraaortic nodes) are a group of lymph nodes residing in the lumbar region. They consist of the following groups: right and left lateral aortic lymph nodes preaortic lymph nodes retroaortic lymph nodes (or 'postaortic')

name: gastrointestinal sphincter
description: A sphincter muscle that is part of the gastrointestinal system

name: rostral process
description: Is a process of the nasal bone directed anteriorly towards the rostrum.

name: middle cardiac vein
description: The middle cardiac vein commences at the apex of the heart, ascends in the posterior longitudinal sulcus, and ends in the coronary sinus near its right extremity.

name: obsolete regional part of thalamus
description: A regional part of brain that is part of a thalamus [Automatically generated definition].

name: styliform element
description: An unjointed, rod-like bony or cartilaginous structures that extend from distal limb joints in tetrapods.

name: renal lobule
description: The portion of a renal lobe consisting of nephrons grouped around a single medullary ray and draining into a single collecting duct; human kidneys have multilobular, multipapillary architecture while mice and rats have unilobular, unipapillary kidneys

name: deep fascia
description: Deep fascia (or 'investing fascia') is a layer of fascia which can surround individual muscles, and divide groups of muscles into compartments. This is the dense fibrous connective tissue that interpenetrates and surrounds the muscles, bones, nerves and blood vessels of the body. It provides connection and communication in the form of aponeuroses, ligaments, tendons, retinacula, joint capsules, and septa. The deep fasciae envelop all bone; cartilage, and blood vessels and become specialized in muscles and nerves. The high density of collagen fibers is what gives the deep fascia its strength and integrity. The amount of elastin fiber determines how much extensibility and resilience it will have.

name: quadrate posterodorsal process
description: Process that is the posterior extension of the quadrate and located dorsal to the quadrate ventral process.

name: border of sublaminar layers S1 and S2
description: The region extending out from the boundary between layers S1 and S2.

name: sex comb
description: A row of darkly pigmented, male specific chaetae located on the prothoracic metatarsal segment of the prothoracic leg. The number of chaetae (teeth) per sex comb varies between individuals, e.g.- Hannah-Alava and Stern report 10-13.

name: nasal turbinal
description: A skeletal element of the ethmoid region with complex morphology that are lined with mucuous membranes involved in either olfaction or air conditioning.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 3
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 3.

name: egg yolk
description: The yellow spheroidal mass of stored food that forms the inner portion of the egg of a bird or reptile and is surrounded by the white.

name: glabella region of bone
description: A zone of the frontal bone that connects the supraorbital rirdges.

name: bile duct epithelium
description: Any epithelium that lines one of the bile ducts.

name: dorsal fin skeleton
description: Median fin skeleton located on the dorsal surface of the organism.

name: fourth ventricle ependyma
description: An ependyma that is part of a fourth ventricle [Automatically generated definition].

name: lower primary incisor tooth
description: A primary incisor tooth that is part of a lower jaw region.

name: set of muscles of vertebral column
jugal bone
description: the quadrilateral bone that forms the prominence of the cheek

name: median eye
description: A median eye is an eye that is connected to a paired or unpaired median anterior neuropil of the syncerebrum by one or several median eye nerves.

name: left extraembryonic umbilical vein
description: A extraembryonic umbilical vein that is in_the_left_side_of a multicellular organism.

name: medial forebrain bundle
description: The Medial forebrain bundle (MFB), is a complex bundle of axons coming from the basal olfactory regions, the periamygdaloid region, and the septal nuclei, and passing to the lateral hypothalamus, with some carrying on into the tegmentum. It contains both ascending and descending fibers. It also represents a part of the mesolimbic pathway, carrying information between the ventral tegmentum and the nucleus accumbens. It is commonly accepted that the MFB is a part of the reward system, involved in the integration of reward and pleasure. Electrical stimulation of the medial forebrain bundle is believed to cause sensations of pleasure. This hypothesis is based upon intracranial self-stimulation (ICSS) studies. Animals will work for MFB ICSS, and humans report that MFB ICSS is intensely pleasurable. This is most likely because the medial forebrain bundle carries information from the ventral tegmental area (VTA) to the nucleus accumbens (nAcc or Acb). The nAcc is a recognized reward center, and activation of the pathway from the VTA to the nAcc is believed to be rewarding, which is why it is sometimes referred to as the hedonic highway. [WP,unvetted].

name: renal corpuscle
description: the structure containing the glomerular capsule and the glomerulus that serves as the initial blood-filtering component of a nephron

name: renal glomerulus
description: A capillary tuft which forms a close network with the visceral epithelium (podocytes) and the mesangium to form the filtration barrier and is surrounded by Bowman's capsule in nephrons of the vertebrate kidney[GO].

name: muscle of anal triangle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a anal part of perineum.

name: palatine uvula
description: Conic projection from the posterior edge of the middle of the soft palate, composed of connective tissue containing a number of racemose glands, and some muscular fibers.

name: xiphihumeralis
description: The most deep of pectoral muscles, found in some mammals

name: lower respiratory tract
description: The segment of the respiratory tract that starts proximally with the trachea and includes all distal structures including the lungs[WP,modified]

name: tracheoesophageal septum
description: The tracheoesophageal septum is formed from the tracheoesophageal folds which fuse in the midline to form a structure called tracheoesophageal septum. It divides the esophagus from the trachea. It divides the foregut tube into the laryngotracheal tube ventrally and esophagus dorsally. Developmental abnormalities can lead to a tracheoesophageal fistula.

name: amniotic cavity
description: A closed space between the embryo and the amnion which contains the amniotic fluid and is formed by the fusion of the parts of the anterior and posterior amniotic folds.

name: margin of tongue
description: The lateral border that separates the dorsum from the inferior surface of the tongue on each side, the two borders meeting anteriorly at the apex..

name: neural nucleus
description: A spatially aggregated collection of nerve cell bodies in the CNS, consisting of one or more subpopulations that share cell type, chemical phenotype, and connections, and including nearby cells that share the same cell type, chemical phenotype, and connections. (CUMBO)

name: eyelid gland
description: Any gland that is part of an eyelid. This includes sebaceous glands (Zeis gland, tarsal gland) and sweat glands (Moll's gland).

name: isthmus of thyroid gland
description: A narrow median bridge that joins together the lower thirds of the two lateral (right and left) lobes of the thyroid gland and usually covers the second and the third tracheal rings; the thyroid isthmus is variable in presence and size, can change shape and size, and can encompass a cranially extending pyramid lobe (lobus pyramidalis or processus pyramidalis), remnant of the thyroglossal duct

name: lung parenchyma
description: A parenchyma that is part of a lung.

name: second instar larva
description: Instar: a stage in the life of an arthropod (as an insect) between two successive molts.

name: suspensory ligament of lens
description: The zonule of Zinn (Zinn's membrane, ciliary zonule) is a ring of fibrous strands connecting the ciliary body with the crystalline lens of the eye. The zonule of Zinn is split into two layers: a thin layer, which lines the hyaloid fossa, and a thicker layer, which is a collection of zonular fibers. Together, the fibers are known as the suspensory ligament of the lens[WP]. Modified or toughened vitreous that suspend the lens at the equator to the non-pigmented epithelium of the ciliary zone. In zebrafish, dorsal zonules are thickened as compared to ventral zonules. In both dorsal and ventral regions, these fibers delimit the vitreous body aqueous humor boundary[ZFA].

name: otolymph
description: Transudate located within the osseus labyrinth. Otolymph can be further classified with respect to whether it is within the membranous labyrinth (endolymph) or outside the mebranous labyrinth (perilymph).

name: joint of girdle
description: A skeletal joint that is part of a appendage girdle region.

name: epithelial bud
description: A bud is a protrusion that forms from an epithelial sheet by localized folding.

name: nasal skeleton
description: Structural framework that provides support to the nasal sacs and ducts.

name: submucosa of digestive tract
description: Any portion of submucosa that lines the digestive tract.

name: tracheobronchial lymph node
description: A lymph node located near the bifurcation of the trachea.

name: ventricular system choroidal fissure
description: The narrow cleft along the medial wall of the lateral ventricle along the margins of which the choroid plexus is attached; it lies between the upper surface of the thalamus and lateral edge of the fornix in the central part of the ventricle and between the terminal stria and fimbria hippocampi in the inferior horn[ZFA].

name: rhombencephalon neural crest
description: A neural crest that has_potential_to_developmentally_contribute_to a hindbrain.

name: dorsal fin distal radial cartilage
description: dorsal fin distal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: patellar ligament
description: The central portion of the common tendon of the quadriceps femoris. It is attached to the apex of the PATELLA and to the lower part of the tubercle of the TIBIA.

name: larynx submucosa gland
description: A gland that is part of a larynx submucosa [Automatically generated definition].

name: caudal melanophore spot
description: distinct colored area on the caudal region of an organism, similar in shape to a spot, i.e. circular.

name: mucosa of maxillary sinus
description: A mucosa that is part of a maxillary sinus [Automatically generated definition].

name: cutaneous vein
description: one of a number of veins in the subcutaneous tissue that empty into deep veins

name: planum terminale
description: Vertical plate of cartilage that is fused posterodorsally to the oblique cartilage and anteriorly to the lamina inferior.

name: obsolete superficial feature part of cerebral cortex
bursa of Fabricius
description: An epithelial and lymphoid organ that develops as a dorsal diverticulum of the proctodeal region of the cloaca in birds. The luminal (interior) surface of the bursa is plicated with as many as 15 primary and 7 secondary plicae or folds. These plicae have hundreds of bursal follicles containing follicle-associated epithelial cells, lymphocytes, macrophages, and plasma cells. Lymphoid stem cells migrate from the fetal liver to the bursa during ontogeny. In the bursa, these stem cells acquire the characteristics of mature, immunocompetent B cells[WP]. The bursa is an organ found in birds involved in B cell differentiation[GO].

name: dermis
description: The dermis is a layer of skin between the epidermis (with which it makes up the skin) and subcutaneous tissues, and is composed of two layers, the papillary and reticular dermis[WP].

name: lamina superior
description: Lateral expansion of the crista intermedia that serves as the roof of the cavum medium.

name: intercostal nerve
description: The intercostal nerves are the anterior divisions (rami anteriores; ventral divisions) of the thoracic spinal nerves from T1 to T11. Each nerve is connected with the adjoining ganglion of the sympathetic trunk by a gray and a white ramus communicans. The intercostal nerves are distributed chiefly to the thoracic pleura and abdominal peritoneum and differ from the anterior divisions of the other spinal nerves in that each pursues an independent course without plexus formation. The first two nerves supply fibers to the upper limb in addition to their thoracic branches; the next four are limited in their distribution to the parietes of the thorax; the lower five supply the parietes of the thorax and abdomen. The 7th intercostal nerve terminates at the xyphoid process, at the lower end of the sternum. The 10th intercostal nerve terminates at the umbilicus. The twelfth thoracic is distributed to the abdominal wall and groin. [WP,unvetted].

name: frontal nerve (branch of ophthalmic)
description: The frontal nerve is the largest branch of the ophthalmic, and may be regarded, both from its size and direction, as the continuation of the nerve. It enters the orbit through the supraorbital foramen, and runs forward between the Levator palpebr√¶ superioris and the periosteum. Midway between the apex and base of the orbit it divides into two branches, supratrochlear nerve and supraorbital nerve. [WP,unvetted].

name: basibranchial I
description: Bilaterally unpaired ventral element with which articulates with lateral paired elements.

name: segment of leg
description: Any appendage segment (UBERON:6007018) that is part of some leg (UBERON:6004640).

name: root of lumbar spinal nerve
description: A spinal nerve root that is part of a lumbar nerve.

name: right ovary
description: An ovary that is part of a right side of organism [Automatically generated definition].

name: annelid pygidium
description: Rearmost segment of annelid worms.

name: tooth 3MD
description: Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 2MD and anterior to tooth 4MD in the mediodorsal tooth row.

name: epithelial-mesenchymal boundary
description: A anatomical line that adjacent_to a epithelium and adjacent_to a mesenchyme.

name: obsolete regional part of sacral spinal cord
pharyngeal arch cartilage
description: A cartilage element that is part of a splanchnocranium.

name: dorsolateral prefrontal cortex layer 1
description: Most superficial layer of the Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex (DLPFC).

name: appendage musculature
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of an appendage.

name: mesenchyme of middle ear
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing middle ear.

name: brain commissure
description: any of the nerve fiber tracts that span the longitudinal fissure between the cerebral and/or cerebellar hemispheres of the brain

name: elastoidin fin ray
description: Fin ray that is composed of elastoidin, unmineralized, and unsegmented.

name: occipital lymph node
description: A lymph node located in the back of the head adjacent to the trapezius muscle.

name: meningeal branch of spinal nerve
description: Branch of spinal nerve that innervates the structures of the vertebral column.

name: posterior spinal artery
description: A spinal artery that arises from the vertebral artery, adjacent to the medulla oblongata[WP,modified].

name: stylohyoid ligament
description: The fibrous cord that connects the tip of the styloid process of the temporal bone to the lesser horn of the hyoid bone

name: distal interphalangeal joint of digit 5
description: A distal interphalangeal joint that is part of a digit 5.

name: endodermal part of digestive tract
description: A portions of the gut that is derived from endoderm.

name: caudal segment of spinal cord
description: A spinal cord segment that adjacent_to a caudal region.

name: peritoneal cavity mesothelium
description: A mesothelium that is part of a peritoneal cavity.

name: proximal epiphysis of femur
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a femur [Automatically generated definition].

name: arteriole smooth muscle
description: A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an arteriole [Automatically generated definition].

name: mentomeckelian
description: Paired, cylindrical, and small bones of endochondral origin that lie anteromedial to the anterior end of Meckel's cartilage. The precursors of the mentomeckelian bones are the larval infrarostral cartilages.

name: pubis
description: A paired endochondral bone making up the anteroventral region of the tripartite pelvic girdle forming part of the ventral edge of the acetabulum. The origin site of many proximal hindlimb muscles. [PHENOSCAPE:ad].

name: magnocellular part of ventral anterior nucleus
adductor hallucis muscle
description: The Adductor hallucis (Adductor obliquus hallucis) arises by two headsboblique and transverse and is responsible for adducting the big toe. It is innervated by the lateral plantar nerve. It evolved from the contrahens I muscle as Man's ancestors' thumbs and big toes became opposable.

name: dentary tooth
description: Tooth that is attached to a dentary/mandible[TAO,modified].

name: axilar scale
description: Scale that is adjacent to the pelvic fin and aligned with the origin of the pelvic fin. It is typically an elongate scale.[Mattox and Toledo-Piza 2012]

name: distal epiphysis of phalanx of pes
magnocellular nucleus of medial geniculate body
hypobranchial II
description: Paired bar that articulates anteriorly with basibranchial I and posteriorly with ceratobranchials II--IV.

name: interosseous muscle of manus
description: Any of the interosseous muscles of the manus (hand). This includes the dorsal and plantar interossei

name: synaptic neuropil domain
description: Region of synaptic neuropil whose boundaries are largely discontinuities in the density of presynaptic terminals: high density in the synaptic neuropil domain, lower or zero density outside this region. These boundaries often correspond to a boundary with glial sheath, tract neuropil or cortex.

name: lumen of blood vessel
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a blood vessel.

name: pharyngobranchial 4 bone uncinate process
description: Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 4.

name: irregular connective tissue
description: Connective tissue, which consists of a population of connective tissue cells, the intercellular matrix of which contains an irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: areolar tissue, mucoid tissue, connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.

name: levator ani muscle
description: The Levator ani is a broad, thin muscle, situated on the side of the pelvis. It is attached to the inner surface of the side of the lesser pelvis, and unites with its fellow of the opposite side to form the greater part of the floor of the pelvic cavity. It supports the viscera in pelvic cavity, and surrounds the various structures which pass through it. In combination with the Coccygeus muscle, it forms the pelvic diaphragm. [WP,unvetted].

name: calcar avis of the lateral ventricle
description: On the medial wall of the posterior cornu of the lateral ventricle is a longitudinal eminence, the calcar avis (hippocampus minor), which is an involution of the ventricular wall produced by the calcarine fissure. It is sometimes visible on ultrasonogram.

name: iliofemoralis muscle
description: Limb extensor that runs from ilium to femur.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of temporal lobe
laryngeal apparatus
description: Apparatus located between the lungs and the buccal cavity. This apparatus is composed of a pair of arytenoid cartilages that are supported by the cricoid ring.

name: ceratohyal-ventral hypohyal joint
description: Joint that articulates the ceratohyal and ventral hypohyal bones. Ceratohyal-ventral hypohyal joint is paired.

name: enthesis
description: The connective tissue between tendon and bone insertion sites, which acts to transmit tensile load from soft tissues to bone. They may be of the dense fibrous connective tissue or fibrocartilage type; fibrous entheses attach directly to bone or periosteum primarily via fibrous tissue, and fibrocartilaginous entheses attach to bone through a transitional layer of fibrocartilage from the fibrous tendon tissue the sites where tendons or ligaments insert into the bone. Recurring stress or inflammatory autoimmune disease can cause inflammation or occasionally fibrosis and calcification of the enthesis.

name: skin of lower lip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a lower lip.

name: caudal principal ray 7
description: Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 6.

name: mesentery of urinary system
description: A mesentery that is part of a urinary system [Automatically generated definition].

name: epicondyle of humerus
description: A epicondyle that is part of a humerus.

name: manual digit 1 phalanx
description: A phalanx that is part of a hand digit 1 [Automatically generated definition].

name: autopod cartilage
description: A autopod endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: pelvis nerve
description: A nerve that is part of a pelvis [Automatically generated definition].

name: central nervous system gray matter layer
description: A layer of of the central nervous system that is part of gray matter.

name: obsolete sensory epithelium of spiral organ
tooth of lower jaw
description: A calcareous tooth that is part of the lower jaw region. In mammals, the lower jaw teeth are attached to the mandible (dentary).

name: epithelium
description: Portion of tissue, that consists of one or more layers of epithelial cells connected to each other by cell junctions and which is underlain by a basal lamina. Examples: simple squamous epithelium, glandular cuboidal epithelium, transitional epithelium, myoepithelium[CARO].

name: thoracodorsal artery
description: The thoracodorsal artery is a branch of the subscapular artery. It travels inferiorly with the thoracodorsal nerve and supplies the latissimus dorsi. [WP,unvetted].

name: submucosa of appendix
description: A submucosa that is part of an appendix [Automatically generated definition].

name: fused metacarpal bones 3 and 4
description: An element formed from the fusion of metacarpal 3 and metacarpal 4.

name: distal tarsal bone 5 cartilage
description: A distal tarsal bone 5 endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: nasal-associated lymphoid tissue
description: The lymphocytic cell population present in the mucosa of the nasopharyngeal duct of some animals.

name: reticular lamina of epithelium
description: A thin extracellular layer that sometimes lies below the basal lamina, is composed chiefly of collagenous fibers, and serves to anchor the basal lamina to underlying connective tissue.

name: mesenchyme of carpal region
description: Mesenchyme of the carpal region that contributes to the carpal skeleton.

name: palpebral branch of infra-orbital nerve
description: A nerve that innervates an eyelid and is a branch of the infra-orbital branch of the maxillary nerve.

name: manual digit 3 phalanx cartilage element
description: A cartilage element that is part of a manual digit 3 mesenchyme.

name: serous gland
description: A gland in which the principal secretory cells are serous secreting cells.

name: dentate gyrus granule cell layer inner blade
sphenoid lesser wing pre-cartilage condensation
description: A orbitosphenoid endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: angioblastic cord
description: the cordlike masses of splanchnic mesenchymal cells ventral to the primordial pericardial coelom that arrange themselves side by side to form the primordia of the endocardial heart tubes

name: myotome somite 16
description: Portion of the somite giving rise to body wall muscle masses. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: thymus primordium
description: A small outgrowth of the pharyngeal epithelium that is the site of lymphocyte cell production[ZFA]. [PMID].

name: internal iliac lymph node
description: The internal iliac lymph nodes (or hypogastric) surround the internal iliac artery and its branches (the hypogastric vessels), and receive the lymphatics corresponding to the distribution of the branches of it, i. e. , they receive lymphatics from all the pelvic viscera, from the deeper parts of the perineum, including the membranous and cavernous portions of the urethra, and from the buttock and back of the thigh. It does not receive lymph from the ovary, testis, or superior half of the rectum; the gonads drain to the paraaortic lymph nodes, while the superior half of the rectum drains to the pararectal lymph nodes.

name: olfactory segment of nasal mucosa
description: That portion of the nasal mucosa containing the sensory endings for olfaction; the organ of smell[MESH].

name: insect embryonic abdomen
description: Abdomen of the embryo.

name: conus medullaris
description: The conus medullaris is the terminal end of the spinal cord. It occurs near lumbar vertebral levels 1 (L1) and 2 (L2). After the spinal cord tapers out, the spinal nerves continue as dangling nerve roots called cauda equina. This terminal nerve root tail is referred to as the filum terminale. The upper end of the conus medullaris is usually not well defined.

name: obsolete cytoarchitectural part of dorsal cochlear nucleus
lateral globus pallidus
description: The more lateral of the two segments of the globus pallidus, abutting the putamen

name: posteromedial process
description: Cartilaginous, paired processes that extend posterolaterally from the posterior margin of the hyoid plate. These processes invest the laryngeal apparatus and are ossified in the adult.

name: cerebellum lobule
description: one of the the ten gyri of the cerebellar cortex

name: obsolete regional part of globus pallidus
pubotibialis
description: Originates in on the pubic cartillage and inserts on the tibia, acts to adduct the hindlimb. Modified from De luliis and Pulera.

name: obsolete predominantly white regional part of hippocampal formation
precentral gyrus
description: Component of the frontal lobe. The appearance and disappearance of the central sulcus is the rostral and caudal boundaries of the precentral gyrus respectively. The medial boundary is specific frontal gyri (superior, middle and inferior) whereas the lateral boundary is the medial bank of the central sulcus (Christine Fennema-Notestine).

name: cranial blood vasculature
description: A blood vasculature that is part of a head.

name: dorsal appendage
description: Paired appendage of the eggshell, located on the anterior-dorsal side of the egg, just posterior to the operculum. Functions as a respiratory structures.

name: ejaculatory duct
description: The Ejaculatory ducts (ductus ejaculatorii) are paired structures in male anatomy, about 2 cm in length. Each ejaculatory duct is formed by the union of the vas deferens with the duct of the seminal vesicle. They pass through the prostate, and empty into the urethra at the Colliculus seminalis. During ejaculation, semen passes through the ducts and exits the body via the penis[WP,unvetted].

name: ear epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a ear.

name: pancreatic lymph node
description: A lymph node that is part of a pancreas [Automatically generated definition].

name: Krause's gland
description: small, mucous accessory lacrimal glands that are found underneath the eyelid where the upper and lower conjuctivae meet. Their ducts unite into a rather long sinus which open into the fornix conjunctiva. There are approximately forty Krause glands in the region of the upper eyelid, and around 6 to 8 in the region of the lower lid. The function of these glands are to produce tears which are secreted onto the surface of the conjuctiva

name: visceral fascia
description: Fascia that suspends a visceral organ.

name: sensory canal
description: Multi-tissue structure that is a fluid-filled canal in the integument and usually dermal bones, and contains one or more neuromast organs.

name: border of sublaminar layers S3 and S4
description: The region extending out from the boundary between sublaminar layers S3 and S4.

name: caudal region
description: Subdivision of an organism along anterior-posterior axis that is the posteriormost region, extending past the anus (or cloaca, if present), consisting of a tail in some fully formed chordates (or a tail bud in embryos). In animals that have a sacral region, this is the region immediately posterior to this.

name: interphalangeal joint of manual digit 4
description: An interphalangeal joint of manus that is part of a manual digit 4.

name: articular system
description: Anatomical system that consists of all the joints of the body.

name: shelled egg
description: The hard-shelled reproductive body produced by a bird and especially by the common domestic chicken; also: its contents used as food.

name: dorsal ocellus
description: A simple visual organ of insects[GO]. Two ocelli appear on the vertical and one on the frontal plate[FBbt]. The multi-tissue structure that is located on the top of the head, composed of the corneal lens, pigment cell, rhabdoms and synaptic plexus[HAO]. Two evolutionary distinct ocellus types exist [2]: dorsal ocelli (or simply 'ocelli'), found in most insects, and lateral ocelli (or stemmata), which are found in the larvae of some insect orders. They are structurally and functionally very different. Simple eyes of other animals, e.g. cnidarians may also be referred to as 'ocelli', but again the structure and anatomy of these eyes is quite distinct from those of the dorsal ocelli of insects[Wikipedia].

name: urinary bladder urothelium
description: The epithelial lining of the luminal space of the urinary bladder.

name: endolymphatic duct
description: the small membranous canal, connecting with both saccule and utricle of the membranous labyrinth, passing through the aqueduct of vestibule, and terminating in the endolymphatic sac

name: withers
description: The ridge between the shoulder blades of a four-legged mammal.

name: musculature of back
description: Any collection of muscles that is part of a back [Automatically generated definition].

name: gustatory organ
description: Any sense organ that functions in (some) detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception of taste (GO:0050912).

name: right extraembryonic umbilical vein
description: A extraembryonic umbilical vein that is in_the_right_side_of a multicellular organism.

name: dorsal longitudinal vein
description: Vessel that connects to the primitive hindbrain channel and the basilar artery at the caudal end of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: retrosplenial region
description: The retrosplenial region is a brain area and part of the cingulate cortex. It is defined by Brodmann area 26, Brodmann area 29 and the Brodmann area 30.

name: internal anterior process of basipterygium
description: Process that is bony and arises from anteromedial corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.

name: manual digit 1 metacarpus cartilage element
description: A manual digit metacarpus cartilage element that is part of a manual digit 1 mesenchyme.

name: subdivision of skeletal system
description: Anatomical cluster consisting of the skeletal elements and articular elements that are part of an individual subdivision of the organism.

name: tonsillar ring
description: the circular lymphoid tissue formed by the lingual, pharyngeal, and facial tonsils

name: diaphragmaticus muscle
description: A skeletal muscle found in crocodilians that is analogous to the diaphragm of mammals

name: muscle layer of esophagus
description: A muscle layer that is part of a wall of esophagus.

name: bregma
description: The bregma is the anatomical point on the skull at which the coronal suture is intersected perpendicularly by the sagittal suture.

name: cranial nerve nucleus
description: Nucleus that receives projections from or contains neurons that send projections through one of the cranial nerves

name: postganglionic parasympathetic fiber
description: A cholinergic axonal fiber projecting from a parasympathetic ganglion to an effector organ

name: epithelium of conjunctiva
description: Layer of nonkeratinized squamous epithelium lining the conjunctiva, overlying scleral tissue

name: ligamentum venosum
description: The ligamentum venosum is the fibrous remnant of the ductus venosus of the fetal circulation. Usually, it is attached to the left branch of the portal vein within the porta hepatis (gateway to the liver). It may be continuous with the round ligament of liver (ligamentum teres hepatis). It is invested by the peritoneal folds of the lesser omentum within a fissure on the inferior surface of the liver between the caudate and main parts of the left lobe.

name: surface of cartilage
description: A anatomical surface that is part of a cartilage element.

name: mesonephric nephron epithelium
description: The mesonephric nephron epithelium is a tissue that covers the surface of a nephron in the mesonephros[GO].

name: epithelial cord
description: A cord of epithelial cells without a lumen and usually several cells thick.

name: hemolymphoid system
description: Anatomical cluster consisting of the hematopoietic system and the lymphoid system, or its analogs.

name: remnant of urachus
description: The median umbilical ligament is a structure in human anatomy. It is a shrivelled piece of tissue that represents the remnant of the embryonic urachus. It extends from the apex of the bladder to the umbilicus, on the deep surface of the anterior abdominal wall. It is unpaired. It is covered by the median umbilical fold Lateral to this structure are the medial umbilical ligament (which is a different structure, not to be confused) and the lateral umbilical ligament.

name: spinal cord neural crest
description: A neural crest that has_potential_to_developmentally_contribute_to a spinal cord.

name: basal ganglion
description: An individual member of a collection of basal ganglia. Basal ganglia are subcortical masses of gray matter in the forebrain and midbrain that are richly interconnected and so viewed as a functional system. The nuclei usually included are the caudate nucleus (caudoputamen in rodents), putamen, globus pallidus, substantia nigra (pars compacta and pars reticulata) and the subthalamic nucleus. Some also include the nucleus accumbens and ventral pallidum[NIF,modified].

name: central figure of scute
description: Anatomical structure consisting of a pattern of ridges on an osteoderm.

name: mucosa of lacrimal canaliculus
description: A mucosa that is part of a lacrimal canaliculus [Automatically generated definition].

name: premaxilla
description: One of the bones of the upper jaw situated between and in front of the maxillae[VHOG].

name: planum triangulare
description: Cartilaginous, distal expansion of the lamina orbitonasalis that invests the pars facialis of the maxilla medially.

name: bursal plica
description: Follicle containing part of bursa of Fabricius. The luminal (interior) surface of the bursa is plicated with as many as 15 primary and 7 secondary plicae or folds. These plicae have hundreds of bursal follicles containing follicle-associated epithelial cells, lymphocytes, macrophages, and plasma cells. Lymphoid stem cells migrate from the fetal liver to the bursa during ontogeny. In the bursa, these stem cells acquire the characteristics of mature, immunocompetent B cells[WP].

name: urachus
description: A fibrous remnant of the allantoic stalk, a narrow fetal canal connecting the apex of the urinary bladder with the umbilicus located in the space of Retzius, between the transversalis fascia anteriorly and the peritoneum posteriorly. its lumen is normally obliterated during development, transforming the urachus into a solid cord, a functionless remnant that persists throughout life as the median umbilical ligament; failure of complete lumen obliteration may result in distinct congenital urachal remnant anomalies[MP].

name: obsolete larval structure
description: Anatomical structure that is part of the larva.

name: obsolete larval structure
description: Anatomical structure that is part of the larva.

name: mediastinum
description: The central part of the thoracic cavity enclosed by the left and right pleurae.

name: mandibular arch neural crest
description: Anterior most migratory stream of cranial neural crest.

name: cavum principale
description: The largest part of the nasal cavity, containing the olfactory epithelium.

name: obsolete regional part of deep cerebellar nuclear complex
left ovary
description: An ovary that is part of a left side of organism [Automatically generated definition].

name: rostral migratory stream
description: Unique telencephalic subventricular zones that extend from the lateral ventricles into the olfactory bulbs. Newly produced GABAergic interneurons migrate along the RMS and settle in the bulb.

name: blastema of regenerating fin/limb
description: A blastema that is part of a regenerating fin/limb.

name: obsolete goblet cell
description: A mucous surface cell type known in tadpoles of Xenopus.

name: endocardium of auricle
description: An endocardium that is part of a atrium auricular region.

name: dorsolateral prefrontal cortex layer 2
description: Layer 2 of neocortex lying just deep to superficial layer 1 of dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.

name: pectoral appendage skeleton
description: Skeletal subdivision consisting of the anterior appendicular limb skeleton, excluding the pectoral girdle.

name: amniotic fold
description: A sheet of somatopleure that grows upward over the embryo and eventually meets in the midline enclosing the embryo, eventually giving rise to the amnion and chorion[Kardong].

name: camptotrichium
description: Fin ray found in dipnoans that are composed of a superficial region of acellular fibrous bone, and a deep, mostly unmineralized, zone (G√©raudie and Meunier 1982)

name: hypurapophysis
description: Lateral process, spine-like or crest-like, at the lateral wall of the haemal arch of the parhypural that serves for insertion of the hypochordal longitudinal muscle. The process may contribute to the lateral protection of the parhypural foramen (where the caudal blood vessels exit the hemal arch) and the hypural foramen (where a caudal heart may be present). The hypurapophysis is paired.

name: communicating branch of spinal nerve
description: Rami communicans (plural rami communicantes) is the term used for a nerve which connects two other nerves. When used without further definition, it almost always refers to a communicating branch between a spinal nerve and the sympathetic trunk. More specifically, it usually refers to one of the following: Gray ramus communicans White ramus communicans

name: lumen of midgut
description: An anatomical cavity that surrounded_by a midgut.

name: pharyngeal arch 1
description: The first of the series of pharyngeal arches that develop into jaw bones or their homologs, and their associated nerves and arteries

name: coagulating gland
description: A lobe of the prostate in rodents that is thin and tubular and is attached to the lesser curvature of the paired seminal vesicles. Secretes substances that contribute to the formation of the copulatory plug.

name: olfactory bulb mitral cell layer
description: The mitral cell layer is composed of pyramidal neurons whose cell bodies are located between the granule cell layer and the plexiform layer

name: larval sense organ
description: Any sense organ that is part of some larva.

name: proximal epiphysis of radius
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a radius [Automatically generated definition].

name: compound cell cluster organ
description: An anatomical structure consisting of multiple cell cluster organs, that has a largely bona-fide boundary and that does not contain portions of tissue.

name: blood vessel smooth muscle
description: smooth muscle found within, and composing the majority of the wall of blood vessels.

name: distal tarsal bone 1
description: Endochondral tarsal bone articulating with centralia and metatarsal 1.

name: epithelium of stomach
description: The epithelial layer of the stomach .

name: magnocellular part of red nucleus
description: The magnocellular red nucleus (RNm) is located in the rostral midbrain and is involved in motor coordination. Together with the parvocellular red nucleus, it makes up the red nucleus.

name: jaw region
description: A subdivision of the head that corresponds to the jaw skeleton, containing both soft tissue, skeleton and teeth (when present). The jaw region is divided into upper and lower regions.

name: precaudal vertebra
description: Vertebral bone lacking hemal spines (Weitzman, 1962), refers generally to the anterior vertebral region bounding the abdominal cavity. Alternate but not quite synonymous terms are abdominal or trunk vertebrae, which bear parapophyses and ribs. In many actinopterygians dorsal to the posterior abdominal cavity there are transitional vertebrae lacking ribs but also without hemal spines or sometimes even enclosed hemal arches. The primary definition would identify these vertebrae as precaudal. Bird and Mabee, 2003.

name: obsolete basihyal
description: Paired, anterior element that articulates medially with basibranchial I and posterolaterally with the paired hypohyals.

name: dorsal interosseous of manus
description: The dorsal interossei of the hand are muscles that occupy the space between the metacarpals. There are four dorsal interossei in each hand. They are specified as 'dorsal' to contrast them with the palmar interossei, which are located on the anterior side of the metacarpals. The dorsal interosseous muscles are bipennate, with each muscle arising by two heads from the adjacent sides of the metacarpal bones, but more extensively from the metacarpal bone of the finger into which the muscle is inserted. They are inserted into the bases of the proximal phalanges and into the extensor expansion of the corresponding extensor digitorum tendon. The middle digit has two dorsal interossei insert onto it while the first digit (thumb) and the fifth digit (little finger) have none[WP].

name: post-anal tail tip
description: The distal end of the tail

name: orbitosphenoid-prootic joint
description: Joint that articulates orbitosphenoid and prootic bones. Orbitosphenoid-prootic joint is paired.

name: dense irregular connective tissue
description: Irregular connective tissue is an irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a dense irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. Examples: connective tissue of peritoneum, connective tissue of fibrous pericardium.

name: postsubiculum
description: Division of subicular cortex characterized by projections from the anterodorsal thalamic nucleus and to a lesser extent the anteroventral nucleus, bordered ventrally and laterally by the presubiculum and dorsally and medially by the retrosplenial granular a cortex.. The border is characterized by an abrupt change in the cyto- and chemoarchitecture

name: patagialis muscle
description: A muscle of the patagium that attaches to the clavicle and the metacarpal

name: commissura rostral, pars ventralis
description: Part of the anterior commissure which abuts the preoptic region dorsally.

name: dorsal hypohyal-ventral hypohyal joint
description: Joint that articulates the dorsal hypohyal and ventral hypohyal bones. Dorsal hypohyal-ventral hypohyal joint is paired.

name: obsolete regional part of ventral cochlear nucleus
skin of upper lip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a upper lip.

name: oculomotor muscle
