description: Large synaptic bouton found in areas like olfactory bulb, cerebellar cortex and thalamus, that contacts many post-synaptic targets[NIF].

name: supraacetabular rim
description: Bony rim that is part of the supraacetabular region.

name: corticospinal tract
description: The corticospinal fibers that arise from the pyramidal cells within the cerebral cortex layer V of the precentral motor area, the premotor area and the postcentral gyrus, then descend into and through the medulla to form the lateral corticospinal tract and the anterior corticospinal tract.

name: apophysis distalis of tibiofibula
description: Swelling on the extensor surface of the distal head of the tibiofibula.

name: cleidobrachialis muscle
description: This muscle makes up the distal segment of the brachiocephalicus. It originates at the clavicular tendon but functionally, from the head and neck through the cleidocervicalis. It inserts at the distal end of the cranial border of the humerus, where it lies between the biceps brachii medially and the brachialis laterally. The muscle partly covers the pectoral muscles at their insertions. In conjunction with the cleidocervicalis, it advances the limb, extends the shoulder and causes lateral movement of the head and neck.

name: trigeminofacial foramen
description: Foramen through which branches of cranial nerves V (trigeminal) and VII (facial) exit.

name: nucal keel
description: Longitudinal process found in all cervical vertebrae, except the atlas, for the attachment of dorsal head musculature.

name: Hatschek's left diverticulum
description: A Hatschek's diverticulum that is in the left side of a multicellular organism.

name: regeneration epithelium of fin/limb
description: A epithelium that is part of a regenerating fin/limb.

name: central pretectal nucleus
description: Any nucleus found in the central pretectum.

name: ureter smooth muscle
description: The smooth muscle tissue surrounding the epithelium of the ureter

name: sternite
description: An adult ventral sclerite.

name: lateral ethmoid wing
description: Superficial and lateral bony projection anterior to orbital region. Sometimes with superficial ornamentation where in direct contact with skin.

name: lamina of gray matter of spinal cord
sacral region of vertebral column
description: Subdivision of vertebral column that corresponds to the sacral subdivision of the body, containing the sacral vertebrae or sacrum.

name: meninx of diencephalon
description: A meninx that is part of a diencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: peripharyngeal space
description: The space filled with loose areolar tissue surrounding the pharynx; it is divided into two major divisions, the parapharyngeal space and the retropharyngeal space.

name: metacarpophalangeal joint of manual digit 1
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 1.

name: submucosa of lobar bronchus
description: A submucosa that is part of a lobar bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: anterior auricular lymph node
description: The preauricular deep parotid lymph nodes (anterior auricular glands or preauricular glands), from one to three in number, lie immediately in front of the tragus. Their afferents drain the lateral surface of the auricula and the skin of the adjacent part of the temporal region; their efferents pass to the superior deep cervical glands.

name: larval prothoracic segment
description: Any prothoracic segment (UBERON:6000017) that is part of some larval thorax (UBERON:6001741).

name: inferior eyelid tarsus
description: An eyelid tarsus that is part of a lower eyelid [Automatically generated definition].

name: lunge feeding organ
description: A fibrous capsule located between the jaws of rorqual whales that contains a gelatinous substance and papillae bearing mechanorecaptors.

name: dental lamina
description: A band of ectodermal cells growing from the epithelium of the embryonic jaws into the underlying mesenchyme and giving rise to the primordia of the enamel organs of the teeth.

name: tarsometatarsus endochondral element
description: A tarsometatarsus bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: sphenoid bone pterygoid process
description: the process projecting downward from either side of the sphenoid bone, in vertebrates divided into two plates, an inner and an outer (sometimes called the lateral and medial); the posterior nares pass through the space, called the pterygoid fossa, between the processes

name: scala tympani
description: the division of the spiral canal of the cochlea lying on the basal side of the spiral lamina

name: obsolete regional part of cochlear duct
incus bone
description: The incus or anvil is the anvil-shaped small bone or ossicle in the middle ear. It connects the malleus to the stapes. It was first described by Alessandro Achillin of Bologna. The incus transmits sound vibrations from the malleus to the stapes. The incus only exists in mammals, and is derived from a reptilian upper jaw bone, the quadrate bone. Embryologically it is derived from the first pharyngeal arch along with the rest of the bones of mastication, such as the maxilla and mandible. [WP,unvetted].

name: posterior inferior iliac spine
description: The posterior border of the ala, shorter than the anterior, also presents two projections separated by a notch, the posterior superior iliac spine and the posterior inferior iliac spine. The posterior inferior iliac spine corresponds with the posterior extremity of the auricular surface.

name: hard palate
description: Anterior portion of the palate consisting of bone and mucous membranes[GO]. The hard palate is formed from bony processes of the maxilla, premaxilla and palatine[Kardong].

name: M. pyriformis
description: Originates on the dorso-lateral border of the distal urostyle and inserts on the dorsal surface of the crista femoris. This muscle inserts between the M. ilio-fibularis/M. glutaeus magnus and M. semimembranosus.

name: prefrontal bone
description: A bone separating the lacrimal and frontal bones in many tetrapod skulls

name: gill filament
description: Portion of tissue that projects outward from the gill and is a thread-like, soft, red respiratory and excretory structure.

name: endothelium of capillary
description: An endothelium that is part of a capillary [Automatically generated definition].

name: external anterior process of basipterygium
description: Process that is bony and arises from anterolateral corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.

name: manual digit 5 metacarpus cartilage element
description: A manual digit metacarpus cartilage element that is part of a manual digit 5 mesenchyme.

name: male reproductive system
description: The organs associated with producing offspring in the gender that produces spermatozoa.

name: buccal salivary gland
description: A salivary gland that is part of a cheek.

name: laryngeal cartilage
description: The cartilaginous structures that support the larynx.

name: spleen marginal sinus
description: The border region surrounding the spleen B cell follicles and the periarteriolar lymphoid sheath that separates it from the marginal zone that mediates lymphocyte entry into the white pulp from the blood

name: pontocerebellar tract
description: the second order neuron fibers of the corticopontocerebellar tracts that cross to the other side of the pons and run within the middle cerebellar peduncles, from the pons to the contralateral cerebellum.

name: calcaneum pre-cartilage condensation
description: A calcaneum endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: pneumatized bone
description: A bone that is hollow or contains many air cells, such as the mastoid process of the temporal bone[TMD].

name: lymph sac of lymph heart
description: An extensive dorsal subcutaneous sac that opens into a lymph heart.

name: caudal-fin organ
description: Organ that consists of a pouch located on the ventral caudal-fin lobe, opening posteriorly, and composed of glandular tissue. The caudal-fin organ presumably functions to secrete pheromones during courtship.

name: vasculature of central nervous system plus retina
buccal epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a buccal mucosa.

name: dorsal fin musculature
description: Musculature that is part of the dorsal fin.

name: digit 3 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 3 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: tracheal primordium
description: Primordium of a single tracheal metamere of the embryonic/larval tracheal system from its appearance as a placode during stage 11 to the completion of fusion with adjacent tracheal metameres in stage 15/16. There are 10 pairs of tracheal primordia - one pair in each segment from T2 to A8. Each tracheal primordium originates as a slight depression in the lateral ectoderm during stage 10 known as a tracheal placode. During stage 11, these placodes invaginate to form tracheal pits that elongate and branch. These pits close over during stage 13. Fusion of tracheal primordia begins at stage 14 with fusion of the dorsal trunk primordia and is complete by early stage 16.

name: cestode
description: Any of a class (Cestoda) of bilaterally symmetrical flatworms parasitic especially in the intestines of vertebrates.

name: head of femur
description: The hemispheric articular surface at the upper extremity of the thigh bone[Stedman, 26th ed]. The femur head is the highest part of the thigh bone. It is supported by the neck of the femur. The head is globular and forms rather more than a hemisphere, is directed upward, medialward, and a little forward, the greater part of its convexity being above and in front. Its surface is smooth, coated with cartilage in the fresh state, except over an ovoid depression, the fovea capitis femoris, which is situated a little below and behind the center of the head, and gives attachment to the ligament of head of femur. If there is a fracture of the neck of the femur, the blood supply through the ligament becomes crucial. In orthopedic surgery, the head of the femur is important because it can undergo avascular necrosis and consequent osteochondritis dissecans. The head is removed in total hip replacement surgery [WP].

name: oral lamina propria
description: A lamina propria that is part of a mucosa of oral region.

name: parenchyma of central nervous system
description: The functional tissue of the central nervous system consisting of neurons and glial cells.

name: palatine tonsil
description: tonsils on the left and right sides at the back of the throat. one of the mucosa-associated lymphoid tissues (MALT), located at the entrance to the upper respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts to protect the body from the entry of exogenous material through mucosal sites[WP].

name: axillary fat pad
description: A fat pad that is part of a axilla.

name: median eminence of neurohypophysis
description: Elevation on the ventral surface of the brain located at the zone of attachment between the hypothalamic floor and the hypophysis (Butler and Hodos, Comparative Vertebrate Neuroanatomy, 2nd ed., 2005, pg. 446).

name: pars articularis of mandibular arch
description: Posterior end of Meckel's cartilage that forms the articular head of the mandibular arch.

name: upper eyelid mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing upper eyelid [Automatically generated definition].

name: limbic lobe
description: Part of cerebral hemisphere located on the medial surface, forming a ring around the brain stem

name: embryonic/larval head sense organ
description: Any sense organ (UBERON:6005155) that is part of some larval head (UBERON:6001730).

name: sagittal sinus
description: Either the inferior or superior sagittal sinus

name: oral epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of the mouth and lines the oral cavity, typically stratified squamous, and may be para-, ortho- or non- keratinized. Primary barrier between oral environment and deeper tissues

name: interdigital region mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing interdigital region.

name: right atrioventricular canal
description: An atrioventricular canal that is in the right side of a atrioventricular region.

name: laryngeus ventralis
description: A branch of the vagus nerve innervating heart, stomach, and lung muscle.

name: masseteric fossa
description: .The fossa for the masseter. In some therapsids, the coronoid process of the dentary bears a large external depression which accommodates the masseter -- an important muscle in closing and in grinding motions of the jaw.

name: aorta
description: The main trunk of the systemic arterial system that carries blood from the heart to all the organs and other structures of the body, bringing oxygenated blood to all parts of the body in the systemic circulation

name: segmental subdivision of organ system
description: The part of some organism that is part of some specified segment.

name: nonsynovial joint
description: Joint in which the articulating bones or cartilages are connected by ligaments or fibrocartilage without an intervening synovial cavity. Examples: sagittal suture, inferior tibiofibular syndesmosis, costochondral joint, pubic symphysis.

name: prechordal cartilage
description: Chondrocranium chondrification center that that forms anterior body of sphenoid, containing the sella turcica and posterior body of sphenoid.

name: sublingual dorsal and ventral fused
description: Sublingual that is the single element resulting from the fusion of the sublingual dorsal ossification and sublingual ventral ossification.

name: m. flexor indicis superficialis proprius
description: Originates on the internal border of the distal carpal 5-4-3 and inserts on the distal end of phalynx I.

name: right putamen
description: A putamen that is part of a right cerebral hemisphere.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of midbrain tegmentum
posterior lateral line primordium
description: A migrating group of cells originating from the posterior lateral line placode. The primordium deposits seven to nine neuromasts and interneuromasts between them during its posterior migration to the tail. Gompel et al, 2001.

name: adipose fin skeleton
description: Median fin skeleton supporting the adipose fin.

name: dorsolateral prefrontal cortex layer 6
description: Innermost layer of dorsolateral prefrontal cortex lying deep to the internal pyramidal cell layer 5. It is cytoarchitectonically defined in the DLPFC by cells of varying sizes. DLPFC layer 6a is characterized by more neurons and layer 6b has comparatively more glia.

name: crista of ampulla of lateral semicircular duct of membranous laybrinth
description: A crista ampullaris neuroepithelium that is part of a lateral semicircular duct.

name: cardiac muscle tissue of interatrial septum
description: A portion of cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a interatrial septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: hair follicle bulge
description: The area located in the bottom of the permanent portion of a resting (telogen) hair follicle where the cells of the external root sheath of the hair follicle are contiguous with the basal layer of the epidermis; this portion of the follicle is involved in the generation of a new hair at the onset of the hair growth cycle (anagen) and contains the hair follicle stem cells

name: epithelial vesicle
description: A closed epithelium with a lumen.

name: simplex uterus
description: The simplex uterus has only one uterine chamber (primates)

name: glaucothoe stage
description: A developmental stage in a hermit crab that has completed the swimming larval stages.

name: extraembryonic ectoderm
description: layer of the endoderm of the extraembryonic tissue.

name: depressor labii inferioris
description: A muscle of facial expression, innervated by the facial nerve, attached to the skin of the lower lip, orbicularis oris muscle, and mandible, and superficial and lateral to the mentalis muscle. See Diogo et al., 2009; Burrows et al., 2011)

name: pterygoid plexus
description: The pterygoid plexus is a venous plexus of considerable size, and is situated between the temporalis muscle and lateral pterygoid muscle, and partly between the two pterygoid muscles.

name: obsolete non-terminally differentiated osteoblast
description: Osteoblast that is non-terminally differentiated and located in cellular bone tissue or under the periosteum in acellular bone.

name: medial part of basal amygdaloid nucleus
anterior nuclear group
description: Mostly gray regional part of anterior thalamic region, consisting of the anterior medial, anterior dorsal and anterior lateral thalamic nuclei in primates. In rodents, it consists of anterior medial and anterior ventral divisions, with several subdivisions of each, according to Paxinos (MM: 2006-10-26)

name: proximal epiphysis of phalanx of manual digit 1
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a manual digit 1 phalanx [Automatically generated definition].

name: parietal branch of the supraorbital canal
description: Branch of supraorbital sensory canal that extends to the parietal.

name: snake venom
description: Solutions or mixtures of toxic and nontoxic substances elaborated by snake (Ophidia) salivary glands for the purpose of killing prey or disabling predators and delivered by grooved or hollow fangs. They usually contain enzymes, toxins, and other factors.

name: prostate luminal epithelium
description: A luminal layer of epithelium that is part of a prostate gland.

name: face
description: A subdivision of the head that has as parts the layers deep to the surface of the anterior surface, including the mouth, eyes, and nose (when present). In vertebrates, this includes the facial skeleton and structures superficial to the facial skeleton (cheeks, mouth, eyeballs, skin of face, etc).

name: vagus nerve nucleus
description: A cranial nerve nucleus that is associated with a vagus nerve.

name: lenticular process of incus bone
description: The long ventral process of the incus bone which articulates with the stapes

name: pulmonary venous system
description: The part of the venous system that drains the lungs[Kardong]

name: biceps brachii
description: A muscle in the forelimb stylopod which in humans has several functions, the most important being to rotate the forearm and to flex the elbow. [WP,unvetted].

name: epicentral bone
description: Intermuscular bone that articulates with the vertebral centrum.

name: vestibular gland
description: Lobular organ the parenchyma of which consists of glandular acini which communicate with the vestibule of vagina. Examples: right vestibular gland, lesser vestibular gland.

name: obsolete marginal blastomere
description: Cells (incompletely cleaved before the YSL forms), located at the surface just at the rim of the blastodisc, external to the deep blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint
description: Joint that articulates the epihyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.

name: Brodmann (1909) area 47
description: Brodmann area 47, or BA47, is part of the frontal cortex in the human brain. Curving from the lateral surface of the frontal lobe into the ventral (orbital) frontal cortex. It is below areas BA10 and BA45, and beside BA11. This area is also known as orbital area 47. In the human, on the orbital surface it surrounds the caudal portion of the orbital sulcus (H) from which it extends laterally into the orbital part of inferior frontal gyrus (H). Cytoarchitectonically it is bounded caudally by the triangular area 45, medially by the prefrontal area 11 of Brodmann-1909, and rostrally by the frontopolar area 10 (Brodmann-1909). It incorporates the region that Brodmann identified as 'Area 12' in the monkey, and therefore, following the suggestion of Michael Petrides, some contemporary neuroscientists refer to the region as 'BA47/12. ' BA47 has been implicated in the processing of syntax in spoken and signed languages, and more recently in musical syntax.

name: intraramal joint
description: A joint in the lower jaw that enhances kinesis and for swallowing prey. Allows enhanced mobility and intraramal bending to increase gape.

name: mediastinum testis
description: The mediastinum testis is a network of fibrous connective tissue that extends from the upper to near the lower extremity of the testis, and is wider above than below. From its front and sides numerous imperfect septa (trabecul√¶) are given off, which radiate toward the surface of the organ, and are attached to the tunica albuginea. They divide the interior of the organ into a number of incomplete spaces, called lobules. These are somewhat cone-shaped, being broad at their bases at the surface of the gland, and becoming narrower as they converge to the mediastinum. The mediastinum supports the rete testis and blood vessels of the testis in their passage to and from the substance of the gland[WP]

name: posterior incudal ligament
description: A fold of mucous membrane that runs from the fossa incudus to the incus.

name: postcranial axial skeleton
description: The postcranial subdivision of skeleton structural components forming the long axis of the vertebrate body; in Danio, consisting of the notochord, vertebrae, ribs, supraneurals, intermuscular bones, and unpaired median fins; in human consists of the bones of the vertebral column, the thoracic cage and the pelvis[ZFA+FMA].

name: skin secretion
description: A portion of organism substance that secreted_by a zone of skin.

name: dorsal part of optic cup
description: The dorsal region of the optic cup that gives rise to the dorsal part of the retina.

name: elbow connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a elbow [Automatically generated definition].

name: late distal convoluted tubule
description: The late distal convoluted tubule contains DCT cells and intercalated (IC) alpha and beta cells and is vasopressin-sensitive[GO].

name: mesentery of jejunum
description: A mesentery that is part of a jejunum [Automatically generated definition].

name: parvocellular oculomotor nucleus
description: Nucleus that is part of the oculomotor nerve complex consisting of preganglionic parasympathetic neurons situated close to the midline at the level of the superior colliculus (Heimer, the Human Brain and Spinal Cord, 1994, pg 244)

name: septal olfactory organ
description: A spatially segregated cluster of sensory cells in the nasal cavity.

name: fenestra endonarina communis
description: Opening on the anterolateral aspect of the nasal capsule. It contains the apertura nasalis externa.

name: distal carpal cartilage element
description: A distal carpal endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: tail intervertebral disc
description: An intervertebral disk that is part of a tail [Automatically generated definition].

name: preopercle horizontal limb-symplectic joint
description: Joint that articulates the posterior edge of the preopercle horizontal limb with the symplectic.

name: great vessel of heart
description: Great vessels is a term used to refer collectively to the large vessels that bring blood to and from the heart.

name: atypical epithelium
description: Epithelium that consists of epithelial cells not arranged in one ore more layers.

name: pulmonary vein
description: Pulmonary veins are blood vessels that transport blood from the lungs to the heart[GO].

name: navicular bursa of manus
description: A navicular bursa that is part of a manus.

name: basicranial fenestra
description: Ventral opening of the neurocranium.

name: manual digit 2 mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing manual digit 2.

name: transverse process of caudal vertebra
description: A transverse process that is part of a caudal vertebra

name: late embryonic stage
description: An embryo stage that covers late steps of the embryogenesis with a fully formed embryo still developing before birth or egg hatching.

name: obsolete central nervous system plus retina
rhombomere 1 lateral wall
description: A rhombomere lateral wall that is part of a rhombomere 1.

name: medial superior olivary nucleus
description: One of two subnuclei of the superior olive located within the caudal pontine tegmentum. Appears as a parasagittal row of transversely oriented bipolar neurons in transverse sections of human, with elongated somata in humans and other primates and large caliber dendrites.

name: root of nail
description: The part of the nail plate that extends into the dermis (nail matrix)

name: proximal tubule
description: In mammals, the proximal tubule is a nephron tubule that connects Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle. It has a brush border epithelial morphology[GO].

name: gustatory epithelium of palate
description: A gustatory epithelium that is part of a roof of mouth.

name: biliary tree
description: A complex network of conduits that begins with the canals of Hering (intralobar bile duct) and progressively merges into a system of interlobular, septal, and major ducts which then coalesce to form the extrahepatic bile ducts, which finally deliver bile to the intestine, and in some species to the gallbladder.

name: medial nucleus of trapezoid body
description: Nucleus in the pontine tegmentum of most mammals that receives projections from the ventral cochlear nucleus via the large specialized synapse, the Calyx of Held. It is not clear whether a well defined nucleus is present in humans, although humans may possess scattered cells with similar input.

name: trunk armor pectoral fenestra
description: An opening in the dermal armour of basal gnathostomes that encloses the pectoral fins. (modified from Young 2010).

name: spinous region of dorsal fin
description: Region of dorsal fin that is composed of spinous rays (vs soft rays). [PHENOSCAPE:LJ]

name: posterior parahippocampal gyrus
description: The posterior parahippocampal gyrus is a portion of the parahippocampal gyrus. It can show deterioration in Alzheimer's disease.

name: secondary chorionic villus
description: A chorionic villus that is has a core of loose connective tissue, which in humans grows into the primary villi about the third week of development.

name: posterior cartilage of palatine
description: posterior cartilage of palatine - cartilage that caps the posterior end of the autopalatine bone. It is typically present in adults.

name: esophageal process
description: Median process located on the posterior end of the cricoid cartilage.

name: proximal phalanx of digit 4
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a autopod digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: cerebellum posterior vermis
description: The posterior portion of the narrow middle zone between the two hemispheres of the cerebellum that is located posterior to the primary fissure

name: renal pelvis
description: A funnel shaped proximal portion of the ureter that is formed by convergence of the major calices [MP].

name: primordium
description: Primordia are populations of contiguous cells that are morphologically distinct and already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue[FBbt, Hartenstein, V. (2004)].

name: suprascapula foramen
description: The route through which structures pass between the base of the neck and the posterior scapular region. It is formed by the suprascapular notch of the scapula and the superior transverse scapular ligament. From http://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/suprascapular+foramen

name: caput ossis cruris
description: Proximal head of the tibiofibula that articulates with the distal head of the femur.

name: auditory foramen
description: Foramen through which cranial nerve VIII (auditory) exits.

name: Hatschek's right diverticulum
description: A Hatschek's diverticulum that is in the right side of a multicellular organism.

name: accessory pretectal nucleus
description: Diencephalic nucleus that is part of the central pretectum and lies dorsolateral to the caudal pretectal nucleus. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

name: trunk sensory canal
description: Sensory canal on trunk which is posterior to the pectoral girdle and often reaching to or onto the caudal fin. The trunk sensory canal is bilaterally paired.

name: caudal region of vertebral column
description: Subdivision of vertebral column that corresponds to the caudal subdivision of the body, containing the caudal vertebrae.

name: meninx of hindbrain
description: A meninx that is part of a hindbrain [Automatically generated definition].

name: insect embryonic/larval brain
description: Brain of the embryo/larva.

name: submucosa of segmental bronchus
description: A submucosa that is part of a segmental bronchus [Automatically generated definition].

name: infra-auricular lymph node
description: The infra-auricular deep parotid lymph nodes are a group of lymph nodes found underneath the ear.

name: larval mesothoracic segment
description: Any mesothoracic segment (UBERON:6000018) that is part of some larval thorax (UBERON:6001741).

name: outer renal medulla vasa recta
description: A vasa recta that is part of a outer medulla of kidney [Automatically generated definition].

name: middle cervical ganglion
description: the small ganglion located at the level of the cricoid cartilage of the laryngeal wall

name: funiculus of spinal cord
description: A funiculus of neuraxis that is part of a spinal cord.

name: mucosa of anal canal
description: A mucosa that is part of an anal canal [Automatically generated definition].

name: hair of head
description: A strand of hair that is part of a head.

name: urinary bladder detrusor smooth muscle
description: bundles of smooth muscle fibers forming the muscular wall of the urinary bladder, which are arranged in a longitudinal and a circular layer and, on contraction, serve to expel urine[MP].

name: crypt of Lieberkuhn of colon
description: An intestinal crypt that is located in the colon. The colonic crypts of Lieberk√ºhn are straight and unbranched and lined largely with goblet cells.

name: fibula endochondral element
description: The major postaxial endochondral element in the posterior zeugopod[Phenoscape].

name: malleus bone
description: The malleus or hammer is a hammer-shaped small bone or ossicle of the middle ear which connects with the incus and is attached to the inner surface of the eardrum. The word is Latin for hammer. It transmits the sound vibrations from the eardrum to the incus. The malleus is unique to mammals, and evolved from a lower jaw bone in basal amniotes called the articular, which still forms part of the jaw joint in reptiles. Embryologically it is derived from the first pharyngeal arch along with the rest of the bones of mastication, such as the maxilla and mandible. [WP,unvetted].

name: neural lobe of neurohypophysis
description: The posterior pituitary (or neurohypophysis) comprises the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland and is part of the endocrine system. Despite its name, the posterior pituitary gland is not a gland, per se; rather, it is largely a collection of axonal projections from the hypothalamus that terminate behind the anterior pituitary gland. [WP,unvetted].

name: endopeduncular nucleus
description: A portion of the nucleus of ansa lenticularis located medial to the posterior limb of the internal capsule, along the course of the ansa lenticularis and the inferior thalamic peduncle or as a separate nucleus within the internal capsule adjacent to the medial GLOBUS PALLIDUS (NeuroNames, http://rprcsgi.rprc. washington.edu/neuronames/ (September 28, 1998)). In non-primates, the entopeduncular nucleus is analogous to both the medial globus pallidus and the entopeduncular nucleus of human.

name: centrale 2
description: The proximal-most rectangular cartilage or bone when two centralelia are present.

name: supraintestinal artery
description: A continuation of the anterior mesenteric artery, which branches out from the dorsal aorta just caudal to the pronephric glomus. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: squamous part of temporal bone primordium
vomeronasal nerve
description: Nerve carrying fibers from the vomeronasal organ epithelium to the accessory olfactory bulb.

name: endothelium of arteriole
description: An endothelium that is part of an arteriole [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal cartilage of external anterior process of basipterygium
description: Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of external anterior process of basipterygium.

name: manual digit 1 phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit 1 mesenchyme.

name: suspensory ligament of breast
description: Cooper's ligaments (also known as the suspensory ligaments of Cooper and the fibrocollagenous septa) are connective tissue in the breast that helps maintain structural integrity. Transmission diffraction tomography can reveal the anatomy. Cooper's Suspensory Ligament should not be confused with the pectineal ligament (sometimes called the inguinal ligament of Cooper) which shares the same eponym.

name: obsolete secondary spermatogonium
description: A type of germ cell that results from the mitotic division of a primary spermatogonium.

name: interdigital space
description: The space between the digits of the hand or foot.

name: spleen trabecular artery
description: one of the branches of the splenic artery[MP]

name: hypaxial region somite 28
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: tibiotarsus
description: The tibiotarsus is the large bone between the femur and the tarsometatarsus in the leg of a bird. It is the fusion of the proximal part of the tarsus with the tibia. A similar structure also occurred in the Mesozoic Heterodontosauridae. These small ornithischian dinosaurs were unrelated to birds and the similarity of their pes bones is best explained by convergent evolution.

name: superior longitudinal fasciculus
description: The superior longitudinal fasciculus (also called the superior longitudinal fascicle or SLF) is a pair of long bi-directional bundles of neurons connecting the front and the back of the cerebrum. Each association fiber bundle is lateral to the centrum ovale of a cerebral hemisphere and connects the frontal, occipital, parietal, and temporal lobes. The neurons pass from the frontal lobe through the operculum to the posterior end of the lateral sulcus where numerous neurons radiate into the occipital lobe and other neurons turn downward and forward around the putamen and radiate to anterior portions of the temporal lobe.

name: caudal-fin ray pump
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of thickened caudal-fin rays modified into a pumping mechanism associated with the caudal-fin organ.

name: pennate muscle
description: A pennate muscle (also called a penniform muscle) is a muscle with fascicles that attach obliquely (in a slanting position) to its tendon. These types of muscles generally allow better stabilization and force production but less flexibility. Individual muscle fibers are formed into bundles of fasciculi and these bundles of fasciculi are formed into bundles of fascicles which compose the entire muscle itself. In a pennate muscle, the fascicles will form an angle with its central tendon. If all the fascicles are on the same side of the tendon, the pennate muscle is called unipennate. Examples of this include certain muscles in the manus. If there are fascicles on both sides of the central tendon, the pennate muscle is called bipennate. The rectus femoris, a large muscle in the quadriceps, is typical. If the central tendon branches within a pennate muscle, the muscle is called multipennate, as seen in the deltoid muscle in the shoulder.

name: left vitelline vein
description: A vitelline vein that is in the left side of a multicellular organism.

name: digit 4 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 4 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: cercaria
description: A usually tadpole-shaped larval trematode worm that develops in a molluscan host from a redia.

name: rhombomere 4
description: the fourth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

name: chorioallantoic membrane
description: The chorioallantoic membrane is a vascular membrane found in eggs of some amniotes, such as birds and reptiles. It is formed by the fusion of the mesodermal layers of two developmental structures: the allantois and the chorion. Three different layers compose the chorioallantoic membrane; these are called the chorionic epithelium, the mesenchyme and the allantoic epithelium. Blood capillaries and sinuses are found between epithelial cells of the chorionic layer, allowing close contact (within 0.2 N<m) with air found in pores of the shell membrane of the egg. As a result, the chorioallantoic membrane allows exchange of gases, such as oxygen, to developing embryos. During embryonic development of birds, the chorioallantoic membrane also plays an essential role in bone formation by transporting calcium into the embryo from the eggshell. Chorioalloantoic membranes from developing chicken eggs are routinely used in biological and biomedical research to investigate development, angiogenesis, tumors, and to propagate and investigate viruses or helminths.

name: metacarpal bone
description: A bone that is part of the metacarpal skeleton.

name: neurohypophysis
description: The posterior part of the pituitary gland that secretes hormones involved in blood pressure regulation such as oxytocin and antidiuretic hormon.

name: suprascapular fossa
description: Fossa on the medial surface on the scapula above the glenoid.

name: lower eyelid mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing lower eyelid [Automatically generated definition].

name: fasciolar gyrus
description: A small paired band that passes around the splenium of the corpus callosum from the lateral longitudinal stria to the dentate gyrus[Biology-Online]. A posterior and upward extension of the dentate gyrus, forming a transitional area between the dentate gyrus and the indusium griseum[BTO].

name: visceral serous pericardium
description: Visceral serous membrane which is continuous with the parietal serous pericardium and is attached to the myocardium[FMA].

name: median artery
description: An artery found in the forearm, between the radial artery and ulnar artery. It runs with the median nerve and supplies the same structures as that nerve. It may be unilateral or bilater

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between manual digits 1 and 2
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between manual digits 1 and 2.

name: sinusoid
description: small blood vessel similar to a capillary but with a fenestrated endothelium. Sinusoids are found in the liver, lymphoid tissue, endocrine organs, and hematopoietic organs such as the bone marrow and the spleen. Sinusoids found within terminal villi of the placenta are not comparable to these; they possess a continuous endothelium and complete basal lamina[WP].

name: obsolete regional part of anterior nucleus of hypothalamus
ramus mandibularis externus
description: Runs together with motor fibers of the hyomandibular trunk of VII. The mandibularis externus of AVLLN branches into three ramules .

name: hyoepiglottic ligament
description: An elastic band connecting the anterior surface of the epiglottis to the upper border of the body of the hyoid bone.

name: cloacal papilla
description: A small, ridge-like projection from the antero-ventral wall of the cloacal chamber.

name: intervertebral cartilage
description: A cartilage element that lies between two successive vertebral centra.

name: pulmonary vascular system
description: The part of the cardiovascular system consisting of all pulmonary arteries and all pulmonary veins.

name: prenasal ossicle
description: Tubular ossifications around extension of nasal lateral line canal in fishes; typically one or two.

name: entire surface of organism
description: Anatomical surface, which is the external surface of the whole body. Examples: There is only one body surface.

name: presumptive hindbrain
description: The rhombencephalon (or hindbrain) is a developmental categorization of portions of the central nervous system in vertebrates. The rhombencephalon can be subdivided in a variable number of transversal swellings called rhombomeres. In the human embryo eight rhombomeres can be distinguished, from caudal to rostral: Rh7-Rh1 and the isthmus (the most rostral rhombomere). A rare disease of the rhombencephalon, 'rhombencephalosynapsis' is characterized by a missing vermis resulting in a fused cerebellum. Patients generally present with cerebellar ataxia. The caudal rhombencephalon has been generally considered as the initiation site for neural tube closure.

name: cardiac muscle tissue of cardiac septum
description: A portion of cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a cardiac septum [Automatically generated definition].

name: hemipenal sheath
description: Soft tissue sheath covering the hemipenis.

name: obsolete regional part of lumbar spinal cord gray matter
prevertebral muscle of neck
description: A prevertebral muscle that is part of a neck.

name: Descemet's membrane
description: A transparent homogeneous acellular layer found between the substantia propria and the endothelial layer of the cornea[MP].

name: buccinator muscle
description: The buccinator is a muscle that is attached to the mandible, skin, pterygomandibular raphe and maxilla, and is innervated by Cranial Nerve VII and participates in oropharyngeal behavior.

name: angular vein
description: The angular vein formed by the junction of the frontal vein and supraorbital vein, runs obliquely downward, on the side of the root of the nose, to the level of the lower margin of the orbit, where it becomes the anterior facial vein. It receives the external nasal veins of the ala nasi, and communicates with the superior ophthalmic vein through the nasofrontal vein, thus establishing an important anastomosis between the anterior facial vein and the cavernous sinus.

name: cellular bone tissue
description: Mineralized bone tissue that always includes non-terminally differentiated osteoblasts and osteocytes.

name: ventral pallium
description: The pallial region located next to the pallium-subpallium boundary.

name: proximal epiphysis of phalanx of manual digit 2
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a manual digit 2 phalanx [Automatically generated definition].

name: basilar artery
description: A major artery that supplues the hindbrain and runs along the ventral keel of the hindbrain.

name: obsolete regional part of basal nuclear complex
replacement tooth row
description: Tooth row consisting of replacement teeth.

name: episcleral layer of eyeball
description: The episclera is the outermost layer of the sclera. It is composed of loose, fibrous, elastic tissue and attaches to Tenon's capsule. A vascular plexus is found between the conjunctiva and the sclera consisting of two layers of vessels, the superficial episcleral vessels and the deep episcleral vessels.

name: skin of eyelid
description: A zone of skin that is part of a eyelid [Automatically generated definition].

name: gyrus
description: A ridge on the cerebral cortex. It is generally surrounded by one or more sulci .

name: dorsal commissural nucleus of spinal cord
description: A continuous column of gray matter along the midline in the dorsal gray commissure that sends fibers to the hypogastric nerve.

name: obsolete commissure of the caudal tuberculum
forelimb wing
description: Forelimb that is used to produce lift for flight through the air.

name: bulb of penis
description: Just before each crus of the penis meets its fellow it presents a slight enlargement, named by Kobelt the bulb of the corpus spongiosum penis. It is homologous to the vestibular bulbs in females.

name: 2nd arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 2nd arch mesenchyme.

name: arch of aorta
description: the convex portion of the aorta between the ascending and descending parts of the aorta; branches from it include the brachiocephalic trunk, the left common carotid artery, and the left subclavian artery; the brachiocephalic trunk further splits to form the right subclavian artery and the right common carotid artery

name: beard
description: The collection of hair that grows on the chin, cheeks and neck of human beings. Usually, only pubescent or adult males are able to grow beards. However, women with hirsutism may develop a beard. When differentiating between upper and lower facial hair, a beard specifically includes the moustache, which refers to hair above the upper lip and around it.

name: recessus lateralis
description: Intracranial space formed by confluence of supraorbital, infraorbital, preopercular and temporal sensory canals. See also Di Dario (2004).

name: areolar gland
description: A sebaceous glands in the areola surrounding the nipple.

name: accessory abducens nucleus
description: A small cluster of neurons in the pontine reticular formation in some mammals, containing the majority of motoneurons innervating thenretractor bulbi muscles of the eye

name: lower deciduous premolar 5
description: Fifth premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.

name: jugal bar
description: elongate bar consisting of fused quadratojugal and jugal and connecting the maxilla to the quadrate

name: gizzard
description: The muscular enlargement of the alimentary canal that has usually thick muscular walls and a tough horny lining for grinding the food and when the crop is present follows it and the proventriculus.

name: malleal ligament
description: A skeletal ligament that attaches to the malleus.

name: appendicular skeleton
description: Subdivision of skeleton which which consists of all the skeletal elements in in the pectoral and pelvic appendage complexes[cjm].

name: male reproductive gland secretion
description: A portion of organism substance that is secreted by a male reproductive gland.

name: ventral part of optic cup
description: The ventral region of the optic cup that gives rise to the ventral part of the retina.

name: wrist connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a wrist [Automatically generated definition].

name: mesonephric epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a mesonephros [Automatically generated definition].

name: pterygopalatine nerve
description: The pharyngeal nerve (pterygopalatine nerve) is a small branch arising from the posterior part of the pterygopalatine ganglion. It passes through the pharyngeal canal with the pharyngeal branch of the maxillary artery, and is distributed to the mucous membrane of the nasal part of the pharynx, behind the auditory tube.

name: pedunculopontine tegmental nucleus
description: The pedunculopontine nucleus (PPN) (or pedunculopontine tegmental nucleus, PPTN) is located in the brainstem, caudal to the substantia nigra and adjacent to the superior cerebellar peduncle. It is composed by a wide variety of neurochemical cell types, including cholinergic, glutamatergic and GABAergic cells. In the classical sense, the PPN is considered to be one of the main components of the reticular activating system. [WP,unvetted].

name: pelvic fin distal radial element
description: Pelvic fin radial element that develops from the pelvic fin endoskeletal disc. Pelvic fin distal radial elements are paired.

name: obsolete regional part of stratum lucidum
septal organ of Masera
description: A small island of olfactory neuroepithelium lying bilaterally at the ventral base of the nasal septum near the entrance of the nasopharynx.

name: hypophyseal fenestra
description: Space enclosed by the trabeculae cranii. The anterior tip of the notochord extends into the posterior region of the hypophyseal fenestra.

name: uterine lumen
description: A organ cavity that is part of a uterus.

name: cavitated compound organ
description: Compound organ that contains one or more macroscopic anatomical spaces.

name: perianal skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of the area surrounding the anus.

name: caudal division of the internal carotid artery
squamous part of occipital bone
description: The squama of the occipital bone, situated above and behind the foramen magnum, is curved from above downward and from side to side.

name: manual digit 3 mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing manual digit 3.

name: perineal body smooth muscle muscle tissue
neonate stage
description: Of or pertaining to the period of time immediately following birth, or to the newborn.

name: upper arm blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a forelimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: superior nasal concha
description: The back part of the medial surface of the labyrinth of ethmoid is subdivided by a narrow oblique fissure, the superior meatus of the nose, bounded above by a thin, curved plate, the superior nasal concha. The bone found in superior nasal concha is part of the ethmoid bone.

name: genital labium
description: One of the folds of skin which form the inner lips (labia minora) and outer lips (labia majora) on both sides of the vaginal opening.

name: bone foramen
description: Anatomical space that is an opening in a bone, usually for passage of blood vessels or nerves.

name: rhombomere 1 roof plate
description: A rhombomere roof plate that is part of a rhombomere 1.

name: distal phalanx of manual digit 2
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 2 [Automatically generated definition].

name: ventral gray commissure of spinal cord
distal tubule
description: The distal tubule is a nephron tubule that consists of the distal convoluted tubule and distal straight tubule segments

name: coccyx
description: A collection of caudal vertebrae in the coccygeal region that are fused and part of the bony pelvis.

name: visceral abdominal adipose tissue
description: Subcutaneous adipose tissue that is located in the peritoneal cavity.

name: common bile duct
description: the part of the biliary tree formed by the union of the cystic duct and the common hepatic duct

name: secondary palatal shelf
description: The outgrowths of the embryonic maxillary prominences that come together during prenatal development to form the secondary palate

name: zygantrum
description: A fossa on the posterior median part of the neural arch of a vertebra (as of a snake) that accommodates the zygosphene of the next vertebra. [PHENOSCAPE:JL]

name: medial lemniscus of midbrain
description: Part of medial lemniscus located within the midbrain

name: tertiary chorionic villus
description: Tertiary chorionic villi contain embryonic blood vessels that develop from mesenchymal cells in the loose connective tissue core. These blood vessels connect up with vessels that develop in the chorion and connecting stalk and begin to circulate embryonic blood about the third week of development in humans.

name: longissimus thoracis muscle
description: The longissimus thoracis is the intermediate and largest of the continuations of the sacrospinalis.[WP]. intermediate erector spinae muscle of back; origin, with iliocostalis and from transverse processes of lower thoracic vertebrae; insertion, by lateral slips into most or all of the ribs between angles and tubercles and into tips of transverse processes of upper lumbar vertebrae, and by medial slips into accessory processes of upper lumbar and transverse processes of thoracic vertebrae; action, extends vertebral column; nerve supply, dorsal primary rami of thoracic and lumbar spinal nerves[Stedmans].

name: pharyngeal opening of pharyngotympanic tube
description: On the lateral wall of the nasal part of the pharynx is the pharyngeal opening of auditory tube (pharyngeal ostium), somewhat triangular in shape, and bounded behind by a firm prominence, the torus or cushion, caused by the medial end of the cartilage of the tube which elevates the mucous membrane.

name: median premaxilla
description: Dermal bone that is located in the middle of the upper jaw, independently formed by fusion of tooth bases attached to soft tissue in the middle portion of the upper lip. The median premaxilla bears teeth in adults.

name: proximal phalanx of digit 5
description: A proximal phalanx that is part of a autopod digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: cortex of kidney
description: Outer cortical portion of the kidney, between the renal capsule and the renal medulla.

name: neural tube
description: In the developing vertebrate, the neural tube is the embryo's precursor to the central nervous system, which comprises the brain and spinal cord. The neural groove gradually deepens as the neural folds become elevated, and ultimately the folds meet and coalesce in the middle line and convert the groove into a closed tube, the neural tube or neural canal (which strictly speaking is the center of the neural tube), the ectodermal wall of which forms the rudiment of the nervous system. [WP,unvetted].

name: synarcual region of vertebral column
description: Series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.

name: sulcus pro musculo extensori cruris brevis
description: Small canal on the proximal head of to the tibiofibula, lateral to the apophysis distalis, for the insertion of the cruris brevis muscle.

name: brachiocephalic muscle
description: The brachiocephalicus is a long and flat, complex of muscles that extends from the lower half of the humeral shaft to the head and neck. The muscle divides into two parts at the clavicular intersection. This is also the point of origin for all the muscles that make up the brachiocephalicus. This point is situated just cranial to the shoulder. The two main sections are the cleidobrachialis which is distal to the clavicular intersection and the cleidocephalicus which extends proximally to the clavivular intersection. The cleidocephalicus can also be divided into the pars cervicalis, which inserts on the broad aponeurosis, over the fibrous raphe of the cranial half of the neck. The other part, the pars mastoideus inserts on the mastoid process of the temporal bone via a strong tendon. The cleidobrachialis extends distally from the clavicular intersection and inserts on the cranial edge of the distal half of the humerus. The tendon that inserts the cleidobrachialis lies between the brachialis muscle and the biceps brachii. As a result of the brachiocephalicus spanning a large region it has the ability to provide a number of actions. These include extending the shoulder joint, protracts the limb, provides lateral movement of the head and allows the neck to be depressed.

name: perichordal tissue
description: Fibrous connective tissue that surrounds the notochord; includes a layer of elastin.

name: embryonic intraretinal space
description: The space separating the outer pigment epithelium and the inner neural retina of the optic cup and of the retina

name: obsolete regional part of spiral organ of Corti
subdivision of vertebral column
description: A collection of all skeletal elements in some subdivision of the vertebral column.

name: meninx of spinal cord
description: A meninx that is part of a spinal cord [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal mesopodial cartilage element
description: A distal mesopodial endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: retropharyngeal space
description: The portion of the peripharyngeal space that is located posterior to the pharynx.

name: submucosa of bronchiole
description: A submucosa that is part of a bronchiole [Automatically generated definition].

name: larval metathoracic segment
description: Any metathoracic segment (UBERON:6000019) that is part of some larval thorax (UBERON:6001741).

name: inner renal medulla vasa recta
description: A vasa recta that is part of a inner medulla of kidney [Automatically generated definition].

name: cervical ganglion
description: The cervical ganglia are paravertebral ganglia of the sympathetic nervous system. They consist of three paravertebral ganglia: superior cervical ganglion middle cervical ganglion inferior cervical ganglion. The inferior ganglion may be fused with the first thoracic ganglion to form a single structure, the stellate ganglion. Nerves emerging from cervical sympathetic ganglia contribute to the cardiac plexus, among other things. [WP,unvetted].

name: mucosa of oral region
description: A mucosa that is part of a oral opening [Automatically generated definition].

name: hair of trunk
description: A strand of hair that is part of a trunk.

name: apocrine sweat gland
description: Apocrine sweat glands are sweat glands composed of a coiled secretory portion located at the junction of the dermis and subcutaneous fat, from which a straight portion inserts and secretes into the infundibular portion of the hair follicle. The ducts of apocrine glands open into the canals of hair follicles. The stimulus for the secretion of apocrine sweat glands is adrenaline, which is a hormone carried in the blood[WP].

name: thyroid gland medulla
description: A medulla that is part of a thyroid [Automatically generated definition].

name: crypt of Lieberkuhn of appendix
description: An intestinal crypt that is located in the appendix.

name: calcaneum endochondral element
description: A calcaneum bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: sebum
description: Fatty lubricant matter secreted by sebaceous glands, and made of made of triglyceride oils, wax, squalene, and metabolytes of fat-producing cells[BTO,WP].

name: ovary septum
description: Septum that divides the ovary, the basal portion of a carpel or group of fused carpels, that encloses the ovule(s)[GO].

name: M. ileo-femoralis
description: Originates from the postero-ventral surface of the ala ossis ilei and from the insertion tendon of M. ileo-fibularis. Inserts along the dorso-medial border of the femur.

name: exoccipital cartilage element
description: A exoccipital endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: adenohypophyseal placode
description: The adenohypophyseal placode forms the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland and gives rise to the endocrine secretory cells of the pituitary

name: endothelium of artery
description: An endothelium that is part of an artery [Automatically generated definition].

name: lateral process of basipterygium
description: Process that is bony and arises from lateral margin of basipterygium lateral to pelvic fin lepidotrichium 1 and projects laterally or anterolaterally.

name: manual digit 2 phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit 2 mesenchyme.

name: sesamoid bone of the peroneus longus muscle
sagulum nucleus
description: A collection of principally small and medium-sized cells in the midbrain tegmentum lying at the margin of the midbrain adjacent to the nuclei of the lateral lemniscus

name: musculus levator bulbi
description: Cranial nerve V innervated; ventral to the eye.

name: hypaxial region somite 30
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: feather covering of ventral part of tail
tarsometatarsus
description: The tarsometatarsus is a bone that is found in the lower leg of certain tetrapods, namely birds. It is formed from the fusion of several bones found in other types of animals, and homologous to the mammalian tarsal (ankle) and metatarsal (pes) bones. Despite this, the tarsometatarsus of birds is often referred to as just the tarsus or metatarsus.

name: myorhabdoid bone
description: Intermuscular bone that is located in the dorsal and ventral forward flexures of the myoseptum.

name: anatomical border
description: An anatomical structure that is located along the line dividing two regions of an anatomical structure.

name: pyloric stomach
description: The mouth of a starfish is located on the underside of the body, and opens through a short esophagus into firstly a cardiac stomach, and then, a second, pyloric stomach. Each arm also contains two pyloric caeca, long hollow tubes branching outwards from the pyloric stomach. Each pyloric caecum is lined by a series of digestive glands, which secrete digestive enzymes and absorb nutrients from the food. A short intestine runs from the upper surface of the pyloric stomach to open at an anus in the center of the upper body

name: digit 5 plus metapodial segment
description: A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit 5 plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.

name: rostral spinocerebellar tract
description: Originates from cells rostral to Clarke's column and sends uncrossed axons through the lateral funiculus to the cerebellum. It reaches the cerebellum partly through the brachium conjunctivum and partly through the restiform body, terminating bilaterally in the anterior lobe of the cerebellum

name: interoceptor
description: A sensory receptor that detects stimulus within the body. Examples of stimuli that would be detected by interoceptors include blood pressure and blood oxygen level.

name: uterine tube infundibulum
description: The funnel-like expansion of the abdominal extremity of the uterine tube[MP]

name: cricoid cartilage
description: A cartilaginous ring that provides support for the arytenoid cartilages and forms the caudal part of the larynx.

name: sphenethmoid
description: Endochondral bone that forms the anterior portion of the braincase and forms from one ossification center on each side of the orbital cartilage.

name: scrotum skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a scrotum.

name: integument
description: The dermis, epidermis and hypodermis.

name: obsolete pars dentalis of maxilla
description: Tooth-bearing part of the maxilla.

name: astragalus-calcaneum unit
description: Osteological unit consisting of the astragalus and calcaneum.

name: forelimb mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing forelimb [Automatically generated definition].

name: emboliform nucleus
description: the small wedge shaped nucleus interposed between the dentate and fastigial nuclei; it receives axons from Purkinje cells of the intermediate area of the cerebral hemispheres and most of its efferent connections travel via the superior cerebellar peduncle

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of red nucleus
chest muscle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a chest [Automatically generated definition].

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between manual digits 2 and 3
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between manual digits 2 and 3.

name: endocrine system
description: Anatomical system that consists of the glands and parts of glands that produce endocrine secretions and help to integrate and control bodily metabolic activity.

name: ligament of vertebral column
description: ligament that joins successive centra. Important in controlling the stiffness of the vertebral column when it flexes.

name: interhyal cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.

name: supradorsal
description: Supradorsals are small paired nodules of cartilage positioned at the distal ends of neural arches and the proximal end of neural spines (Arratia et al., 2001).

name: rectal venous plexus
description: The hemorrhoidal plexus (or rectal venous plexus) surrounds the rectum, and communicates in front with the vesical venous plexus in the male, and the uterovaginal plexus in the female. A free communication between the portal and systemic venous systems is established through the hemorrhoidal plexus.

name: septohippocampal nucleus
description: Part of septal nuclear complex. In the human, it refers to the most caudal of scattered clusters of neurons in the septum pellucidum that extend, on the underside of the corpus callosum, from the level of the medial septal nucleus to the CA fields ( Crosby-1962 ). In the rat it is associated with the lateral septal nucleus throughout its rostro-caudal course toward the CA fields ( Swanson-1998. Adapted from Brain Info.

name: anal fin ray
description: Soft ray that is part of the anal fin.

name: presumptive sinus venosus
description: Portion of tissue that is part of the heart tube and will become the sinus venosus.

name: cardiac muscle tissue of myocardium
description: A portion of cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a myocardium [Automatically generated definition].

name: pronephric duct
description: In mammals, the pronephric duct is the predecessor of the Wolffian duct[WP].

name: cerebellar vermis
description: A subregion of the cerebellar cortex, consisting of the most medial zone of the cerebellar cortex, stradding the midline. May be continuous with the lateral cerebellar hemispheres in some areas of the cerebellum, e.g., dorsally, or separated by deeper fissures in others (e.g., ventrally)

name: radial facet
description: Facet to accommodate the radius on the distal end of the humerus. [PHENOSCAPE:NI]

name: ventral body wall
description: The ventral part of the body wall

name: Reichert's cartilage
description: A continuous cartilaginous formation in mesenchyme of the second pharyngeal arch in the embryo. The longer cranial or styloid segment is continuous with the otic capsule; its inferior end is angulated and is situated very close to the oropharynx. The smaller caudal segment is in contact with the body and greater horn of the hyoid cartilaginous structure

name: extrinsic auricular muscle
description: Auricular muscle attaching the cartilage of the ear to the epicranial aponeurosis. The 3 extrinsic auricular muscles in humans are: anterior auricular muscle superior auricular muscle posterior auricular muscle [WP,modified].

name: sphenoid region
description: Anatomical cluster that forms the floor and sidewalls of the middle part of the cranium.

name: temporal sulcus
description: Any of three grooves in the temporal lobe including the inferior, middle, and superior temporal sulci.

name: non-mineralized avascular GAG-rich matrix
description: Avascular GAG-rich matrix that is not mineralized.

name: nerve plexus
description: Anatomical junction where subdivisions of two or more neural trees interconnect with one another to form a network through which nerve fibers of the constituent nerve trees become regrouped; together with other nerve plexuses, nerves and ganglia, it constitutes the peripheral nervous system. Examples: cervical nerve plexus, brachial nerve plexus, sacral nerve plexus[FMA].

name: haemolymphatic fluid-testis barrier
description: A barrier between the blood or haemolymphatic fluid and the testes.

name: proximal epiphysis of phalanx of manual digit 3
description: A proximal epiphysis that is part of a manual digit 3 phalanx [Automatically generated definition].

name: mesencephalic artery
description: The major artery of the midbrain, which crosses the midbrain medially to meet its partner the mesencephalic vein.

name: left colon
description: The distal portion of the colon; it develops embryonically from the hindgut and functions in the storage and elimination of waste.

name: venom-injecting tooth
description: A fang that is used to inject venom into prey, through either a tube or a groove

name: suprachoroid lamina
description: On the external surface of the optic choroid is a thin membrane, the suprachoroid lamina, composed of delicate non-vascular lamellae-each lamella consisting of a network of fine elastic fibers among which are branched pigment cells.

name: medial pallium
description: Subdivision of pallium that is located is the medial position in vertebrates with an evaginated brain and in the distal position in vertebrates with an everted brain.

name: stomach glandular region
description: A region of the stomach that is lined with glandular epithelium.

name: skin of lip
description: A zone of skin that is part of a lip [Automatically generated definition].

name: endothelial blood brain barrier
description: A blood brain barrier that is composed of endothelial cells.

name: nucleus of spinal cord
description: A neural nucleus that is part of the spinal cord.

name: hypomaxilla
description: Dermal bone bearing teeth located between the distal end of the premaxilla and the middle of the maxilla. The hypomaxilla is a paired bone.

name: head electric organ
description: An electric organ that is part of a head.

name: tube
description: Any hollow cylindrical anatomical structure containing a lumen through which substances are transported.

name: bulb of vestibule
description: Aggregations of erectile tissue that are an internal part of the clitoris. They can also be found throughout the vestibule: next to the clitoral body, clitoral crura, urethra, urethral sponge, and vagina.

name: 3rd arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 3rd arch mesenchyme.

name: interorbital septum
description: Anatomical cluster composed of one or more bones and tissue that separates the orbits.

name: triceps brachii
description: The triceps brachii muscle (Latin for 'three-headed' muscle of the arm, it is called a three headed muscle because there are three bundles of muscle, each of different origin, joining together at the elbow) is the large muscle on the back of the human upper limb. It is the muscle principally responsible for extension of the elbow joint (i.e. straightening of the arm). Though a similarly-named muscle, the triceps surae, is found on the lower leg, the triceps brachii is commonly called simply the 'triceps'. [WP,unvetted].

name: collection of eyelashes
description: A collection of hair on face that is part of a eyelash.

name: head taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located on the skin of the head.

name: lower molar 3
description: Third molar (counting anteroposteriorly) in the lower jaw.

name: musculo-phrenic vein
description: Any of the veins that accompany the musculophrenic artery and drain blood from the upper abdominal wall, the lower intercostal spaces, and the diaphragm.

name: labial cartilage
description: Distinct cartilage around the jaws of elasmobranchs

name: primary nerve cord
description: A cluster of neurons that is the most prominent longitudinally extending condensed part of a nervous system.

name: foramen cecum of frontal bone
description: The frontal crest of the frontal bone ends below in a small notch which is converted into a foramen, the foramen cecum, by articulation with the ethmoid. This foramen varies in size in different subjects, and is frequently impervious; when open, it transmits a vein from the nose to the superior sagittal sinus. This has clinical importance in that infections of the nose and nearby areas can be transmitted to the meninges and brain from what is known as the danger triangle of the face.

name: lateral malleal ligament
description: A malleal ligament that extends from the bony margin of the notch of Rivinus to the neck of the malleus.

name: brain dura mater
description: The fibrous membrane forming the outer of the three coverings that surrounds the brain within the cranial cavity; consists of two layers including the periosteal layer and the meningeal layer.

name: female reproductive gland secretion
description: A portion of organism substance that is secreted by a female reproductive gland.

name: synaptic neuropil block
description: A closely associated group of synaptic neuropil domains.

name: hip connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a hip [Automatically generated definition].

name: hilar portion of hepatic duct
description: The segment of either hepatic duct located in the hilum of the liver.

name: obsolete pelvic fin basipterygial radial element
description: Pelvic fin radial element that is an endochondral fused radial elements or pterygiophores at the base of the pelvic fin.

name: endoderm of buccopharyngeal membrane
description: An endoderm that is part of a buccopharyngeal membrane.

name: bifurcation of trachea
description: This is the point at which the trachea splits into two (left and right) principal bronchi. It is located in the region of the fourth to sixth intercostal space, though this varies with species and with respiratory phase. This position closely associates the bifurcation with the heart base. The thickened median crest initiating the bifurcation is called the tracheal carina .

name: proctodeum portion of cloaca
description: Most distal cloacal compartment; function is copulation and in some species develops a penis[Kardong]

name: fenestra lateralis nasi
description: Opening on the lateral side of the nasal capsule.

name: hemisphere of embryo
description: One of two hemispheres of the embryo at the zygote or blastula stage[WP,modified]

name: synovial membrane of synovial joint
description: Soft tissue that lines the non-cartilaginous surfaces within joints with cavities (synovial joints).

name: m. interscapularis
description: Muscle which originates from the ventro-medial surface of the suprascapula and inserts on the ventral surface of the scapula.

name: inner cell mass derived epiblast
description: An embryonic structure that is derived from the inner cell mass and lies above the hypoblast and gives rise to the three primary germ layers

name: cauda equina
description: The cauda equina is a structure within the lower end of the spinal column of most vertebrates, that consists of nerve roots and rootlets from above. The space in which the cerebrospinal fluid is present is actually an extension of the subarachnoid space.

name: primordial hindbrain channel
description: The paired vessels that run along the lateral walls of the hindbrain and drain into the anterior cardinal veins. Isogai et al. (2002)

name: inner spiral sulcus
description: A concavity in the floor of the cochlear duct formed by the overhanging vestibular lip.

name: manual digit 4 mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing manual digit 4.

name: lower leg blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a lower leg [Automatically generated definition].

name: middle nasal concha
description: The medial surface of the labyrinth of ethmoid consists of a thin lamella, which descends from the under surface of the cribriform plate, and ends below in a free, convoluted margin, the middle nasal concha. It is rough, and marked above by numerous grooves, directed nearly vertically downward from the cribriform plate; they lodge branches of the olfactory nerves, which are distributed to the mucous membrane covering the superior nasal concha.

name: labium majora
description: One of the folds of skin which form the outer lips on both sides of the vaginal opening

name: obsolete skeletogenic cell
description: Cell that has the potential to form a skeletal cell type (e.g., cells in periosteum, cells in marrow) and produce extracellular matrix (often mineralized) and skeletal tissue (often mineralized).

name: rhombomere 2
description: the second transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

name: obsolete regional part of diencephalon
description: A regional part of brain that is part of a diencephalon [Automatically generated definition].

name: limb external integument structure
description: Dermal, epidermal, glandular and pigment structures of the limb integument.

name: distal phalanx of manual digit 3
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 3 [Automatically generated definition].

name: dorsal gray commissure of spinal cord
description: the part of the gray commissure in the spinal central gray posterior to the central canal of the spinal cord

name: intermediate tubule
description: The intermediate tubule is a nephron tubule that lies between the proximal and distal tubules

name: lacrimal sac
description: The upper dilated end of the nasolacrimal duct that is lodged in a deep groove formed by the lacrimal bone and frontal process of the maxilla; it connects the lacrimal canaliculi, which drain tears from the eye's surface, and the nasolacrimal duct, which conveys this fluid into the nasal cavity; like the nasolacrimal duct, the sac is lined by stratified columnar epithelium with mucus-secreting goblet cells, and is surrounded by connective tissue.

name: subcutaneous abdominal adipose tissue
description: Subcutaneous adipose tissue that is located in the abdominal region.

name: pygal plate of carapace
description: One of three plates on the posterior end of the carapace, posterior to the neural plates.

name: common hepatic duct
description: Predominantly extrahepatic bile duct which is formed by the junction of the right and left hepatic ducts, which are predominantly intrahepatic, and, in turn, joins the cystic duct to form the common bile duct[GAID]. The common hepatic duct is the duct formed by the convergence of the right hepatic duct (which drains bile from the right functional lobe of the liver) and the left hepatic duct (which drains bile from the left functional lobe of the liver). The common hepatic duct then joins the cystic duct coming from the gallbladder to form the common bile duct[WP].

name: clavicular facet
description: A notch for the articulation of the clavicle on other girdle elements.

name: obsolete postzygapophysis
description: Posteriorly projecting processes allowing de facto contact between consecutive vertebrae (some soft tissues are also present) via articular facets. [PHENOSCAPE:NI]

name: superior medullary velum
description: The superior medullary velum (anterior medullary velum, valve of Vieussens) is a thin, transparent of white substance, which stretches between the superior cerebellar peduncles; on the dorsal surface of its lower half the folia and lingula are prolonged. It forms, together with the superior cerebellar peduncle, the roof of the upper part of the fourth ventricle; it is narrow above, where it passes beneath the inferior colliculi, and broader below, where it is continuous with the white substance of the superior vermis. A slightly elevated ridge, the fraenulum veli, descends upon its upper part from between the inferior colliculi, and on either side of this the trochlear nerve emerges.
