Blood is supplied by branches from the superior cerebellar artery. [WP,unvetted].

name: intercalary element of fore digit
description: Small elements present in all digits of the manus, when present in a taxon. Each intercalary element articulates with the anteroventral end of the penultimate phalanx proximally and the distal phalanx distally.

name: longissimus cervicis muscle
description: A muscle with origin in transverse processes of upper thoracic vertebrae, and insertion in transverse processes of middle and upper cervical vertebrae that extends cervical vertebrae.

name: protractor operculi
description: Muscle located in the lateral region of the cheek, linking the lateral surface of opercle with the posterolateral margin of the suspensorium (usually the preopercle).

name: distal interphalangeal joint of digit 3
description: A distal inter-phalangeal joint that is part of the 3rd digit.

name: major calyx
description: portion of the urinary collecting system within the kidney that drains several minor calyces

name: synarcual region
description: Axial subdivision that includes a series of fused cervical vertebrae or vertebral elements. Based on Jeffrey C. Carrier. Biology of Sharks and Their Relatives, 2012. CRC Press.

name: pseudotympanum
description: Anatomical structure that is formed as a hiatus in the muscles covering the anterior chamber of the swim bladder in the area of ribs 5 and 6.

name: eminentia arcuata
description: Small crest on the extensor surface of the proximal head of the tibiofibula (tibial side).

name: omotransversarius muscle
description: The omotransversarius is a straplike muscle, which advances and adducts the forelimb, as well as flexes the neck laterally. It covers the transverse processes of the cervical vertebrae, lying to their side. The omotransversarius lies ventral to the trapezius, cranial to the deltoid muscle and is covered cranially by the cleidocervicalis. It extends from the atlas to the spine of the scapula, with its origin on the transverse process of the atlas and its insertion in the distal end of the spine of the scapula. Its name can be split into omo, which is Greek for shoulder, and tranversarius which relates to its attachment to the transverse process of the atlas. This muscle is innervated by the accessory nerve.

name: replacement tooth trench
description: Anatomical space within a bone in which teeth develop.

name: periventricular pretectal nucleus
description: A nucleus medial to the central pretectal nucleus in the periventricular zone.

name: kidney field
description: region of the embryo into the area in which the kidney rudiment will develop.

name: xiphoid cartilage
description: A costal cartilage that is part of a xiphoid process.

name: post-otic sensory canal
description: Sensory canal between and in close proximity to the trunk sensory canal and anteriorly with the otic and preoperculo-mandibular sensory canals. The post-otic sensory canal is bilaterally paired.

name: ischial cartilage element
description: A ischial endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: bone of craniocervical region
description: A bone that is part of a craniocervical region.

name: obsolete lamina II of gray matter of spinal cord
subdivision of spinal cord lateral column
distal mesopodial pre-cartilage condensation
description: A distal mesopodial endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: metacarpophalangeal joint of manual digit 2
description: A skeletal joint that connects a metacarpal bone and connects a proximal phalanx of manual digit 2.

name: submental lymph node
description: The submental lymph nodes (or suprahyoid) are situated between the anterior bellies of the Digastrici. Their afferents drain the central portions of the lower lip and floor of the mouth and the apex of the tongue. Their efferents pass partly to the submandibular lymph nodes and partly to a gland of the deep cervical group situated on the internal jugular vein at the level of the cricoid cartilage.

name: larval abdomen
description: Any abdomen (UBERON:6000020) that is part of some larva (UBERON:6001727).

name: respiratory system submucosa
description: A submucosa that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: tunica vasculosa lentis
description: An extensive capillary network, spreading over the posterior and lateral surfaces of the lens of the eye. It disappears shortly after birth.

name: pelvis blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a pelvis [Automatically generated definition].

name: lunge feeding vibrissa
description: A vibrissa on the lower jaw of rorqual whales that is hypothesized to form part of the lung feeding system.

name: musculature of body
description: The subdivision of the musculoskeletal system that consists of all the muscles of the body[VSAO, modified].

name: epidermal ridge of digit
description: The grooves in the outermost layer of skin on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet where sweat glands open.

name: supraoccipital endochondral element
description: A supraoccipital bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: cartilage of external ear
description: A cartilage that is part of a external ear [Automatically generated definition].

name: myocoele
description: The cavity within a myotome

name: shell septum
description: Septum that divides the internal chambers (camerae) of the shell of a cephalopod, namely nautiloids or ammonoids.

name: lymph node secondary follicle
description: A secondary follicle that is located in a lymph node

name: endothelium of venule
description: An endothelium that is part of a venule [Automatically generated definition].

name: lateropterygium
description: Bone that is attached or adjacent to lateral margin of basipterygium and anterior to pelvic fin lepidotrichium 1. The lateropterygium is a paired bone.

name: manual digit 3 phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit 3 mesenchyme.

name: baleen plate
description: A keratinous sieve composed of bristles that enables filter feeding in the mouth of mysticete whales.

name: sclerotome somite 1
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: supragenual nucleus of pontine tegmentum
description: A group of neurons embedded in the pontine central gray of the pontine tegmentum. Located dorsal to the internal genu of the facial nerve, it is found in the human ( Paxinos-2012 ), the macaque ( Paxinos-2009a ), the rat ( Swanson-2004 ), and the mouse ( Franklin-2008 ). Functionally it is part of the dorsal pontine gray of the subcortical motor system ( Swanson-2004 )

name: middle lateral line nerve (MLLN)
description: Sensory nerve of the posterior lateral line component. It develops from the postotic middle placode. MLLN innervates neuromasts located over the otic capsule and the suprabranchial line of neuromasts.

name: hypaxial region somite 6
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: body wall
description: The external portion of an animal body derived from ectoderm and mesoderm layers that encloses the body cavity.

name: muscle of pectoral girdle
description: Any muscle organ that is part of a pectoral girdle region.

name: embryonic lymph sac
description: A population of lymphatic endothelial cell precursors that will form the lymph vessels.

name: tube foot
description: One of the numerous external, fluid-filled muscular tubes of echinoderms, such as the starfish or sea urchin, serving as organs of locomotion, food handling, and respiration[BTO]. Tube feet consist of two parts: ampulla and podia. Ampulla contain both circular muscles and longitudinal muscle, whereas the podia contain the latter only. Thus the podia use suction to attach to the substratum[WP].

name: tela choroidea of midbrain cerebral aqueduct
description: Tela choroidea that lines the tectal ventricle.

name: efferent duct
description: The efferent ducts (or efferent ductules or ductuli efferentes) connect the rete testis with the initial section of the epididymis. The ductuli are unilaminar and composed of columnar ciliated and non-ciliated (absorptive) cells. The ciliated cells serve to stir the luminal fluids, possibly to help ensure homogeneous absorption of water from the fluid produced by the testis, which results in an increase in the concentration of luminal sperm. The epithelium is surrounded by a band of smooth muscle that helps to propel the sperm toward the epididymis.

name: major sublingual duct
description: The duct that drains the anterior portion of the sublingual gland and opens at the sublingual papilla

name: outflow tract of ventricle
description: A ventricular outflow tract is a portion of either the left ventricle or right ventricle of the heart through which blood passes in order to enter the great arteries. The right ventricular outflow tract (RVOT) is an infundibular extension of the ventricular cavity which connects to the pulmonary artery. The left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT), which connects to the aorta, is nearly indistinguishable from the rest of the ventricle[WP].

name: vestibulocerebellar tract
description: White matter tract containing axons arising in the vestibular ganglion primarily projecting to the ipsilateral cerebellum via the inferior cerebellar peduncle (Heimer, L. The Human Brain, 2nd ed., 1995, pg 370).

name: obsolete pars dentalis of premaxilla
description: Tooth-bearing part of the premaxilla.

name: extracleithrum
description: Narrow bone that lies ventral to the level of insertion of the pectoral fin and is sutured to the posterior edges of both the clavicle and cleithrum. Based on Forey 1998.

name: paraterminal gyrus
description: The paraterminal gyrus (subcallosal gyrus, peduncle of the corpus callosum) is a narrow lamina on the medial surface of the hemisphere in front of the lamina terminalis, behind the parolfactory area, and below the rostrum of the corpus callosum. It is continuous around the genu of the corpus callosum with the supracallosal gyrus. [WP,unvetted].

name: intercotylar space
description: Space between the atlantal cotyles.

name: arm skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of an arm [Automatically generated definition].

name: posterior maxillary process
description: Process that extends posteriorly from the planum triangulare and invests the maxilla laterally and the anterior ramus of the pterygoid medially.

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between manual digits 3 and 4
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between manual digits 3 and 4.

name: anterior parietal artery
description: The artery that delivers blood to the anterior portion of the parietal lobe.

name: body of sphenoid
description: The body of the sphenoid bone, more or less cubical in shape, is hollowed out in its interior to form two large cavities, the sphenoidal air sinuses, which are separated from each other by a septum.

name: hepatic peritoneum
description: Peritoneum that surrounds the liver.

name: vesical venous plexus
description: The vesical plexus envelops the lower part of the bladder and the base of the prostate and communicates with the pudendal and prostatic plexuses. It is drained, by means of several vesical veins, into the hypogastric veins.

name: pectoral fin ray
description: Soft ray that is part of the pectoral fin.

name: ependyma
description: The thin epithelium-like membrane composed of ependymal cells that lines the ventricular system of the brain and the spinal cord.

name: presumptive atrioventricular canal
description: A presumptive structure that has the potential to develop into a atrioventricular canal.

name: cardiac muscle tissue of papillary muscle
description: A portion of cardiac muscle tissue that is part of a papillary muscle [Automatically generated definition].

name: interdigital region between digits 3 and 4
description: An interdigital region that adjacent_to a digit 3 and adjacent_to a digit 4.

name: blood island
description: Blood islands are structures in the developing embryo which lead to many different parts of the circulatory system. They primarily derive from plexuses formed from angioblasts. Within them, vacuoles appear through liquefaction of the central part of the syncytium into plasma. The lumen of the blood vessels thus formed is probably intracellular. The flattened cells at the periphery form the endothelium. The nucleated red blood corpuscles develop either from small masses of the original angioblast left attached to the inner wall of the lumen or directly from the flat endothelial cells. In either case the syncytial mass thus formed projects from and is attached to the wall of the vessel. Such a mass is known as a blood island and hemoglobin gradually accumulates within it. Later the cells on the surface round up, giving the mass a mulberry-like appearance. Then the red blood cells break loose and are carried away in the plasma. Such free blood cells continue to divide. Blood islands have been seen in the area vasculosa in the omphalomesenteric vein and arteries, and in the dorsal aorta[WP, unvetted].

name: olfactory bulb outer nerve layer
description: Superficial layer of the main olfactory bulb containing axons from the olfactory nerve and glial cells

name: crista ampullaris
description: The crista ampullaris is the sensory organ of rotation located in the semicircular canal of the inner ear. The function of the crista ampullaris is to sense angular acceleration and deceleration.

name: dermal intracranial joint
description: Hinge in the skull skeleton to allow for kinetic movement of different parts. [PHENOSCAPE:NI]

name: external capsule of telencephalon
description: Any of the series of white matter fiber tracts in the brain that run between the most lateral segment of the lentiform nucleus and the claustrum; the white matter of the external capsule contains fibers known as corticocortical association fibers which are responsible for connecting the cerebral cortex to another cortical area; the capsule appears as a thin white sheet of white matter and provides a route for cholinergic fibers from the basal forebrain to the cerebral cortex; it eventually joins the internal capsule around the lentiform nucleus.

name: frontal sinus
description: The frontal sinus occupies the dorsal part of the skull medial to the orbit. It overlaps cranial and nasal cavities and is often referred to as the conchofrontal sinus. .

name: dorsal body wall
description: The dorsal part of the body wall

name: left subclavian artery
description: The subclavian artery that supplies the left pectoral appendage

name: olfactory region
description: Anatomical cluster that is located in the anterior region of the cranium and provides structural support for the olfactory organ.

name: pectoral fin
description: Paired fin that is located in the thoracic region of the body.

name: conjunctiva
description: the mucous membrane that lines the inner surface of the eyelids and the front of the eyeball

name: superior cerebellar artery
description: The superior cerebellar artery (SCA) arises near the termination of the basilar artery. It passes lateralward, immediately below the oculomotor nerve, which separates it from the posterior cerebral artery, winds around the cerebral peduncle, close to the trochlear nerve, and, arriving at the upper surface of the cerebellum, divides into branches which ramify in the pia mater and anastomose with those of the inferior cerebellar arteries. Several branches are given to the pineal body, the anterior medullary velum, and the tela chorioidea of the third ventricle. [WP,unvetted].

name: right colon
description: The proximal portion of the colon, extending from the ileocecal valve usually to a point proximal to the left colic flexure; it develops embryonically from the terminal portion of the midgut and functions in absorption.

name: scleral endothelium
description: An endothelium that is part of a sclera.

name: skin of external ear
description: A zone of skin that is part of a external ear [Automatically generated definition].

name: glial blood brain barrier
description: A blood brain barrier composed of glial cells.

name: obsolete decussation of medial funicular nucleus
ascending process of the parasphenoid
description: Process that is the lateral projection of the parasphenoid arising and articulating with the more dorsal portions of the neurocranium, usually at the level of the prootic.

name: electroreceptor organ
description: An organ that is capable of detecting electrical stimulus

name: appendage
description: Major subdivision of an organism that protrudes from the body[DOS, CARO].

name: palatal taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located on the soft palate, in the roof of the mouth.

name: 4th arch mesenchyme from head mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that develops_from a head mesenchyme from mesoderm and is part of a 4th arch mesenchyme.

name: pad
description: Surface structure that is a portion of the integument thickened relative to surrounding area.

name: moustache
description: facial hair grown on the outer surface of the upper lip. It may or may not be accompanied by a type of beard, a facial hair style grown and cropped to cover most of the lower half of the face.

name: pectoral fin actinotrichium
description: Actinotrichium that is part of the pectoral fin.

name: pharyngeal taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located in the pharynx.

name: lower pharyngobranchial toothplate
description: Pharyngeal toothplate of the lower jaw region; typically associated with ceratobranchial 5 element.

name: adult central complex
description: A midline crossing complex of 4 synaptic neuropil domains of the adult brain: the ellipsoid body, the fan-shaped body, the paired noduli, and the protocerebral bridge. It is closely associated with another paired synaptic neuropil domain, the lateral complex. It lies in the middle of the brain between the pedunculi of the mushroom bodies and is bounded ventrally by the esophagus, dorsally by the pars intercerebralis and laterally by the antenno-glomerular tracts.

name: hemiazygos vein
description: The hemiazygos vein (vena azygos minor inferior) is a vein running superiorly in the lower thoracic region, just to the left side of the vertebral column.

name: Hadjikhani et al. (1998) visuotopic area V2d
pterosphenoid
description: Endochondral bone that sutures with the orbitosphenoid anteriorly, the frontal bone dorsally and the sphenotic and prootic posteriorly. The pterosphenoid forms part of the orbitosphenoid region. The pterosphenoid bears foramina that accommodate branches of the trigeminal and facial nerves. The pterosphenoid is a paired bone.

name: lateral condyle of quadrate
description: Condyle on the lateral side of the quadrate

name: primary dorsal nerve cord
description: A nerve cord in the dorsal mid-line that is the most prominent nerve cord.

name: tibiofibula
description: Paired, endochondral bones formed by the fusion of the tibia and fibula. They form the shanks, extending from the knees to the ankles.

name: superior malleal ligament
description: A malleal ligament that extends from the tempen tympani to the head of the malleus.

name: spinal dura mater
description: A dura mater that is part of a spinal cord [Automatically generated definition].

name: respiratory system fluid/secretion
description: A portion of organism substance that secreted_by a respiratory system.

name: knee connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a knee [Automatically generated definition].

name: glomerular mesangium
description: A thin membrane which helps to support the capillary loops in a renal glomerulus. It is connective tissue composed of mesangial cells - myofibroblasts phenotypically related to vascular smooth muscle cells (MUSCLE, SMOOTH, VASCULAR), PHAGOCYTES and the mesangial EXTRACELLULAR MATRIX.

name: peripeduncular nucleus
description: A group of neuron cell bodies that form a thin, caplike configuration over the dorsolateral aspect of the crus cerebri; many of its cells are acetylcholinesterase positive.

name: cavity of pericardio-peritoneal canal
description: A tube lumen that is part of a pericardio-peritoneal canal.

name: cloacal lumen
description: A anatomical space that is enclosed by a cloaca.

name: accessory XI nerve
description: A cranial nerve that originates from neurons in the medulla and in the cervical spinal cord.

name: levator mandibulae externus superficialis
description: Responsible for the closing of the jaw.

name: blastodisc derived epiblast
description: An epiblast (generic) that develops_from a blastodisc.

name: outer spiral sulcus
description: A concavity in the outer wall of the cochlear duct between the spiral prominence and the spiral organ.

name: palatine process of maxilla
description: A thick, horizontal process of the maxilla. It forms the anterior three quarters of the hard palate, the horizontal plate of the palatine bone making up the rest.

name: manual digit 5 mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing manual digit 5.

name: sac of scrotum
description: Any of the two testis-carrying compartments of the scrotum.

name: osseus cochlea
description: The osseous cochlea is the bony foundation that forms the small shell arrangement for the cochlear nerve.

name: upper leg skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a hindlimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: inferior nasal concha
description: A turbinal located on the maxilla bone.

name: presumptive embryonic/larval nervous system
description: The sum of all the structures in the embryo that will develop into the embryonic/larval nervous system.

name: brain ventricle
description: one of the system of communicating cavities in the brain that are continuous with the central canal of the spinal cord, that like it are derived from the medullary canal of the embryo, that are lined with an epithelial ependyma, and that contain a serous fluid

name: archicortex
description: A portion of the cerebral cortex that, with the paleocortex, develops in association with the olfactory system, and which is phylogenetically older than the neocortex and lacks its layered structure. The embryonic archicortex corresponds to the cortex of the dentate gyrus and hippocampus in mature mammals. Being part of the limbic system, it has functions related to emotions and formation of memory. Signals being sent from the limbic lobe to the hippocampal formations can go via the archicortex as an intermediate.

name: mineralized skeletal tissue
description: Skeletal tissue that is mineralized.

name: obsolete regional part of lateral hypothalamic region
description: A multi-tissue structure that is part of a lateral hypothalamic area.

name: tail external integument structure
description: Dermal, epidermal, glandular and pigment structures of the tail integument.

name: distal phalanx of manual digit 4
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 4 [Automatically generated definition].

name: apex of lumbar spinal cord dorsal horn
external acoustic meatus
description: A tube running from the outer ear to the middle ear. The human ear canal extends from the pinna to the eardrum and is about 26 mm in length and 7 mm in diameter.

name: extraperitoneal space
description: The extraperitoneal space is the portion of the abdomen and pelvis which does not lie within peritoneum. It includes: Retroperitoneal space Retropubic space The space in the pelvis is divided into the following components: prevesical space perivesical space perirectal space

name: nuchal plate of carapace
description: The anteriormost plate of the carapace.

name: right hepatic duct
description: The duct that drains bile from the right half of the liver and joins the left hepatic duct to form the common hepatic duct.

name: rectus thoracis muscle
description: Rectus thoracis is a very small quadrilateral muscle sheet from the lateral thorax runs from the 3rd-1st rib that is in continuation with rectus abdominis. Its functioning muscle in respiration.

name: dorsal iliac process
description: Posteriordorsal process of the ilium.

name: pre-axial region
description: Anatomical region lying to the anterior or dorsal side of the metapterygial axis. [PHENOSCAPE:AD]

name: supraneural 3 cartilage
description: Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebrae 3 and 4.

name: longissimus capitis
description: A longissimus muscle that lies medial to the longissimus cervicis, between it and the semispinalis capitis. It arises by tendons from the transverse processes of the upper four or five thoracic vertebrae, and the articular processes of the lower three or four cervical vertebrae, and is inserted into the posterior margin of the mastoid process, beneath the splenius capitis and sternocleidomastoid.[WP,unvetted].

name: humerovertebral ligament
description: Ligament that links the tip of the postcleithral process of the cleithrum with either the vertebral column (at the vertebral parapophysis or rib of the sixth vertebra) or with the soft tissue around the postcleithral region.

name: distal interphalangeal joint of pedal digit 3
description: A distal inter-phalangeal joint that is part of the 3rd pedal digit.

name: minor calyx
description: portion of the urinary collecting system within the kidney that drains one renal papilla

name: individual digit of digitopodial skeleton
description: A subdivision of the skeleton of the autopod consisting of the phalanges of a single digit plus the associated metapodial element.

name: obsolete regional part of middle ear
adipose eyelid
description: Surface structure that is a fleshy membrane covering part of the eye.

name: sulcus distalis ossis cruris
description: In a fused tibiofibula, longitudinal furrow in the distal portion of the compound bone that demarcates the area of fusion of both elements.

name: premaxilla replacement tooth trench
description: Replacement tooth trench that is located in the premaxilla.

name: intraculminate fissure of cerebellum
description: A fissure that divides the culmen lobule (lobules IV and V)

name: dorsal fin middle radial element
description: Dorsal fin radial element that is the rod-like internal median skeletal support element of the dorsal fin located between the dorsal fin proximal radial element and dorsal fin distal radial element.

name: otic lateral line neuromast
description: Neuromast that is part of the otic lateral line. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)

name: anlage
description: Anlagen are populations of contiguous cells, typically arranged in one plane, that are morphologically indistinct, but that already correspond in extent to a later organ/tissue.

name: xiphoid process bone
description: A bone tissue that is part of a xiphoid process.

name: ischial pre-cartilage condensation
description: A ischial endochondral element that is composed primarily of a pre-cartilage condensation.

name: artery of upper lip
description: The superior labial artery (superior labial branch of facial artery) is larger and more tortuous than the inferior labial artery. It follows a similar course along the edge of the upper lip, lying between the mucous membrane and the Orbicularis oris, and anastomoses with the artery of the opposite side. It supplies the upper lip, and gives off in its course two or three vessels which ascend to the nose; a septal branch ramifies on the nasal septum as far as the point of the nose, and an alar branch supplies the ala of the nose.

name: lamina III of gray matter of spinal cord
subdivision of spinal cord dorsal column
gland of foregut
description: A gland that is part of a foregut [Automatically generated definition].

name: distal mesopodial bone
description: A distal mesopodial endochondral element that is composed primarily of a bone tissue.

name: lymph node of lower limb
description: A lymph node that is part of a hindlimb.

name: larval abdominal segment
description: Any segment (UBERON:6000003) that is part of some larval abdomen (UBERON:6001746).

name: larynx submucosa
description: A submucosa that is part of a larynx [Automatically generated definition].

name: reticular layer of dermis
description: The thicker, deeper layer of the dermis, comprised of criss-crossing collagen fibers that form a strong elastic network and also containing blood and lymph vessels, nerves and nerve endings, and hair follicles

name: ulna cartilage element
description: A cartilaginous condensation that has the potential to develop into a ulna.

name: pes blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a foot [Automatically generated definition].

name: head or neck skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a craniocervical region.

name: obsolete regional part of substantia nigra
central cervical spinocerebellar tract
description: Central cervical spinocerebellar tract

name: stapes endochondral element
description: A stapes bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: skin of chest
description: A zone of skin that is part of a chest [Automatically generated definition].

name: left lung lower lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a lower lobe of left lung.

name: ilio-marsupialis muscle
description: A muscle that originates on the anterior iliac spine that passes through the inguinal canal before dividing into four branches, each attaching to a pouch nipple

name: lateral tuberal nucleus
description: Nerve cell nuclei situated ventrally in the intermediate hypothalamic region, mainly in the lateral hypothalamic area.

name: M. iliacus internus
description: Muscle originates on the ventral border of the ala ossis ilei to insert on the dorso-medial surface of the femur.

name: geniculate placode
description: Rostralmost epibranchial placode. Associated with 1st branchial cleft.

name: endothelium of vein
description: An endothelium that is part of a vein [Automatically generated definition].

name: hypural plate
description: Perichondrally ossified bone that results from the fusion of two or more hypurals and support a variable number of principal caudal lepidotrichia. The hypural plate is an unpaired median bone.

name: manual digit 4 phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit 4 mesenchyme.

name: baleen plate bristle
description: A keratinous bristle that enables filter feeding in the mouth of mysticete whales.

name: sclerotome somite 12
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: interoceptive system
description: The system that is responsible for sensing the internal state of the body.

name: fringe on postaxial edge of finger IV
hypaxial region somite 9
description: Somite-derived body wall muscle present ventral to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: caudal rod
description: Multi-tissue structure that is a cartilaginous or collagenous bar supporting the caudal appendage.

name: inguinal mammary gland
description: A mammary gland that is part of a inguinal part of abdomen.

name: echinoderm pyloric cecum
description: The pyloric ceca (or digestive glands) and the cardiac stomach produce digestive enzymes in starfishes. Digested material is absorbed through the pyloric ceca for transport to the rest of the body. Each pyloric cecum extends the length of each arm.

name: subcapsular sinus of lymph node
description: A space between the capsule and the cortex which allows the free movement of lymphatic fluid and so contains a sparsity of lymphocytes. It is continuous with the similar lymph sinuses that flank the trabeculae.

name: tela choroidea of fourth ventricle
description: Tela chorioidea that lines the fourth ventricle[ZFA]. The tela chorioidea of the fourth ventricle is the name applied to the triangular fold of pia mater which is carried upward between the cerebellum and the medulla oblongata. It consists of two layers, which are continuous with each other in front, and are more or less adherent throughout: The posterior layer covers the antero-inferior surface of the cerebellum. The anterior layer is applied to the structures which form the lower part of the roof of the ventricle, and is continuous inferiorly with the pia mater on the inferior peduncles and closed part of the medulla[WP].

name: aqueous vein
description: A vessel that receives aqueous humor from the sinus venosus sclerae (canal of Schlemm)

name: male genital duct
description: A duct or series of ducts that transports sperm from the gonad. In mammals this is from the seminiferous tubules through rete testis, vas efferentia, epididymis, vas deferens, ejeculatory duct to the urethra.

name: minor sublingual duct
description: Any of the 8-20 small ducts that open into the mouth on the surface of the sublingual fold

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of pontine reticular formation
foregut epithelium
description: A epithelium that is part of a foregut.

name: outflow tract aortic component
description: An outflow tract that is part of a aorta.

name: anatomical cavity
description: Anatomical space which contains portions of one or more body substances and is bounded by the internal surface of one maximally connected anatomical structure. Examples: cranial cavity, pharyngeal recess space, nasal cavity, tooth socket, cavity of serous sac, lumen of stomach, lumen of artery, fornix of vagina.

name: anterior intestinal portal
description: opening of the foregut into the midgut

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of transverse frontopolar gyri complex
muscle of neck
description: Any muscle that is part of the cervical (neck) region.

name: hepatic sinusoidal space
description: A sinusoidal space that is part of a hepatic sinusoid.

name: left lobe of thyroid gland
description: A lobe of thyroid gland that is in the left side of a thyroid gland.

name: anterior dorsal fin
description: A dorsal fin located anterior to posterior dorsal fin. [WD]

name: ventral nucleus of lateral lemniscus
description: The lateral lemniscus is a tract of axons in the brainstem that carries information about sound from the cochlear nucleus to various brainstem nuclei and ultimately the contralateral inferior colliculus of the midbrain. Three distinct, primarily inhibitory, cellular groups are located interspersed within these fibers, and are thus named the nuclei of the lateral lemniscus. [WP,unvetted].

name: caput glenoidale
description: Convex articular facet of the vertebral centrum for the articulation with the adjacent centrum.

name: femoral gland
description: A gland arranged along a row on the underside of the hindlimb in some lizards[Kardong]

name: insect region of integument
description: A region of cuticle and its underlying epidermis.

name: mesenchyme of interdigital region between manual digits 4 and 5
description: An interdigital region mesenchyme that is part of a interdigital region between manual digits 4 and 5.

name: postcranial axial skeletal system
description: Subdivision of the skeletal system which consists of the postcranial axial skeleton plus associated joints.

name: gastrointestinal peritoneum
description: Peritoneum that surrounds the stomach and intestines.

name: uterine venous plexus
description: The uterine plexuses lie along the sides and superior angles of the uterus between the two layers of the broad ligament, and communicate with the ovarian and vaginal plexuses. They are drained by a pair of uterine veins on either side: these arise from the lower part of the plexuses, opposite the external orifice of the uterus, and open into the corresponding hypogastric vein.

name: radial cartilage
description: radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: sphenoparietal sinus
description: The cavernous sinus receives the superior ophthalmic vein through the superior orbital fissure, some of the cerebral veins, and also the small sphenoparietal sinus, which courses along the under surface of the small wing of the sphenoid.

name: median fin lepidotrichium
description: Lepidotrichium that is part of a median fin.

name: skeletal muscle tissue of diaphragm
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a diaphragm [Automatically generated definition].

name: primitive knot
description: organizer for gastrulation in vertebrates. The primitive knot starts as a regional knot of cells that forms on the blastodisc immediately anterior to where the outer layer of cells will begin to migrate inwards - an area known as the primitive streak. Posterior to the node is the primitive pit, where the cells of the epiblast (the upper layer of embryonic cells) initially begin to invaginate. This invagination expands posteriorly into the primitive groove as the cells layers continue to move into the space between the embryonic cells and the yolk. This differentiates the embryo into the germ layers - endoderm, mesoderm, and ectoderm. The primitive knot migrates posteriorly as gastrulation proceeds, eventually being absorbed into the tail bud.[WP]. the regional thickening of cells at the rostral tip of the vertebrate primitive streak through which gastrulating cells migrate anteriorally to form tissues in the future head and neck; this region organizes the formation of the three embryonic layers and establishes the longitudinal axis and the polarity of the embryo[MP].

name: crista terminalis
description: The vertical crest of the interior wall of the right atrium that lies to the right of the sinus of the vena cava and separates this from the remainder of the right atrium

name: deep cervical lymph node
description: The deep cervical lymph nodes are a group of cervical lymph nodes found near the internal jugular vein. They can be divided into upper and lower groups, or superior and inferior groups. Alternatively, they can be divided into deep anterior cervical lymph nodes and deep lateral cervical lymph nodes. They can also be divided into three groups: superior deep jugular, middle deep jugular, and 'inferior deep jugular'.

name: anterior distal condyle of femur
description: Anatomical projection in the distal region of the femur. [PHENOSCAPE:NI]

name: cribriform plate
description: A zone of the ethmoid that is received into the ethmoidal notch of the frontal bone and roofs in the nasal cavities. [WP,modified].

name: future foramen cecum
description: A thickened and indented region in the midline in the floor of the rostral part of the pharyngeal region of the foregut, located between the second and third branchial arches that is the first indication of the thyroid primordium. [Kaufman_MH_and_Bard_JBL, The_anatomical_basis_of_mouse_development_(1999)_San_Diego:_Academic_Press, p.132]

name: anterior vena cava
description: A vein that carries deoxygenated blood from the upper half of the body into the right atrium of the heart.

name: dermatocranium
description: Subdivision of skeleton that includes all dermal bones in the cranial skeleton[ZFA,modified].

name: middle temporal sulcus
description: A groove or cleft that divides the outer surface of the temporal lobe running in the same direction but at a lower level to the superior temporal sulcus.

name: pelvic fin
description: Paired fin located in the abdominal position of the body.

name: palpebral conjunctiva
description: A thin transparent mucous membrane that covers the posterior surface of the eyelids and is continuous with the bulbar conjunctiva at the conjunctival fornicies.

name: velar vocal fold
description: On of a pair of medial protrusions of the intra-pharyngeal ostium (an oval opening within the soft palate that connects the oral and nasal portions of the pharynx), used in vocalization in Koalas.

name: posterior cerebral artery
description: The posterior cerebral artery (PCA) is one of a pair of blood vessels that supplies oxygenated blood to the posterior aspect of the brain in human anatomy]. It arises near the intersection of the posterior communicating artery and the basilar artery and connects with the ipsilateral middle cerebral artery (MCA) and internal carotid artery via the posterior communicating artery (PCommA). [WP,unvetted].

name: substantia propria of sclera
description: A stroma that is part of a sclera.

name: left hepatic vein
description: A hepatic vein that is part of a left lobe of liver.

name: obsolete regional part of spinal cord dorsal horn
nerve of head region
description: A nerve that is part of a head.

name: dermethmoid
description: Dermal bone of the dorsal surface of the olfactory region. Dermethmoid can be paired or median.

name: replacement element
description: Skeletal element that forms as a replacement or substitution of another element or tissue.

name: maxillary tooth row
description: Tooth row that is on the maxilla.

name: median fin radial cartilage
description: median fin radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

name: mouth roof taste bud
description: A taste bud that is located on the roof of the mouth.

name: nucleus of lateral lemniscus
description: Groups of cells situated largely within the fiber bundles of the lateral lemniscus. Two nuclei are usually distinguished: a ventral group and a dorsal group (Brodal, Neurological Anatomy, 3rd ed., 1981, pg. 619).

name: lower premolar 1
description: First premolar (counting anteroposteriorly ) in the lower jaw.

name: greater palatine artery
description: The greater palatine artery is a terminal branch of the maxillary artery. It branches off of the maxillary artery in the pterygopalatine fossa and descends through the greater palatine foramen along with the greater palatine nerve and supplies the hard palate. It also anastomosis through the incisive canal with the sphenopalatine artery to supply the nasal cavity.

name: C3 segment of cervical spinal cord
description: The segment of the spinal cord that corresponds to the third cervical vertebra in most mammals.

name: lateral dorsal aorta canal
description: One of the branches of the dorsal aorta, after it enters the aortic canal

name: zone of long bone
description: An organ part that is part of a long bone [Automatically generated definition].

name: hyaloid artery
description: An artery that is part of the optic stalk of the eye and extends from the optic disc through the vitreous humor to the lens.

name: radio-ulna
description: Paired, long bones of endochondral origin formed by the fusion of the radius and ulna.

name: atrioventricular canal endocardium
description: Endocardium that is part of the atrioventricular canal[ZFA,vetted].

name: chin ventral margin
description: Subdivision of the head consisting of the area along the lower edge of the chin.

name: anterior malleal ligament
description: A malleal ligament that extends from the anterior tympanic wall to the anterior process of the malleus.

name: interventricular septum
description: Cardiac septum which separates the right ventricle from the left ventricle.[FMA]

name: medial orbitonasal foramen
description: Opening on the postnasal wall for the medial branch (= ramus medialis nasi) of the ophthalmicus nerve.

name: mammary gland fluid/secretion
description: A substance that is secreted by a mammary gland. The substance may differ depending on phase, with colostrum produced during pregancy/early lactation, and milk produced afterwards.

name: pedal digit connective tissue
description: A portion of connective tissue that is part of a toe [Automatically generated definition].

name: metanephric tubule
description: A metanephric tubule is an epithelial tube that is part of the metanephros[GO].

name: extraglomerular mesangium
description: the tissue comprised of mesangial cells that fill the triangular space between the macula densa and the afferent and efferent arterioles of the juxtaglomerular apparatus

name: associated mesenchyme of foregut-midgut junction
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a foregut-midgut junction.

name: obsolete regional part of dorsal cochlear nucleus
digit skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a digit [Automatically generated definition].

name: cloacal vent
description: The opening of the cloacal chamber to the outside of the organism. Birds maintain a single cloacal opening throughout their lives.

name: ramus nasalis internus
description: Distal part of the opthalmicus profundus gives rise to 2 ramules: palatinus and cutaneous.

name: fenestra nasobasalis
description: Small opening at the anterior tip of the nasal capsule, on the floor of the cavum inferius. It is located medially to the base of the inferior prenasal cartilage and serves for the passage of the ramus medialis narium and arteria orbitonasalis.

name: centroquartal bone
description: A tarsal bone that is formed from the fusion of the central and 4th tarsal bones.

name: sigmoid artery
description: The sigmoid arteries, two or three in number, run obliquely downward and to the left behind the peritoneum and in front of the Psoas major, ureter, and internal spermatic vessels. Their branches supply the lower part of the descending colon, the iliac colon, and the sigmoid or pelvic colon; anastomosing above with the left colic, and below with the superior hemorrhoidal artery.

name: levator mandibulae externus profundus
description: Muscle which is responsible for the closing of the jaw.

name: obsolete part of neuraxis
description: Part of brain and spinal cord excluding retina.

name: lateral dorsal aorta
description: Connect the outflow of the aortic arches to the dorsal aorta. The place where the lateral dorsal aorta fuse is is called the radiax of the aorta. Isogai et al. 2001.

name: superficial middle cerebral vein
description: A vein that runs along the fissure of Sylvius to the cavernous sinus on the lateral surface of the brain and connects to the superior sagittal and transverse sinuses.

name: great auricular nerve
description: A nerve arising from the second and third cervical nerves from the cervical plexus and innervating the skin over the parotid gland, the skin of part of the ear, the adjacent portion of the scalp, cheek, and angle of the jaw.

name: 1st arch pharyngeal cleft
description: A groove that is situated between the 1st and 2nd pharyngeal arch.

name: pedal digit 2 mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing pedal digit 2.

name: raphe of perineum
description: The perineal raphe extends from the anus, through the mid-line of the scrotum (scrotal raphe) and upwards through the posterior mid-line aspect of the penis (penile raphe).

name: medial entorhinal cortex
description: One of two subdivisions of the entorhinal cortex, located medially.

name: upper arm skin
description: A zone of skin that is part of a forelimb stylopod [Automatically generated definition].

name: presumptive embryonic/larval central nervous system
description: The sum of all the structures in the embryo that will develop into the embryonic/larval central nervous system.

name: vena cava
description: Any of the veins that carries deoxygenated blood from a part of the body into the right atrium of the heart.

name: adductor pollicis muscle
description: A muscle in the manus that functions to adduct the thumb. It has two heads: transverse and oblique. It is a fleshy, flat, triangular, and fan-shaped muscle deep in the thenar compartment beneath the long flexor tendons and the lumbrical muscles at the center of the palm. It overlies the metacarpal bones and the interosseous muscles[WP].

name: obsolete basihyal cartilage
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is median and is the anterior-most cartilage of the ventral hyoid arch.

name: distal phalanx of manual digit 5
description: A distal phalanx that is part of a hand digit 5 [Automatically generated definition].

name: somitomeric trunk muscle
description: The somitomeric trunk muscle is derived from somitomeric mesoderm. The muscle begins its development with the differentiation of the muscle cells and ends with the mature muscle. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.[GO].

name: obsolete duct part of cochlear canal
suprapygal plate of carapace
description: A plate that lies between the posteriormost neural plate and the pygal plate.

name: left hepatic duct
description: The duct that drains bile from the left half of the liver and joins the right hepatic duct to form the common hepatic duct.

name: axis intercentrum
description: The intercentrum unit of the axis vertebra.¬†

name: Weberian ossicle set
description: Anatomical cluster that consists of the Weberian ossicles.

name: radial artery
description: branch of the brachial artery beginning below the elbow and extending down the forearm around the wrist and into the palm.

name: mediopharyngobranchial
description: Pharyngeal arch cartilage, elongate and usually bifurcated posteriorly, located anteriorly on the upper branchial arches, attached to the anterior tips of the first infrapharyngobranchials. It supports rows of gill rakers on each side and is not homologous to other structures in the teleost gill-arch skeleton. One or two mediopharyngobranchials may be present.

name: distal interphalangeal joint of manual digit 3
description: A distal inter-phalangeal joint that is part of the 3rd manual digit.

name: renal papilla
description: Tip of renal pyramid projecting into a minor calyx.

name: primary somatosensory area barrel field layer 5
inter-frontal joint
description: Joint between the left and right frontal bone.

name: sulcus proximalis ossis cruris
description: In a fused tibiofibula, longitudinal furrow in the proximal portion of the compound bone that demarcates the area of fusion of both elements.

name: dentary replacement tooth trench
description: Replacement tooth trench that is located in the dentary.

name: anal fin middle radial element
description: Anal fin radial element that is the rod-like internal median skeletal support element of the anal fin located between the anal fin proximal radial element and anal fin distal radial element.

name: thyroid diverticulum
description: endodermal bud derived from the endodermal epithelium of the embryonic pharyngeal floor[MP]. The thyroid diverticulum is the embryological structure from which thyroid follicular cells derive. It grows from the floor of the pharnyx[WP].

name: distal carpal bone 3 cartilage
description: A distal carpal bone 3 endochondral element that is composed primarily of cartilage tissue.

name: artery of lower lip
description: The Iinferior labial artery (inferior labial branch of facial artery) arises near the angle of the mouth; it passes upward and forward beneath the Triangularis and, penetrating the Orbicularis oris, runs in a tortuous course along the edge of the lower lip between this muscle and the mucous membrane. It supplies the labial glands, the mucous membrane, and the muscles of the lower lip; and anastomoses with the artery of the opposite side, and with the mental branch of the inferior alveolar artery.

name: lamina IV of gray matter of spinal cord
pharyngeal gland
description: Racemose mucous glands beneath the mucous membrane of the pharynx.

name: posterior fascicle of palatopharyngeus
description: The thinner portion of the muscle of the palatopharyngeal arch, originating in the region of the midline where its fibers interdigitate with the contralateral partner, then passing posterior to the levator veli palatini muscle to join the longitudinal layer of pharyngeal musculature; acts as a sort of sphincter, reducing the caliber of the isthmus of fauces at the palatopharyngeal arch.

name: lymph node of upper limb
description: A lymph node that is part of a forelimb.

name: falciform fat
description: A large fat pad that is located at the base of the abdominal wall, in the falciform ligament of the liver.

name: respiratory system lamina propria
description: A lamina propria that is part of a respiratory system [Automatically generated definition].

name: hyaline cartilage tissue
description: Cartilage tissue primarily composed of type II collagen (thin fibrils) and a glassy appearance.

name: manual digit blood vessel
description: A blood vessel that is part of a finger [Automatically generated definition].

name: tonsil crypt
description: Tonsils consist of an extensive system of crypts, which result in a large internal surface. The tonsils contain four lymphoid compartments that influence immune functions, namely the reticular crypt epithelium, the extrafollicular area, the mantle zones of lymphoid follicles, and the follicular germinal centers. In human palatine tonsils, the very first part exposed to the outside environment is tonsillar epithelium.

name: mucosa of rectum
description: A mucosa that is part of a rectum [Automatically generated definition].

name: gular fold
description: A transverse fold of skin across the throat (Peters 1964).

name: crista contacta
description: Thin, horizontal ridge that extends medially from the corpus of the septomaxilla; it lays on the lamina inferior.

name: incus endochondral element
description: A incus bone or its cartilage or pre-cartilage precursor.

name: syrinx organ
description: vocal organ of birds, located at the base of a trachea

name: left lung upper lobe bronchiole
description: A bronchiole that is part of a upper lobe of left lung.

name: branch of ilio-marsupialis muscle
description: One of the branches of the ilio-marsupialis that attaches to a pouch nipple

name: intermandibularis
description: Is a mandibular muscle that develops into the ventral intermandibularis anterior and posterior muscles.

name: ocular side
description: Organism subdivision that is the side of the body possessing eyes.

name: secondary follicle corona
description: The part of the secondary follicle that surrounds the germinal center.

name: petrosal placode
description: Epibranchial placode between geniculate and nodose. Associated with 2nd branchial cleft.

name: leptocephalous larva
description: Larval stage in some teleosts before metomorphosis.

name: manual digit 5 phalanx pre-cartilage condensation
description: A pre-cartilage condensation that is part of a manual digit 5 mesenchyme.

name: sclerotome somite 15
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: iliac lymph sac
description: An embryonic lymph sac that forms near the junction of the iliac veins with the posterior cardinal veins.

name: taeniae tecti marginalis
description: Compose lateral rim of frontoparietal fenestra, ventrally confluent with orbital cartilages, posteriorly confluent with tectum synoticum.

name: nail plate
description: The nail plate is the hard and translucent portion of the nail, composed of keratin.

name: anal fin distal radial element
description: Rod-like internal median skeletal support elements of the anal fin, which articulate with the lepidotrichia distally.

name: mammary ridge
description: A ridge of epidermal cells that will form the mammary placodes.

name: right lung caudal lobe epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a lower lobe of right lung.

name: sclerotome somite 11
description: Medial ventral region of the somite that will form vertebral cartilages. Kimmel et al, 1995.

name: median sacral artery
description: The median sacral artery (or middle sacral artery) is a small vessel, which arises from the back of the aorta, a little above its bifurcation. It descends in the middle line in front of the fourth and fifth lumbar vertebr√¶, the sacrum and coccyx, and ends in the glomus coccygeum (coccygeal gland). From it, minute branches are said to pass to the posterior surface of the rectum. On the last lumbar vertebra it anastomoses with the lumbar branch of the iliolumbar artery; in front of the sacrum it anastomoses with the lateral sacral arteries, and sends offsets into the anterior sacral foramina. It is crossed by the left common iliac vein, and is accompanied by a pair of ven√¶ comitantes; these unite to form a single vessel, which opens into the left common iliac vein.

name: lower central secondary incisor tooth
description: A lower jaw incisor that is in_the_central_side_of a dentition.

name: smooth muscle layer in fatty layer of subcutaneous tissue
description: A smooth muscle tissue that is part of a hypodermis.

name: tela choroidea of third ventricle
description: Tela chorioidea that lines the third ventricle[ZFA]. The part of the choroid plexus in relation to the body of the ventricle forms the vascular fringed margin of a triangular process of pia mater, named the tela chorioidea of the third ventricle, and projects from under cover of the lateral edge of the fornix. Blood is supplied by branches from the superior cerebellar artery[WP].

name: head ectomesenchyme
description: mesenchymal cells derived from neural crest cells that contribute to development of the hard and soft tissue in the head and neck, including the branchial arches[MP].

name: efferent duct epithelium
description: An epithelium that is part of a efferent duct.

name: Hassall's corpuscle
description: The small spherical bodies of epithelial cells found in the medulla of the thymus, that are arranged in a concentric pattern around clusters of degenerating lymphocytes, eosinophils and macrophages

name: rhombomere 5
description: the fifth transiently divided segment of the developing rhombencephalon; rhombomeres are lineage restricted, express different genes from one another, and adopt different developmental fates; rhombomeres are numbered in caudal to rostral order

name: duodenum lamina propria
description: A lamina propria that is part of a duodenum.

name: obsolete regional part of superior colliculus
description: A multi-tissue structure that is part of a superior colliculus.

name: facial mesenchyme
description: Mesenchyme that is part of a developing face.

name: muscle of abdomen
description: Muscle (organ) which is a part of the abdomen. Examples: external oblique, rectus abdominis.

name: renal venous blood vessel
description: Any member of the network of tubes that return blood from the renal tissues to the systemic circulation.

name: obsolete suprascapular fossa
description: Fossa located on the medial surface of the scapula above the glenoid

name: precentral operculum
description: The ventrolateral lip of the precentral gyrus, which overlies the insula and is bounded by the lateral fissure (Brain Info).

name: fossa glenoidalis
description: Concave articular facet of the vertebral centrum for the articulation with the adjacent centrum.

name: femoral pore
description: Femoral pores are a part of a holocrine secretory gland found on the inside of the thighs of certain lizards and amphisbaenians which releases pheromones to attract mates or mark territory. In certain species only the male has these pores and in other species, both sexes have them, with the males being larger.[1] Femoral pores appear as a series of pits or holes within a row of scales on the ventral portion of the animal's thigh.

name: segmental subdivision of integument
description: A segmental subdivision of the integument of the whole animal.

name: cervical lymph node
description: Cervical lymph nodes are lymph nodes found in the neck. [WP,unvetted].

name: ligament of knee joint
description: A ligament that is part of a knee joint.

name: middle vesical artery
description: The middle vesical artery, usually a branch of the superior vesical artery, is distributed to the fundus of the bladder and the seminal vesicles.

name: digastric branch of facial nerve
description: The digastric branch of facial nerve arises close to the stylomastoid foramen, and divides into several filaments, which supply the posterior belly of the Digastricus; one of these filaments joins the glossopharyngeal nerve.

name: synovial limb joint
description: Any synovial joint that is part of a (free) limb.

name: nucleus of trapezoid body
description: A nucleus embedded within the fibers of the trapezoid body.

name: paired fin spine
description: Fin spine that is part of a paired fin.

name: obsolete predominantly gray regional part of superior olive
skeletal muscle tissue of iliacus
description: A portion of skeletal muscle tissue that is part of a iliacus [Automatically generated definition].

name: prechordal plate
description: A horseshoe-shaped thickening of the endoderm at the cranial (rostral) end of the primitive streak formed by the involution of Spemann's organizer cells which, together with the notochord, induces the formation of the neural plate from the overlying ectodermal cells and contributes mesodermal type cells to the surrounding tissue

name: interlobular artery
description: The branches of the arcuate arteries of the kidney that radiate outward throught the renal columns and supply the glomeruli[MP]. The first set of renal bloodvessels, the interlobular arteries (or cortical radiate arteries, or cortical radial arteries), are given off at right angles from the side of the arcuate arteries looking toward the cortical substance, and pass directly outward between the medullary rays to reach the fibrous tunic, where they end in the capillary network of this part. These vessels do not anastomose with each other, but form what are called end-arteries. In their outward course they give off lateral branches; these are the afferent vessels for the renal corpuscles; they enter the capsule, and end in the glomerulus. From each tuft the corresponding efferent vessel arises, and, having made its egress from the capsule near to the point where the afferent vessel enters, breaks up into a number of branches, which form a dense plexus within Bowman's capsule.

name: spiracular notch
description: Soft tissue notch/opening lying on a spiracle.[PHENOSCAPE:NI]

name: decidua capsularis
description: The layer of uterine endometrium overlying the implanted chorionic vesicle and facing the uterine cavity

name: caudal pontine reticular nucleus

The pontis caudalis is rostral to the gigantocellular nucleus and is located in the caudal pons, as the name would indicate. The pontis caudalis has been known to mediate head movement, in concert with the nucleus gigantocellularis and the superior colliculus. The neurons in the dorsal half of this nuclei fire rhythmically during mastication, and in an anesthetized animal it is possible to induce mastication via electrical stimulation of the PC or adjacent areas of the gigantocellular nucleus. The pontis caudalis is also thought to play a role in the grinding of teeth during sleep.

The cervical loop is a histologic term indicating a specific epithelial structure at the apical side of the tooth germ, consisting of loosely aggregated stellate reticulum in the center surrounded by stratum intermedium. These tissues are enveloped by a basal layer of epithelium known on the outside of the tooth as outer enamel epithelium and on the inside as inner enamel epithelium. During root formation the inner layers of epithelium disappear and only the basal layers are left creating Hertwig's Epithelial Root Sheath (HERS). At this point it is usually referred to as HERS instead of the cervical loop to indicate the structural difference[WP].

name: reticulotegmental nucleus
description: The tegmental pontine reticular nucleus (or pontine reticular nucleus of the tegmentum) is an area within the floor of the midbrain. This area is known to affect the cerebellum with its axonal projections. These efferent connections have been proven to project not only ipsilaterally, but also to decussate and project to the contralateral side of the vermis. It has also been shown that the projections from the tegmenti pontis to the cerebellar lobes are only crossed fibers. The n.r. tegmenti pontis also receives afferent axons from the cerebellum. This nucleus is known for its large amount of multipolar cells and its particularly reticular structure. The n.r. tegmenti pontis is topographically related to pontine nuclei (non-reticular), being just dorsal to them. The nucleus reticularis has been known to mediate eye movements, otherwise known as so-called saccadic movement. This makes sense concerning their connections as it would require a nucleus which receives and projects to the cerebellum to mediate that kind of complex circuitry. Also, behaviorally this makes sense as no one thinks about saccadic movements when scanning a room and the saccadic movements are not directly controlled by the cortex. The nuclei of the cerebellum are the most traditionally studied mostly because it is easy to see which nuclei degrade when the cerebellum is amputated. The neurons of the lateral reticular formation are very important for reflexes and the mediation of posture. It has been shown in cats that electrical stimulation of the reticular formation can make a standing cat lie down. Conversely if the cat is stimulated in an alternate spot it can make a lying cat stand.
